# Bowling Alone — Detailed Notes
<!-- pp. 1-20 -->

## Chapter 1: Thinking about Social Change in America

### The Puzzle: Declining Civic Organizations (1990s)

- **Glenn Valley, PA Bridge Club**: 40+ members playing regularly as of 1990, broke up soon after despite half-century history
- **Little Rock, AR Sertoma Club**: ~50 members attended weekly luncheon (mid-1980s) → 7 regulars by decade later
- **Roanoke, VA NAACP**: Active civil rights force since 1918, membership withered from ~2,500 to few hundred by 1990s; 1998 president contest drew only 57 voters
- **VFW Post 2378, Berwyn, IL**: Once bustling working-class country club for veterans, by 1999 membership dwindled to "struggle just to pay taxes"; Tom Kissell observed "Kids today just aren't joiners"
- **Dallas Charity League**: Met every Friday morning for 57 years, held last meeting April 30, 1999; average age risen to 80+, last member joined 2 years prior
- **Vassar alumnae book sale, DC**: Closed 51st annual sale (1999); co-chair noted volunteers "in their sixties, seventies, and eighties. They're dying, and they're not replaceable"
- **Tewksbury Memorial HS marching band**: 40 new uniforms purchased (1999), only 4 students signed up; 20 years earlier band numbered 80+

> "The puzzle: In the last several decades of the twentieth century all these community groups and tens of thousands like them across America began to fade."

### The Civic Vitality of the 1950s-60s

- Membership rolls and activity lists had **lengthened steadily** for as long as anyone could remember
- Organizations no longer revitalized by fresh members as in the past
- Leaders flummoxed—assumed problem was local or organizational-specific, commissioned reform studies
- 1960s seemed threshold of **new era of expanded involvement**
  - Great Depression's civic drought ending
  - Activity shot up year after year
  - Churches and synagogues packed—more Americans worshiping together than decades earlier, possibly more than ever in American history

### The Optimism of the Early 1960s

- Americans appeared to have **time on their hands**
- **1958 study** (Center for the Study of Leisure, University of Chicago): "the most dangerous threat hanging over American society is the threat of leisure"
- **Life magazine** (Feb 1964): "Americans now face a glut of leisure... The task ahead: how to take life easy"

> "As a matter of fact, mankind now possesses for the first time the tools and knowledge to create whatever kind of world he wants.... Despite our Protestant ethic, there are many signs that the message is beginning to get through to some people.... Not only are Americans flocking into bowling leagues and garden clubs, they are satisfying their gregarious urges in countless neighborhood committees to improve the local roads and garbage collections and to hound their public servants into doing what the name implies."

### Political Engagement Rising

- **Robert E. Lane** (1959): "the ratio of political activists to the general population, and even the ratio of male activists to the male population, has generally increased over the past fifty years"
- **Daniel Bell & Virginia Held**: "there is more participation than ever before in America...and more opportunity for the active interested person to express his personal and political concerns"
- **Voting turnout**: Women got vote 1920, through 1960 turnout in presidential elections rose at 1.6% every four years
- Simple straight-line projection suggested turnout would reach ~70% by nation's bicentennial (1976)

### Trust and Civic Confidence Peak (mid-1960s)

- **1965**: Disrespect for public life seemed waning
- Gallup: Americans who would like children "go into politics as a life's work" nearly doubled in decade (36% but never before recorded so high)
- **Trust in neighbors** rose from already high 66% during/after WWII to **peak of 77% in 1964**
- Civic-minded **WWII generation** (John F. Kennedy's cohort) picking up torch of leadership

### But the Era Wasn't Perfect

- 1950s-60s hardly "golden age" for marginalized Americans
  - **Segregation** by race (legal) and gender (social) was norm
  - **Intolerance** declining but still disturbingly high
  - **Environmental degradation** only just exposed (Rachel Carson)
  - **Betty Friedan** not yet deconstructed feminine mystique
  - **Grinding rural poverty** still to be discovered by national media
  - **Infant mortality** (1960): 26 per 1,000 births (44 per 1,000 for Black infants)—nearly 4x worse than end of century

- However: **engagement in community affairs and sense of shared identity/reciprocity had never been greater** in modern America
- Prospects for broad-based civic mobilization to address national failings seemed bright

### Education and Generational Promise

- Education **by far the best predictor** of engagement in civic life
- Universities in midst of most far-reaching expansion in American history
- First **baby boomers** approaching college
- Education seemed key to both greater tolerance and greater social involvement
- Young African Americans in South launching civil rights struggle
- White colleges in North awakening from 1950s silence

**Doug McAdam** on the "can do" generation:

> "We were a 'can do' people, who accomplished whatever we set out to do. We had licked the Depression, turned the tide in World War II, and rebuilt Europe after the war.... Freedom Summer was an audacious undertaking consistent with the exaggerated sense of importance and potency shared by the privileged members of America's postwar generation."

### Demographic Advantage: The Baby Boom

- America's population unusually young (baby boom)
- Civic involvement generally doesn't bloom until middle age
- Short-run: youthful demography dampened ebullience of civil society
- Long-run future looked bright:
  - Could look forward to swelling membership rolls in 1980s when boomers reached peak "joining" years
  - Bull session buzz about **"participatory democracy"** and **"all power to the people"** seemed to augur widespread engagement

**1968 prophecy** from acute social observer:

> "Participatory democracy has all along been the political style (if not the slogan) of the American middle and upper class. It will become a more widespread style as more persons enter into those classes."

### Introduction of "Social Capital" Concept

**Social capital**: Social networks have value, analogous to physical/human capital
- Just as screwdriver (physical capital) or college education (human capital) increases productivity (individual and collective)
- **Social contacts affect productivity** of individuals and groups
- Physical capital = physical objects
- Human capital = properties of individuals
- **Social capital = connections among individuals**—social networks and norms of **reciprocity** and **trustworthiness** that arise from them
- Closely related to **"civic virtue"**
- Difference: "social capital" emphasizes civic virtue is most powerful when **embedded in dense network of reciprocal social relations**
- Society of many virtuous but isolated individuals is NOT rich in social capital

### Historical Etymology of "Social Capital"

Term independently invented **at least 6 times** in 20th century:

1. **L. J. Hanifan** (1916): Progressive Era reformer, state supervisor of rural schools in West Virginia
   - Writing to urge community involvement for successful schools
   - Invoked "social capital" to explain why

> "those tangible substances [that] count for most in the daily lives of people: namely good will, fellowship, sympathy, and social intercourse among the individuals and families who make up a social unit.... The individual is helpless socially, if left to himself.... If he comes into contact with his neighbor, and they with other neighbors, there will be an accumulation of social capital, which may immediately satisfy his social needs and which may bear a social potentiality sufficient to the substantial improvement of living conditions in the whole community. The community as a whole will benefit by the coöperation of all its parts, while the individual will find in his associations the advantages of the help, the sympathy, and the fellowship of his neighbors."

2. **1950s**: Canadian sociologists characterized club memberships of arriviste suburbanites
3. **1960s**: **Jane Jacobs** lauded neighborliness in modern metropolis
4. **1970s**: **Glenn Loury** analyzed social legacy of slavery
5. **1980s**: **Pierre Bourdieu** (French social theorist) and **Ekkehart Schlicht** (German economist) underlined social/economic resources embodied in social networks
6. **1980s**: **James S. Coleman** put term firmly on intellectual agenda, using it (as Hanifan had) to highlight social context of education

### Individual vs. Collective Faces of Social Capital

**Private face**: Individuals form connections that benefit own interests
- **"Networking"**: Most get jobs because of whom we know, not what we know (social capital, not human capital)
- **Ronald Burt**: Executives with bounteous Rolodex files enjoy faster career advancement
- **Claude S. Fischer**: "Social networks are important in all our lives, often for finding jobs, more often for finding a helping hand, companionship, or a shoulder to cry on"

**Public face**: Social capital has **"externalities"** affecting wider community
- Not all costs/benefits accrue to person making contact
- Well-connected individual in poorly connected society ≠ as productive as well-connected individual in well-connected society
- Poorly connected individual derives spillover benefits from living in well-connected community
- Example: If crime rate lowered by neighbors keeping eye on one another's homes, I benefit even if personally spending time on road

### Social Capital as Both Private and Public Good

**Service clubs** (Rotary, Lions): mobilize local energies to raise scholarships/fight disease while providing members with friendships and business connections

**Networks sustain rules of conduct**:
- Involve mutual obligations by definition
- "Contacts" ≠ "connections"
- Networks foster **norms of reciprocity**
  - **Specific reciprocity**: I'll do this for you if you do that for me
  - **Generalized reciprocity**: I'll do this for you without expecting anything specific back, confident someone else will do something for me down the road
  - **Golden Rule**: one formulation of generalized reciprocity
  - Example: Gold Beach, Oregon Volunteer Fire Department T-shirt: **"Come to our breakfast, we'll come to your fire"**—specific reciprocity, but onlookers smile recognizing underlying generalized reciprocity (firefighters will come even if you don't)

### Generalized Reciprocity and Efficiency

- Society with generalized reciprocity **more efficient** than distrustful society
- Money more efficient than barter
- Don't have to balance every exchange instantly
- **Trustworthiness lubricates social life**
- Frequent interaction among diverse people → norm of generalized reciprocity
- **Civic engagement and social capital entail mutual obligation and responsibility for action**
- **L. J. Hanifan and successors** recognized social networks and norms of reciprocity can facilitate cooperation for mutual benefit
- Economic and political dealing embedded in **dense networks of social interaction** → incentives for opportunism and malfeasance reduced
- Why **diamond trade** (extreme fraud possibilities) concentrated in close-knit ethnic enclaves
- Dense social ties facilitate gossip and valuable ways of cultivating **reputation**—essential foundation for trust in complex society

### Forms and Uses of Social Capital

**Not a single "thing"**—comes in many shapes/sizes with different uses:
- **Extended family**: form of social capital
- **Sunday school class**: form of social capital
- **Poker regulars** on commuter train
- **College roommates**
- **Civic organizations** you belong to
- **Internet chat group** you participate in
- **Network of professional acquaintances** in address book

### Bridging vs. Bonding Social Capital

**Most important distinction**: **Bridging (inclusive)** vs. **Bonding (exclusive)**

**Bonding social capital**:
- By choice or necessity, inward looking
- Tend to reinforce exclusive identities and homogeneous groups
- Examples: ethnic fraternal organizations, church-based women's reading groups, fashionable country clubs

**Bridging social capital**:
- Outward looking
- Encompass people across diverse social cleavages
- Examples: civil rights movement, many youth service groups, ecumenical religious organizations

### Bonding Social Capital Benefits

- Good for **undergirding specific reciprocity** and **mobilizing solidarity**
- Dense networks in ethnic enclaves provide crucial social/psychological support for less fortunate members
- Furnishing start-up financing, markets, and reliable labor for local entrepreneurs
- By contrast, bridging networks better for **linkage to external assets** and **information diffusion**

**Mark Granovetter**: When seeking jobs or political allies:
- **"Weak" ties** (distant acquaintances moving in different circles) actually **more valuable** than "strong" ties (relatives and intimate friends in same sociological niche)
- Bonding social capital good for **"getting by"**
- Bridging social capital crucial for **"getting ahead"**

### Bridging Generates Broader Identities

- Bonding social capital bolsters narrower selves
- **1829 New Bedford, Massachusetts community lyceum** founding: **Thomas Greene** eloquently expressed insight

> "We come from all the divisions, ranks and classes of society ... to teach and to be taught in our turn. While we mingle together in these pursuits, we shall learn to know each other more intimately; we shall remove many of the prejudices and ignorance or partial acquaintance with each other had fostered.... In the parties and sects into which we are divided, we sometimes learn to love our brother at the expense of him whom we do not in so many respects regard as a brother.... We may return to our homes and firesides [from the lyceum] with kindlier feelings toward one another, because we have learned to know one another better."

### Bonding as Superglue, Bridging as WD-40

- Bonding social capital: **sociological superglue**
- Bridging social capital: **sociological WD-40**
- Bonding creates strong in-group loyalty, may create strong out-group antagonism (as Thomas Greene and New Bedford neighbors knew)
- Might expect negative external effects more common with bonding form
- Nevertheless, under many circumstances **both bridging and bonding social capital can have powerfully positive social effects**

<!-- pp. 21-40 -->

### Bonding vs. Bridging Social Capital

- Groups simultaneously bond along some social dimensions and bridge across others
- **Knights of Columbus**: created to bridge cleavages among ethnic communities while bonding along religious and gender lines
- Internet chat groups: bridge geography, gender, age, and religion while being homogeneous in education and ideology
- **Bonding and bridging are "more or less" dimensions**, not either-or categories, for comparing different forms of social capital
- No reliable, comprehensive, nationwide measures of social capital exist that distinguish "bridgingness" from "bondingness"
- This distinction will be less prominent in the book's empirical analysis, but remains conceptually important

### American Cultural Tension: Community vs. Individualism

- "Social capital" is new language for a very old debate about **community vs. individualism** in American intellectual circles
- Historical oscillation: **Liberation from ossified community bonds** is a recurrent theme in American culture
  - Pilgrims' escape from religious convention (17th century)
  - **Emerson** ("Self-Reliance"), **Thoreau** ("Civil Disobedience"), **Whitman** ("Song of Myself")
  - **Sherwood Anderson's** 20th-century celebration of struggle against conformity in *Winesburg, Ohio*
  - Even **Alexis de Tocqueville** acknowledged individualism's "calm and considered feeling which disposes each citizen to isolate himself from the mass of his fellows"

> "Our national myths often exaggerate the role of individual heroes and understate the importance of collective effort." — Putnam

- **David Hackett Fischer**: Paul Revere's alarm succeeded only because of networks of civic engagement in Middlesex villages—towns had well-organized local militia
- **Myth of rugged individualism** continues to strike a powerful inner chord in American psyche

### Contemporary Civic Malaise

- **Declensionist narratives** about community have a long pedigree—nostalgia for past golden ages is perennial
- **Barry Wellman**: "Pundits have worried about the impact of social change on communities ever since human beings ventured beyond their caves"
- At century's end, ordinary Americans shared this sense of civic malaise:
  - **1987 survey**: 53% of baby boomers thought their parents' generation was better at "being a concerned citizen"; only 21% thought their own generation was better
  - **77%** said nation was worse because of "less involvement in community activities"
  - **1992**: Three-quarters of U.S. workforce said "breakdown of community" and "selfishness" were "serious" or "extremely serious" problems
  - **1996**: Only 8% said "honesty and integrity of the average American" were improving; 50% said becoming less trustworthy
  - **1999**: Two-thirds said America's civic life had weakened in recent years, social and moral values were higher when they were growing up, and society was focused more on the individual than the community
  - **80%** said there should be more emphasis on community, even if more demanding on individuals

### Putnam's Thesis: Not Steady Decline, But Recent Reversal

- **Not arguing** community bonds have weakened steadily throughout American history or even the last hundred years
- American history is a story of ups and downs—*not just downs*—of civic engagement, collapse *and* renewal
- **Within living memory**, bonds of community were becoming *stronger*, not weaker
- **Argument**: At least in appearance, in the declensionist tradition, so important to avoid simple nostalgia
- Life in communities as we enter the twenty-first century is different from the 1950s and 1960s
- **Method to curb nostalgia: count things**
  - Are club meetings less crowded today than yesterday, or does it just seem so?
  - Are neighborhood barbecues less common now, or is it childhood recollection with wishful reminiscence?
  - Are friendly poker games less common now, or merely that we ourselves have outgrown poker?
  - League bowling may be passé, but what about softball and soccer?
  - Are strangers less trustworthy now?
  - Are boomers and X'ers really less engaged in community life, or are they engaged in new ways?

### Methodological Approach: Triangulating Evidence

- Studying evolving social climate analogous to challenge facing **meteorologists measuring global warming**
- Must make imperfect inferences from all available evidence
- **"Two source" rule**: Never report anything unless at least two independent sources confirm it
- Nearly every major generalization rests on more than one body of independent evidence
- Where divergent sources discovered, notes disparity
- Professional obligation to present all relevant evidence, exculpatory and incriminating
- Confirmatory evidence from multiple studies typically in notes, so skeptical readers should examine those notes as well as text

### Evidence Strategy

- Seeking as diverse a range of evidence as possible on continuities and change in American social life
- If transformation is as broad and deep as believed, it ought to show up in many different places—casting a broad net
- Social change, like climatic change, is inevitably uneven—life not lived in a single dimension
- **Anomalies may contain important clues** to what is happening
- American society is massive and polymorphous; civic engagement comes in many sizes and shapes
- Forms of social capital—ways we connect with friends, neighbors, and strangers—are varied

### Structure of the Book

**Section II** (Why?): Explores wide range of possible explanations—overwork, suburban sprawl, welfare state, women's revolution, racism, television, mobility, divorce

**Section III** (So What?): Quantifiable effects of social capital on different aspects of life
- Schools and neighborhoods don't work as well when community bonds slacken
- Economy, democracy, even health and happiness depend on adequate stocks of social capital

**Section IV**: Examines impact of tides on all aspects of American society, causes and consequences, and what might be done to reverse them

**Section V**: Optimistic challenge—contemplating possible therapies
- A century ago, Americans faced strikingly similar social and political issues
- Civic decay can be reversed
- Aim: provoke national deliberation and experimentation about renewing American civic engagement and social connectedness in the twenty-first century

### Illustrative Story: John Lambert and Andy Boschma

- **October 29, 1997**: John Lambert (64, white, retired University of Michigan Hospital employee) and Andy Boschma (33, African American, accountant) knew each other only through bowling league at Ypsi-Arbor Lanes in Ypsilanti, Michigan
- Lambert had been on kidney transplant waiting list for three years
- Boschma unexpectedly offered to donate one of his kidneys

> "Andy saw something in me that others didn't. When we were in the hospital Andy said to me, 'John, I really like you and have a lot of respect for you. I wouldn't hesitate to do this all over again.' I got choked up. I obviously feel a kinship [with Lambert]. I cared about him before, but now I'm really rooting for him." — Boschma

- Story speaks for itself, but photograph in *Ann Arbor News* revealed Boschma is white and Lambert is African American
- They bowled together—**in small ways like this, and in larger ways, too, we Americans need to reconnect with one another**
- That is the simple argument of this book

