## SECTION TWO: Trends in Civic Engagement and Social Capital

## Chapter 2: Political Participation

### American Political Participation: Transformed Over Three Decades

- Americans' involvement with politics and government has been transformed over the past three decades
- Not the only or most dramatic alteration in how we connect with communities, but **most widely discussed**
- With the singular exception of voting, American rates of political participation compare favorably with other democracies
- **American voter turnout ranks just above the cellar**, narrowly besting Switzerland but below all twenty-two other established democracies
- Americans are fairly active politically outside the ballot booth

### Voting Decline

- **1960**: 62.8% of voting-age Americans voted (Kennedy vs. Nixon)
- **1996**: 48.9% voted (Clinton, Dole, Perot)—**very nearly the lowest turnout in the twentieth century**
- Presidential election participation declined by roughly a quarter over thirty-six years
- Turnout in off-year and local elections down by roughly the same amount

### Two Qualifications on Voting Decline

1. **Registration requirements have been relaxed** over the last four decades
   - "Motor voter" registration: nationwide introduction, states spent $100 million to try to swell ranks of new voters
   - **Turnout has declined despite lower barriers**—even facing a lower hurdle, fewer Americans are making the jump

2. **Historical disenfranchisement of blacks**
   - For much of American history, many people (especially blacks in the South) were disenfranchised
   - **Jim Crow laws** introduced in 1890s decimated turnout in the South, artificially depressed national average for next seventy years
   - Standard measures of turnout lump disenfranchised millions with other nonvoters, understating effective turnout during first two-thirds of twentieth century
   - **1965 Voting Rights Act**: millions of newly enfranchised men and women in the South exercised right to vote for first time
   - **American national turnout figures took credit for inclusion of southern blacks**, obscuring fact that fewer of the rest of us who had the right to vote all along are now actually exercising it

### Outside the South: Longest Decline in American History

- Outside the South, slide in electoral participation since 1960 is the **longest decline in American history**
- Voting in 1996 and 1998 elections was substantially lower than in any other presidential and off-year elections in nearly two centuries
- Even within the South, turnout in 1996 was very nearly the lowest in 164 years (except for forced disenfranchisement 1896-1964)
- **Not in nearly two centuries have so many American citizens freely abstained from voting** as in past few years

### Who Are the Nonvoters?

- Explanations: growing distrust of government, declining party mobilization, fraying social bonds, political dealignment, and many more
- Virtually all long-run decline in turnout due to **gradual replacement of voters who came of age before or during New Deal and World War II** by generations who came of age later

### Generational Change: Intracohort vs. Intercohort

**Intracohort change**: Many individuals change their tastes and habits in a single direction simultaneously
- Type of change can occur quickly and be reversed just as quickly
- Example: Large numbers of Americans fall in love with sport utility vehicles in 1990s—automotive marketplace can be quickly transformed, and transformed in different direction just as quickly
- Change is detectable within each age cohort

**Intercohort change**: Slower, more subtle, harder to reverse
- If different generations have different tastes or habits, social physiology of birth and death will eventually transform society, *even if no individual ever changes*
- Example: Much change in sexual mores over last several decades has been of this sort—relatively few adults changed their views about morality; most who did actually became more conservative
- In aggregate, American attitudes toward premarital sex have been radically liberalized—stricter beliefs gradually replaced by later generation with more relaxed norms
- Change is detectable only across different age groups
- **Precisely because the rhythm of generational change is slower paced, it is more nearly inexorable**

### Technology Adoption: Mix of Both Processes

- Use of new technology (telephone, Internet) illustrates mixture of individual and generational processes
- When introduced, many people try out the new phone or Web browser
- Virtually none of early growth in usage attributable to generational change
- Change is easier for young people, so immediate impetus for growth is dampened by ingrained habits of older generations
- Example: Middle-aged Americans today recall how reluctantly their parents picked up the phone for a long-distance call, well after long-distance rates had fallen
- Gradually, generational differences became the dominant feature of this social change
- **Virtually all of the decline in personal letter writing over the past several decades** attributable not to individuals' changing habits, but to replacement of one generation accustomed to communicating with distant friends in writing by a younger generation more accustomed to picking up the phone

### Voting Decline: Almost Entirely Generational

- Distinction between intracohort and intercohort change crucial to understanding what's been happening to turnout in America over last thirty years
- **Very little of the net decline in voting is attributable to individual change**; virtually all of it is generational
- Throughout their lives and whatever their station in life and level of political interest, **baby boomers and their children have been less likely to vote than their parents and grandparents**
- As boomers and their children became a larger fraction of national electorate, average turnout rate was inexorably driven downward

### Generation Gap in Civic Engagement

- Generation gap in civic engagement is common in American communities these days
- One reason why decline in turnout continues so ineluctably, seeming to defy all efforts to reverse it (such as motor voter registration)
- Trend is pervasive, affecting not just presidential politics, but also state and local elections and even voting on bond issues
- Whatever the ups and downs of individual candidates and issues, each campaign's efforts to get out the vote must begin at a lower base level—**every year the Grim Reaper removes another swath of the most politically engaged generation** in the American electorate

### Voting as Proxy for Broader Civic Engagement

- Voting is by a substantial margin the most common form of political activity
- Embodies the most fundamental democratic principle of equality
- **Not to vote is to withdraw from the political community**
- Like the canary in the mineshaft, voting is an instructive proxy measure of broader social change
- Compared to demographically matched nonvoters, voters are more likely to:
  - Be interested in politics
  - Give to charity
  - Volunteer
  - Serve on juries
  - Attend community school board meetings
  - Participate in public demonstrations
  - Cooperate with fellow citizens on community affairs
- Sometimes hard to tell whether voting causes community engagement or vice versa
- Recent evidence suggests **the act of voting itself encourages volunteering and other forms of good citizenship**
- **When voting rates decline by 25 percent or more**, it is hardly a small matter for American democracy

### Voting Is Not a Typical Mode of Political Participation

- **Sidney Verba, Kay Schlozman, and Henry Brady** (political scientists) conclude:
  - "It is incomplete and misleading to understand citizen participation solely through the vote"
  - Compared with those who engage in various other political acts, voters report a different mix of gratification and different bundle of issue concerns
  - "[V]oting is sui generis"
- **Declining electoral participation is merely the most visible symptom of broader disengagement from community life**
- Like a fever, electoral abstention is even more important as a sign of deeper trouble in the body politic than as a malady itself
- **It is not just from the voting booth that Americans are increasingly AWOL**

### Political Knowledge and Interest

- Political knowledge and interest in public affairs are critical preconditions for more active forms of involvement
- Americans at century's end are about as likely to know which party controls the House of Representatives or who their senators are as were their grandparents a half century ago
- We are much better educated than our grandparents
- Since civics knowledge is boosted by formal education, it is surprising that civics knowledge has not improved accordingly
- **Average college graduate today knows little more about public affairs than did the average high school graduate in the 1940s**

### Interest in Public Affairs: Gradual Decline

- **Roper pollsters** (1974-1998): "Have you recently been taking a good deal of interest in current events and what's happening in the world today, some interest, or not very much interest?"
- Popular interest in current events naturally tends to rise and fall with what's in the news—chart looks like sawtooth traces left by errant seismograph
- Beneath choppy waves, **tide of the public's interest in current events gradually ebbed by roughly 20 percent over this quarter century**
- Another long-term series of annual surveys found **political interest steadily slumped by one-fifth between 1975 and 1999**
- Scandals and war can still rouse our attention, but generally speaking, fewer Americans follow public affairs now than did a quarter century ago

### Political Interest Decline: Also Generational

- Even more worrying are **intergenerational differences** in political knowledge and interest
- Like decline in voting turnout, slow slump in interest in politics and current events is due to **replacement of an older generation relatively interested in public affairs by a younger generation relatively uninterested**
- Among both young and old, curiosity about public affairs continues to fluctuate in response to daily headlines, but **the base level of interest is gradually fading**, as an older generation of news and politics junkies passes slowly from the scene
- Fact that decline is generation-specific argues against view that public affairs have simply become boring in some objective sense

### Post-Baby Boom Generations: Less Politically Knowledgeable

- **Post-baby boom generations** (men and women born after 1964) who came of age in 1980s and 1990s are **substantially less knowledgeable about public affairs**, despite proliferation of sources of information
- Even in midst of national election campaigns in 1980s and 1990s, these young people were about a third less likely than their elders to know, for instance, which political party controlled the House of Representatives

### Political Knowledge Gap: Recent Development

- Today's generation gap in political knowledge does not reflect some permanent tendency for the young to be less well informed
- **From earliest opinion polls in 1940s to mid-1970s**, younger people were at least as well informed as their elders were, but that is no longer the case
- News and information gap, affecting not just politics, but even things like airline crashes, terrorism, and financial news, first opened up with the boomers in the 1970s and widened considerably with the advent of the X generation
- **Daily newspaper readership among people under thirty-five dropped from two-thirds in 1965 to one-third in 1990**
- **TV news viewership in this same age group fell from 52 percent to 41 percent**
- Today's under-thirties pay less attention to the news and know less about current events than their elders do today or than people their age did two or three decades ago

<!-- pp. 41-60 -->

## Chapter 2 (continued): Political Participation — Cooperative vs. Expressive Forms

### Cooperative Activities Decline Most

- **Activities requiring coordination declined sharply**: Forms that depend on others' actions (serving on committees, attending meetings, working for political parties) fell most steeply
- **Individual expressive acts more stable**: Writing letters, running for office, writing articles declined modestly or remained stable
- **Coordination problem**: "If I'm the only member of a committee, it's not a 'committee,' and if no one else comes to a meeting on the bond issue, it is not a 'meeting,' even if I show up"
- **Social capital vulnerability**: Activities that bring citizens *together* and embody social capital declined most rapidly

### Cooperative vs. Expressive Distinction

- **Cooperative behaviors**: Require at least two participants—serving on committees, attending meetings, working collectively
  - Engage broader public interests
  - More vulnerable to free-riding and coordination problems
- **Expressive behaviors**: Can be done alone—writing letters, making speeches
  - More individualistic, correspond to narrowly defined interests
  - Political systems need both articulation of grievances AND coalition-building for resolving differences

### Table 1: Trends in Political and Community Participation

**Relative change 1973–74 to 1993–94** (Roper surveys):

- Served as officer of club/organization: **−42%**
- Worked for political party: **−42%**
- Served on committee for local organization: **−39%**
- Attended public meeting on town/school affairs: **−35%**
- Attended political rally or speech: **−34%**
- *Participated in at least one of twelve activities*: **−25%**
- Made a speech: −24%
- Wrote congressman or senator: −23%
- Signed a petition: −22%
- Member of "better government" group: −19%
- Held/ran for political office: −16%
- Wrote letter to paper: −14%
- Wrote article for magazine/newspaper: −10%

### Universal Decline Pattern

- **Utterly uninvolved rose dramatically**: From 46% (1973) to 64% (1994) engaged in *none* of these dozen activities—32 million fewer Americans involved
- **Active citizens cut in half**: Those engaging in at least three activities dropped from 20% to 11%
- **Consistent across demographics**: Decline appeared in all population sectors—men/women, blacks/whites, cities/suburbs/rural, all regions, upper/lower class

### Education and Participation

- **Absolute declines greatest among educated**: College-educated attendance at public meetings fell from 34% to 18%
- **Relative declines worse for less educated**: High school graduates' public meeting attendance fell from 20% to 8%; elementary school only fell from 7% to 3%
- **Serious deterioration across all education levels**

## Summary: Political Participation Trends (1960s–1990s)

### What Remained Stable

- **Civic knowledge comparable**: Americans score similarly on civics tests as parents did, despite four more years average formal schooling
- **Election-time engagement steady**: No less likely to talk politics or express interest in campaigns
- **Informed spectators**: Remain reasonably well-informed about public affairs

### What Declined Sharply (since mid-1960s)

- **Running for office/writing Congress**: 10–15% less likely to voice views publicly
- **Interest in politics/public affairs**: 15–20% less interested
- **Voting likelihood**: ~25% less likely to vote
- **Public meeting attendance**: ~35% less likely (partisan and nonpartisan)
- **Party politics engagement**: ~40% less engaged in political organizations of all sorts

> "We remain, in short, reasonably well-informed spectators of public affairs, but many fewer of us actually partake in the game."

## The Political Alienation Hypothesis

### Mid-1960s Political Confidence

- **One in four agreed** (1960s): "People like me don't have much say in government" or "Public officials don't care what people like me think"
- **Three in four could trust government** to do right most of the time
- Americans felt politically effective

### 1990s Cynicism

- **Three in four didn't trust government** to do right most of the time
- **Dramatic reversal example**: April 1966 (Vietnam War, race riots in Cleveland/Chicago/Atlanta)—66% *rejected* view that "people running the country don't really care what happens to you"
- **December 1997** (longest peace/prosperity period in generations)—57% *endorsed* that same cynical view
- Today's cynical views may be more accurate than 1960s Pollyannaish views, but they undermine political confidence needed to motivate involvement

### Political System Dysfunction

- **Rising alienation and declining confidence** may explain disengagement from politics
- **Lack of compelling collective projects**: Redirected energies away from conventional politics into less formal, more voluntary, more effective channels
- Next question: Does this story hold for social and civic involvement beyond politics?

---

## Chapter 3: Civic Participation

> "Americans of all ages, all stations in life, and all types of disposition are forever forming associations. There are not only commercial and industrial associations in which all take part, but others of a thousand different types—religious, moral, serious, futile, very general and very limited, immensely large and very minute…. Nothing, in my view, deserves more attention than the intellectual and moral associations in America." — **Alexis de Tocqueville**

### American Associational Genius

- **Tocqueville's observation (early 19th century)**: Americans more likely involved in voluntary associations than citizens of most other nations; only small northern European nations outrank us as joiners
- **Organizational diversity**: *World Almanac* lists 2,380 groups—Aaron Burr Society to Zionist Organization of America, including Grand United Order of Antelopes, Elvis Presley Burning Love Fan Club, Polish Army Veterans Association of America, Southern Appalachian Dulcimer Association, National Association for Outlaw and Lawman History
- **Grassroots vitality**: Americans involved in PTAs, recreational groups, work-related groups (labor unions/professional organizations), religious groups, youth groups, service/fraternal clubs, neighborhood/homeowners groups, charities
- **Organizational continuity**: Same array has characterized Americans since at least 1950s

### Three Categories of Associations

1. **Community based**: Social, civic, leisure groups—B'nai B'rith to PTA
2. **Church based**: Religious organizations
3. **Work based**: Labor unions, professional organizations

## The Paradox: Association Explosion vs. Membership Collapse

### Apparent Growth: National Organizations

- **Sheer numbers tripled**: Nonprofit organizations of national scope in *Encyclopedia of Associations* doubled from 10,299 (1968) to 22,901 (1997)
- **Per capita increase**: Nearly two-thirds increase over three decades (accounting for population growth)
- **"Participation revolution" claims**: Some observers spoke hastily of transformation in American politics and society
- **Interest group explosion**: Washington lobbying groups proliferated since 1960s—more groups claiming to speak for more categories of citizens

### Reality Check: Letterhead Organizations

- **Most lack mass membership**: Groups like Animal Nutrition Research Council, National Conference on Uniform Traffic Accident Statistics, National Slag Association have no individual members
- **Median membership tiny**: 1988 *Encyclopedia of Associations* median was one thousand members; 1962 median was ~10,000 members
- **Organizations tripled, average membership one-tenth as large**: Proliferation of letterheads, not grassroots participation boom

### Geographic Concentration: The Washington Phenomenon

- **Old organizations in heartland**: Boy Scouts (Irving, TX), Knights of Columbus (New Haven, CT), American Legion/Kiwanis (Indianapolis), Civitan (Birmingham), Jaycees (Tulsa), Lions Clubs (Oak Brook, IL), Optimists (St. Louis), NAACP (Baltimore), Veterans of Foreign Wars (Kansas City), Camp Fire Boys and Girls (Atlanta), Boys and Girls Clubs (New York—Hadassah/Alcoholics Anonymous)
- **New organizations in Washington, DC**: AARP at 6th and E Streets (not Florida/California/Arizona where constituents are); Children's Defense Fund, Common Cause, National Organization for Women, National Wildlife Federation, Greenpeace, Friends of the Earth, National Gay and Lesbian Task Force, National Trust for Historic Preservation, Wilderness Society, National Right to Life Committee, Zero Population Growth—all within blocks of Capitol Hill
- **Professionally staffed advocacy organizations**: Not member-centered, locally based associations

### The New "Associationism"

- **Focus on policy expression**: Expressing views in national political debate, not providing regular connection *among* individual members
- **Financial support from citizens**: May speak faithfully on behalf of ordinary citizens but not really *composed* of citizen members like church congregations, reading groups, or fraternal organizations
- **Lack of local chapters**: Of eighty-three public-interest groups founded in early 1970s, two-thirds had no local chapters at all; another 12% had no more than twenty-five chapters nationwide (average one per two states)
- Only nine had as many as one hundred local chapters nationwide

> **Rotary alone has nearly twice as many chapters as all eighty-three public-interest groups combined.**

### Mailing List Membership

- **Survey of 205 national "citizens groups" (1985)**: Less than one-third had chapters to which individual members belonged and paid dues
- **More recently founded groups less chapter-based**: Among citizens' groups founded after 1965, barely one in four had chapters with individual members
- **Membership means writing a check**: Moving a pen, not making a meeting

### Case Study: AARP (American Association of Retired Persons)

- **Dramatic growth**: 400,000 card-carrying members (1960) to 33 million (mid-1990s)
- **Minimal engagement required**: Few seconds annually to sign a check
- **Politically significant but socially minimal**: Demands little of members' energies, contributes little to social capital
- **Less than 10% belong to local chapters**
- **Grassroots activities on life support even during maximum membership growth** (per AARP staff)
- **More in common with mail-order commercial organizations than old-fashioned face-to-face associations**
- **Origins**: Founded as mail-order insurance firm

### Tertiary Associations

- **"New associationism" needs new label**: Perhaps **"tertiary associations"**—distinct from classic "secondary associations"
- **For vast majority, membership = writing check or reading newsletter**
- **Few attend meetings**: Many never have meetings at all
- **Unlikely to encounter other members**: Bond between National Wildlife Federation/National Rifle Association members less like gardening club/prayer group bond, more like bond between two Yankees fans on opposite coasts or two L. L. Bean catalog users—shared interests/symbols/leaders/common enemy, not aware of each other's existence

### Social Connectedness Verdict

- **Vigor of Washington-based organizations unreliable guide** to vitality of social connectedness and civic engagement in American communities
- **Need to examine community-based associations** with local chapters where members actually meet

## Veterans' Organizations: Case Study in Declining Real Involvement

### Appearance vs. Reality

- **Encyclopedia count**: Veterans' organizations nearly tripled (1980–1997)—single most vigorous sector of organizational growth
- **Careful national surveys**: Rate of membership in veterans' organizations among American men and women *fell* by ~10%
- **Not surprising**: Number of living veterans fell 9% across same eighteen years
- **Explosive organizational growth coincided with declining involvement by veterans**

### Similar Pattern: Trade Unions

- **Encyclopedia listings grew 4%** (1980–1997)
- **Fraction of employees belonging to unions plummeted 35%+**
- **More organizations ≠ more members**

## Environmental Organizations: Growth Through Marketing, Not Engagement

### Environmental Defense Fund (EDF)

- **Membership tripled**: 100,000 (1988) to 300,000 (1995)
- **Officials attribute expansion to "better marketing efforts"**: Switch to "front-end prospecting" (free gift to nonmembers, then ask for donation) vs. "back-end prospecting" (gifts after donations received)

### Greenpeace

- **Became largest environmental organization in America**: Accounted for more than one-third of all members in national environmental groups at peak (1990)
- **Extremely aggressive direct-mail program**
- **Leadership concerned about junk mail spectacle**: Temporarily cut back direct-mail solicitation
- **Membership hemorrhaged**: Plummeted 85% by 1998

### Lesson

- **Mail-order "membership" = poor measure of civic engagement**, especially for associations lacking local chapters where members can participate
- Need evidence from organizations that *do* involve members directly in community-based activity

## Chapter-Based Organizations: The Real Story

### Figure 8: Average Membership Rate in Thirty-two National Chapter-Based Associations, 1900–1997

**Long upward wave (1900–1960s)**:
- More women belonged to women's clubs
- More rural residents belonged to Grange
- More youths belonged to Scouts
- More Jews belonged to Hadassah and B'nai B'rith
- More men belonged to service clubs
- **Rising educational levels** important factor—aggregate increase in membership exceeded even that

> "As the decades passed, America seemed more and more to fit Tocqueville's description."

### Great Depression Impact (1930s)

- **Sharp dip in civic involvement**: Membership records of virtually every adult organization bear scars
- **Some paused in ebullient growth; others reversed extraordinarily**: League of Women Voters, Elks, Moose, Knights of Columbus membership cut in half (1930–1935)
- **Underlines effects of acute economic distress on civic engagement** (topic revisited in chapter 11)

### World War II Boom (1940s–1960s)

- **Losses recouped by early 1940s**
- **Massive outpouring of patriotism and collective solidarity**: War's end redirected energies into community life
- **Two decades following 1945 = one of most vital periods of community involvement in American history**
- **"Market share" for thirty-two organizations skyrocketed**
- **Dramatic breadth**: Civic explosion encompassed virtually every organization—"old-fashioned" (Grange, Elks) to newer service clubs (Lions, League of Women Voters)

### The Decline Begins (Late 1950s–1997)

- **Burst of community involvement began to tail off by late 1950s**: Absolute membership continued rising for a while
- **Late 1960s/early 1970s**: Membership growth began falling further behind population growth
- **Decline deepened**: Absolute membership began to slip, then plummet
- **By century's close, massive postwar boom in membership rates eliminated**

**On average** (across all organizations):
- **Membership rates plateaued 1957**
- **Peaked early 1960s**
- **Period of sustained decline began 1969**
- **Rates more than doubled 1940–45 to peak**
- **Slightly less than halved between peak and 1997**

### Organizational Variation

- **Effects of Great Depression varied**: Massive declines in Masons and Hadassah; youth organizations (4-H, Boy Scouts, Girl Scouts) immune to economic distress affecting adults
- **Postwar boom timing varied**: Grange and General Federation of Women's Clubs ended by mid-1950s; Rotary and Optimists remained on higher plateau until 1980s
- **NAACP**: Spiked sharply during WWII, collapsed early 1950s, regained highest levels early 1960s, then stagnated and slumped from 1970s onward
- **Behind each decline**: Individual tales of leadership success/failure, organizational tenacity, strategic blunders, vicissitudes of social life and politics

### Remarkable Common Pattern

- **Very different organizations—different constituency, age, leadership—entered rough water at about same time in last quarter of 20th century**

## Parent-Teacher Association (PTA): Dramatic Rise and Fall

### Mid-20th Century Dominance

- **Among most common community organizations**: Grassroots survey (early 1960s) found PTA had more members than any other secular organization
- **More than one in six adult Nebraskans** reported PTA membership
- **Absolute number relatively high during baby boom** (no surprise)

### Unprecedented Growth (1910–1960)

- **Percentage of parents nationwide who joined more than doubled** (1945–1960)
- **Continuing vertiginous, almost uninterrupted growth** since founding (1910)
- **Average annual addition**: 1.6% of all American families with kids (400,000 families/year) added to PTA membership rolls

### The Reversal (1960–1997)

- **Shocking suddenness (1960)**: Six decades of organizational growth captured graphically in Figure 9
- **Subsequent decline leveled off two decades later**: Membership in PTA returned to level of 1943, utterly erasing postwar gains
- **Brief 1980s rebound vanished by late 1990s**
- **Average annual loss (after 1960)**: 1.2% of all American families with kids (250,000 families/year) dropped out

### Recent Study Findings

> "Membership declined from a high in the early 1960s of almost fifty members per 100 families with children under eighteen to fewer than twenty members per 100 families with children under eighteen in the early 1980s. Although participation rebounded somewhat in the 1980s and the early 1990s, the organization never recaptured its membership heights of the late 1950s and early 1960s. [Recently the organization has experienced renewed decline.] Between 1990 and 1997, the PTA lost half a million members, even though the number of families with children under eighteen grew by over 2 million and public school enrollment grew by over 5 million."

### PTA Success Story Interrupted

- **One of most impressive organizational success stories in American history**: Unabated, almost exponential growth over first six decades of 20th century
- **Interrupted only by briefest pauses during Great Depression and one year during WWII**
- **Success due to connectedness appeal**: Millions of parents wanted to be engaged somehow in children's education
- **Easy to sneer at cookies, cider, small talk in cynical era**, but membership betokened commitment to participate in practical, child-focused form of community life

### Collapse Significance

- **No less sensational than earlier growth**
- **What accounts for dramatic turnaround?**

### Optical Illusion: Local School Service Organizations

- **Some decline is optical illusion**: Parental involvement in local school service organizations (not all affiliated with national PTA) did not fall as rapidly as PTA-affiliated membership
- **1970s following disagreements** about school politics and national dues: Many local parent-teacher organizations disaffiliated from national PTA to join competing organizations or remain wholly independent (many subsequently withered)
- **Bitter battles over school desegregation (1960s)**: Wholesale disaffiliation from national PTA in several southern states
- While genuine organizational loss, may not have marked withdrawal of southern parents from organizational life of local schools

### Real Decline After Accounting for Specifics

- **After accounting for all specific gains and losses**: Reasonably clear that parental participation in parent-teacher groups of all sorts suffered substantial decline in decades after 1960
- **No need to romanticize 1950s PTA meetings** to recognize many Americans nowadays are less involved with their kids' education

## Common Pattern: Rapid Growth to 1960s, Abruptly Halted, Followed by Rapid Decline

- **Features across diverse organizations**: Rapid growth to 1960s, abruptly halted, followed by rapid decline
- **Significant piece in mosaic of evidence** on changing civic involvement in American communities
- **Each organization very different in constituency, age, leadership**—yet entered rough water at about same time

## Two Important Caveats

### Caveat 1: Popularity of Specific Groups May Wax and Wane

- **Independent of general community engagement level**: Even though historical analysis cast wide net in terms of organization types, possibly newer, more dynamic organizations escaped scrutiny
- **Picture of decline may apply only to "old-fashioned" organizations**, not all community-based organizations
- **Sociologist Tom Smith**: "Ultimately, if we want to know whether group membership *in general* has been increasing [or decreasing], we have to study group membership *in general*."

### Caveat 2: Formal Membership May Not Reflect Actual Involvement

- **Individual "belonging" to half dozen groups may be active in none**
- **What really matters**: Not merely nominal membership, but active and involved membership
- **Need to turn from formal organizational records to social surveys**: Can encompass organizational affiliations of all sorts and distinguish formal membership from actual involvement

## Survey Evidence: National Institute of Mental Health (NIMH) Studies

### Michigan-NIMH Study (1957 and 1976)

- **Careful nationwide surveys** on behalf of NIMH
- **1976 replication** led by one of earlier researchers, taking great care to make studies as nearly identical as possible
- **First wave** conducted roughly a decade before organizational records suggest postwar peak of civic engagement
- **Second wave** conducted roughly a decade after peak

### Key Finding: "Reduced Integration into Social Structure"

- Over two turbulent decades, **informal socializing with friends/relatives declined ~10%**
- **Organizational memberships fell by 16%**
- **Church attendance declined 20%** (topic addressed more directly in a moment)
- **Significant declines in**: Unions; church groups; fraternal and veterans organizations; civic groups (PTAs); youth groups; charities; catch-all "other" category
- **Best available survey evidence consistent with organizational record**: Membership in voluntary associations among ordinary Americans declined modestly between mid-1950s and mid-1970s

## Post-1970s Survey Evidence: Three Major Archives

1. **General Social Survey (GSS)**
2. **Roper Social and Political Trends archive**
3. **DDB Needham Life Style archive**

### GSS Findings: Formal Membership Stable (1970s–1990s)

- **Most comprehensive measure** of trends in Americans' formal membership in many different types of groups
- **Formal membership rates not changed much** (at least if we ignore rising educational levels)
- **Percentage claiming formal membership in *some* organization fallen a bit**, but glacial trend so far—from little less than 75% (mid-1970s) to little less than 70% (early 1990s)
- **Declines**: Church-related groups, labor unions, fraternal organizations, veterans groups
- **Increases offset declines**: Professional, ethnic, service, hobby, sports, school fraternity, and other groups
- **Only substantial increase in professional organizations**; that growth barely kept pace with occupational growth in professions themselves

### Educational Levels Adjusted

- **If we account for rise in educational levels** (assumption: more Americans nowadays have skills/interests that traditionally brought people into civic life): Overall declines more marked
- **Among college graduates**: Organizational membership declined ~30%
- **Among high school dropouts**: Decline ~30%
- **Net decline in formal organizational membership modest at best**

## Active Participation: Dramatic Decline

### Organizational Leadership

- **Service as organizational officer/committee member very common** among active members of American organizations
- **1987 data**: 61% of organization members had served on committee at some time or other; 46% had served as officer
- **Among self-described "active" members** (~half of adult population): 73% had served as committee member at some time, 58% had served as officer, only 21% never served as either
- **Overwhelming majority of active members in most voluntary associations in America cajoled into playing some leadership role**

### Leadership Role Decline (1973–1994)

- **Number of men and women who took *any* leadership role in *any* local organization sliced by more than 50%**
- **From "old-fashioned" fraternal organizations to new age encounter groups**
- **Figure 10 summary**: Fraction of population actively involved in organizational life as either officer or local committee member
- **Dismaying trend began accelerating after 1985**: Ten short years (1985–1994), active involvement in community organizations fell 45%
- **By this measure, nearly half of America's civic infrastructure obliterated in barely a decade**

### Club Meeting Attendance

- **DDB Needham Life Style surveys (1975–1999)**: Eighty-seven thousand+ Americans asked, "How many times in the last year did you attend a club meeting?"
- **Figure 11 shows form of civic engagement dwindled over last quarter of 20th century**

**1975–76 data**:
- Americans attended **twelve club meetings on average each year**—essentially once a month
- **64% of all Americans attended at least *one* club meeting in previous year**

**1999 data**:
- Figure shrunk by fully **58% to five club meetings per year**
- **38% attended at least one club meeting**

> "In short, in the mid-1970s nearly two-thirds of all Americans attended club meetings, but by the late 1990s nearly two-thirds of all Americans *never* do."

- **By comparison with other countries**: May still seem nation of joiners
- **By comparison with own recent past**: Are not—at least if "joining" means more than nominal affiliation

## Time Diary Evidence: Organizational Involvement Declining

### Remarkable Consistency

- **Two different survey archives** suggest active involvement in local clubs/organizations of all sorts fell by more than half in last several decades of 20th century
- **Estimate remarkably consistent with evidence of entirely unexpected sort**

### Time Diaries (1965–1995)

- **Each decade national samples asked to complete "time diaries"**: Recording how they spent every minute of randomly chosen "diary day"
- **Can reconstruct how average American's use of time gradually evolved** over three decades (1965–1995)

### Time Allocation Findings (John Robinson, director)

- **Broadly speaking, time allocations not changed dramatically over this period**: Averaged just about exactly eight hours of sleep a night throughout decades
- **Important exceptions**:
  - **Watching TV consumes more time now**
  - **Spend less time now on housework and child care**
  - **Slice of time devoted to organizational activity always been relatively modest**: Even faithful reading groups/service clubs usually meet only once a week or once a month, not once a day
- **Nevertheless, diaries show clearly**: Time we devote to community organizations has fallen steadily over this period

### Measured in Hours per Month

- **Average American's investment in organizational life** (apart from religious groups, examined separately): Fell from **3.7 hours/month (1965)** to **2.9 hours (1975)** to **2.3 hours (1985 and 1995)**
- **Average day 1965**: 7% of Americans spent some time in a community organization
- **Average day 1995**: 3% of all Americans
- **Nearly half of all Americans in 1960s invested some time each week** in clubs and local associations
- **Less than one-quarter in 1990s**
- **Further analysis**: Decline attributable to **generational replacement**—members of any given generation investing as much time in organizational activity as they ever were, but each successive generation investing less

### Adjusted for Educational Levels

- **If we account for rapid growth in educational levels over this period**: All slumps in associational involvement (leadership involvement, meeting attendance, time spent, etc.) even more dramatic
- **Among burgeoning numbers of college graduates**: Average number of club meetings per year fell **55%** (from thirteen meetings/year to six)
<!-- pp. 61-80 -->

### Summary: Organizational Decline (continued)

- Decline in organizational activity roughly equal across all educational levels—but relative decline greater at bottom of hierarchy since less educated were less involved to begin with
- If current rate continues, clubs would become extinct in less than 20 years
- Four independent data streams converge on estimate: active involvement in local organizations fell by more than half in last several decades of 20th century

### Consumer Spending Evidence

- **Leisure dollar metric**: 1929, 6 cents of every consumer leisure dollar went to club/fraternal dues
- Post-WWII dip to 4 cents (TV arrival), recovery to 5 cents by end of 1950s
- During last three decades: fell from 5 cents to 3 cents
- By 1997, measure of relative priority for organizational commitments down 40% from postwar peak in 1958

### Organizational Membership Trends

- First two-thirds of 20th century: Americans' involvement in civic associations rose steadily (except Great Depression)
- Last third: only mailing list membership expanded—creation of "tertiary" associations whose members never meet
- **Face-to-face involvement plummeted** across all data sources (organizational records, surveys, time diaries, consumer expenditures)
- Formal membership in organizations edged down 10-20% in last third of century
- **Active involvement collapsed** at astonishing rate, more than halving most participation indexes in few decades

### The Paradox

- Many Americans claim to be "members" but no longer spend time in organizations
- Stopped doing committee work, stopped serving as officers, stopped attending meetings
- Despite rapid increases in education giving more people skills/resources/interests for civic engagement
- Americans dropping out of community life generally, not just political life

### Next Domains to Examine

- Religion and work—two extremely important sectors that occupy central place in many American lives
- Trends in these domains will significantly affect collective stock of social capital

## Chapter 4: Religious Participation

### America's Religious Exceptionalism

- US is one of most religiously observant countries in contemporary world
- Most God-believing, religion-adhering, fundamentalist, and religiously fecund country—more new religions born than any other society
- **Tocqueville** commented at length on Americans' religiosity
- **Phillip Hammond** (religious historian): "ever since nation's founding, a higher proportion of Americans have affiliated with church or synagogue—right through 1950s"
- Religious adherence grew steadily from 17% (1776) to 62% (1980)
- Other scholars argue church "membership" became less stringent over time—participation in congregations probably remained relatively constant (35-40% for past 300 years)

### Churches as Social Capital Repositories

- **"The church is people"** (Reverend Craig McMullen, Dorchester Temple Baptist Church, Boston)—relationships, not buildings
- Nearly half of all associational memberships are church-related
- Half of all personal philanthropy is religious
- Half of all volunteering occurs in religious context
- Religious institutions support wide range of activities: Social Service Training, AIDS Awareness, Ecology Task Force, Narcotics Anonymous, Business/Professional Women's Club, martial arts classes, bowling alleys (Garden Grove Crystal Cathedral)

### Civic Skills and Recruitment

- Churches provide incubator for civic skills, norms, community interests, and recruitment
- Religiously active people learn to give speeches, run meetings, manage disagreements, bear administrative responsibility
- They befriend others who recruit them into other community activity
- **Churchgoers substantially more likely** to be involved in secular organizations, vote, participate politically, have deeper informal social connections

### Religious Involvement and Social Capital

- Regular worshipers much more likely to visit friends, entertain at home, attend club meetings, belong to various groups
- **Religiosity rivals education** as powerful correlate of civic engagement
- In survey asking people to enumerate daily personal encounters: religious attendance most powerful predictor of number of encounters
- Regular church attendees reported talking with 40% more people daily

### Philanthropy and Volunteering

- 75-80% of church members give to charity vs. 55-60% of nonmembers
- 50-60% of church members volunteer vs. 30-35% of nonmembers
- Religious adherents more likely to contribute time/money to activities beyond their own congregation
- Even excluding religious causes, active involvement in religious organizations among strongest predictors of both philanthropy and volunteering

### Link Between Religion and Altruism

- **Kenneth Wald** (close student of religion): "Religious ideals are potentially powerful sources of commitment and motivation"—people make enormous sacrifices if they believe driven by divine force
- But social ties in religious communities at least as important as religious beliefs per se in accounting for volunteerism and philanthropy
- Connectedness, not just faith, responsible for beneficence of church people

### Social Services Provided by Churches

- American religious communities spend roughly $15-20 billion annually on social services
- Nationwide 1998: nearly 60% of all congregations (higher proportion of larger congregations) contribute to social service, community development, or neighborhood organizing
- 33% of churchgoers support food programs for hungry
- 18% support housing programs like Habitat for Humanity
- **Partners for Sacred Places**: 93% of older urban congregations provide community services (food pantries, self-help groups, recreational programs), 80% of beneficiaries not congregation members

### Churches and Social Movements

- **Black churches** especially prominent in rebuilding inner-city communities (Boston 10-Point Coalition)
- Most successful model for grassroots community organizing—**Industrial Areas Foundation**—rooted institutionally in local parishes and congregations
- Churches provided organizational/philosophical bases throughout American history: abolition, temperance (19th century), civil rights, right-to-life (20th century)

> **On civil rights movement**: "[T]he Black church functioned as the institutional center of the modern civil rights movement.... Churches provided the movement with an organized mass base; a leadership of clergymen largely economically independent of the larger white society and skilled in the art of managing people and resources; an institutionalized financial base through which protest was financed; and meeting places where the masses planned tactics and strategies and collectively committed themselves to the struggle."

- **C. Eric Lincoln** (sociologist of religion): Black church in role as lyceum, conservatory, forum, social service center, political academy, financial institution "has been and is for Black America the mother of our culture, the champion of our Freedom, and hallmark of our civilization"

### Religious Involvement and Civic Engagement

- Religious involvement crucial dimension of civic engagement
- Trends in civic engagement closely tied to changing patterns of religious involvement

### Stability of Religious Beliefs

- Americans' religious commitment reasonably stable over last half century by yardstick of personal beliefs
- Virtually all Americans say they believe in God, three out of four believe in immortality
- Gallup poll: responses about "how important religion is in [their] life" suggest only modest slippage over decades
- However: "Unless religious impulses find a home in the individual heart or soul, they will have few long-lasting public consequences"

### Trends in Religious Behavior: The Debate

- Classical sociological theory of **secularization**: as society becomes modern, it becomes more secular
- Fits Western Europe reasonably well, but many 1950s/1960s observers doubted fit for America
- In recent years: continuing vitality of religion in America "rediscovered" by academic specialists
- By century's end: "Scholars have had it with talk of secularization. They earn their spurs by telling what's good about churches"
- Important to weigh conflicting evidence about trends in participation in religious institutions over last half century

### Church Membership Trends

- Both sides agree church membership very likely at all-time high in 1950s
- Both discern "modest market correction" (falloff in religious observance) in 1960s/early 1970s
- Trends over last quarter century more controversial due to uncertainties about reliability of denominational membership figures
- Membership figures debatable because: denominations vary in strictness of definition, only irregularly updated, self-reports may be inflated, not all churches keep accurate records
- Poll data generally record higher membership figures than ecclesiastical records (many lapsed members continue to identify as Presbyterian, Jewish, Catholic)

### Church Membership Data (Figure 12)

- Survey evidence and denominational reports generally consistent: rise in church membership from 1930s to about 1960, followed by plateau, then long slow slump of roughly 10% between 1960s and 1990s
- Percentage of Americans identifying as having "no religion" risen steadily and sharply from 2% (1967) to 11% (1990s)

### Church Attendance Trends

- Need to go beyond formal membership to actual participation
- Five independent survey archives covering last half century generally agree: roughly 40-45% of Americans claim to have attended religious services in any given week over these five decades
- Earliest surveys show sharp rise of 15-20% in church attendance rate from 1950s to 1960s
- Decline of same magnitude by early 1970s
- Five archives diverge after 1975, but most reasonable summary: attendance has declined—modestly but unmistakably—by roughly 10-12% over last quarter century
- Slump more marked in second half of period (mid-1980s to mid-1990s)

### Church Attendance Consolidation (Figure 13)

- Sharp rise in church attendance in first decades after WWII
- Decline of roughly one-third between late 1950s and late 1990s, with more than half of total decline occurring in 1960s

### Overreporting of Church Attendance

- Skeptical sociologists begun to question whether Americans really as religiously observant as surveys suggest
- Careful comparisons with actual counts of parishioners suggest many "misremember" whether they actually made it to services last week
- Estimates of overreporting range as high as 50%
- Some scholars believe rate of overreporting actually higher today than generation ago—if so, survey evidence may underestimate falloff in actual church attendance
- **Participation in organized worship services probably lower today than 25 years ago and surely lower than 40 years ago**

### Decline in Church-Related Social Activities

- Americans' involvement in social life of church beyond worship itself—Sunday schools, Bible study groups, "church socials"—fallen at least as fast as church membership and attendance
- 1950s: roughly one in four Americans reported membership in church-related groups apart from church membership itself
- Late 1980s/1990s: figure cut in half to roughly one in eight
- University of Michigan-NORC study: 50% decline in membership in church-related groups between 1957 and 1976
- General Social Survey: between 1974 and 1996, membership in church-related groups fell by at least 20%
- **Americans' involvement in social life of religious institutions apart from formal worship services has fallen, probably by one-third since 1960s and by one-half or more since 1950s**

### Time Diary Evidence

- Time diaries from 1965, 1975, 1985, and 1995 fully confirm decline
- Americans in 1995 devoted on average only two-thirds as much time to religion (both worship and religiously related social activities) as in 1965
- Steady decline from 1 hour 37 minutes per week (1965) to 1 hour 7 minutes (1995)
- Not that sermons getting shorter—fraction of population that spent any time on religion at all fell by nearly one-half

### Summary: Three to Four Decades of Decline

- Over last 3-4 decades: Americans become about 10% less likely to claim church membership
- Actual attendance and involvement in religious activities fallen by roughly 25-50%
- Virtually all postwar boom in religious participation—and perhaps more—has been erased
- Broad historical pattern: up from first third of century to 1960s, then down from 1960s to 1990s
- Same pattern noted for secular community-based organizations and political participation

### Forms of Involvement

- In all three cases (politics, community organizations, religion), more demanding form of involvement—actual attendance vs. formal membership—greater the decline
- Seen from without, institutional edifice appears virtually intact—little decline in professions of faith, formal membership down just a bit
- When examined more closely: decay has consumed load-bearing beams of civic infrastructure

### Generational Differences

- Decline largely attributable to generational differences
- Any given cohort seems not to have reduced religious observance over years, but more recent generations less observant than their parents
- Slow but inexorable replacement of one generation by next has gradually but inevitably lowered national involvement in religious activities

### Life Cycle Pattern in Religiosity

- Marriage and children encourage greater involvement in church activities
- Middle-aged and older people (more conscious of mortality) seem more drawn to religion than younger people
- To detect significant long-run change: must compare rates of religious participation among people of same age at different eras
- If younger people today less observant than people their age used to be, then even if today's young people gradually become more religiously involved as they age, they may never catch up with pace of predecessors
- Aggregate level of religious engagement in society will tend to fall over time

### Church Attendance by Age Group (1970s-1990s)

- Church attendance among people under sixty dropped by roughly 10-20%
- Church attendance among people sixty and over increased slightly
- Modest increase in religious involvement among oldest generation (born 1930s or earlier) not enough to counterbalance declining involvement of children and grandchildren

### The Baby Boomer Pattern

- When boomers in twenties (1960s and 1970s), more disaffected from religious institutions than their predecessors
- As boomers married, had children, settled down: tended to become more involved with organized religion, just as their parents had
- But boomers began this life cycle move toward church at much lower level of religious involvement and have never closed the gap
- Even now, in their forties and fifties, boomers remain less religiously involved than middle-aged people were generation ago
- **Wade Clark Roof** estimate: two-thirds of all boomers reared in religious tradition dropped out, something less than half have returned
- As boomers' more religious parents depart from scene, average level of religious engagement continues to decline

### Wade Clark Roof and William McKinney on Baby Boomers

> "Large numbers of young, well-educated, middle-class youth... defected from the churches in the late sixties and the seventies.... Some joined new religious movements, others sought personal enlightenment through various spiritual therapies and disciplines, but most simply 'dropped out' of organized religion altogether.... [The consequence was a] tendency toward highly individualized religious psychology without the benefits of strong supportive attachments to believing communities. A major impetus in this direction in the post-1960s was the thrust toward greater personal fulfillment and quest for the ideal self.... In this climate of expressive individualism, religion tends to become 'privatized,' or more anchored in the personal realms."

### Privatized Religion and Social Capital

- **Privatized religion** may be morally compelling and psychically fulfilling, but it embodies less social capital
- More people "surfing" from congregation to congregation more frequently—less committed to particular community of believers
- Last several decades witnessed flourishing of publicity about various cult groups (transcendental meditation to Unification Church of Reverend Moon)
- Careful studies show none of these movements attracted enduring American membership of more than few thousand—infinitesimal fraction in adult population of 200 million
- Even for those who remain religiously inclined: "privatized religion knows little of communal support, and exists by and large independent of institutionalized religious forms; it may provide meaning to the believer and personal orientation, but it is not a shared faith, and thus not likely to inspire strong group involvement.... 'Believers' perhaps, but 'belongers,' not."

### Defense of Privatized Religion

- Not argument that privatized religion morally/theologically frivolous, or that inherited religious traditions inherently superior
- **Stephen Warner** (admirer of freer market for self-determined religious affiliation): "There is considerable evidence that religious switchers are morally serious"
- But by most accounts: "the big 'winner' in the switching game is the growing secular constituency"

### Social Revolution of 1960s and 1970s

- **Phillip Hammond** (survey of churchgoers in North Carolina, Massachusetts, Ohio, California): "The social revolution of the 1960s and 1970s accelerated the shifting balance between [the collective and individual role of the church], doing so by greatly escalating a phenomenon we will call 'personal autonomy.' Personal autonomy thus has not only led to a decline in parish involvement ... but it has also led to an alteration in the meaning of that involvement."
- Active involvement in life of parish depends heavily on degree to which person linked to broader social context—having friends in parish, in neighborhood, at work, being part of closely knit personal network
- Supporting beams for religiously based social involvement weakened in recent decades
- **Bottom line**: While for many boomers privatized religion worthy expression of autonomous moral judgment, institutionalized religion less central to their lives than to their parents' lives

### Generation X and Future Trends

- Religious orientations of Generation X strongly suggest long-run ratcheting down of religious involvement has not yet run its course
- For more than three decades college freshmen filled out standard questionnaire about senior year in high school
- Boomers entering college in 1966: 9% said they "never" attended church services
- Late 1990s, when boomers' children filling out questionnaire: index of complete disengagement from organized religion doubled to 18%
- Fraction of college freshmen who avowed "none" as religious preference doubled from 7% (1966) to 14% (1997)
- Another rigorous series of annual surveys: fraction of high schoolers who attend church services every week fell from 40% (late 1970s) to 32% (early 1990s)

### Generalization Caveats

- Oversimplification in at least two important respects:

1. **Not everyone affected equally**: While one group of Americans withdrawn from active involvement in faith-based communities, another group as fully involved as ever
   - Fraction of population entirely disconnected from organized religion increased
   - Fraction intensely involved relatively stable
   - Result: country becoming ever more clearly divided into two groups—devoutly observant and entirely unchurched
   - Some might see parallel to trends in politics—more true believers, more dropouts, fewer moderates
   - Sociological substratum underlies "culture wars" of recent years
   - Although polarization shouldn't be exaggerated, may have regional dimension: religious disengagement most marked in North (especially Northeast) and most limited in southern Bible Belt

2. **Pace and direction of change varied among denominations**: Protestant and Jewish congregations lost market share in membership, while Catholics and other religions gained
   - Since WWII: percentage of Protestants in US population fallen by roughly 3 to 6 percentage points per decade, decline roughly one-quarter overall
   - Percentage of Jews fallen by about 0.5 percentage point per decade, decline roughly half overall
   - By contrast: Catholic share of population risen by 1 to 1.5 percentage points per decade, increase roughly one-third overall
   - "No religion" rose by about 2 percentage points per decade, roughly quadrupling
   - Fraction of US population that claimed to be Protestant fell by 12 to 15 percentage points (nearly one-fifth) in last third of 20th century, probably sharpest such decline in US history

### Immigration Effects

- Divergent growth rates influenced by immigration from Latin America for Catholics and from Asia for other religions
- Hispanics now constitute one-quarter of American Catholics
- Catholic Church once again playing important role in connecting immigrants to broader American society, contributing to social capital formation
- But new influx only partially conceals degree to which native-born Americans becoming less involved in church

### Protestant Denominational Shifts

- Shifts even more marked within broad family of Protestant denominations
- Over last 40 years: mainline denominations (Methodist, Presbyterian, Episcopal, Lutheran, Congregational, American Baptist, etc.) heavily lost "market share"
- Evangelical and fundamentalist groups (Southern Baptist, Pentecostal, Holiness, Assemblies of God, Church of God in Christ, Jehovah's Witnesses, Mormons, independent congregations) continued to grow
- Sometimes at pace slower than before, now barely matching national population growth
- While mainline Protestantism still significant part of religious landscape: congregations dwindling, aging, less involved in religious activities
- Fraction of all church members who belong to evangelical churches risen—probably by roughly one-third in quarter century after 1960
- But for Protestants as whole: evangelical gains not enough to offset mainline losses
- Growth occurred at both ends of religious spectrum: most orthodox and most secular, while middle has collapsed

### Church Attendance by Denomination

- While numbers of self-identified Catholics continued to grow, traditionally high Catholic rate of observance (measured by attendance at mass) declined steadily
- Among dwindling number of Protestants: rate of weekly attendance held up reasonably well, in part because of shift among Protestant denominations toward more evangelical congregations
- But since there are fewer self-identified Protestants now: fraction of Americans who attend Protestant worship services regularly has declined significantly over last three to four decades
- In other words: more Catholics becoming merely nominal church members, while large and steadily growing number of Protestants and Jews abandoning their religion entirely

### Declines Among Black Americans

- Declines in religious involvement characterize blacks at least as much as whites
- Even though blacks continue to be more religiously observant than whites
- Decline in church attendance between mid-1970s and mid-1990s nearly as great among blacks as among whites
- Membership losses from church groups slightly greater among blacks
- Among blacks as among whites: mainline Protestant denominations seem to have suffered relative decline, while evangelical congregations surged

### Revitalization of Evangelical Religion

- Perhaps most notable feature of American religious life in last half of 20th century
- Church historians **Roger Finke and Rodney Stark**: this development merely latest reenactment of familiar drama from American religious history
- Insurgent, more disciplined, more sectlike, less "secularized" religious movement overtakes more worldly, establishmentarian denominations
- Methodists did this to Episcopalians in mid-19th century, now fundamentalists done it to Methodists

### Evangelical Churches and Social Capital

- From one perspective: development reinvigorates religion and creates vibrant social capital within new evangelical churches
- Achievements of evangelicals over last several decades in creating energetic religious communities justly admired by religious leaders across spectrum
- Many of most important episodes of social capital formation in American history rooted in religious revivals, may be on cusp of another such period

### Limits of Evangelical Social Capital

- **Wade Clark Roof** observed: "Conservative religious energies are channeled in the direction of recovery of faith *within* the religious tradition and of reaffirmation of religious and life-style boundaries within the dominant culture.... Growing churches and synagogues are usually exclusive in character, capable of drawing both social and religious boundaries."
- Historically: mainline Protestant church people provided disproportionate share of leadership to wider civic community
- Evangelical and Catholic churches put more emphasis on church-centered activities
- **Robert Wuthnow** (reviewing sweep of American history): "whereas the mainline churches participated in progressive social betterment programs during the first half of the twentieth century, evangelical churches focused more on individual piety"

### Evangelical Insularity

- Both individually and congregationally: evangelicals more likely to be involved in activities within their own religious community but less likely to be involved in broader community
- Evangelicals attend church more regularly than mainline Protestants, far more generous philanthropically (giving average 2.8% of family income vs. 1.6%), attend Sunday school and Bible study groups more regularly, have more close friends in same congregation
- **George Marsden**: "The fundamental-ist churches offer far stronger community to their members than do their moderate-liberal Protestant counterparts.... [They] are some of the most cohesive non-ethnic communities in America"

### Social Capital Investment

- Social capital of evangelicals invested at home more than in wider community
- Among evangelicals: church attendance is *not* correlated with membership in community organizations
- Exceptions exist (Charles Colson's Prison Fellowship Ministries works across denominational and racial lines in 600 prisons nationwide to restore inmates to membership in community)
- Most evangelical volunteering supports religious life of congregation itself—teaching Sunday school, singing in choir, ushering at worship services—but does not extend to broader community as much as volunteering by members of other faiths

### Mainline vs. Evangelical Civic Engagement

- Today's mainline Protestants and Catholics more likely to be involved in volunteering and service in wider community
- Among mainline Protestants, and to lesser extent Catholics: church attendance less closely tied to religious volunteering but more closely tied to secular volunteering
- In these faiths: church attendance correlated with membership and indeed leadership in secular groups
- In both evangelical and mainline congregations: religiously involved learn transferable civic skills (management and public speaking)
- But mainline Protestants more likely to transfer them to wider community
- **Robert Wuthnow** concludes: "Mainline Protestant churches encourage civic engagement in the wider community, whereas evangelical churches apparently do not"

### Conservative vs. Liberal Congregations

- Same contrast appears at congregational level
- Self-described conservative congregations less likely than liberal or moderate congregations to offer social outreach services or programs
- Notable exception: right-to-life activities
- (Political participation of evangelical Christians examined more closely in chapter 9)
- During civil rights era: black civic engagement positively correlated with involvement in mainline black churches, but negatively associated with involvement in black fundamentalist denominations
- Fact that evangelical Christianity rising and mainline Christianity falling means religion less effective now as foundation for civic engagement and "bridging" social capital

### Wuthnow on Religion's Role

> "Religion may have a salutary effect on civil society by encouraging its members to worship, to spend time with their families, and to learn the moral lessons embedded in religious traditions. But religion is likely to have a diminished impact on society if that is the only role it plays. What interested Tocqueville about voluntary organizations was…their ability to forge connections across large segments of the population, spanning communities and regions, and drawing together people from different ethnic backgrounds and occupations."

- It is that broader civic role that, with few exceptions, evangelical religion has not yet come to play in contemporary America

### Summary: Religious Entry in Social Capital Ledger

1. Religion is today, as it has traditionally been, a central fount of American community life and health
   - Faith-based organizations serve civic life both directly (providing social support to members and social services to wider community) and indirectly (nurturing civic skills, inculcating moral values, encouraging altruism, fostering civic recruitment among church people)

2. Broad oscillations in religious participation during 20th century mirror trends in secular civic life
   - Flowering during first six decades of century, especially in two decades after WWII
   - Then fading over last 3-4 decades
   - As in secular life: more intense form of involvement, greater recent decline
   - Though minority of population continues to find demanding denominations especially appealing
   - Moreover, as in politics and society generally: disengagement appears tied to generational succession
   - For most part younger generations ("younger" here includes boomers) less involved both in religious and in secular social activities than were predecessors at same age

3. American religious life over this period has also reenacted historically familiar drama by which more dynamic and demanding forms of faith have surged to supplant more mundane forms
   - At least so far: community-building efforts of new denominations directed inward rather than outward, thus limiting their otherwise salutary effects on America's stock of social capital
   - In short, as 21st century opens: Americans going to church less often than three or four decades ago, and churches we go to are less engaged with wider community
   - Trends in religious life reinforce rather than counterbalance ominous plunge in social connectedness in secular community

<!-- pp. 81-100 -->

## Union Membership Decline

### Structural vs. Demand Factors

- Economic shift from industrial to service economy explains only **one-quarter** of union decline
- All structural changes (industry mix, women's employment, regional shifts) account for **barely half** of total decline
- Within specific jobs and industries, unionization fell sharply across the board:
  - Manufacturing: -62%
  - Mining: -79%
  - Construction: -78%
  - Transportation: -60%
  - Service sector: -40%
- Only government employment briefly resisted (1962-79 surge after Kennedy administration legalized collective bargaining for executive branch)
- Public sector unionization has stagnated since late 1970s

### Decline in Demand for Union Membership

- Comprehensive study concluded "virtually all the decline in unionization between 1977 and 1991 seems to be due to decline in demand for union representation"—fewer workers want to join
- **Not primarily** about public disgust at union corruption/featherbedding (public resentment has declined steadily for two decades while membership continued falling)
- Public resentment may be a **consequence** of union power, not a cause of continuing decline
- Core issue: skepticism about the idea of **"membership"** itself, not just "union"

> "The young worker thinks primarily of himself. We are experiencing the cult of the individual, and labor is taking a beating preaching the comfort of coalition." — **Peter Pestillo**, labor economist (two decades ago)

## Professional Associations: A Parallel Pattern

### Initial Growth Appearance

- Professional association membership rates **doubled** over last four decades (1950s-1990s: 8-10% → 16-20%)
- General population membership rose from 13% (1974) to 18% (1994)—nearly 50% increase in two decades
- Major organizations showed explosive growth:
  - **American Medical Association**: 126,042 (1945) → 296,637 (1995)
  - **American Institute of Architects**: 8,500 (1950) → 23,300 (1970) → 47,271 (1997)
  - **American Society of Mechanical Engineers**: 19,688 (1945) → 53,810 (1968) → 107,383 (1997)
  - **Institute of Electrical and Electronic Engineers**: 111,610 (1963) → 242,800 (1997)
  - **American Bar Association**: 34,134 (1945) → 118,916 (1965) → 357,933 (1991)

### The Market Share Decline (Figure 15)

- **Critical insight**: Must compare membership to total professionals in each field
- **First two-thirds of 20th century**: Sharp, steady rise in membership rates (typically 5-10% → 50-90% by 1960s)
- **Same postwar acceleration** (1940s-1960s) seen in community and religious organizations
- Membership rates roughly **doubled between 1945-1965**

### Peak and Reversal by Profession

- **AMA**: peaked 1959
- **American Dental Association/American Institute of Architects**: both peaked 1970
- **ABA**: peaked 1977
- **American Institute of Certified Public Accountants**: peaked 1993
- **American Nurses Association**: 190,000 to 175,000 (1977-1998) despite RNs doubling from 1M → 2M; "market share" cut in half (18% → 9%)
- **ASME**: postwar boom ended by 1950s, never regained pre-Depression peak
- **IEEE**: formed 1963 from merger of two rapidly growing organizations, but market share decline began at birth

### Growth Masked by Professional Expansion

- Downturn in membership rates after 1970 initially masked by rapid growth in national pool of professionals
- Even with declining catch rates, fishing was still very good
- Example: American Institute of Architects membership more than doubled (1970-1997), but fraction of architects who were members fell from 41% → 28%
- IEEE membership more than doubled (1963-1997) despite "market share" falling from 51% → 37%

### Leadership Recognition and Response

- Association leadership gradually noticed declining membership rates
- Eventually relative decline turned into absolute decline despite professions continuing to grow
- Leadership began discussing causes: excessive dues, stale programs, competing specialized associations
- Hypothesis: As professions became bigger and more complex, members shifted interests from general professional identity (medicine) to specialized subfields (perinatal anesthesiology, intellectual property bar)
- Initial evidence doesn't support specialization hypothesis—even specialized groups like American College of Surgeons and American Society of Anesthesiology experienced stagnating/declining membership

### Exception Proves the Rule

- While absolute number of Americans in professional associations has grown significantly over thirty years, this is the **singular exception** to general pattern of declining membership
- Even professional associations follow the **same pattern** of growth in sociability during first two-thirds of century, followed by sudden stagnation and decline during last third
- Leaves aside whether membership in unions and professional associations today means active participation in local chapters as it once did

## The Workplace Hypothesis

### Shift from Residence to Workplace Networks

- **Social capital** in formal employee organizations has not increased to offset declines in political, civic, and religious organizational activity
- Subtle shift: residence-based → workplace-based networks; locational communities → vocational communities
- More Americans working outside home than a generation ago (67% in 1997 vs. 59% in 1950)
- Hypothesis: Simply transferred friendships, civic discussions, community ties from front porch to water cooler

### Anecdotal Support

- **Alan Wolfe** interviews with middle-class suburbanites (1995-96):
  - **Jeremy Toole** (Cobb County, GA): "These days people get about 90 percent of their social connections from the workplace"
  - **Diana Hamilton** (Sand Springs, OK): "People's lives revolve around their work. They make their friends at work, they do their community service through work"
  - **Elizabeth Tyler** (Brookline, MA): "I feel very much like I belong to a community of work... to a community with my own office, with my own company, within my own industry"

### Historical Context of Work-Life Integration

- Industrial Revolution began separating place of work from place of residence
- More time spent in factories and offices away from home
- By end of 20th century: more Americans in labor force than ever before
- Professionals and blue-collar workers alike: long hours together, eating together, traveling together, arriving early, staying late
- More divorces, later marriages, more living alone in unprecedented numbers
- **Arlie Russell Hochschild**: Workplace increasingly serves as **sanctuary** from stresses of marriage, children, housework

> "As more Americans spend more of their time 'at work,'" hypothesizes one observer, "work gradually becomes less of a one-dimensional activity and assumes more of the concerns and activities of both private (family) and public (social and political) life."

### 1980s-1990s Management Trends

- "Total quality management," "quality circles," "team building" became dominant themes
- Books: *The Search for Meaning in the Workplace*, *Creating Community Anywhere*, *Business as a Calling*
- Urged executives to "establish within the firm a sense of community and respect for the dignity of persons"
- By 1992: 55% of business establishments had teams (41% for majority of core workers), 41% had "quality circles"
- Office design began configuring workplace to bolster employees' sense of connectedness
- Evocative labels: "watering holes," "conversation pits," "campfires"
- **Hochschild**: "New management techniques so pervasive in corporate life have helped transform the workplace into a more appreciative, personal sort of social world"

### Evidence of Workplace Social Capital

- Modern workplace encourages regular collaborative contacts—ideal for social capital creation
- Many form rewarding friendships, feel sense of community, enjoy norms of mutual help and reciprocity
- **Families and Work Institute surveys (1990s)**: Nine out of ten workers agree "I look forward to being with the people I work with each day" and "I feel I'm really part of the group of people I work with"
- About half of all workers have at least one close personal tie at work
- **1997 survey**: Just over half of all conversations took place in workplace; when just working adults considered, fraction jumped to more than two-thirds
- Many have close personal connections at work
- Broader benefit: Workplace much more diverse racially and politically than most other social settings

### Three Major Counterarguments

#### 1. No Evidence of Increase

- **No evidence whatever** that socializing in workplace has actually **increased** over last several decades
- Of all domains of social/community connectedness surveyed, systematic long-term evidence on workplace-based connections has proven most difficult to find
- Many today have friends at work, but unclear if more likely than parents' generation
- Some indirect evidence discussed later suggests trend in **opposite direction**

#### 2. Glass Half-Empty

- Social connectedness in workplace might be described as **glass half-empty**, not merely half-full
- Most studies find co-workers account for **less than 10% of our friends**
- Workplace ties tend to be casual and enjoyable, but **not intimate and deeply supportive**
- Most careful study: When asked to list closest friends, less than half of full-time workers put even one co-worker on list
- On average, neighbors more likely to appear than coworkers
- When asked whom they would turn to discuss "important matters," less than half listed even a single co-worker
- Though most who work outside home have acquaintances among workmates, for only a **small minority** does workplace account for most close personal ties
- Americans' most important personal networks are **not** centered mainly in workplace

#### 3. Workplace Restructuring Damages Social Ties

- Several important trends in American workplace over last decade or two have been **damaging** to social ties
- Nature of implicit employment contract transformed during 1980s-1990s by downsizing, "right sizing," "reengineering," and other economic restructuring
- During 1980s: Layoffs and job uncertainty grew primarily from business cycle
- During 1990s: Restructuring became regular management tool even during prosperous times
- One 1993 study: Even in boom year of 1993-94, nearly half of all firms laid off workers (big cuts, averaging 10% of each company's workforce)
- Old employment contract not in writing but was central organizing principle of employee-management relations and understood by all

> "World War II veterans joining IBM were instructed to consult with their wives before taking the job, because 'once you came aboard you were a member of the corporate family for life.'"

- Half century later: Increased competition in global marketplace, improved information technology, greater focus on short-term financial returns, new management techniques combined to make virtually all jobs more "contingent"
- Fastest-growing industries in 1980s: **"outplacement" services** (revenues grew from $35M in 1980 → $350M in 1989)
- **Peter Cappelli** summarizes research on changing employment practices, particularly among white-collar workers: "The old employment system of secure, lifetime jobs with predictable advancement and stable pay is dead"

### Impact on Trust and Social Connectedness

- One consequence: Increased employee anxiety
- More independence from firm, flatter hierarchies, less paternalism, more reward for merit and creativity have been good for many firms and employees
- Even when corporate morale and employee commitment badly damaged, corporate productivity often improved
- **Purpose**: Evaluate impact on **trust and social connectedness** in workplace, not economic consequences
- **Balance sheet is negative**

#### Employee Reactions to Restructuring

- **Charles Heckscher** interviews with white-collar workers in firms undergoing restructuring:
  - Most common reaction: "Put your head down," focusing more narrowly on one's own job
  - Workers whose jobs spared often experienced "survivor shock"
  - Some relished independence and greater opportunity afforded to individuals under new system
  - Most middle managers even in successful firms agreed: "We're all alone out here. It's been very stressful"
  - "The reorganization disrupted the network of relationships among people at all levels"
  - Relationships with peers became more distant
  - "Rather than turning on each other, most people drifted apart, becoming more isolated and wanting to be left alone"

#### Impact Beyond the Workplace

- Changed employment contract not good for involvement in broader community
- **Peter Cappelli**:

> "Much of contemporary American society has been built on stable employment relationships characterized by predictable career advancement and steady growth in wages. Long-term individual investments such as home ownership and college educations for children, community ties and the stability they bring, and quality of life outside of work have all been enhanced by reducing risk and uncertainty on the job."

- All undermined by new deal at work
- Workplace remains significant recruiting ground for volunteers (92% of corporate executives encourage employees to become involved in community service)
- Most comprehensive national survey: Fraction recruited by someone at work slipped from 15% (1991) → 12% (1999)
- No doubt firms and work-based volunteer recruiters have good intentions, but **so far**, workplace remains **far less important** than churches and other civic organizations as recruitment networks for volunteerism

### Job Instability Across Workforce

- Not all employees affected by changes in implicit employment contract
- Blue-collar workers have long faced job insecurity recently hitting middle management
- Over last three decades: Job stability at **all educational levels** in American workforce has declined
- Fewer of us remain very long in same job or even same company
- Although job instability remains higher among blue-collar workers, it has **increased much more rapidly** among white-collar workers (growing fraction of workforce, traditionally contributed disproportionately to civic life)
- Trend toward "job churning": Concentrated among men (previously in more stable jobs), but women continue to have much lower job tenure (more likely to move in/out of labor market)
- "Returns to tenure" (wage/salary benefits from seniority) have fallen—more income depends on what we've done recently, less on how long we've been in job
- One consequence of performance-based pay and job security: Increase degree of competition among peers (if only implicitly)
- Teamwork stops feeling so amicable when you are subtly competing with teammates for your livelihood

#### Contingent and Nonstandard Work

- Surprisingly large and growing fraction of American workforce has **"contingent" or "nonstandard" jobs**:
  - Part-time employees
  - Temps
  - "Independent contractors" (consultants)
  - "On-call" workers (substitute teachers, etc.)
- Best recent studies: Nearly **30% of all U.S. workers** fall into this broad category (about one-half part-timers, one-quarter independent contractors)
- Temping and part-time work both appear to be growing
- Many workers in irregular jobs by choice (software programmers, management consultants, parents balancing work and family obligations)—find them rewarding both personally and financially
- Apart from high-status consultants, most people in nonstandard jobs say they would prefer regular, full-time, noncontingent employment

### Impact on Social Ties

- **All** these structural changes in workplace—shorter job tenure, more part-time and temporary jobs, even independent consultancy—**inhibit workplace-based social ties**
- Three-quarters of all independent contractors have no regular work colleagues
- Part-time workers have only two-thirds as many friends from work as full-time workers
- Friendships at work decrease with job instability, even when job changes voluntary
- None of these patterns surprising—successful investment in social capital takes time and concerted effort
- Birds of passage, whether by choice or necessity, generally don't nest
- Implication: Nearly **one-third of all U.S. workers** have jobs that discourage durable social connections, and **that fraction is rising**

### Mixed Forces in Contemporary Work Life

- Some features foster informal workplace social capital:
  - More time at work
  - More emphasis on teamwork
- Other features point in opposite direction:
  - Downsizing
  - Fraying of ties to particular firm
  - Growth of contingent work
- Impact of changing office technology (especially e-mail) harder to evaluate systematically at this point
- General effect of computer-mediated communication on social capital discussed in chapter 9

### Evidence on Long-Term Trends

- Hard evidence on long-term trends in frequency of water-cooler discussions of civic affairs or incidence of close friendships among co-workers is apparently nonexistent
- Weaker form of indirect evidence available through surveys of job satisfaction
- Many studies show social connections with co-workers are strong predictor (some say **strongest single predictor**) of job satisfaction
- People with friends at work are happier at work
- **If** social capital at work has risen significantly in recent decades, presumably that should show up in warmer feelings about work (at least if we control for adverse changes in financial and job security)

#### Job Satisfaction Trends

- **1955 and 1990s Gallup polls**: Asked working Americans, "Which do you enjoy more, the hours when you are on your job, or the hours when you are not on your job?"
  - 1955: 44% preferred hours on job
  - 1999: Barely one-third (16%) felt that way
- According to Roper polls: Proportion of Americans "completely satisfied" with their job fell from 46% (mid-1970s) → 36% (1992)
- Some disaffection traceable to concerns about job security and personal finances
- Even controlling for financial security, **General Social Survey** reveals modest long-term slippage (roughly 10% overall) in job satisfaction between 1972-1998
- Recent surveys suggest many employees chronically angry on the job
- Many researchers believe incivility and aggression in workplace are on the rise
- **Balance of evidence**: Quite apart from material insecurity, American workers certainly no happier in workplace today than a generation ago and probably are less happy
- Evidence hard to square with hypothesis that workplace has become the new locus of Americans' social solidarity and sense of community

### Final Caution on Workplace as Public Square

- Unlike most other domains of sociability, in this area we **lack definitive evidence** one way or the other
- Author's view: Any solution to problem of civic disengagement in contemporary America must include **better integration between our work lives and our community and social lives**
- Final note of skepticism necessary about workplace as new public square for American communities
- In the end, "work" entails time and effort destined to serve **primarily material, not social, ends**
- Work-based networks often used for instrumental purposes, somewhat undercutting their value for community and social purposes

#### Alan Wolfe's Observation

> "Because we form such ties to promote the highly secular activities of getting and spending, friendships and connections developed at work are generally assumed to have a more instrumental character: we use people, and they use us, to solicit more business, advance our careers, sell more products, or demonstrate our popularity.... If so, it follows that even if the decline of civil ties in the neighborhood is being compensated by new ties formed at work, the instrumental character of the latter cannot be an adequate substitute for the loss of the former."

### Employer Control and Surveillance

- At work, our time is our employer's, not our own
- Paid to work, not to build social capital
- Employer has legal right to draw line between work time and personal time
- Court decisions have given employers wide latitude to monitor and control communications in workplace
- Monitoring increasing rapidly, facilitated by ease of intercepting electronic communications
- **1999 American Management Association survey**: Two-thirds of employers record employee voice mail, e-mail, or phone calls, review computer files, or videotape workers
- Such surveillance becoming more common
- Rights of free speech and privacy essential to public deliberation and private solidarity are, to put it mildly, **insecure in the workplace**
- Substantial reforms in public law and private practice would be necessary before water cooler could become equivalent of back fence or town square

### Conclusion

- Most of us nowadays employed
- Most of the time most of us work with other people
- In fundamental sense, workplace is natural site for connecting with others
- **Balance of evidence speaks against** hopeful hypothesis that American social capital has not disappeared but simply moved into workplace
- Americans at beginning of 21st century demonstrably less likely than parents were to join with co-workers in formal associations
- New forces that might foster socializing in workplace counterbalanced by equally new forces that inhibit types of social ties (durable yet flexible, wide-ranging) important to civic life and personal well-being
- For the **one American adult in three who is not employed**, workplace ties are nonexistent
- **The workplace is not the salvation for our fraying civil society**

<!-- pp. 101-120 -->

### Family Dinners and Informal Socializing Decline

- **Family togetherness declining across all forms** (1976-1997, Roper polls of families with children aged 8-17):
  - Vacationing together: 53% → 38%
  - Watching TV together: 54% → 41%
  - Attending religious services together: 38% → 31%
  - "Just sitting and talking" together: 53% → 43%

> "It is hard not to read these figures as evidence of rapidly loosening family bonds."

### The Decline of Schmoozing: Bars, Restaurants, and Social Spaces

- **Going out to bars/nightclubs/taverns declined 40-50%** from mid-1970s to late 1990s (three independent survey series confirm)
- Americans increasingly "staying home in the evening" — *Cheers* has become "a period piece"

**Figure 19**: Family dinner agreement trends show dramatic crossover — "Definitely Agree" plummets from ~50% (1977) to ~33% (1999), while "Disagree" rises from ~17% to ~25%

**Figure 20**: Eating and drinking establishments per 100,000 people (1970-1998):
  - Full-service restaurants: fell by one-quarter
  - Bars and luncheonettes: cut in half
  - Fast-food outlets: doubled

- **Coffee bars (e.g., Minneapolis cappuccino bar hosting discussion groups)** provide new conversational opportunities, but net decline in eating/drinking establishments remains substantial
- Unlike neighborhood bars where "everybody knows your name," fast-food patrons are anonymous — confirms disappearance of **Ray Oldenburg's "great good place"** (hangouts that "get you through the day")
- Americans have chosen to "grab a bite and run rather than sit a while and chat"

### The Collapse of Card Playing

**Card playing as social barometer:**
- **1940 survey**: Playing cards found in 87% of American homes (vs. 83% radios, 36% telephones)
- Mid-20th century: One pack sold *each year* for every two Americans aged 14+

**Figure 21**: Card game sales track civic involvement pattern precisely — steady growth 1890s-1920s, slump during Depression, explosive post-WWII growth, then precipitous decline

**Bridge dominated by 1950s:**
- 1958 estimate: 35 million Americans (nearly one-third of all adults) were bridge players
- Millions belonged to regular card clubs
- 1961 survey (Nebraska): nearly 1 in 5 adults in regular foursomes
- Bridge was a **highly social pastime** — "Mixed doubles" clubs were gendered spaces for informal conversation
- Bridge encouraged conversation beyond the game itself (though "serious" players played in silence)

**Card playing plunged 1981-1999:**
- Mid-1970s: ~40% of adults played monthly (ratio of card players to moviegoers was 4:1)
- 1981-1999: Average frequency dropped from 16x/year to 8x/year
- By 1999: still outdrew movies 4:3, but **gap closing fast**
- At current decline rate, card playing would **disappear entirely in less than two decades**
- 500 million card games played annually, but falling by **25 million games/year**
- If one conversation per ten games: **50 million fewer "microdeliberations" about community affairs annually** vs. two decades ago

**Generational collapse:**
- Average age of American Contract Bridge League members: 64 and rising (1999)
- Decline concentrated among baby boomers and their children
- Card games concentrated in retirement communities — "sociological equivalent of isolated ecological niches where endangered species often make a last stand"
- To 1990s college students, "bridge" sounded as antique as "whist" to their parents

**Figure 22**: Card playing vs. other leisure activities (1975-1999) — card playing drops from ~15x/year to ~7x/year, while video games, casino visits, and movies remain flat or rise modestly

**Substitutes are solitary:**
- Computer/video games, casino gambling provide "spice of chance" but lack social dimension
- Internet-based bridge: players focused "entirely on the game itself, with very little social small talk"
- Microsoft Solitaire players "rarely play in a group"
- Megacasinos feature "acres of lonely 'players' hunched in silence over one-armed bandits"
- Bridge, poker, gin rummy, canasta **not being replaced by equally "schmoozable" leisure activity**

### Other Indicators of Social Withdrawal

**Greeting cards:**
- Sending greeting cards declined 15-20% over last decade or two (both married and single)
- Predates Internet/e-mail by at least a decade
- Represents more than shift from real to virtual greetings
- People send more cards as they age (especially if living alone), boosting sales in aging America
- **At any given age, Americans now send fewer cards than people that age did a generation ago**
- Again: generational differences underlying transformation

**Figure 23**: "Spend a social evening with someone who lives in your neighborhood" (General Social Survey, 1974-1998):
  - Married people: ~30x/year → ~20x/year (one-third decline)
  - Single people: ~50x/year → ~35x/year

- When compared with mid-1950s, **neighborhood ties in 1990s perhaps less than half as strong**
- Average American still socializes with neighbors every couple weeks, but "measurably more feeble now than a generation ago"

**Neighborhood associations:**
- Recent publicity suggests they're more common now; one survey: 1 in 8 adults involved
- However, similar associations were frequent in earlier decades
- *Life* magazine (1960s) ran paean to Americans "satisfying their gregarious urges in countless neighborhood committees"
- **Urban sociologist Barrett A. Lee**: "recent proliferation of social science literature on neighborhood organizations implies that these groups are newcomers to the urban scene. However, even the slightest amount of digging will suffice to correct that misleading impression…. [N]eighborhood organizations first appeared near the end of the last century and were well represented in most large cities prior to the Great Depression."

**Long-term neighborhood studies (Boston to Seattle):**
- Late 20th century neighborhoods occasionally mobilized for *political* purposes
- Organized *social* life at neighborhood level (street carnivals, amateur theatricals, picnics, potlucks, dances, etc.) **much more vibrant in first half of 20th century than in its waning years**

**Neighborhood watch groups:**
- Have become more common over last 20 years, often with immediate impact on reducing crime
- 1998 DOJ survey (12 cities): 11% attended neighborhood watch meeting to help protect from crime (6% in last year)
  - Compare: 14% kept weapon at home, 15% owned guard dog, 41% installed extra locks
- In short: **we invest more in guns, dogs, and locks than in social capital for crime defense**
- Participation in neighborhood watch programs "almost always decays after an initial burst of enthusiasm, unless rooted in neighborhood organization of a more comprehensive sort"
- Crime watch groups may have become more common, but provide **"frail replacement for the vanished social capital of traditional neighborhoods — sociological AstroTurf, suitable only where the real thing won't grow"**

### Time Budget Studies Confirm Decline

**Figure 24**: Informal socializing (time diary studies, 1965-1995):
  - % recording *any* informal socializing on a diary day: 65% (1965) → 39% (1995)
  - Average daily time on informal socializing: 85 minutes (1965) → 57 minutes (1995)
  - **We spent only two-thirds as much time on informal socializing at century's end as we had three decades earlier**

**NPD Group study (1992-1998):**
- Average American spent nearly 15% more time on child/pet care (probably due to "baby echo" — children of baby boomers)
- Roughly 5-7% more time each on personal grooming, entertainment, sleep, exercise, transportation
- **Largest changes: time spent at worship and visiting with friends — both fell by more than 20%**

### Schmoozing Patterns Across Social Categories

- Density of informal social connections varies by category: higher among women than men, higher among young and retired than middle-aged, etc.
- **Level of schmoozing differs, but *trends* downward are very similar in all segments:**
  - Down among both women and men
  - Down in all age categories
  - Down in all social classes
  - Down in all parts of the country
  - Down in big cities, suburbs, and small towns
  - Down among both married couples and single people
- **Informal social connectedness has declined in all parts of American society**

### The Education Paradox in Informal Socializing

- Recall: education is the **strongest predictor of formal community involvement**
- Education expanded sharply over last 20 years, yet formal community involvement is down sharply
- One implication: **without the boost from higher education, formal involvement might have declined even more rapidly**

**Similar paradox in informal social involvement:**
- Schmoozing is higher among single and childless people
- Number of single and childless people rose significantly over last two decades
- **Should have led to *increased* informal social interaction** — opposite of what we found

**As conventional family structures became rarer:**
- We might have expected the real-life equivalent of *Cheers* and *Friends* to replace civic organizations and dinner parties
- **In fact: we witnessed the decline of the latter without compensating increase in the former**
- **Implication: Something else must be even more powerfully depressing the rate of schmoozing** in contemporary America

## Leisure Time Shifts: From Social to Solitary

### Sports Participation Trends

**Sports clubs:**
- General Social Survey: membership grew from 19% (1974-75) to 21% (1993-94)
- However, many studies find participation rates in most sports have **actually fallen in recent decades**
- Population growing, so gross number of participants is growing in some cases
- But as **fraction of population**, participation fell 10-20% over last decade or two in:
  - Softball, tennis, racket games (table tennis), volleyball, football, bicycling
  - Skiing (downhill, cross-country, water), hunting, fishing, camping, canoeing, jogging, swimming

**National Sporting Goods Association, Sporting Goods Manufacturers Association, DDB Needham Life Style studies, National Center for Health Statistics all agree:**
- Nationwide participation in softball **dropped by roughly one-third between mid-1980s and late 1990s**

**New sports vs. traditional sports:**
- New sports: in-line skating, snowboarding (younger), fitness walking, gym activities (health-conscious), golf (senior citizens)
- Most new sports **not as "social" as many traditional athletic activities**
- Most dramatic increases: **"in-home" activities** (treadmills, workout equipment)
- None attracts nearly as many participants as declining traditional sports
- Among team sports, soccer and basketball are up, but **not enough to offset simultaneous falloffs in all other major team sports** (softball, baseball, volleyball, football)
- **Sports participation is modestly but unambiguously down over last decade or so, particularly affecting team and group sports**

### Generational Patterns in Sports

**Declines sharpest among the young, not the aging:**
- Among 20-somethings: average attendance at exercise classes more than halved (8x/year mid-1980s → 3x/year 1998)
- Over same period: attendance doubled among Americans 60+ (2x/year → 4x/year)
- Swimming and health club attendance show same generational discrepancy — down among younger, steady or up among older
- Sports participation (except exercise walking) declines with age, but laid on life cycle pattern is **same generational profile** (down among boomers and X'ers, up among their parents and grandparents) noted earlier for social and political participation
- **Twin trends — rising recreational activity among older generation, falling among younger generation — have been under way since early 1960s**

**Youth sports:**
- Most youth sports seem to have been stagnant or declining over last several decades
- **After exponential increase in youth soccer in 1980s, even participation in that fashionable sport slowed in 1990s**
- Most other major sports suffered significant declines in adolescent participation in recent years
- Important exception: **growth in organized school-based sports for women** (partly due to Title IX requiring equal opportunity for women in federally funded athletic programs)
- But even this major initiative **has not offset the more general decline in formal and informal sports participation among American youth**
- Because of "baby echo" absolute number of participants in many youth sports has risen
- What's relevant: **rates of participation have been declining**

### Fitness and Health Clubs: Not a Social Offset

**Fitness discussed more in 1990s than 1970s:**
- Health clubs "all the rage"
- Could this offset slumps in other forms of social connection?

**Evidence suggests not:**
- All fitness activities combined (apart from walking) **much less common than more prosaic activities of card playing or dinner parties**
- Even with 1990s' bust in card playing and boom in health clubs: **three times as many Americans play cards regularly as visit a health club regularly**
- Only among single, 20-something, college graduates are health club visits more common than card games
- Despite mass media impression: only **1 in 15 American adults** falls into that demographic category
- Even if health clubs offered limitless opportunities for schmoozing (rather than merely staring at a monitor while working out in silence): **growth in health clubs is dwarfed by collapse of less trendy forms of informal connectedness**

**1980s-1990s saw no net gain in number of times average American jogs, attends exercise/aerobic classes, or visits health club:**
- Rise in these years offset by decline in jogging and exercise classes

**Figure 25**: Stagnation in fitness except walking (1970-2000) — health club attendance, exercise classes, jogging all flat around 3-4x/year

**Walking for exercise:**
- More common than all other forms of workout combined
- Increased by about one-third over last decade
- However: increasing popularity due **entirely to fitness boom among older Americans** (precisely the group that has most resisted nationwide decline in connectedness)

**Athletic activity trends reviewed:**
- Down nationwide
- Down even faster among young adults
- Down least (or not at all) among senior citizens
- Visible counterpart: **"obesity epidemic"** sweeping America in recent decades
  - Up nationwide
  - Up even faster among young adults
  - Up least of all among older Americans
- **Fitness is not a domain that has offset the erosion of social capital elsewhere in American society**

### Bowling: The Exception That Proves the Rule

**Bowling holds its own among major sports:**
- Most popular competitive sport in America
- Bowlers outnumber:
  - Joggers, golfers, softball players: more than 2:1
  - Soccer players (including kids): more than 3:1
  - Tennis players or skiers: 4:1
- Despite "retro" image: 1996 even 20-somethings went bowling ~40% more often than in-line skating
- More recently: greater numbers of young people attracted by "cosmic bowling" or "Rock 'N' Bowl" (high-tech combination)
- Participation in all other major sports more highly concentrated among either young men or upper middle class

**Figure 25 shows walking for exercise trend rising, while other fitness metrics remain flat**

**Bowling is solidly middle-American:**
- Common among both men and women
- Common among couples and singles
- Common among working-class and middle-class
- Common among young and old

**Population growth → more bowlers than ever before:**
- But **league bowling has plummeted in last 10-15 years**
- 1980-1993: number of bowlers in America increased 10%
- League bowling decreased by more than 40%

**Figure 26**: The Rise and Decline of League Bowling (1900-2010+):
- Shows century-long pattern matching other forms of social capital examined
- Steady growth from beginning of century (except during Depression and WWII)
- Explosive growth 1945-1965
- Stagnation until 1970s
- Precipitous plunge over last two decades of century
- Peak mid-1960s: 8% of American men, nearly 5% of American women were bowling team members
- Projections: if steady decline continues at pace of last 15 years, **league bowling would vanish entirely within first decade of new century**

**Economic significance:**
- 1996: 91 million Americans bowled at some point during the year — **more than 25% more than voted in 1998 congressional elections**
- Between 2-3% of American adults regularly bowled in leagues (1980s' plunge onward) — though dropping fast
- Decline threatens bowling lane proprietors' livelihood
- According to one of nation's largest bowling lane chains: **league bowlers consume 3x as much beer and pizza as solo bowlers**
- **Money in bowling is in the beer and pizza, not the balls and shoes**
- Broader social significance: **social interaction and even occasionally civic conversations over beer and pizza that solo bowlers forgo**
- Whether bowling beats balloting in most Americans' eyes: **bowling teams illustrate yet another vanishing form of social capital**

### League vs. Solo Bowling: Schmoozing Implications

**Non-league bowling ≠ "bowling alone":**
- Poetic license authorizes this description
- Any observant visitor to bowling alley can confirm: **informal groups outnumber solo bowlers**
- Insofar as informal groups represent schmoozing: fact that participation in bowling has held steady in recent years **actually represents an exception to general diminishment of informal ties**

**However:**
- **League bowling**, by requiring regular participation with diverse set of acquaintances, **did represent a form of sustained social capital not matched by an occasional pickup game**

### Passive Spectatorship Rising

**Americans spending less time *doing* sports, more time *watching* sports:**
- Sports spectatorship rising rapidly — helps explain rapid rise in salaries of professional athletes
- Growth in spectatorship reflects television viewing habits, but also reflected in live attendance
- Adjusted for population growth: **attendance at major sporting events nearly doubled since 1960s**
- Year-to-year fortunes vary with excitement and labor-management relations
- Virtually all major sports have seen growth in per capita attendance over last four decades: professional baseball, basketball, football, hockey, stock-car racing, college football and basketball

**Figure 27**: The Growth of Spectator Sports, 1960-1997 — attendance at major sporting events per 1,000 population rises from ~350 (1960) to ~700 (2000)

**Spectatorship not a dead loss from social capital perspective:**
- Sitting with friends in bleachers for Friday night high school football game might be just as productive of community as sitting across a poker table
- At least for fans of winning teams: sense of shared enthusiasm for common passion can generate certain sense of community
- Long-suffering Red Sox fans know: even shared adversity can build community

**However:**
- Striking that same changing balance between active participation and passive spectatorship found in sphere of sports parallels what we noted earlier in political sphere
- In football, as in politics: **watching a team play is not the same thing as playing on a team**

### Culture: Observing Up, Doing Down

**Similar phenomenon in other spheres of American life:**
- Both popular and high culture: audience growth has generally matched or exceeded population growth
- Surveys suggest steady or even increasing per capita attendance at:
  - Art museums
  - Pop and rock concerts
  - Movies

**1986-1998 cultural trends:**
- Churchgoing: -10%
- Museumgoing: +10%
- Home entertaining: -25%
- Moviegoing: +25%
- Club meeting attendance: -33%
- Pop/rock concert attendance: +33%

**"Doing" culture (as opposed to merely consuming it) has been declining:**
- Town bands, jazz jamming, gathering around the piano — once classic examples of community and social involvement

**Playing musical instruments:**
- Average frequency cut from nearly 6x/year (1976) to barely 3x/year (1999)
- % of Americans who play an instrument at all: fell by fully one-third (30% → 20%) over this period
- Exposure to music lessons dropping in recent generations

**National Association of Music Merchants surveys:**
- Fraction of households in which even one person plays an instrument: fallen steadily from 51% (1978) to 38% (1997)
- We certainly have not lost our taste for *listening* to music — any more than for watching sports
- But **far fewer of us play together**

### Summary: Informal Social Connectedness in Decline

> "When Aristotle observed that man is by nature a political animal, he was almost surely not thinking of schmoozing."

**Nevertheless:**
- Evidence suggests most Americans connect with fellows in myriad informal ways
- Human nature being what it is: unlikely to become hermits

**But:**
- Evidence also suggests that **across very wide range of activities, last several decades have witnessed striking diminution of regular contacts with friends and neighbors**
- We spend less time in conversation over meals
- We exchange visits less often
- We engage less often in leisure activities that encourage casual social interaction
- We spend more time watching (admittedly, some in presence of others)
- We spend less time doing
- We know our neighbors less well
- We see old friends less often

**In short:**
- Not merely "civic" activities that engage us less, but also **informal connecting**
- **Whether this silent withdrawal from social intercourse has affected our propensity to pitch in on common tasks and to show consideration for bystanders is the question to which we turn in the next two chapters**

## Chapter 7: Altruism, Volunteering, and Philanthropy (continued)

### Social Networks Drive Giving and Volunteering

- **Figure 29** shows correlation between social ties and volunteering: people who entertain friends frequently are much more likely to volunteer
- Social connections encourage giving through multiple mechanisms beyond altruistic attitudes
- **"Someone asked me"** is the most common answer for why people volunteer; conversely, **"Nobody asked"** is why blood donors don't give
- Fund-raising = friend-raising: the more involved in social networks, the more likely to be recruited
- **Volunteering fosters more volunteering**: organizational involvement inculcates civic skills and lifelong altruism
  - Youth who volunteered are half again as likely to donate as adults and twice as likely to volunteer later
  - Receiving help makes people more likely to help others — ripple effect
  - Tocqueville: **"the habits of the heart"** — giving, volunteering, and joining are mutually reinforcing

- **Figure 30**: Blood donation fostered by both churchgoing and club attendance
  - Church attenders (2+/month) and club attenders (monthly+) donate at ~16% rate
  - Non-attenders of both donate at ~11% rate

### Trends in Philanthropy: The Rise and Fall, 1929-1998

- **Total charitable giving has risen steadily** in absolute dollars, adjusted for inflation and population
- Per capita giving nearly doubled 1960-1995: $280 → $522 (constant 1993 dollars)

**But growth is misleading** — our income also rose:
- Real per capita spending on flowers/seeds/plants nearly tripled same period
- Real per capita spending on all recreation nearly quadrupled
- **Philanthropy relative to income is dismaying**: in 1990s Americans donated smaller share of income than any time since 1940s

**Figure 31: The Rise and Fall of Philanthropic Generosity**
- First half of 20th century: era of increasing national generosity
- Philanthropy nearly doubled as share of income 1929-1960 (rising ~50% between 1944-1960)
- Beginning 1961: **steady four-decade decline**, entirely erasing postwar gains
- Total giving fell from 2.26% of national income (1964) to 1.61% (1998) — relative fall of 29%
- 1960: gave ~$1 per $2 spent on recreation
- 1997: gave <$.50 per $2 spent on recreation

**Parallel with social capital decline, not economy**:
- During Great Depression (1929-39): income fell 3%, but charity rose 25%+
- Next two decades (1939-60): income soared 74%, charity rose at same slow pace as Depression
- After 1960: through booms and busts of 60s/70s/80s/90s, generosity steadily shriveled
- Brief exception: middle 1980s tax code changes
- **Waxing and waning of generosity tracks social capital, not financial capital**

### Religious and Secular Giving Both Declined

**Figure 32**: Long-term trends in Protestant, Catholic, and United Way giving (all as fraction of national income)
- All three show postwar boom followed by post-1960 plunge

**Protestant giving (1921-1995)**:
- Fell sharply 1960-1972 *per member*
- Protestant membership itself fell throughout period
- Thus Protestant giving as fraction of national income continued falling
- **John and Sylvia Ronsvalle** (church finance scholars): decline not limited to theological spectrum
- Evangelicals give larger fraction of income, but their *per member* contribution fell even faster than mainline Protestants
- **"Benevolences"** (external charity) fell more rapidly (down 38% since 1968) than **"congregational finances"** (down 12% since 1968)
- Growing slice of shrinking pie consumed by internal operations, leaving less for ministering to the world

**Catholic giving (1960-1989)**:
- Religious giving as fraction of income slashed even more dramatically than Protestants
- Fell 59% between 1960-63 and 1988-89

**United Way giving (1920-1997)**:
- Contributions to United Way organizations now less than half the 1960 level
- Reached level not seen since early in century
- "Alternative campaigns" for activist nonprofits in 1980s-90s made little dent in long-term decline

### Self-Reported Giving Declined Too

- Roper and Yankelovich pollsters confirm decline across all walks of life
- **Figure 33**: 1980s first half data vs. mid-1990s
  - Nearly half of Americans reported contributing to charity in previous month (1980s)
  - By prosperous mid-1990s barely one in three reported any charitable contribution in previous month
  - Religious giving "occasionally": fell from >50% to <40%
  - What donors told pollsters squares with reports from recipients

**Material implications if generosity matched 1960 levels**:
- United Way campaigns: +$4 billion/year
- U.S. religious congregations: +$20 billion/year
- Total national philanthropy: +~$50 billion/year

### Why Did Giving Decline?

**Idiosyncratic explanations rejected**:
- Protestant decline linked to inadequate emphasis on "stewardship" among congregational leaders
- Catholic decline attributed to disaffection with church doctrine (birth control, male hegemony)
- United Way decline blamed on 1992 sex-and-embezzlement scandal + competition from "alternative campaigns"

**Actual explanation**: breadth and simultaneity of post-1960 declines suggests wider social change
- Not foibles of particular organizations
- After years of high and rising generosity, **Americans became steadily more tight-fisted over last four decades**
- Precisely when we also disengaged from social life of communities

## Chapter 8: Reciprocity, Honesty, and Trust

### Generalized Reciprocity as Social Capital Touchstone

**David Hume's farmer parable**: mutual labor today/tomorrow depends on confidence and security — both lose harvests without mutual confidence

- **Generalized reciprocity**: I'll do this for you now, without expecting anything immediately in return, confident down the road you or someone else will return the favor
- **Michael Taylor**: individual act combines short-term altruism + long-term self-interest in vague, uncertain expectation of future help
- Reciprocity = series of short-run altruistic acts that together typically make every participant better off

### The Golden Rule and Self-Interest Rightly Understood

- Norm of generalized reciprocity fundamental to civilized life
- All prominent moral codes contain equivalent of Golden Rule
- Ironic perversion: **"Do unto others before they do unto you"** epitomizes self-interested "me decade"
- **Tocqueville**: Americans resisted temptation to take advantage of each other, looked out for neighbors
- American democracy worked not because Americans obeyed impossibly idealistic selflessness, but because they pursued **"self-interest rightly understood"**

**Examples of generalized reciprocity**:
- Raking leaves before they blow onto neighbors' yard
- Lending dime for parking meter
- Buying round of drinks on overtime week
- Keeping eye on friend's house
- Taking turns bringing snacks to Sunday school
- Caring for child of crack-head one flight down

### Reciprocity Reduces Transaction Costs

- Return of favor sometimes immediate/straightforward (neighborhood lawn raking)
- Sometimes long-term/conjectural (benefit of living where people care for neglected children)
- At extreme, generalized reciprocity hard to distinguish from altruism, difficult to cast as self-interest
- Nevertheless: what Tocqueville insightfully meant by "self-interest rightly understood"

**Economic advantages**:
- When we can relax guard, **transaction costs** reduced
- Trusting communities have measurable economic advantage
- Background stress of daily transaction costs (worrying about right change, checking locked door) may explain why life expectancy enhanced in more trustful communities
- Society relying on generalized reciprocity more efficient than distrustful society (same reason money more efficient than barter)
- **Honesty and trust lubricate inevitable frictions of social life**

### Trust Requires Trustworthiness

- "Honesty is the best policy" wise maxim only if others follow same principle
- Social trust valuable community asset if — but only if — it is warranted
- We'll both be better off if honest toward one another than if fearing betrayal we decline to cooperate
- Only seeker of sainthood will be better off being honest in face of persistent dishonesty
- **"Generalized reciprocity is a community asset, but generalized gullibility is not"**
- **Trustworthiness, not simply trust**, is key ingredient

### How to Ensure Good Faith

**Legal system**: courts and law enforcement
- However, if we needed legal advice and police presence for simplest agreement, escalating transaction costs would preclude mutually beneficial cooperation
- **Diego Gambetta** (student of trust and Mafia): "Societies which rely heavily on use of force likely to be less efficient, more costly, and more unpleasant than those where trust maintained by other means"

**Social fabric**: dense networks of social exchange
- Effective norm of generalized reciprocity bolstered by dense networks
- If two would-be collaborators are members of tightly knit community, likely to encounter one another in future — or hear about each other through grapevine
- Reputations at stake worth more than gains from momentary treachery
- **Honesty encouraged by dense social networks**

### Thick Trust vs. Thin Trust

**Thick trust**: embedded in personal relations that are strong, frequent, nested in wider networks
- Trusting Max at corner store because you've known him for years

**Thin trust**: in "the generalized other"
- Your new acquaintance from coffee shop
- Rests implicitly on some background of shared social networks and expectations of reciprocity
- Even more useful than thick trust — extends radius of trust beyond roster of people we can know personally

**As social fabric becomes threadbare**:
- Effectiveness in transmitting and sustaining reputations declines
- Power to undergird norms of honesty, generalized reciprocity, and thin trust is enfeebled

### Social Trust as "Standing Decision"

**Wendy Rahn and John Transue**: "social, or generalized, trust can be viewed as 'standing decision' to give most people — even those whom one does not know from direct experience — the benefit of the doubt"

**Social trust strongly associated with**:
- Many other forms of civic engagement and social capital
- Trusting citizens volunteer more often, contribute more to charity, participate more in politics and community organizations
- Serve more readily on juries, give blood more frequently, comply more fully with tax obligations
- More tolerant of minority views
- Display many other forms of civic virtue

**People more active in community life**:
- Less likely (even in private) to condone cheating on taxes, insurance claims, bank loan forms, employment applications
- **Experimental evidence**: people who believe others are honest are themselves less likely to lie, cheat, or steal; more likely to respect rights of others
- **Honesty, civic engagement, and social trust are mutually reinforcing**

### Declining Perceptions of Honesty and Morality

**Figure 37**: 1952-1998 decline in percent saying people in general lead as good lives (honest and moral) as they used to
- 1952: ~50%
- 1965: ~43%
- 1976: ~32%
- 1998: ~27%

### The Central Question: Trends in Social Trust

- Important diagnostic test for social capital trends: how have reciprocity and social trust evolved?
- Not merely thick trust in people we know intimately, but **thin trust in the anonymous other**
- How are trends in social capital and civic engagement reflected in trends in honesty and social trust in America?

### Measuring Social Trust vs. Political Trust

- Subject here: **social trust**, *not* trust in government or other social institutions
- Trust in other people logically quite different from trust in institutions and political authorities
- Could easily trust neighbor and distrust city hall, or vice versa
- Empirically: social and political trust may or may not be correlated
- Theoretically: must be kept distinct
- **Trust in government may be cause or consequence of social trust, but it is not *the same thing***

### Four Decades of Dwindling Trust

**Figure 38**: Adults and teenagers (1960-1999)
- Standard survey question: "Generally speaking, would you say that most people can be trusted, or that you can't be too careful in dealing with people?"
- Adults: steady decline from ~55% (1960) to ~35% (late 1990s)
- High school students: sharper decline from ~55% (1975) to ~25% (mid-1990s)

**Ambiguity in responses**:
- Question taps feelings about trustworthiness of generalized other (thin trust)
- But meaning murky: could mean:
  1. Honesty is rarer these days
  2. Other people's behavior hasn't changed, but we've become more paranoid
  3. Neither ethical demands nor behavior changed, but we now have more information about treachery (lurid media reports)

### Survey Reports as Accurate Social Experience

- Social geography suggests survey reports about honesty and trust should be interpreted **prima facie as accurate accounts** of respondents' social experiences
- Virtually all societies: "have-nots" less trusting than "haves" (probably because haves treated with more honesty and respect)
- In America:
  - Blacks express less social trust than whites
  - Financially distressed less than financially comfortable
  - People in big cities less than small-town dwellers
  - People who have been victims of crime or divorce less than those who haven't
- Reasonable to assume patterns reflect actual experience rather than different psychic predispositions

**When such people tell pollsters most people can't be trusted**: they are not hallucinating — they are reporting their experience

### City Size and Social Trust

- As noted in previous chapter: virtually all forms of altruism (volunteerism, community projects, philanthropy, directions for strangers, aid for afflicted) demonstrably more common in small towns
- Crime rates 2-3x higher in cities
- Victims of crime and violence (wherever they live) express reduced social trust
- Store clerks in small towns more likely to return overpayment than urban counterparts
- People in small towns more likely to assist "wrong
<!-- pp. 141-160 -->

## Chapter 8: Reciprocity, Honesty, and Trust (continued)

### Urban vs. Rural Trust Patterns

- Urban dwellers express more distrust than small-town residents, but this reflects **realistic assessment** of actual social environment, not paranoia
- Small-town advantages in trust are genuine: cheating on taxes, insurance claims, bank applications 3x more likely condemned in small towns
- Car dealers in small towns perform far fewer unnecessary repairs than big-city dealerships
- **Medieval proverb**: "City air liberates" — but enfeebled thin trust is "a fair price for that freedom"

### Social Trust as Both Objective and Subjective

- Trust reflects both **actual social environment** and personal psychology (cynicism, paranoia, projections)
- People who feel untrustworthy are less trusting of others
- Social trust can create **vicious or virtuous spirals**: expectations influence behavior, which reinforces expectations
- Views about reciprocity and generalized trust are "especially influenced by personal experience and social customs early in life" — why called "formative years"

### Historical Decline in Trust

- **1952**: Americans split 50-50 on whether society was as morally upright as the past
- **1998**: By 3-to-1 margin, Americans believe society is less honest/moral than past
- Survey archives screen out "golden glow" by comparing feelings today with what earlier generation **actually said** at the time
- Evidence suggests **social trust rose from mid-1940s to mid-1960s**, peaking 1964 — middle-aged Americans in 1960s were living in **more trusting** society than the one they grew up in

### The Long Decline: Mid-1960s Onward

- **Mid-1960s reversal** initiated long-term decline in social trust (Figure 38)
- Every year fewer aver "most people can be trusted," more caution needed in dealing with people
- Decline **steeper among younger Americans** than older, especially since 1985
- Americans experiencing more friction in daily lives than parents/grandparents did a generation ago

### Generational Succession Driving Decline

- Most decline in American social trust since 1960s **attributable to generational succession**
- Generational decline has **accelerated in last decade or two**
- **1970s**: ~80% of Americans born in first third of century believed "most people are honest," late 1990s they continued holding that optimistic view in almost unchanged degree
  - But their share in population fell from nearly 1 in 2 adults (1975) to barely 1 in 8 adults (1998)
- **1970s**: ~75% of those born 1930-1945 believed in essential honesty of others, views changed little over subsequent decades
- **Baby boomers** (born 1946-1960): ~60% agreed in 1970s "most people are honest," views unchanged in late 1990s
- **Post-1960 generation**: Not out of adolescence in mid-1970s, but by mid-1980s roughly half denied "most people are honest"
- **By 1999**: This mistrustful younger generation constituted nearly one-third of adult population

### The Replacement Effect

- At century's end, generation with trust quotient of nearly 80% was being rapidly replaced by one with trust quotient of barely half that
- **Inevitable result**: Steadily declining social trust, *even though each individual cohort is almost as trusting as it ever was*
- Result is **generational succession**, not individual aging effects

### Crime and Social Trust

- **Figure 41**: Crime rates began rising sharply in middle 1960s, just as social capital/trust/trustworthiness began down
- Crime itself may be symptom of weakened social control
- Crime rates responsive to: youthfulness of population, evolution of illegal drug use (especially crack cocaine), rate of incarceration
- Unlikely more than fraction of post-1960 crime increase attributable to generic drop in national honesty
- **1990s crime drop** premature to herald as harbinger of sea change in law-abidingness

### Alternative: The Rise of Law as Social Control

- Alternative to generalized reciprocity/socially embedded honesty: **rule of law** — formal contracts, courts, litigation, adjudication, enforcement
- If thin trust evaporating, expect greater reliance on law as basis for cooperation
- One way to explore: examine changing national investment in **legal system**

### Employment in Policing and Law (Figure 42)

- **20th century** was century of industrialization, urbanism, big government, big business
- Yet as fraction of total U.S. workforce, employment of guards, police, lawyers grew relatively little for most of 20th century
- America had **fewer lawyers per capita in 1970 than in 1900**
- Two world wars, booms of 1920s and 1950s, Great Depression, New Deal, metamorphosis from rustic to metropolitan nation — **none raised lawyering ratio**

### Post-1970 Legal Explosion

- **After 1970**: Ratio of lawyers to rest of us suddenly exploded, more than doubling in next quarter century
- **By 1995**: America had 40% more police/guards and 150% more lawyers/judges than projected from 1970, even given population/economy growth
- Massive expansion of legal profession was **not** simply part of growth of all professions
- After 1970, legal profession grew **3x faster than professions as a whole**
- Legal and medical professions grew roughly in tandem for first seven decades of 20th century, but after 1970 legal profession grew **twice as fast** as medical
- **1970**: 3% fewer lawyers than doctors in U.S.
- **1995**: 34% more lawyers than doctors
- **1970**: 1 lawyer per 4.5 engineers (economy became more "technology intensive")
- **By 1995**: 1 lawyer for every 2.1 engineers

### Explaining the Legal Boom

- Explanation not entirely clear
- On supply side: Vietnam draft deferments, affirmative action played role in law school enrollments
- More puzzling: why rest of us **doubled investment in lawyering** after contenting ourselves with constant (much lower) supply for previous 70 turbulent years
- On demand side: rise in crime rate after 1970 obviously important for growth in security personnel
- Criminal law not major growth area of bar, so crime played little role in doubling demand for lawyers
- Some argue simply growth of affluence and socioeconomic complexity, but hard to see why had no effect before 1970
- Government regulation probably part of explanation (though New Deal corporatism and birth of welfare state had no similar effect in 1930s-1940s)
- Rapid increase in divorce in 1970s part of story — itself closely tied to changes in American social capital
- Careful research has cast doubt on "litigation explosion" idea — court dockets not generally more crowded today

### The Rise of "Preventive Lawyering"

- Largest increase on demand side seems to be **"preventive lawyering"**
- Beginning around 1970, informal understandings no longer seemed adequate or prudent
- Suddenness of change and timing uncannily similar to trends in other social capital measures
- Spouses, neighbors, business partners, parents and children, pastors and parishioners, donors and recipients — all abruptly began demanding to "get it in writing"

### Marc Galanter on Lawyers as Artificial Trust

> "Like the provider of artificial hormones that supplement the diminished supply coursing through the body, the lawyer contrives enforceability to supplement the failing supply of reciprocity, moral obligation, and follow-feeling. … Lawyers contrive to provide "artificial trust." … Because lawyers are producers and vendors of impersonal "cool" trust, they are the beneficiaries of the decline of its low-cost rival."

### Declining Trust Among Lawyers Themselves

- Even trust among lawyers seems impaired by decline of social capital
- **Law professors R. J. Gilson and Robert Mnookin**: As stability of social networks has declined and one-time-only encounters increased, lawyers worry less about reputation for honesty, knowing this, they too trust one another less and cooperate less

### The Broader Implication

- Treasure spent on "getting it in writing" has steadily expanded since 1970, as has amount spent on getting lawyers to anticipate and manage disputes
- This development may be **one of most revealing indicators** of fraying of social fabric
- We rely increasingly on formal institutions and law to accomplish what we used to accomplish through **informal networks reinforced by generalized reciprocity** — that is, through social capital

---

## Chapter 9: Against the Tide? Small Groups, Social Movements, and the Net

### Three Countertrends to Examine

- Not all organizations lost membership, not all personal relationships atrophied
- Three important countertrends:
  1. **Small groups**: Encounter groups, reading groups, support groups, self-help groups
  2. **Social movements**: Civil rights, student movement, peace movement, women's movement, gay/lesbian movement, abortion/right-to-life movements, religious conservative movement, environmental movement, animal rights
  3. **Internet and telecommunications**: "Computer-mediated communication" or CMC — could new "virtual communities" replace old-fashioned physical communities?

### The Small-Group Movement

- **Robert Wuthnow**: Leading student of small-group movement
- **40% of all Americans** claim to be "currently involved in [a] small group that meets regularly and provides support or caring"
- ~Half are Sunday school classes, prayer fellowships, Bible study groups (church-related, whose decline discussed in chapter 4)
- Nearly 5% participate in self-help group (Alcoholics Anonymous, Association for Retarded Citizens)
- Nearly as many in book discussion groups and hobby clubs
- Wuthnow describes as **"quiet revolution"** in American society, redefining community in more fluid way, antidote to social disconnectedness

### Small Groups as Social Capital

- Nearly 2 in 5 members reported other members helped them out when someone was sick
- 3 in 5 said group had extended help to someone outside the group
- 4 in 5 agreed group made them "feel like you weren't alone"
- Small groups represent important stock of social capital
- What about secular support and discussion groups (beyond religious)?

### Reading Circles: Historical Context

- Emerged as important feature of middle-class American life in **second half of 19th century**, as spread of education combined with growth of leisure time
- Attracted predominantly women
- First decades after Civil War: Concentrated on intellectual "self-improvement"
- Groups also encouraged self-expression, intense friendship, what later generation would call "consciousness-raising"
- Focus gradually widened from literary pursuits to community service and civic betterment
- **Turn of century example**: One newly elected president told group, "I have news for you. Dante is dead. He has been dead for several centuries, and I think it is time we dropped the study of *his* Inferno and turned our attention to our own." Another echoed, "We prefer Doing to Dante, Being to Browning. …We've soaked in literary effort long enough"
- From such groups were born **suffrage movement and numerous other civic-minded initiatives of Progressive Era**

### Literary Groups: Longevity and Civic Impact

- Informal literary groups can be extremely long lived
- Example: Self-rejuvenating group of 35 in **Fayetteville, Arkansas**, met twice a month since **1926**
- Intense personal, intellectual, occasionally even political bonds forged in lively discussions
- Regular participants become more involved in wider community affairs as well, moving from Dante to Doing
- By converting solitary intellectual activity (reading) into social/civic one, discussion groups provide fertile forcing bed for both *schmoozers* and *machers*

### Current State of Reading Groups

- Many observers believe America now in midst of another boom in reading groups, like late 19th century
- Several grassroots organizations striving to make it so
- Sadly, evidence to support hopeful view hard to find
- Numbers uncertain, but appears as many Americans involved in literary/artistic/discussion groups in **1960s and 1970s** as in late 1990s
- Since participation heaviest among single women and college graduates, and those categories encompass higher portion of Americans today than 3-4 decades ago, somewhat surprising popularity hasn't blossomed more
- Proportion of single female college graduates who belong to literary/artistic/study/discussion group actually **fell from 1 in 3 (1974) to 1 in 4 (1994)**
- Verdict on small groups must be mixed: surely contribute to civic engagement and social capital, but **little evidence they've grown in numbers** that would significantly offset civic decay

### Self-Help and Support Groups: Growth

- By contrast, participation in **self-help and support groups has unquestionably grown** in recent years
- Most common: **"twelve-step" groups** like Alcoholics Anonymous (founded 1935) and 130+ national analogues (Gamblers Anonymous, Co-Dependents Anonymous)
- **Alcoholics Anonymous (AA)**: Claims ~1 million members in U.S., Al-Anon cousin for family/friends counts another 400,000 members
- Many support groups for victims of specific diseases/problems: muscular dystrophy, AIDS, single parenting
- Commercially organized self-help groups: Jenny Craig, Weight Watchers, some therapy groups
- One recent national survey: **2% of all adults** were currently active in some support or self-help group
- Another comprehensive survey: **Lifetime rate ~3%**
- For perspective: All participants in self-help groups (newcomers and old-timers combined) outnumbered 2-to-1 by dropouts from league bowling over last two decades

### Small Groups Adding "Formal Organization" to Interpersonal Life

- Wuthnow avers small group movement **"adding important element to way modern life is organized"**
- "It is extending principles of formal organization into arena of interpersonal life that was largely spontaneous and unorganized until very recently"
- Some medical professionals still debate advantages of lay support vs. professional therapy
- In practice, two approaches are converging
- Comprehensive study of self-help groups in California: More than 60% have professional leaders, blurring line between self-help and group therapy
- Increasing body of evidence: Support groups—especially interpersonal ties they offer—provide **measurable health and emotional benefits** to many participants

### Support Groups as Substitute for Weakened Intimate Ties

- In some respects, support groups **substitute for other intimate ties** that have weakened in fragmented society
- Serve people disconnected from more conventional social networks
- Rate of participation in such groups is **2-4x higher among divorced and single people** than married
- **Alfred H. Katz and Eugene I. Bender**: "To be physically handicapped, poor, a former mental patient, or an object of exploitation or social disapproval is an identity that society forces on many unwilling 'deviants.' …We see self-help groups as vehicles through which these outcast persons can claim and grow toward new identities, redefining themselves and society; and can overcome solitariness through identification with a reference group; and sometimes can work toward social ends or social change that they see as important"

### Social Capital Remedies for Neglected Problems

- Growth of these groups reflects **application of social capital remedies to previously neglected problems**
- Gay support groups, Association for Retarded Citizens, overweight people's support groups bring problems hitherto dealt with in isolation into communal forum
- Just as AA helped recast alcoholism as social problem needing social/spiritual remedies, newer support groups bring what were thought to be private problems into public realm
- Support groups serve important range of needs for people who might otherwise lack access to social capital

### Support Groups and Broader Civic Goals

- In some cases, such groups also come to pursue broader civic goals
- **Mothers Against Drunk Driving (MADD)** and Association for Retarded Citizens illustrate range of public purposes and activities that have emerged from this sector
- On other hand, self-help and support groups **do not typically play same role as traditional civic associations**
- Alone among 22 different sorts of groups to which Americans belong, **membership in self-help groups completely unrelated to any other form of group affiliation**
- Not nearly so closely associated with regular community involvement (voting, volunteering, giving to charity, working on community problems, talking with neighbors) as more traditional civic associations (religious, youth, neighborhood, school service, fraternal, service groups)

### Robert Wuthnow's Assessment

> "[T]he kind of community [these small groups] create is quite different from the communities in which people have lived in the past. These communities are more fluid and more concerned with the emotional states of the individual.… The communities they create are seldom frail. People feel cared for. They help one another. They share their intimate problems.… But in another sense small groups may not be fostering community as effectively as many of their proponents would like. Some small groups merely provide occasions for individuals to focus on themselves in the presence of others. The social contract binding members together asserts only the weakest of obligations. Come if you have time. Talk if you feel like it. Respect everyone's opinion. Never criticize. Leave quietly if you become dissatisfied.… We can imagine that [these small groups] really substitute for families, neighborhoods, and broader community attachments that may demand lifelong commitments, when, in fact, they do not."

### Social Movements: The Omnipresent Connection

- If linkage of small groups to public life sometimes tenuous and hard to detect, comparable connection for social movements is **omnipresent**
- All social movements have historical roots, nearly all epochs witness grassroots organization for social change
- **1960s** was without doubt **most portentous decade in 20th century** from perspective of grass-roots social change
- Beginning with successes of black civil rights movement, wave after wave of popular mobilization swelled and crested in ensuing years

### The Movements of the 1960s-1980s

- **Free Speech Movement** (Berkeley, 1964)
- **Vietnam protests** (Chicago 1968, then Washington D.C., hundreds of other towns/cities in 1970s)
- **Stonewall Inn uprising for gay rights** (1969)
- **Mass demonstrations for environmental quality** (Earth Day 1970)
- **Women's liberation** in boardrooms and bedrooms across country throughout 1970s
- **Massive and widespread demonstrations for/against abortion** during 1980s

### Social Activism Expanding Civic Repertoire

- Social activism of 1960s greatly expanded **repertoire of readily available and legitimate forms of civic engagement**
- **Boycotts** began with blacks and buses in Alabama, then applied by farmworkers to grapes in California, abortion advocates to pizza in Michigan, upholders of traditional family values to amusement parks in Florida
- **Protest marches** once outraged authorities in scores of local communities, became so routine that police and demonstrators became joint choreographers
- Segments of American population (Left and Right) who had been quiescent or silently suppressed, suddenly felt empowered and plunged into public life
- **Standing at close of century**, virtually impossible to overstate impact of these social movements on lives of most American communities and citizens
- In most private moments as in most public ones, our behavior and values bear imprint of those movements

### Social Movements and Social Capital: Chicken and Egg

- Social movements and social capital so closely connected, sometimes hard to see which is chicken and which egg
- **Social networks are quintessential resource** of movement organizers
- Reading groups became sinews of suffrage movement
- Friendship networks (not environmental sympathies) accounted for who became involved in grassroots protest after Three Mile Island nuclear accident
- Social ties more than ideals or self-interest explain who was recruited to **Freedom Summer**, climactic moment in civil rights movement
- Local church connections account for solidarity underlying **Christian Coalition**
- Precisely because social capital essential for social movements, **its erosion could shroud their prospects for the future**

### Social Movements *Create* Social Capital

- Social movements also *create* social capital, fostering new identities and extending social networks
- Not only did preexisting interpersonal ties bring volunteers to Mississippi for Freedom Summer, but "the annealing heat of that tumultuous summer forged lifelong identities and solidarities"
- "Mississippi exposed them to a way of life and a vision of community that most of the volunteers found enormously appealing," reports **Doug McAdam** (collective biographer of volunteers)
- They carried that vision with them into student movement, peace movement, women's movement, environmental movement, many more
- "The volunteers left Mississippi not only more disposed toward more activism, but in a better structural position, by virtue of their links to one another, to act on these inclinations"
- **Kenneth Andrews** has shown: Community infrastructure generated by Mississippi civil rights movement in early 1960s had impact on local African American political power for decades to come

### Collective Protest Creates Enduring Bonds

- Whether among gays marching in San Francisco or evangelicals praying together on Mall, or in earlier era autoworkers downing tools in Flint, **act of collective protest itself creates enduring bonds of solidarity**
- Many now domesticated sing-along favorites have origins in highly contentious social movements: "Oh! Susanna!," "Battle Hymn of the Republic," "We shall overcome," "Blowin' in the Wind"
- **Collective protest strengthens shared identity**, certainly for participants and sometimes for their heirs, "anchoring individuals in participatory cultures"
- Social movements with grassroots involvement both embody and produce social capital

### National "Social Movement Organizations" vs. Grassroots

- Whether national "social movement organizations" — from Greenpeace to Moral Majority — do as well is another matter
- Even sympathetic commentators on maturing movements of 1960s (like sociologist **Margit Mayer**) have observed: Their organizational legacy was often Washington-based, full-time, professional, staff-run organizations, with "social entrepreneurs" cultivating comfortable conscience constituencies and "concentrat[ing] on manipulating the mass media so as to influence public opinion and to generate elite responses and policy changes"

### John McCarthy: Social Infrastructural Deficit

- Sociologist **John McCarthy** has argued professional social movement organizations arise precisely as response to **"social infrastructural deficit"** — cases in which "widespread sentiment exists favoring or opposing a social change, but the lack of available infrastructures inhibits the mobilization of the sentiment"

### Pro-Life vs. Pro-Choice: Ground War vs. Air War

- McCarthy points out: Although pro-choice and pro-life positions both garner substantial support in opinion polls, two movements structured quite differently
- **Pro-life movement** rests on thousands of church-based grassroots organizations and can efficiently mobilize supporters for direct action on basis of those preexisting social networks
- Example: 1993 National Right to Life Committee claimed **13 million members and 7,000 local chapters**
- By contrast, **pro-choice movement** (particularly with demise in 1980s of organized grassroots women's liberation movement) lacks preexisting social infrastructure and therefore must rely heavily on national advocacy organizations, using technology of direct mail, telemarketing, media campaigns
- **National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League**: Membership more than tripled from 132,000 (1989) to nearly 500,000 (1996), but within two years membership plunged to 190,000, of whom state leaders estimated only about 3-5% had done more than write a check
- Such volatility emblematic of **affiliation based on symbolic identification rather than personal networks**
- **Debra Minkoff** correctly observes: "In the absence of the opportunity or resources to establish face-to-face interactions, such symbolic affiliation may be the only available mobilizing structure that can link isolated individuals"
- However, should not mistake symbolic ties for personal ones

### "Ground War" vs. "Air War" Strategy

- Neither "ground war" strategy nor "air war" strategy politically or morally superior
- Rather, they are adapted to different resource endowments
- **Pro-life ground war** (like civil rights ground war before it) adapted for "social capital rich" environment with dense preexisting social networks of reciprocity
- **Pro-choice air war** adapted to "social capital poor" environment
- In latter case, existence of well-developed national social movement organization using "air war" techniques is **sign not of presence of grassroots engagement, but of its absence**

### Historical Significance of the 1960s-1970s: Open Question

- **By common consent**, 1960s (and early 1970s) was period of uncommon social and political mobilization
- What was historical significance of this period and what was to be its sequel?
- Did movements of those years represent **cresting of long wave of rising civic involvement** — indeed same upswelling whose conventional contours traced in earlier chapters?
- Did this cycle of protest then recede, leaving behind only professionalized and bureaucratized interest groups, still bearing banners of social movements but deployed now as defensive light air force, not massed infantry for change?
- Is all that remains of that proud period of deepened citizenship now captured by camp bumper sticker — "Nuke the gay whales for Jesus"?
- Or instead did 1960s produce **durable and more advanced repertoire of civic engagement**, leaving as legacy many rich new forms of connectedness, a "movement society" in which "elite challenging" behavior becomes perpetual, conventional, routinely deployed by advocates of many different causes?
- **In short**: Did 1960s mark birth of era or merely climax of one?

### Difficulty Answering the Question

- This question surprisingly difficult to answer rigorously
- Perhaps because most of best academic research of last two decades has been produced by children of 1960s, much of it takes for granted that new era of expanded participation dawned in 1968
- To be sure, case studies of specific movements sometimes describe backlash, weakening, retreat, even quietism
- Most social historians agree: As organized, grassroots effort, **civil rights movement was receding by 1970**, and **women's movement began to decline with defeat of Equal Rights Amendment in 1982**
- By contrast, most studies of **environmental movement tout its continuing ability** to rouse millions of Americans to civic activity

### The Environmental Movement: Instructive Case

- Development of American environmental movement over last four decades provides **instructive insights** into fate of social movements of 1960s
- Important grassroots conservation organizations (Sierra Club, National Audubon Society/NAS) founded at turn of 20th century
- Modern era of environmentalism began during 1960s, punctuated by exclamation point of **Earth Day 1970**, celebrated by reported 20 million participants across country
- With ensuing acceptance of environmentalism in Washington and then onset of energy crisis, membership growth of movement lagged during 1970s
- But under threat to environmental gains posed by Reagan administration, movement rebounded during 1980s
- **By 1990**, according to one estimate, environmental movement counted more than 10,000 organizations nationwide

### Environmental Membership Explosion (Figure 43)

- Over four decades, membership in **national environmental organizations exploded**
- Membership in major organizations rose from about 125,000 (1960) to 1 million (1970), then doubled to 2 million (1980) and more than tripled again to **6.5 million (1990)**
- Although growth slowed substantially in 1990s, in quantitative terms this remains remarkable organizational success story rivaling PTA from 1930s to 1960s
- Some enthusiastic observers speak of **"participatory environmentalism"**

### Greenpeace: Development in a Nutshell

- **Greenpeace** illustrates development in nutshell
- Founded 1972, tripled membership in barely 5 years from 800,000 (1985) to 2,350,000 (1990)
- Bounding past rival groups that had dwarfed it decade before
- Becoming by far largest U.S. environmental organization, more than 2x as big as nearest competitor (National Wildlife Federation)
- This phenomenal growth in environmental organizations occurred precisely in period in which many other civic organizations were withering
- Even women's movement had wilted
- At first blush, Figure 43 seems strong evidence that last several decades have witnessed *not* general decline in civic engagement, but merely **reorientation from "old-fashioned" to "contemporary" affiliations**, away from Rotary and League of Women Voters to Greenpeace and Sierra Club

### The Crucial Innovation: Direct Mail

- Unfortunately, in main this ebullient growth swelled mailing lists of what we earlier termed **"tertiary" organizations** — organizations in which "membership" is essentially honorific rhetorical device for fund-raising
- Affiliation with Greenpeace (and its peers elsewhere on ideological spectrum) does not represent sort of interpersonal solidarity and intense civic commitment that brought millions of students, African Americans, gays and lesbians, peace activists, right-to-lifers to thousands of marches, rallies, sit-ins as part of social movements of 1960s and 1970s
- **Crucial innovation** that explains trend in Figure 43 is not deeper civic consciousness, but **direct mail**

### Direct Mail as Mobilization Tool

- In 1965, **National Audubon Society** mailed 1 million invitations to membership — extraordinary number for organization that then counted fewer than 50,000 members
- Within 6 years its postage bill had doubled, as Audubon headquarters sent out 2 million letters in 1971
- By then, with stimulus of direct mail boosting growth to almost 25% a year, Audubon membership had ballooned to more than 200,000
- Technique spread across spectrum of environmental associations
- By 1990, Greenpeace was mailing out **48 million letters annually**
- Virtually all major American environmental groups (as well as dozens of smaller organizations dedicated to "charismatic" animals, like Mountain Lion Foundation, Save the Manatee, Pheasants Forever) are **addicted to direct mail** as tool of mobilization and membership retention
- Indeed, few national environmental organizations (such as Izaak Walton League) that have forsworn direct mail have experienced no growth whatsoever over last 30 years
- Example: 1960 Izaak Walton League had 51,000 members vs. 15,000 for Sierra Club
- By 1990, after 3 decades of direct-mail growth hormones, **Sierra Club membership stood at 560,000** vs. 50,000 for Izaak Walton League

### Direct Mail: Multiple Purposes

- Direct mail serves multiple purposes
- Leading academic expert on environmental fund-raising, **Christopher Bosso**, says: "Direct mail has been a lucrative, relatively low cost way to educate the public about both an issue and a group; it lowers the cost of individual participation to just writing a check"
- Whether technique is "low cost" for organization depends on how we do accounting
- Typically these organizations allocate **20-30% of budget to fund-raising and associated advertising**
- Typically rate of return is **1% to 3%**, depending on how well mailing list has been chosen
- Adding "front-end" or "back-end" premium can double rate of return
- Once signed up, new "members" have loyal organizational pen pal, for average environmental organization requests money from "members" **9 times a year**
- (Fair is fair: 8 of every 9 direct mail appeals from nonprofit organizations are thrown away unopened)
- Typically **dropout rate after first year is 30%**, although in some cases (like Common Cause in 1980s) dropout can exceed 50%
- On other hand, members who stay past first year are more reliable sources of revenue
- As one environmental strategist said, **"We know what it costs us to bring in a member; we know we lose money to bring people in, [but] it is an investment program"**

### "Members" Really Means "Donors"

- Recruiting "members" (actually, "donors" or "supporters" would be more accurate term) has become exact science
- "We know how many new people we have to bring in each year," explained one membership director
- "A large percentage are from direct mail. We are trying to get away from mailing so many pieces, but right now it is the most effective way to bring in new members"
- Added another, "We have a certain amount of attrition … and we have a certain amount of desired growth, and based on our response rate we have to mail that number of pieces to maintain our membership level and growth rate"
- A third wrote with disarming candor, "Although our membership is not declining, it is becoming increasingly more challenging to bring in new members at an affordable cost per donor.… Whoever finds a new niche market is the winner!!!"

### Low Organizational Commitment

- As one might expect from this process of recruiting "members," **organizational commitment is low**
- Compared with members recruited through face-to-face social networks (including recipients of gift memberships from friends and relatives), **direct-mail recruits drop out more readily, participate in fewer activities, and feel less attachment to the group**
- Direct-mail recruits also hold **more extreme and intolerant political views** than members recruited through social networks
- Thus perhaps less surprising that Greenpeace, which had tripled in membership to 2,350,000 between 1985 and 1990, then ***lost 85 percent of its members in the next eight years***

### "Old-Fashioned" vs. "New" Organizations

- By contrast, *none* of "old-fashioned" chapter-based organizations that attained record membership after World War II and whose travails summarized in Figure 8 lost as much as 85% of membership in *three or four decades* from postwar peak to end of century
- Reason obvious yet crucial in understanding difference between older and newer organizational types
- **Members of Moose Club or Hadassah are joined to organization not merely by symbolic ties, but by real ties to real people** — that is, by social capital
- Members of local American Legion post are kept there, not mainly by patriotism or by desire to lobby for more funds for Veterans Administration, but by **long-standing personal ties among the guys**
- Tensile strength of newer organizations is much weaker
- As **Christopher Bosso** concludes, supporters of mail-order organizations are less "members" than **"consumers" of a cause**
- "The sharp decline in Greenpeace's numbers in the 1990s may reflect a market axiom that today's hot product is tomorrow's remaindered bin"

### Not Even Considering Themselves "Members"

- Most affiliates of tertiary associations do not even consider themselves "members"
- More than half of **Environmental Defense Fund "members"** say that "I don't really think of myself as a member; the money I send is just a
<!-- pp. 161-180 -->

## Chapter 6: Social Movements and the Sixties (continued)

### The Reality of "Checkbook Membership"

- Environmental groups exhibit **"checkbook affiliation"** rather than genuine activism
- Survey of five major environmental organizations: less than three years' average affiliation, over half belonged to 4+ groups, only 8% self-described as "active"
- **Direct-mail recruitment** creates overlap—groups prospect from same mailing lists
- Members valued as supporters and donors, not activists
- Comparison: unlike civil rights activists who sat at lunch counters in Greensboro 1960

### Minimal Commitment Across Organizations

- **National Rifle Association**: membership tripled 1977-1996 despite national trend toward gun control, but annual renewal rate barely 25%
- **National Abortion Rights Action League (NARAL)**: half don't self-describe as members, 3/4 don't know if friends are members, 2/3 never encouraged friends to join
- Sociologist **John McCarthy**: members "did not talk with their friends about membership in the organization"
- Members see themselves as **fans, not players**

### "Proxy" Political Participation

- Leaders and members don't see groups as vehicles for **participatory democracy**
- Friends of the Earth and Amnesty International: "being politically active" not an important reason for joining
- **"Cheap participation"**: can make political statement below threshold of serious engagement, without costs of "real" participation

> "Mail-order groups permit a form of political participation which can be labeled cheap participation. For a cost below the threshold of serious analysis by the relatively affluent potential member, they can make a political statement of preference, without engaging in the costs (time and money) of 'real' participation.... It is the casual nature of the engagement rather than subsequent disillusionment that accounts for turnover."

### Bureaucratization of Social Movements

- **John McCarthy and Mayer Zald** (early 1970s): social movements increasingly taken over by paid functionaries, bureaucratization, mass promotion, professional careers, philanthropic foundations, government funding
- **Ronald Shaiko** (1990s): organizations now hiring "economists, Ivy League lawyers, management consultants, direct mail specialists, and communications directors"
- Professionalization is not betrayal—**Christopher Bosso**: environmental groups playing roles mature organizations must in political context
- **Competition for dues** makes tertiary organizations sensitive to constituents; those failing to win support die
- **Robert Michels's** "iron law of oligarchy" applied to traditional civic organizations too
- Argument: direct-mail organizations provide neither **connectedness among members** nor direct engagement in civic give-and-take
- "Participatory democracy" through **citizenship by proxy is an oxymoron**

### Limited Local Infrastructure

- Only 2-3 of major environmental organizations have any local chapters
- Membership director quoted: *"Membership simply means that you gave us some money at least once in the last two years"*
- **Sierra Club** survey (1989): members much more politically active than average American, but only 13% ever attended a single meeting
- **National Audubon Society**: claims hundreds of chapters nationwide, but in Texas only 3-4% of 28,000 members are active
- Comparison: **every week twenty times as many Texans** gather for lunch at "old-fashioned" Rotary clubs

### Grassroots Environmentalism—Overstated Claims

- Claims of "fundamental change" since 1970: "rapid increase in number and prominence of *grassroots* organizations"
- Public support weakened noticeably as 20th century ended
- 1990: 3/4 of Americans considered themselves "environmentalists"
- By end of 1990s: self-declared environmentalists fell by 1/3 to only 50%
- Survey data: 60% claim to recycle, 50% gave money to environmental group in past 5 years, 30% signed petition, 10% claim to be member, 3% took part in protest/demonstration

### Evidence of Decline, Not Growth

- **Yankelovich Partners** surveys: "I'm concerned about what I myself can do to protect our environment and natural resources"
  - Rose from 50% (1981) to 55% (1990-92)
  - Fell steadily to 40% (1999)—lowest recording in nearly two decades
- Systematic evidence suggests **decline** in state/local conservation and environmental activism over several decades
- Verdict: claim of growing grassroots environmental activism is **"not proved"**

### Religious Conservatives: The Real Grassroots Movement

- **1950s-60s**: McCarthyism, John Birch Society, White Citizens' councils, Wallace presidential campaign—mass-based conservative movements, but mobilized at most several hundred thousand participants
- **1970s**: riding wave of religious fundamentalism, **Christian Right** emerged
- **1980s**: formation of several genuinely grassroots conservative evangelical organizations
  - **Operation Rescue** (violent antiabortion)
  - **Christian Coalition** (Pat Robertson and Ralph Reed)
  - **Promise-Keepers** (nominally apolitical)
  - **Moral Majority** (Jerry Falwell)
- Christian Coalition and Promise-Keepers each claimed several million active participants—largest conservative movement in 20th century
- Actual specifics uncertain for organizations founded less than decade ago
- Significance: appearance of **substantial cadre of highly motivated citizen-activists**

### Post-WWII Evangelical Shift

- Center of gravity of Protestant evangelicalism moved from rural/socially peripheral fringe toward **middle-class suburban communities**
- **National Association of Evangelicals** membership more than tripled 1940s-1970s
- Evangelical churches hit less hard by subsequent decline in religious observance
- Traditional repugnance of fundamentalism for political involvement **gradually reversed**

### Evangelicals and Political Participation

- **Robert Wuthnow**: Pre-1974, evangelicals *less* disposed to political participation than other Americans (less likely to vote, join political groups, write officials, favor religious involvement in politics)
- Post-1974: most studies found them *more* involved politically
- Shift due partly to expansion of evangelicalism into social strata more accustomed to political participation
- Also: evangelicalism itself became more sympathetic to civic engagement
- **Christian Smith**: "Which Christian tradition is actually doing the work of trying to influence American society? It is the evangelicals who are most walking their talk."

### Social Capital and Political Mobilization

- Political mobilization of evangelicals illustrates how **social capital, civic engagement, and social movements feed on one another**
- New issues (abortion, sexual morality, "family values"), new techniques (television), new generation of political entrepreneurs
- Unlike environmentalists, evangelicals have **firm and enduring organizational foundations**
- Close observers: "Religious people are enmeshed in webs of local churches, channels of religious information, and networks of religious associations that make them readily available for mobilization"
- Movement both drawing on and replenishing stocks of **social capital** in at least one portion of American society

### Evangelical Activist Demographics

- Older, whiter, more educated, more affluent—but **religion extraordinarily important** in their lives
- National sample of religious activists: 60-70% attended church *more than once a week* (vs. <5% of other Americans)
- 3-5 times more active than average American in virtually all forms of civic and political life

### 1996 Election and Religious Mobilization

- Evangelicals more than twice as likely to discuss election in church with friend and be contacted by religious interest group
- More likely contacted by religious groups than by parties or candidates
- Most important predictor of contact: neither demography nor theology, but **social engagement in religious community**
- Religious contacts—especially talking politics in church with a friend—had demonstrable impact on who voted and for whom
- Link between church community involvement and political mobilization was **powerful and direct**
- Religious conservatives created the **largest, best-organized grassroots social movement** of last quarter century
- Among evangelical Christians, rather than ideological heirs of the sixties, we find strongest evidence of upwelling of civic engagement against the ebb tide

### Elite-Challenging Participation and Ballot Initiatives

- **Figure 44**: Statewide ballot initiatives 1900-1998
- Pattern: *falling* from early century until late 1960s (except *rise* during Great Depression), then **skyrocketing** in last third of century
- Contrary to populist pedigree: cannot be taken as reliable sign of civic engagement
- Five states (California, Oregon, North Dakota, Colorado, Arizona) account for over half of all ballot initiatives in 20th century
- California alone drives much recent growth—not a good metric for citizen involvement everywhere
- Most scholars agree civic activists sometimes place issues on ballot

### Ballot Initiatives as Fundraising Tests

- Past two decades: virtually all successful drives relied on **professional circulation firms**
- **California Commission on Campaign Financing** study: "Any individual, corporation, or organization with approximately $1 million to spend can now place any issue on the ballot"

> "Qualifying an initiative for the statewide ballot is thus no longer so much a measure of general citizen interest as it is a test of fundraising ability."

- Most signers don't read what they sign
- Direct-mail and radio/TV advertising (much deceptive) more important than grassroots activity
- Campaign spending is strong predictor of outcome; surveys indicate "a very low degree of voter sophistication" on referenda issues

### Alternatives to Group Lobbying

- **Betty Zisk** study (Massachusetts, Michigan, Oregon, California 1976-1982): "Far from replacing group lobbying efforts vis-à-vis the legislature, the initiative and referenda campaigns seem to *provide an alternative channel* for the very group activities the reformers denounced"
- Opportunity for direct participation did not galvanize large numbers of voters
- Rise of ballot initiatives is better measure of **power of well-financed special interests** than civic engagement

### Demonstrations and Protests

- Demonstrations/protests in Washington became larger and more frequent since late 1960s (media-savvy organizers)
- Great civil rights and Vietnam marches of sixties preceded and followed by continuing activism in communities
- **"March on Washington"** in 1990s provides no assurance of continuing, community-based action
- Example: **"Stand in the Gap" rally** (Oct 4, 1997)—half million men on Mall, largest religious gathering in American history—Promise-Keepers virtually collapsed six months later, laying off entire staff

### Protest Participation Trends

- **Roper Social and Political Trends survey archive**: adults who had *ever* been in protest march or sit-in rose from 7% (1978) to 10% (1994)
- Other 1970s-80s-90s surveys: participation estimated at roughly 1 in 10-15 adults, with slight tendency to rise
- Abortion issue accounts for roughly 1/3 of all protest activity
- Explanation for rising fraction: departure of *pre*-1960s generation of *non* protesters at top of age hierarchy, *not* addition of new protesters at bottom
- **Figure 45**: protesting *less* common among twenty-somethings now than among people that age in sixties, but protesting became *more* common among middle-aged and older people as sixties generation aged
- Protest marchers have **steadily and rapidly grayed** over past several decades

### Protests as Complement, Not Alternative

- Protests/demonstrations are not an *alternative* to conventional politics, but a **complement**
- Protesters unusually active politically in more ordinary ways too
- Participation in demonstrations and civil disobedience not much more common nowadays than in sixties
- More widely seen as legitimate by nonparticipants
- "Movement-type" political actions accepted as "standard operating procedure" across political spectrum
- Actual involvement limited to **small and aging fraction** of population
- Petitioning and local public meetings have slumped over last decade or two
- **David Meyer and Sidney Tarrow**: "movement society" hypothesis ultimately concedes amount of highly contentious forms actually used by citizens "seems to be more circumscribed than it was two decades ago"

## Chapter 7: Telecommunications and Social Capital

### The Telephone—A Cautionary Tale

- Telephone use grew exponentially throughout 20th century
- Diffusion into American homes followed familiar trajectory—rising steadily first two-thirds of century, except Great Depression reversal
- 1945-1998: local calls per capita climbed from 304 to 2,023 annually; long-distance calls exploded from 13 to 353
- Most growth represented business/commercial communication, but purely social calls also increased
- **1982**: most half of all American adults talked on phone (locally or long-distance) with friends or relatives virtually every day
- **Figure 46b**: long-distance personal phone calls accelerated after 1984 deregulation before leveling off in 1990s
- Cell phones in 1990s made telephone nearly ubiquitous
- **1998**: Pew Research Center: 2/3 of adults had called friend or relative previous day "just to talk"

### Early Misjudgments About the Telephone

- For nearly half century after 1876 invention, social implications badly misjudged by analysts and even phone company itself
- **Alexander Graham Bell** originally expected telephone to serve broadcasting function (music on tap)—later became province of radio
- Early 20th century telephone executives convinced primary customer was businessman; discouraged "socializing" by telephone
- **Claude Fischer**: "[F]or a generation or more there was a mismatch between the ways people actually used the telephone and how industry men imagined it would or should be used"

### Telephone's Ambiguous Effects

- Evaluating effects on social relations surprisingly difficult even with hindsight
- **Ithiel de Sola Pool**: telephone seems to have effects in diametrically opposite directions
- Saves physicians from house-calls but physicians initially believed it increased them (patients could summon doctor rather than travel)
- Allows dispersal of centers of authority, but also allows tight continuous supervision of field offices from center
- **Socially**: telephone both gives and takes away
- 1975 switching center fire cut telephone service on Lower East Side of Manhattan for three weeks: 2/3 felt isolated, but 1/3 visited other people in person more frequently
- Telephone appears to reduce both **loneliness and face-to-face socializing**

### Telephone Reinforced Existing Local Ties

- **1891 telephone official**: technology would bring "epoch of neighborship without propinquity"
- **1933 comprehensive study**: point-to-point medium (unlike mass media) reinforced existing **local ties** more than distant ones
- Mid-1970s phone company records: 40-50% of all phone calls originating from household made within two-mile radius; 70% within five-mile radius
- ~20% of residential calls made to single number; roughly half made to one of only five numbers
- **Martin Mayer**: "People make most of their telephone calls within the neighborhood in which they live"
- Type of household making heaviest use: **family with teenagers** that recently moved to new neighborhood in same metropolitan area—using telephone to maintain personal relationships severed by space
- "One does not meet new friends on the telephone"

### Telephone as Reinforcement, Not Transformation

- Telephone seems to have had effect of **reinforcing, not transforming or replacing**, existing personal networks
- Compare top half of Figure 46 (telephone diffusion first 2/3 of 20th century) with any earlier charts of community engagement over same period—conclusion obvious
- At least in those years, **telecommunications and conventional forms of social connectedness were complements, not alternatives**
- **Claude Fischer**: historical analysis of telephone's social impact concludes telephone did not radically alter American ways of life—"Americans used it to more vigorously pursue their characteristic ways of life"

### Telephone Increased Frequency, Not New Connections

> "The adoption of the telephone probably led people to hold more frequent personal conversations with friends and kin than had previously been customary, even if it also led them to curtail some visits. ...In total, calling probably led to more social conversations with more people than before."

- Calls may have substituted for longer visits or chats with family members, or simply took up time that would have been spent alone

### Telephone and Increasing Privatism

- Telephone implicated more in another trend: **increasing privatism**—participation in and valuation of private social worlds vs. larger public community
- Little evidence telephone enabled people to become involved in distinctively new organizational commitments
- Home telephone allowed subscribers to maintain more frequent contact with kin and friends by **chatting briefly a few times a week** instead of at greater length once a week
- Little sign telephone calling opened up new social contacts

### Telephone's Mundane Impact on Social Capital

- Telephone facilitated *schmoozing* with old friends, offsetting some disconnection described in chapter 6
- Has not engendered new friendships nor substantially altered characteristic activities of *machers*
- **Daniel Boorstin**: "The telephone was only a convenience, permitting Americans to do more casually and with less effort what they had already been doing before"

### The Internet Era Begins

- As 21st century opens, only few years into era of widespread Internet access
- Speed of diffusion substantially greater than almost any other consumer technology
- Television: 1% to 75% market penetration required nearly seven decades
- Internet: equivalent passage will require little more than seven years
- Spring 1999: nearly 1/3 of adult population (~64 million) had used Internet, up by 10+ million from barely six months earlier

### Early Internet Adoption Patterns

- Like virtually all technical consumer innovations, caught on most rapidly and fully among younger generations
- 1999 study: young people in general much less likely to seek out political information than older cohorts, but more likely to use Internet as preferred means of access
- American Association of Retired Persons website reportedly receiving half million visitors monthly
- New medium drew people of all generations, as if mesmerized

### Virtual Forms of Civic Engagement

- Within few years of Internet launch, simulacra of most classic forms of social connection and civic engagement could be found online
- Mourners could attend virtual funerals over Web
- *Today in Funeral Service*: on-line funeral "kind of de-personalizes it, but it's better than missing it"
- Virtual vows arrived; **America Online cyberwedding** (June 1997): largest to date, marrying thousands of couples simultaneously while spectators "watched" and "cheered" from virtual pews
- **Yahoo**: at last count mentioned 500+ places where one could pray virtually, including **Yaale Ve'Yavo** (Orthodox Jewish site) forwarding e-mail prayers to Jerusalem for affixing to Western Wall
- Easter services, Passover seders, grief counseling, cancer support groups, volunteering, cyberromance, hundreds of thousands of chat groups, voting, lobbying, even AIDS Action Council "virtual march on Washington" (logged over 23,000 "poster-carrying marchers")
- All these forms of **virtual social capital** and more could be found in cyberspace

### Is "Virtual Social Capital" a Contradiction?

- Central question: whether "virtual social capital" is itself contradiction in terms—no easy answer
- Early flawed conjectures about telephone warn that equally early conjectures about Internet likely similarly flawed
- Few things can yet be said with confidence about connection between social capital and Internet technology
- One truism: **timing of Internet explosion means it cannot possibly be causally linked to crumbling of social connectedness** described in previous chapters
- Voting, giving, trusting, meeting, visiting, etc. had all begun to decline while Bill Gates still in grade school
- By time Internet reached 10% of American adults in 1996, nationwide decline in social connectedness and civic engagement had been under way for at least quarter century
- Whatever future implications of Internet, **social intercourse over last several decades of 20th century was not simply displaced from physical space to cyberspace**
- Internet may be part of solution to civic problem, or may exacerbate it, but **cyberrevolution was not the cause**

### Early Internet Users No Less Civically Engaged

- Early users of Internet technology no less (and no more) civically engaged than anyone else
- **1999**: three independent studies (including my own) confirmed once we control for higher educational levels of Internet users, they are **indistinguishable from nonusers** when it comes to civic engagement
- Results prove little about *effects* of the Net, because likelihood that Internet users are self-selected in relevant ways
- Absence of any correlation between Internet usage and civic engagement could mean:
  - Internet attracts reclusive nerds and energizes them, OR
  - Net disproportionately attracts civic dynamos and sedates them
- Too early to assess long-run social effects of Internet empirically

### Potential Advantages and Disadvantages

- Consider some of *potential* advantages and disadvantages of computer-mediated communication for American civic life
- Neither apocalyptic "gloom and doom" prognosticators nor utopian "brave new virtual community" advocates probably on target
- How are "virtual" communities likely to be different from the "real" thing?

### Communication as Prerequisite for Community

- **Community, communion, and communication** intimately as well as etymologically related
- Communication is fundamental prerequisite for social and emotional connections
- Telecommunications in general and Internet in particular substantially enhance ability to communicate
- Seems reasonable to assume net effect will be to enhance community, perhaps even dramatically
- **Social capital is about networks**, and Net is the network to end all networks
- By removing barriers of time and distance, students of computer-mediated communication like sociologist **Barry Wellman**: "Computer-supported social networks sustain strong, intermediate, and weak ties that provide information and social support in both specialized and broadly based relationships. ...Computer-mediated communication accelerates the ways in which people operate at the centers of partial, personal communities, switching rapidly and frequently between groups of ties"

### Utopian Visions of Virtual Community

- Like 19th-century futurists contemplating telephone vistas, enthusiasts for "virtual community" see computer networks as basis for kind of utopian communitarianism
- **Starr Roxanne Hiltz and Murray Turoff**: early prophets of computer-mediated communication predicted "we will become the Network Nation, exchanging vast amounts of both information and socioemotional communications with colleagues, friends and 'strangers,' who share similar interests ... we will become a 'global village'"
- **Michael Strangelove**:

> "The Internet is not about technology, it is not about information, it is about communication—people talking with each other, people exchanging e-mail.... The Internet is mass participation in fully bidirectional, uncensored mass communication. Communication is the basis, the foundation, the radical ground and root upon which all community stands, grows, and thrives. The Internet is a community of chronic communicators."

### Enthusiast Testimonials

- **Howard Rheingold**: "homesteader on the electronic frontier" reported, "Why should a community accessible only via my computer screen sounded cold to me at first, but I learned quickly that people can feel passionately about e-mail and computer conferences. I've become one of them. I care about these people I met through my computer"
- **John Perry Barlow** (co-founder Electronic Frontier Foundation): found no parallel in recorded history for advent of computer-mediated communication—"We are in the middle of the most transforming technological event since the capture of fire"

### Internet as Information Transmission Tool

- Internet is powerful tool for transmission of information among physically distant people
- Tougher question: whether that flow of information itself fosters social capital and genuine community
- Information is important, but as **John Seeley Brown and Paul Duguid** of Xerox's Palo Alto Research Center emphasize, information itself needs a social context to be meaningful
- "The tight focus on information, with the implicit assumption that if we look after information everything else will fall into place, is ultimately a sort of social and moral blindness"
- At its best, computer-mediated communication allows wider, more efficient networks that strengthen our ties to social world and increase our "intellectual capital"—information can be shared at virtually no cost
- People with different pieces of puzzle can collaborate easily
- Computer-mediated communication can support large, dense, yet fluid groups that cut across existing organizational and geographic boundaries, increasing involvement of otherwise peripheral participants (recent retirees studied in one corporate experiment in electronic communication)

### Virtual Communities by Shared Interests

- Social networks based on computer-mediated communication can be organized by **shared interests rather than by shared space**
- By century's end thousands of far-flung, nationally defined networks had sprung up, linking like-minded people as disparate as BMW fanciers, bird-watchers, and white supremacists
- Echoing precisely (but perhaps unconsciously) early speculations about effects of telephone, **MIT computer scientist Michael L. Dertouzos** speculated about millions of "virtual neighborhoods" based on shared avocations rather than shared space
- Certainly cyberspace already hosts thousands of hobby and other special interest groups, and if participation in such groups becomes widespread and durable, then perhaps prediction may be right this time

### Virtual Communities May Be More Egalitarian

- Virtual communities may also be more egalitarian than real communities in which we live
- At least for foreseeable future, computer-mediated communication drastically truncates information about one's discussion partners
- **Rheingold** argues invisibility of text-based communication prevents people from forming prejudices prior to their encounters
- Canine cybernaut in famous *New Yorker* cartoon: "On the Internet no one knows you're a dog"
- Thus, assuming widespread cyberaccess, "virtual communities" may be more heterogeneous with regard to physical factors as race, gender, and age, although they may be more homogeneous with respect to interests and values

### Anonymity and Democratic Potential

- Anonymity and absence of social cues inhibit social control—after all, why we have secret ballot
- Thus cyberspace seems in some respects more democratic
- Ironically, this advantage of computer-mediated communication depends on fact that at least with current technology, it actually transmits *less* information among participants than face-to-face communication
- Research shown on-line discussions tend to be more frank and egalitarian than face-to-face meetings
- Computer-mediated communication may lead to flatter hierarchies
- In workplace networks, experiments shown computer-mediated communication is less hierarchical, more participatory, more candid, and less biased by status differences
- Women, for example, less likely to be interrupted in cyberspace discussions

### Cyberspace Democracy—Hope and Reality

- Some of allegedly greater democracy in cyberspace based more on hope and hype than careful research
- Political culture of Internet, at least in early stages, is astringently libertarian
- In some respects cyberspace represents **Hobbesian state of nature, not a Lockean one**
- **Peter Kol-lock and Marc Smith**: "It is widely believed and hoped that the ease of communicating and interacting online will lead to a flourishing of democratic institutions, heralding a new and vital arena of public discourse. But to date, most online groups have the structure of either an anarchy [if unmoderated] or a dictatorship [if moderated]"

### Internet Reduces Transaction Costs for Mobilization

- High speed, low cost, and broad scope of mobilization possible on Internet can be advantage for political organizers, by reducing transaction costs, particularly for widely scattered groups of like-minded citizens
- Example: **1997 Nobel Prize–winning International Campaign to Ban Landmines** organized by Jody Williams primarily over Internet from her home in rural Vermont
- As early as 1995, **Mark Bonchek** reported "27,000 people read the alt.politics.homosexuality newsgroup regularly with an average of 75 messages per day. As its name suggests, alt.politics.homosexuality is a forum for people to discuss issues and distribute information related to politics and homosexuality"
- Bonchek found surprising range of positions on these issues in postings to this forum, both sympathetic and hostile toward homosexuality

### Internet May Lower Threshold Too Much

- On other hand, computer-mediated communication so lowers threshold for voicing opinions that, like talk radio, it may lead not to deliberation, but to din
- Consider *Mother Jones* advertisement (April 1999) for *www.ifnotnow.com*:

> If you care
> you can do something ... easy!
> *www.ifnotnow.com*
> Be a full-time citizen activist ...
> ... for 5 minutes a week!
> Over a dozen of the best social advocacy groups
> provide the information
> —you read alerts, send letters, get responses,
> and monitor results—all at the click of a button.
> It's a one-stop shop for staying involved.
> We want to make it easy for you to make a difference!
> Make your voice heard!
> *www.ifnotnow.com*
> Sign up for a free trial now!

- If generalized, this shortcut to civic expression would simply exacerbate imbalance between talking and listening that is prominent feature of contemporary civic disengagement
- **John Seeley Brown and Paul Duguid**: "the ability to send a message to president@whitehouse.gov ... can give the illusion of much more access, participation, and social proximity than is actually available"
- Millions more of us can express our views with click of mouse, but is anyone listening?

### Potential Benefits of Computer-Mediated Communication

- Potential benefits of computer-mediated communication for civic engagement and social connectedness are impressive
- Internet offers low-cost and in many respects egalitarian way of connecting with millions of one's fellow citizens, particularly those with whom one shares interests but not space or time
- Liberating social ties from constraints of time—through what experts term **"asynchronous communication"**—may turn out to be more important effect of Internet than liberation from constraints of space

## Four Serious Challenges to Computer-Mediated Communication

### Challenge 1: The Digital Divide

- **"Digital divide"** refers to social inequality of access to cyberspace
- Certainly in early years of Internet heavy users were predominantly younger, highly educated, upper-income white males
- Exhaustive **1997 study by Census Bureau**: least connected groups in American society were rural poor, rural and inner-city racial minorities, and young, female-headed households
- Gaps by education, income, race, and family structure appeared to be widening, not narrowing
- **Pippa Norris** found both in United States and in Europe the Internet has *not* mobilized previously inactive groups but has instead reinforced existing biases in political participation
- **Sociologist Manuel Castells** argues forcefully:

> "because access to computer-mediated communication is culturally, educationally, and economically restrictive, and will be so for a long time, the most important cultural impact of computer-mediated communication could be potentially the reinforcement of the culturally dominant social networks"

- Specter of kind of cyberapartheid, in which bridging social capital is diminished as elite networks become less accessible to have-nots, is indeed frightening
- For very reason it is widely recognized as key challenge that must be addressed
- Given political will, this problem is tractable
- If Internet seen as kind of 21st-century public utility, then inexpensive, subsidized access (including both hardware and user-friendly software) can be made available in libraries, community centers, Laundromats, and even private residences, much as low-cost telephone service was subsidized in 20th century
- This first challenge of Internet to community connectedness is **serious but not insurmountable**

### Challenge 2: Loss of Nonverbal Communication

- Second challenge technically more difficult to resolve
- Computer-mediated communication transmits much less nonverbal information than face-to-face communication
- **MIT's Dertouzos** asks the right question: "Which qualities of human relationships will pass well through tomorrow's information infrastructures and which ones will not?"

### Human Skill at Sensing Nonverbal Messages

- Humans remarkably effective at sensing nonverbal messages from one another, particularly about emotions, cooperation, and trustworthiness
- Seems possible that ability to spot nonverbal signs of mendacity offered significant survival advantage during long course of human evolution
- **Psychologist Albert Mehrabian** writes in *Silent Messages: Implicit Communication of Emotions and Attitudes* that in "realm of feelings" our "facial and vocal expressions, postures, movements, and gestures" are crucial
- When our words "contradict the messages contained within them, others mistrust what we say—they rely almost completely on what we do"

### Nonverbal Communication Cannot Pass Through Computer-Mediated Communication

- Computer-mediated communication, now and for foreseeable future, masks enormous amount of nonverbal communication that takes place during even most informal face-to-face encounter
- Emoticons in e-mail (like ':)') implicitly acknowledge this fact, but provide only faintest trace of information in actual facial expression
- Eye contact, gestures (both intentional and unintentional), nods, faint furrowing of brow, body language, seating arrangements, even hesitation measured in milliseconds—none of this mass of information that we ordinarily process almost without thinking in face-to-face interaction is captured in text

### Depth and Speed of Feedback Lost

- **Nitin Nohria and Robert G. Eccles**: face-to-face encounters provide depth and speed of feedback impossible in computer-mediated communication

> "Relative to electronically mediated exchange, the structure of face-to-face interaction offers an unusual capacity for interruption, repair, feedback, and learning. In contrast to interactions that are largely sequential, face-to-face interaction makes it possible for two people to be sending and delivering messages simultaneously. The cycle of interruption, feedback, and repair possible in face-to-face interaction is so quick that it is virtually instantaneous. As [sociologist Erving] Goffman notes, 'a speaker can see how others are responding to her message even before it is done and alter it midstream to elicit a different response.' When interaction takes place in a group setting, the number of 'conversations' that can be going on simultaneously when the interactants are face-to-face is even harder to replicate in other media."

### Computer-Mediated Communication Inhibits Trust

- Poverty of social cues in computer-mediated communication inhibits interpersonal collaboration and trust, especially when interaction is anonymous and not nested in wider social context
- Experiments comparing face-to-face and computer-mediated communication confirm that **richer the medium of communication, the more sociable, personal, trusting, and friendly the encounter**

### Computer-Mediated Communication Weaknesses

- Computer-mediated communication is, to be sure, **more egalitarian, frank, and task oriented** than face-to-face communication
- Participants in computer-based groups often come up with wider range of alternatives
- However, because of paucity of social cues and social communication, participants in computer-based groups find it harder to reach consensus and feel less solidarity with one another
- They develop sense of "depersonalization" and are less satisfied with group's accomplishments
- Computer-based groups quicker to reach intellectual understanding of their shared problems—probably because they are less distracted by "extraneous" social communication—but they are much worse at generating trust and reciprocity necessary to implement that understanding

### Cheating and Reneging More Common

- Cheating and reneging more common in computer-mediated communication, where misrepresentation and misunderstanding are easier
- Participants in computer-based settings less inhibited by social niceties and quicker to resort to extreme language and invective—**"flaming"** is commonly used term among cybernauts, compelling image of communication as hand-to-hand combat with flamethrowers
- Computer-mediated communication good for sharing information, gathering opinions, and debating alternatives, but **building trust and goodwill is not easy in cyberspace**
- **John Seeley Brown and Paul Duguid**: "interactions over the Net, financial or social, will be as secure not as its digital encryption, which is a relatively cheap fix, but as the infrastructure—social as well as technical—encompassing that interaction"

### Widespread Use Requires MORE Face-to-Face Contact

- For these reasons, **Nohria and Eccles** suggest, widespread use of computer-mediated communication will actually require *more frequent* face-to-face encounters
- "An extensive, deep, robust social infrastructure of relationships must exist so that those using the electronic media will truly understand what others are communicating to them"
- Experience in Blacksburg, Virginia, electronic community network suggests "when you overlay an electronic community directly on top of a physical community, that creates a very powerful social pressure to be civil. If you're going to yell at somebody on the Net, or flame them out, you may run into them at the grocery store, and they may turn out to be your neighbor"
- In other words, **social capital may turn out to be a *prerequisite for,* rather than a *consequence of,* effective computer-mediated communication**

### Problems Less Serious for Clear, Practical Issues

- All these problems less serious in dealing with clear, practical issues, but more serious in situations of uncertainty and ambiguity
- If computer-mediated communication is nested within an ongoing face-to-face relationship, the complications are much reduced
- Arranging to meet spouse at restaurant might be easily handled via computer-mediated communication, but wrangling with new neighbor about her loud parties would not
- Archetypal interaction with new pal on Internet lacks precisely the social embeddedness that seems essential to overcome lack of social cues within medium itself
- Face-to-face networks tend to be dense and bounded, whereas computer-mediated communication networks tend to be sparse and unbounded
- **Anonymity and fluidity in virtual world** encourage "easy in, easy out," "drive-by" relationships
- That very casualness is appeal of computer-mediated communication for some denizens of cyberspace, but it discourages creation of social capital
- If entry and exit are too easy, **commitment, trustworthiness, and reciprocity will not develop**

### Challenge 3: Video/Audio Enhancements Unlikely Soon

- Video and audio enhancements of computer-mediated communication may in time reduce these difficulties, but that is **unlikely to happen soon**
<!-- pp. 181-200 -->

### Internet and Cyberspace: Threats to Social Capital

**Cyberbalkanization risk**: Internet enables narrow interest communities (BMW 2002 enthusiasts, specific hobbies) that reduce exposure to diversity
- Physical communities force interaction with people who differ demographically and ideologically
- Virtual communities allow "utopian collectivities—communities of interest, education, tastes, beliefs, and skills"
- **Stephen Doheny-Farina**: "In cyberspace we can remake the world out of an unsettled landscape"
- Risk: place-based heterogeneity replaced by interest-based homogeneity
- Filtering technologies automate screening of "irrelevant" messages, narrowing communication circles
- Reduces serendipitous connections—knowing and caring more about less

**Computer scientist Paul Resnick**: Future may involve multiple "cyberclubs" with overlapping memberships rather than all-encompassing communities or isolated ghettos
- Weak ties bridging distinct groups could create "interwoven community of communities"

**Will Internet displace face-to-face interaction?**
- 1999 survey: 42% of Internet users watched less TV vs. 19% who read fewer magazines, 16% who read fewer newspapers
- Early experimental study: extensive Internet usage linked to greater social isolation and depression
- Commercial incentives favor individualized entertainment over community engagement
- Community-friendly technology may require incentives from outside marketplace

**Conclusion on Internet effects**: Both utopianism and jeremiads likely misplaced
- History of telephone suggests computer-mediated communication will *complement*, not *replace*, face-to-face communities
- **Barry Wellman study** of research scholars: Internet helps maintain ties over distances, but physical proximity still matters—scholars who see each other often email more
- Internet reinforces existing relationships rather than substitutes for them

**MIT researcher Dertouzos**: Physical proximity needed to cement important professional and social encounters
- **Dan Huttenlocher** (Cornell): Digital technologies good at maintaining existing communities, less effective at making new ones
- Key question: What will we do with the Internet—use it to enhance social capital or be seduced by "virtual community" mirage?

> "The Internet will not *automatically* offset the decline in more conventional forms of social capital, but it has that potential."

### Summary: Exceptions to Civic Decline

**Four clearest exceptions to civic disengagement trend**:
1. Rise in youth volunteering (chapter 7)
2. Growth of telecommunication, particularly Internet
3. Vigorous growth of grassroots activity among evangelical conservatives
4. Increase in self-help support groups

These diverse countercurrents show society evolves in multiple ways simultaneously—valuable reminder of potential for civic renewal. However, these developments don't outweigh evidence that most Americans are less connected to communities than 2-3 decades ago.

**Central question**: What explains the reversal of civic-minded trends that characterized the first two-thirds of the twentieth century?

---

## SECTION THREE: Why?

---

## Chapter 10: Introduction

### The Mystery of Civic Decline

**Summary of civic decline** (first two-thirds of 20th century):
- Americans increasingly active in social and political life—churches, union halls, bowling alleys, clubrooms, committee tables, dinner tables
- Year by year: more charitable giving, more community projects, increasingly trustworthy behavior
- Then mysteriously and simultaneously began doing all those things less often

**Current state vs. past**:
- Still more civically engaged than citizens in many other countries
- But compared to our own recent past: less connected
- Remain interested, critical spectators—"kibitz, but we don't play"
- Maintain facade of formal affiliation but rarely show up
- Invented new ways of expressing demands that demand less of us
- Less likely to engage in collective deliberation (voting booth, meeting hall)
- When we do show up, disconcertingly few friends and neighbors present
- Less generous with money and time
- Less likely to give strangers benefit of the doubt

**Social networks atrophied**:
- Thin, single-stranded, surf-by interactions replacing dense, multistranded, well-exercised bonds
- **Morris Janowitz**: "communities of limited liability"
- **Claude Fischer, Robert Jackson**: "personal communities"—evanescent, single-purpose organizations allowing easy bonding and breaking
- **Grassroots groups** being replaced by staff-led interest groups
- Place-based social capital supplanted by function-based social capital
- Withdrawing from networks of reciprocity that once constituted communities

**Timing puzzle**: Decline didn't begin with Pilgrims—within living memory, tide was moving strongly in opposite direction toward more active social and political participation, greater generosity, trustfulness, connectedness
- Whatever detailed assessment of reversal, its suddenness, thoroughness, and unexpectedness constitute intriguing mystery
- Why, beginning in 1960s-1970s and accelerating in 1980s-1990s, did fabric of American community begin to unravel?

**Importance of solving the mystery**:
- Puzzle of importance to future of American democracy
- Classic brainteaser: corpus delicti, crime scene with clues, many potential suspects
- Plausible miscreants have impeccable alibis; important clues hint at developments long before curtain rose
- Like Agatha Christie's *Murder on the Orient Express*: more than one perpetrator
- Need to sort ringleaders from accomplices
- Author hasn't entirely solved mystery—invites reader help in sifting clues

### Investigative Strategy

**Serial crime approach**: Look for common features among victims
- If drop in participation greatest among working women, might suggest one explanation
- Author will examine whether declines correlated across time and space with certain social characteristics

**Two weaknesses in strategy**:

1. **Synergistic effects**: Effects spread beyond point of initial contact
   - If dinner party undermined by women's movement into workforce, effects visible among stay-at-homes too
   - Once fraternal club starts downhill, even non-TV watchers wouldn't show up
   - Saw evidence of such effects: more rapid decline in *collective* activities than *individual* activities (public meetings vs. letters to editor)
   - Synergistic effects thwart unequivocal verdicts

2. **Universal decline**: *None* stands out in initial lineup
   - Civic disengagement appears as equal opportunity affliction
   - Sharp declines in club meetings, friend visits, committee service, church attendance, philanthropic generosity, card games, electoral turnout hit virtually all sectors
   - Trends down among women and men, coasts and heartland, homeowners and renters, black ghettos and white suburbs, small towns and metros, Protestants and Catholics, affluent and impoverished, singles and married couples, unskilled laborers and small-business people, top managers, Republicans and Democrats and independents, parents and childless, full-time workers and homemakers

**Levels vs. trends differ**:
- More informal socializing among women, more civic involvement among well-to-do, less social trust among African Americans, less voting among independents, more altruism in small towns, more church attendance among parents
- But the *trends* in civic engagement very similar across categories
- Example: 1974-1994, 18% of whites attended public meeting on local affairs vs. 13% of blacks, but each race's attendance rate cut in half
- More people in rural Vermont in 1999 than metropolitan Boston, but *fewer* in rural Vermont 1999 than 1959
- With respect to *change* in civic engagement, no readily identifiable "hot spots" on demographic map

### Education as a Suspect

**Education's massive effect on civic engagement**:
- One of most important predictors of social participation—voting to associational membership to chairing committees to hosting dinner parties to giving blood
- Little effect on *schmoozing* (informal social connectedness), but positively correlated with church-related groups
- Especially powerful predictor of participation in public, formally organized activities
- Four additional years of education (e.g., going to college): 30% more interest in politics, 40% more club attendance, 45% more volunteering
- College graduates 2x as likely to serve as officer/committee member, attend public meeting, write Congress, attend political rally
- Same pattern applies to men and women, all races and generations
- Education extremely powerful predictor of civic engagement

**Why does education boost civic engagement?**
- Partly proxy for privilege—social class and economic advantage
- But when income, social status, and education used together to predict civic engagement, education stands out as primary influence
- Educational attainment may be marker of unusual ambition, energy, or innate trait encouraging civic involvement
- Finally, educated people more engaged because of skills, resources, and inclinations imparted at home and in school
- More education means more participation across individuals, states, localities, and (during first two-thirds of 20th century) across time

**Massive educational upgrade of American population**:
- 1960: 41% of adults graduated high school; 1998: 82%
- 1960: 8% had college degree; 1998: 24%
- 1972-1998: proportion with <12 years education cut in half (40% to 18%); proportion with >12 years nearly doubled (28% to 50%)
- Generation educated around dawn of 20th century (mostly didn't finish high school) replaced by baby boomers and successors (mostly attended college)

**The education paradox**: Education boosts civic engagement sharply, and educational levels have risen massively. Therefore growth in education should have increased civic engagement.
- First investigative foray leaves us more mystified
- Whatever forces lie behind slump in civic engagement and social capital, those forces affected all levels of American society
- Social capital eroded among 1-in-12 Americans with graduate degrees, 1-in-8 Americans who didn't make it into high school, and all strata in between
- Mysterious disengagement of last third of century afflicted all echelons of society

### Possible Explanations (Lineup of Suspects)

- Busyness and time pressure
- Economic hard times
- Movement of women into paid labor force and stresses of two-career families
- Residential mobility
- Suburbanization and sprawl
- Television, electronic revolution, and other technological changes
- Changes in structure and scale of American economy (chain stores, branch firms, service sector, globalization)
- Disruption of marriage and family ties
- Growth of welfare state
- Civil rights revolution
- **The sixties** (most actually happened in seventies): Vietnam, Watergate, disillusion with public life; cultural revolt against authority (sex, drugs, etc.)

**Author's approach**: Won't address all theories in definitive form, but must winnow the list
- Tempting to assume one big effect has one big cause (two-career families, materialism, TV)—usually a fallacy
- Social trend as pervasive as civic disengagement probably has multiple causes
- Task: assess relative importance of factors

**Tests for valid explanations**:

1. *Is the proposed explanatory factor correlated with social capital and civic engagement?*
   - If not, difficult to see why factor should be in lineup
   - Example: many women entered paid labor force, but if working women no less engaged than housewives, harder to attribute downturn to two-career families

2. *Is the correlation spurious?*
   - If parents more likely to be joiners than childless, might be important clue
   - However, if correlation entirely due to effects of age, would have to remove declining birth rate from suspect list

3. *Is the proposed explanatory factor changing in the relevant way?*
   - People who move often have shallower community roots—could be important part of answer, but *only if* residential mobility itself had risen during this period

4. *Is it possible that the proposed explanatory factor is the result of civic disengagement, not the cause?*
   - If newspaper readership closely correlated with civic engagement across individuals and time, need to weigh possibility that reduced circulation is result (not cause) of disengagement

Next five chapters examine potential influences on creation and destruction of social capital.

---

## Chapter 11: Pressures of Time and Money

### Time Pressure as Explanation

**Pervasive busyness**: Most obvious suspect behind tendency to drop out
- "I don't have enough time" most common explanation for failure to participate
- "Too busy" most common explanation for not volunteering
- We *feel* busier now than a generation ago
- Mid-1960s to mid-1990s: proportion who "always feel rushed" jumped by more than half
- 1980s-1990s: more reported "work very hard most of the time" and "frequently stayed late at work"
- Groups that feel most harried: full-time workers (especially with advanced education), women, people aged 25-54, parents of younger children, especially single parents

**Economic pressures**: Job insecurity, declining real wages (especially lower two-thirds of income distribution)
- Economic climate mid-1970s to mid-1990s: increasing anxiety
- Combined pressures of time and money may be main explanation for civic disengagement

**Evidence challenges time pressure theory**:

**Aggregate work hours roughly constant since WWII**:
- **Economists Ellen McGrattan and Richard Rogerson**: "number of weekly hours of market work per person in United States has been roughly constant since World War II" (half century during which civic engagement first ballooned then shriveled)
- Important shifts beneath aggregate stability: paid work from men to women, from older to younger people
- Men as whole spent fewer hours in paid work in 1990s than 1950s
- Men over 55 have far more leisure time today (early retirement, some involuntary)
- Clearly women work more hours outside home now than 30 years ago

**Men and women in labor force: probably no major change in work hours**:
- Debate among economists, but best guess: not much change
- Time diary studies: nonwork time burdens reduced, including housework and child care (fewer children today)
- **John Robinson and Geoffrey Godbey**: 6.2-hour-per-week *gain* in free time 1965-1995 for average American—4.5 hours women, 7.9 hours men—due to less housework and earlier retirement

**Robinson-Godbey claim contested but evidence suggests no general decline in free time that might explain civic disengagement**:
- Harris polls: median time Americans say we have "available to relax, watch TV, take part in sports or hobbies, go swimming or skiing, go to movies, theater, concerts, or other forms of entertainment, get together with friends, and so forth" remained rock-steady at 19-20 hours per week over last quarter century
- Time diary studies suggest actually up to twice that much free time
- Despite conflicting evidence, reasonable to conclude *the last three decades have seen no general decline in free time in America that might explain civic disengagement*
- May have been significant net increase in leisure time over these years

**How gains and losses in free time distributed**:

1. Much new "free time" not easily convertible to civic engagement
   - Comes in scattered moments amid harried schedule and in large involuntary chunks to older men forced to take early retirement

2. Less educated Americans gained free time; college-educated counterparts lost it
   - Hours-per-week edge of college-educated Americans over high school dropouts lengthened from 6 hours (1969) to 13 hours (1998)
   - Robinson and Godbey: "working class" has less work, "leisure class" less leisure

3. Dual-career families more common, spending more time at work than they used to
   - Married couples average 14 more hours at work each week in 1998 than 1969
   - For that segment of society—well-educated middle-class parents—whose energies historically provided disproportionate share of community infrastructure, the time bind is real
   - Perhaps witnessed redistribution of free time from people (mostly younger, more educated women) who would have invested it in community engagement toward people (mostly older, less educated men) more likely to consume it privately

**Free hours not necessarily *the same hours***:
- Coordinating schedules more burdensome
- Consistent with fact that *collective* forms of civic engagement declined more rapidly than *individual* forms

**Evidence not entirely consistent with "hassle" theory**:

1. Heavy time demands *not* associated with lessened involvement in civic life, even among people with identical levels of education and income
   - Employed people *more* active civically and socially than those outside paid labor force
   - Among workers, longer hours often linked to *more* civic engagement, not less
   - People who report heaviest time pressure *more* likely to participate in community projects, attend church and club meetings, follow politics, spend time visiting friends, entertain at home

2. **Sidney Verba study**: Amount of free time seems to have little or no effect on whether he or she becomes civically active
   - Only social activity busy, harried people engage in *less* than others: dinner with families

**Positive correlation between civic activity and work hours doesn't mean working longer *causes* greater civic involvement**:
- Way to get something done: give it to busy person
- Some of us more harried precisely because we are civically engaged
- Neither fact implies if we became even busier (working much longer hours), would also become more involved in community life (at some point 24-hour constraint binding)
- Evidence shows hard work does not *prevent* civic engagement
- Time diary studies: people who spend more time at work do feel more rushed, and these harried souls spend less time eating, sleeping, reading books, engaging in hobbies, doing nothing
- Compared with rest of population, they also spend a lot less time watching television—almost 30% less
- However, they do *not* spend less time on organizational activity
- Those always on the run forgo *ER* before Red Cross and *Friends* before friends

**Busy people tend to forgo one activity—TV watching—that is most lethal to community involvement**

### Financial Pressures as Explanation

**Financial anxieties rose over last quarter of 20th century**:
- Early 1970s: inflation triggered by Vietnam War plus two massive global oil shocks brought down curtain on ebullient economic prosperity of 1950s-1960s
- Two fat and happy decades followed by two lean and nervous decades
- 1970s-1980s: financial anxieties mounted among Americans of all walks of life
- Recovery of 1990s didn't erase pervasive uneasiness left by those two decades
- Early 1975: 74% said "our family income is high enough to satisfy nearly all our important desires" (bottom of most serious recession in 40 years)
- 1999: despite 8 uninterrupted years of growth, that barometer of economic satisfaction had fallen to 61%
- Americans remained more troubled and skittish economically than we had been 30 years earlier—perhaps because material aspirations expanded in meantime

**Financial worries and economic troubles profoundly depressing effect on social involvement** (formal and informal):
- Great Depression triggered only significant interruption in rising tide of civic participation and social connectedness during first two-thirds of 20th century
- Contrary to expectations that unemployment would radicalize victims, social psychologists found jobless became passive and withdrawn, socially as well as politically
- As economic situation becomes more dire, focus narrows to personal and family survival
- People with lower incomes and those who feel financially trapped much less engaged in all forms of social and community life than those better off
- Example: even comparing people with identical income and education levels, men and women in financially most worried third attend only two-thirds as many club meetings as people in least worried third

**Financial anxiety associated with less frequent moviegoing**, but also:
- Less time spent with friends
- Less card playing
- Less home entertaining
- Less frequent church attendance
- Less volunteering
- Less interest in politics
- Even social activities with little or no financial cost inhibited by financial distress
- Only leisure activity positively correlated with financial anxiety: watching TV
- When combine financial worries, income, and education to predict various forms of civic engagement and social connectedness, income itself becomes insignificant
- Not low income per se, but financial worry it engenders, that inhibits social engagement
- Even among well-to-do, sense of financial vulnerability dampens community involvement

**Powerful bill of particulars for economic hard times explanation**: Economic hard times lower incomes, raise debt levels, make jobs more precarious, perhaps more demanding. Stress rises, civic engagement falls. Case seems open and shut.

**Defense has strong counterevidence**:

1. Decline in civic engagement appears to have begun before economic troubles of 1970s, and decline continued unabated during booms of mid-1980s and late 1990s
   - Economy went up and down, but social capital only went down

2. Declines in engagement and connectedness virtually as great among affluent segments as among poor and middle-income wage earners
   - Very little sign disengagement concentrated among those who bore brunt of economic distress of last two decades
   - Example: among third of U.S. population *least* troubled by financial worries, attendance at club meetings fell from 13 times per year to 4 times per year
   - Among *most* troubled financially, decline was from 9 times per year to 4 times per year
   - Even among fortunate 1-in-18 Americans who avows family "definitely" has "more to spend on extras than most of our neighbors do," pace of entertaining at home fell from 17 times per year in 1975 to 10 times per year in 1999, while annual club attendance was falling from 13 to 5
   - Economic good fortune has not guaranteed continued civic engagement

**Some observers argue**: Decline in social capital in last 20 years been concentrated among more "marginalized" sectors of population

**Others blame civic disengagement on AWOL, self-centered, upper-middle-class elite** who abandoned traditional civic responsibilities

**Balance of evidence speaks against both views**: Central fact is by virtually all measures of civic disengagement and all measures of socioeconomic status, trends very similar at all levels
- Examined with microscope, dropouts may be faintly greater among financially distressed, but differences slight and inconsistent
- Comfortable not dropping out *more* rapidly than afflicted, but neither dropping out much *less*

**Holding both real income and financial satisfaction constant** (trick done more easily in statistical world than real world) does little to attenuate fall in civic engagement and social connectedness:
- At most, spread of financial anxiety might account for 5–10% of total decline in church attendance, club membership, home entertaining, and the like
- Neither objective nor subjective economic well-being has inoculated Americans against virus of civic disengagement
- **Pressures of time and money are supporting actors in mystery story, but neither easily cast in the lead**

### Women's Employment as Explanation

**Most portentous social change of last half century**: Movement of women out of home into paid labor force
- Fraction of women working outside home doubled from fewer than 1-in-3 (1950s) to nearly 2-in-3 (1990s)
- On average, women spending roughly one more hour per day in paid labor in 1990s than 1960s
- Since there only 24 hours in day, something had to give
- Most, if not all, of that additional time at work recouped by cutting back on household chores and child care
- Seems plausible cutbacks also affected community involvement
- Most of our mothers were homemakers, most invested heavily in social-capital formation—jargony way of referring to countless unpaid hours in church suppers, PTA meetings, neighborhood kaffeeklatsches, and visits to friends and relatives
- However welcome and overdue feminist revolution may be, hard to believe it had no impact on social connectedness
- Could this be primary reason for decline of social capital over last generation?

**Getting job outside home has two opposing effects on community involvement**:
- *Increases opportunity* for making new connections and getting involved
- *Decreases time* available for exploring those opportunities

**Generally speaking, people active in workforce more involved in community life**:
- Role of housewife often socially isolating
- Homemakers belong to different types of groups from working women (more PTAs, fewer professional associations)
- In aggregate, working women belong to slightly more voluntary associations
- Earlier in 20th century, men belonged to more civic and professional organizations and took more active role in public life, but that sex difference faded as women moved into paid workforce

**"Public involvement" gap narrowed downward over last several decades**:
- Activities like working for political party or serving as local organizational leader faded more rapidly among men than among women, some of whom had only recently entered work-related circles of influence
- While number of men running for public office fell by about one-quarter between 1974 and 1994, number of female candidates actually rose over these years, sharply narrowing gender gap, at least at local level
- Similarly, even though membership in bar association lagged behind growth of lawyers, more women lawyers meant relatively more women active in bar association
- In this sense, movement of women toward professional equality tended to increase their civic involvement

**In one specific and expanding category—single moms—evidence quite strong** that work outside home has positive effect on virtually all forms of civic engagement, from club membership to political interest
- With kids to care for and without spouse to help, these women often isolated socially except for connections at work
- In short, work outside home means exposure to larger array of social and community networks
- Insofar as this factor dominant, movement of women into paid labor force certainly did not contribute to national decline of social capital and civic engagement and may actually have muted that decline

**On other hand, women have traditionally invested more time than men in social connectedness**:
- Although men belong to more organizations, women spend more time than men in informal conversation and other forms of *schmoozing*, and they participate more in religious activities
- Precisely because women's traditional investments in social capital were so time-intensive, their rate of investment has been reduced by their movement into paid labor force

**Comparing two women of same age, education, financial security, and marital and parental status**: Full-time employment appears to cut home entertaining by roughly 15%, informal visiting with friends by 25%, volunteering by more than 50%
- Moreover, husbands of women who work full-time are, like their wives, less likely to attend church, volunteer, and entertain at home
- Conversely, other things being equal, women who work full-time (and their husbands) spend more time on personal relaxation (videos, movies, TV, and shopping)—in short, zoning out
- When both members of couple have worked in high-stress jobs all day, relaxation, not frenetic civic engagement, is understandably preferred leisure activity
- These sorts of evidence make it plausible to suppose movement of women into paid labor force has been significant contributor to national decline in community involvement

**In short, work outside home, especially full-time work, is double-edged sword** with respect to civic engagement—more opportunity, but less time
- Because of these crosscurrents, some detailed evidence is hard to reconcile with theory that women's liberation caused our civic crisis
- Example: time diary data between 1965 and 1985 show while decline in actual organizational activity in recent years concentrated among women, employed women actually spending more time on organizations than before, while nonemployed women spending less
- Moreover, time diary data suggest decline in *schmoozing* since 1965 has also been concentrated among nonemployed women
- Decline in PTA membership and club attendance actually been greatest among "traditional moms"—married women with kids at home and no paid employment
- These figures suggest women who work full-time may have been more resistant to slump than those who do not

**These patterns might be, at least in part, optical illusion**:
- Women who have chosen to enter workforce doubtlessly differ in many respects from women who have chosen to stay home
- Perhaps some forms of community involvement appear to be rising among working women and declining among housewives precisely because sort of women who, in earlier era, were most involved with their communities have been disproportionately likely to enter workforce, thus simultaneously lowering average level of civic engagement among remaining homemakers and raising average among women in workplace
- Obviously we have not been running great national controlled experiment on effects of work on women's civic engagement, in which women randomly assigned to work or stay home, so questions of self-selection and causality are difficult to resolve

**Can get further insight into implications of employment for women's civic and social life** by considering simultaneously two dimensions of women's work life:
1. Amount of time spent in work outside home
2. Preference for employment outside home

**DDB Needham Life Style data permit measuring these two dimensions simultaneously**:
- All women in survey asked whether full-time employees, part-time employees, or full-time homemakers
- Those employed (full-time or part-time) asked whether work primarily for personal satisfaction or primarily for financial necessity
- Those who are full-time homemakers asked whether stay at home primarily for personal satisfaction or primarily to take care of children
- In real world such decisions doubtless made for mixture of all these motivations and others besides
- Nevertheless, as crude first cut, this standard question distinguishes between women who are working (or not working) mainly because they *want* to and those who are working (or not working) mainly because they *have* to

**Figure 47 shows how women are distributed across these two dimensions**:
- Column A: women employed full-time primarily out of financial necessity; over last two decades constituted on average 31% of all women
- Their numbers almost doubled from about 21% of all women in 1978 to 36% in 1999
- Column B: women employed full-time primarily for personal satisfaction; 11% of total sample, figure that has not changed much over these two decades
- Of all women who work full-time, fraction who say doing so primarily out of financial necessity has risen from two-thirds to more than three-quarters

**At least in these surveys, *virtually all the increase in full-time employment of American women over the last twenty years is attributable to financial pressures, not personal fulfillment***


<!-- pp. 201-220 -->

## Chapter 11: Women's Work and Civic Engagement (continued)

### Distinguishing Choice vs. Necessity in Women's Work

**Figure 47 framework**: Separates women by work status AND motivation
- Column A: Full-time work by necessity (kids/money) — 31% of women
- Column B: Full-time work for personal satisfaction — 11% of women
- Column C: Part-time work by necessity — 11% of women
- Column D: Part-time work for satisfaction — 10% of women
- Column E: Homemaker (childcare primary reason) — 8% in 1978 → 7% in 1999
- Column F: Not working for personal satisfaction — 37% in 1978 → 23% in 1999

**Key insight**: This distinction helps isolate *consequences* of work vs. *self-selection* effects. Do working women attend church less because work creates time pressure, or because religious women are less likely to work outside the home?

### Full-Time Work Depresses Civic Engagement Regardless of Motivation

**Figure 49 data**: Club meetings per year (compared to average man)
- Homemaker by choice: 2.7 meetings above average
- Part-time by choice: 3.2 meetings above average
- Part-time by necessity: 2.1 meetings above average
- Full-time by choice: 1.4 meetings above average
- Full-time by necessity: 0.7 meetings above average

**Three major findings**:

1. **All women more engaged than men**: Every column rises above baseline, regardless of work status
2. **Full-time work sharply reduces engagement** — whether by choice or necessity. Sharp falloff in right-hand columns of Figure 49
3. **Choice matters**: Women working by choice (whether full-time, part-time, or at home) show higher engagement than women in same situation by necessity. Back row columns are taller than front row

**Lowest engagement**: Women working full-time by necessity — the fastest-growing category of women, incurring the steepest civic penalty

**Highest engagement**: Part-time workers by choice — appears to be a "golden mean" for balancing family, community, and self

### Pattern Extends Beyond Clubs

Same effects appear across:
- **Church attendance**: Full-time workers attend 4 fewer times/year
- **Home entertaining**: 1-2 fewer times/year
- **Visiting friends**: One-third less time
- **Volunteering**: 4 fewer times/year

Full-time work reduces both formal and informal community involvement. Since Figure 48 showed nearly all growth in female employment 1978-1999 was by necessity (not choice), self-selection played minimal role.

### Self-Selection Effect is Modest

Women working by choice are more civically engaged than women working by necessity (compare front vs. back columns in Figure 49). This suggests socially active women were somewhat more likely to enter workforce than their less civic-minded sisters — but compared to work's direct effect, self-selection is modest.

### Policy Implication: Part-Time Work as Solution

> "One practical way to increase community engagement in America would be to make it easier for women (and men too) to work part-time if they wished."

Holding constant education, marital status, parental status, financial situation — the civic advantage of part-time work is NOT merely due to type of women who choose it.

### Important Qualifications

**First qualification**: NOT claiming working women are "to blame" for civic disengagement

Women's movement toward professional equality:
- Released creative energy and increased individual autonomy
- Net plus for American society
- But broader social ledger must include costs of social/community activities collectively foregone
- Previous generation of homemakers engaged in many socially productive activities
- Sons did NOT assume greater share of social responsibilities as evidence shows

**Second qualification**: Full-time employment hasn't inhibited ALL organizational involvement

Women's participation in more public civic activities has been *enhanced* by full-time employment (noted earlier in book). Same for formal membership in professional/service organizations. For some working women, increased *opportunity* for involvement has outweighed decreased *time*, swimming against society-wide current of disengagement.

**Third and most important qualification**: Neither women entering workforce nor financial distress can be the main reason for civic decline

> Based on evidence, best guess: both factors together account for less than *one-tenth* of total decline.

**The emergence of two-career families over the last quarter of the twentieth century played a visible but quite modest role in the erosion of social capital and civic engagement.**

### Evidence from Unaffected Groups

Focus on two groups least affected: unmarried men and married women without full-time employment who are financially comfortable (bachelors and affluent housewives).

**Affluent housewives**:
- Higher *level* of engagement than other women — more visiting, entertaining, club meetings
- But *declines* in these activities are virtually as great among affluent housewives as among other women
- Dropout from public meetings, party work, local leadership has been *greater* among affluent housewives than rest of population

**Bachelors**:
- Similar decline in club meetings, visiting friends, working on community projects, serving as local leader, signing petitions
- At least as great among bachelors as among rest of Americans

**Conclusion**: National civic disengagement over past several decades cannot be attributed primarily to movement of women into paid labor force. The central exculpatory fact: civic engagement and social connectedness have diminished almost equally for both women and men, working or not, married or single, financially stressed or financially comfortable.

---

## Chapter 12: Mobility and Sprawl

### Residential Stability and Civic Engagement

Americans have always been nomadic — nearly 1 in 5 move each year, 2 in 5 expect to move in next five years. From frontier/immigrant past, Americans learned to plunge into new community institutions when moving.

**Nevertheless, frequent repotting disrupts root systems**. Time needed to put down new roots.

**Residential stability strongly associated with civic engagement**:
- Recent arrivals less likely to: vote, have supportive networks, know neighbors, belong to organizations
- People expecting to move in next 5 years are 20-25% less likely to: attend church, club meetings, volunteer, work on community projects
- **Homeowners** much more rooted than renters (only 1 in 4 homeowners expect to move in 5 years vs. 2/3 of renters)
- Homeowners substantially more likely to be involved in community affairs

**Mobile communities** = less well integrated:
- Higher residential turnover → less friendly inhabitants
- Higher crime rates, lower school performance
- Even longtime residents have fewer ties with neighbors in high-mobility communities
- Mobility undermines civic engagement and community-based social capital

### But Mobility Hasn't Increased

**Can rising mobility be the central villain? No.**

Residential mobility has NOT increased over last fifty years. Census records show both long-distance and short-distance mobility have slightly *declined* in recent decades.

**1950s**: 20% of Americans changed residence each year, 7% moved to different county/state
**1990s**: Figures are 16% and 6%

Americans today are slightly *more* rooted residentially than a generation ago:
- 1968: Average American adult lived in same locality for 22 years
- Three decades later: Figure essentially unchanged
- Homeownership rose to all-time record high of 67% in 1999
- Expectations about likelihood of moving have been steady for at least last quarter century

**Verdict on mobility: This theory is simply wrong.**

### But Have We Moved to Less Connected Places?

Even if moving rates are stable, perhaps we've moved to places less congenial to social connectedness.

**Now, as in the past, connectedness differs by community type**. Compared with other Americans, residents of nation's largest metropolitan areas (*both* central cities *and* suburbs):
- 10-15% fewer group memberships
- 10-15% fewer club meetings
- 10-20% less frequent church attendance
- 30-40% less likely to serve as officers/committee members or attend public meetings on local affairs

**Figures 50 and 51 illustrate these differences**. As noted in chapter 7, residents of small towns and rural areas are more altruistic, honest, and trusting. Even among suburbs, smaller is better from social capital point of view. Getting involved in community affairs more inviting when scale of everyday life is small and intimate.

### Is This Just Self-Selection?

Could it be that the *type* of people who congregate in biggest metropolitan areas are predisposed against civic engagement?

**No.** Reexamined evidence holding constant: age, gender, education, race, marital status, job status, parental status, financial circumstances, homeownership, region. Comparing two people identical in all these respects:

Resident of major metropolitan area (central city or suburb) is significantly less likely to:
- Attend public meetings
- Be active in community organizations
- Attend church
- Sign petitions
- Volunteer
- Attend club meetings
- Work on community projects
- Visit friends

**Metropolitans are less engaged because of where they are, not who they are.**

### The Suburbanization of America, 1950-1996

**Figure 52** traces changes in where Americans have lived over last half of twentieth century:

1. **Outside metro areas** (small towns, rural): 44% in 1950 → 20% in 1996
2. **Central city** of metro area: 33% in 1950 → 31% in 1996
3. **Suburbs** (metro but outside central city): 23% in 1950 → 49% in 1996

In 1950s barely half of Americans lived in metro area; in 1990s roughly 4 in 5 did. **Throughout this era we've been moving to places less hospitable to civic engagement.**

Best available research found no evidence of suburbanization abating in 1990s. Thus decline in social connectedness over last third of twentieth century might be attributable to continuing eclipse of small-town America.

### Urban Doom Prophecies vs. Reality

Americans have been moving from countryside to city for more than a century amid constant jeremiads from antiurban prophets:

> **Mark Twain (1867)**: "[New York] is a splendid desert—a domed and steepled solitude, where a stranger is lonely in the midst of a million of his race.... A man walks his tedious miles through the same interminable street every day, elbowing his way through a buzzing multitude of men, yet never seeing a familiar face, and never seeing a strange one the second time.... The natural result is ...the serene indifference of the New Yorker to everybody and everything without the pale of his private and individual circle."

> **Henry George**: American urbanization beyond Gotham — "Squalor and misery, and the vices and crimes that spring from them, everywhere increase as the village grows to the city."

**At least until recently, however, urbanization appears to have had no deleterious effect on civic involvement.** Americans were moving into city in great numbers throughout first two-thirds of twentieth century, all the while civic engagement was high and rising. Recent declines in forms of civic engagement are virtually identical everywhere — in cities big and small, in suburbs, in small towns, and in countryside. No part of America has been immune from this epidemic. **So more must surely be involved than simply urbanization.**

### Suburbanization's Different Character

**Could disengagement be linked not to urbanization, but to suburbanization?**

Suburbs have been feature of American life since mid-nineteenth century, driven by transportation revolutions. Streetcar, then automobile enabled millions to live on leafy urban periphery while enjoying economic, commercial, cultural advantages of city.

Post-WWII: Widespread car ownership + government-subsidized road/home-building boom → accelerated movement to suburbs (not different in kind from earlier trends, but different in degree).

**Suburbanization meant**:
- Greater separation of workplace and residence
- Greater segregation by race and class

Such segregation hardly new to American cities, but took on new character in postwar period. In classic American city neighborhoods tended to be homogeneous, but municipalities were heterogeneous — often crazy-quilt pattern with Ukrainian blocks adjacent to Irish areas, Jewish neighborhoods next to black ones, servants living near upper-class homes they served. **In suburbanized America municipalities were increasingly homogeneous in ethnic and class terms.**

### Initial Postwar Suburban Enthusiasm

Initially, postwar suburbanization produced frontierlike enthusiasm for civic engagement. Booster mythology fostered by suburban developers was positively communitarian.

**Park Forest, Chicago suburb** studied by urbanist **William Whyte** for *The Organization Man*:

> YOU BELONG IN PARK FOREST!
>
> The moment you come to our town you know:
> You're welcome
> You're a part of the big group
> You can live in a friendly small town
> Instead of a lonely big city
> You can have friends who want you—
> And you can enjoy being with them.
> Come out. Find out about the spirit of Park Forest.

**Whyte reported**: Park Forest was "hotbed of participation." With 66 adult organizations and high population turnover making each insatiable for new members, Park Forest probably swallowed up more civic energy per hundred people than any other community in the country.

**Herbert Gans** moved to Levittown, New Jersey to study its social life — reported Levittowners were "hyperactive joiners." Image of suburban life from 1960s studies was one of unusually active involvement in neighborhood activities. Americans seemed to be rediscovering civic virtues of small-town life.

### Later Suburban Fragmentation

As suburbanization continued, however, suburbs themselves fragmented into sociological mosaic — collectively heterogeneous but individually homogeneous. People fleeing city sorted themselves into more and more finely distinguished "lifestyle enclaves," segregated by race, class, education, life stage, and so on.

**White flight** was only most visible form of this movement toward metropolitan differentiation. At century's end some suburbs were upper-middle-class, but many others were middle-middle, lower-middle, or even working-class. Some were white, but others were black, Hispanic, or Asian. Some were child focused, but others composed predominantly of swinging singles or affluent empty nesters or retirees.

Many suburbs had come to resemble theme parks, with uniform architecture and coordinated amenities and boutiques. By 1980s "common interest developments" and "gated communities" began to proliferate — private homeowner associations and visible physical barriers manned by guards supplemented invisible sociological barriers distinguishing each community from neighbors.

**1983**: 15% of development projects in Orange County, California were gated communities
**Within 5 years**: Fraction had doubled

### Homogeneity Reduces Civic Engagement

One might expect numbing homogeneity of these new suburban enclaves to encourage certain social connectedness, if only of "bonding," not "bridging," sort.

**Suburban developers in 1990s** continued to sell community: "Remember the street you grew up on?" ran one Internet ad. "Where neighbors knew neighbors. Live there again—at Greenfield at The Wheatlands. Greenfield is a traditional hometown for families who aspire to the good life."

**Most evidence actually points in opposite direction**. Not only are canvasing politicians and Girl Scouts selling cookies excluded from exclusive communities, but affluent residents themselves also appear to have surprisingly low rate of civic engagement and neighborliness even within their boundaries.

**Eric Oliver**, political scientist, careful survey of community involvement in suburbs across America: Greater social homogeneity of a community, lower the level of political involvement.

> "By creating communities of homogeneous political interests, suburbanization reduces the local conflicts that engage and draw the citizenry into the public realm."

### Suburban Isolation and Privatization

**M. P. Baumgartner**, ethnographer, lived in suburban New Jersey community in 1980s:

More than in compulsive togetherness ascribed to classic suburbs of 1950s, she found culture of atomized isolation, self-restraint, and "moral minimalism." Far from seeking small-town connectedness, suburbanites kept to themselves, asking little of neighbors and expecting little in return.

> **New urbanist architects Andres Duany and Elizabeth Plater-Zyberk**: "The suburb is the last word in privatization, perhaps even its lethal consummation, and it spells the end of authentic civic life."

**Lewis Mumford** (60+ years ago): "Suburbia is a collective effort to lead a private life."

**Now**, privatization of suburban life has become formalized and impersonal. Gated communities are innately introverted, as traditional urban neighborhoods were innately extroverted.

**Robert Lang and Karen Danielsen**, close students of gated communities:

> "In the past, suburbanites used gentle nudges to prod neighbors to act responsibly—when their grass grew a bit too high, for instance. Now a representative from the community association comes by to precisely measure grass and, for a fee, will mow lawns that have grown unruly. The whole process formalizes a social exchange that has historically been informal."

### Kenneth T. Jackson's Conclusion

**Kenneth T. Jackson**, preeminent historian of American suburb:

> [A] major casualty of America's drive-in culture is the weakened "sense of community" which prevails in most metropolitan areas. I refer to a tendency for social life to become "privatized," and to a reduced feeling of concern and responsibility among families for their neighbors and among suburbanites in general for residents of the inner city.... The real shift, however, is the very important one in which our lives are now centered inside the house, rather than on the neighborhood or the community. With increased use of automobiles, the life of the sidewalk and the front yard has largely disappeared, and the social intercourse that used to be the main characteristic of urban life has vanished.... There are few places as desolate and lonely as a suburban street on a hot afternoon.

### Edge Cities and Polycentric Megalopolises

In earlier postwar period the larger structure of typical metropolitan area remained monocentric — people lived in suburbs but continued to travel into central city for work and commerce.

Gradually, however, both jobs and shops migrated into suburbs too → agglomerations of shopping malls, corporate headquarters, office and industrial parks — what **Joel Garreau** calls "edge cities."

Older, radially structured urban areas of Northeast were succeeded by sprawling, polycentric megalopolises of Sunbelt. By beginning of twenty-first century more and more of us commute from one suburb to another. More and more of our shopping is done in megamall in yet a third suburb.

**Segregatory zoning policies** have excluded such gathering places as local shops and restaurants from residential areas, at same time federal tax policy encouraged shopping center boom.

### The Mall as Privatized Public Space

Rather than at grocery store or five-and-dime on Main Street where faces were familiar, today's suburbanites shop in large, impersonal malls.

Although malls constitute America's most distinctive contemporary public space, they are carefully designed for one primary, private purpose — to direct consumers to buy. Despite aspirations of some developers, **mall culture is not about overcoming isolation and connecting with others, but about privately surfing from store to store** — in presence of others, but not in their company.

Suburban shopping experience does not consist of interaction with people embedded in common social network. Fewer and fewer of us actually spend much time in central city or in any other single site.

**One Californian observed**: "I live in Garden Grove, work in Irvine, shop in Santa Ana, go to the dentist in Anaheim, my husband works in Long Beach, and I used to be the president of the League of Women Voters in Fullerton."

**Our lives are increasingly traced in large suburban triangles**, as we move daily from home to work to shop to home.

### The Automobile's Symbiosis with Suburbs

Difficult to overstate symbiosis between automobile and suburb:
- One car per household in 1969 → nearly two cars per household in 1995
- Even though average household size was shrinking
- 1973-1996: Fraction describing second automobile as "necessity" (not "luxury") nearly doubled from 20% to 37%
- By 1990 America had more cars than drivers
- Much of this change occurred recently: As late as 1985 only 55% of new single-family homes included space for 2+ cars; by 1998 that index was 79% and rising

### Increased Time Investment in Automobiles

Suburbanization of last thirty years has increased not only financial investment in automobile, but also our investment of time.

**1969-1995** (government surveys of vehicle usage):
- Average trip to work increased by 26%
- Average shopping trip increased by 29%
- Number of commuting trips per household rose 24%
- Number of shopping trips per household almost doubled
- Number of other trips for personal/family business more than doubled
- Each trip much more likely to be made alone:
  - Average vehicle occupancy fell from 1.9 in 1977 → 1.6 in 1995
  - For trips to/from work, average occupancy fell from 1.3 → 1.15

Since vehicle occupancy cannot fall below 1.0, these figures represent:
- Decline of 1/3 in passenger occupancy for all trips
- Decline of 50% in passenger commuting

### Time Spent Alone in Car

One inevitable consequence of how we organize our lives spatially: We spend measurably more of every day shuttling alone in metal boxes among vertices of our private triangles.

American adults average **72 minutes every day behind the wheel** (Department of Transportation's Personal Transportation Survey) — more than we spend cooking or eating and more than twice as much as average parent spends with kids.

Private cars account for 86% of all trips in America, and 2/3 of all car trips are made alone. This figure has been rising steadily.

### Dominance of Driving Alone to Work

**Commuting** accounts for little more than 1/4 of all personal trips, but for structure of lives of working Americans it is the single most important trip of day.

Number of people who work at home has risen, but proportion remains tiny — less than 4% of workforce in 1997 worked even *one* day a week at home. Home-based workers drive as much as commuting workers (more trips to mall, offsetting fewer trips to work).

**Over last 2-3 decades driving alone has become overwhelmingly dominant mode of travel to work**:
- **1960**: 61% drove to work in private vehicle
- **1995**: 91% drove to work in private vehicle
- All other forms of commuting — public transit, walking, etc. — declined

Mass transit plays small and declining role in transportation of most metropolitan areas nationwide. **1995**: 3.5% of all commuting trips were on mass transit.

Carpooling too has fallen steadily for more than two decades:
- Fraction of all commuters who carpool cut in half since mid-1970s
- Projected to reach only 7-8% by 2000
- **By end of 1990s, 80-90% of Americans drove to work alone**, up from 64% as recently as 1980

### Longer, Farther Commutes

**We are also commuting farther**:
- **1960-1990**: Number of workers who commute across county lines more than tripled
- **1983-1995**: Average commuting trip grew 37% longer in miles
- Travel time increased only 14% because speed of average commute increased by nearly 1/4

**Three factors made for faster travel** (at least in recent past):
1. Switch from carpools/mass transit to single-occupancy vehicles (quicker for individual worker though socially inefficient)
2. Increase in suburb-to-suburb commuting
3. Greater flexibility in work hours

**On the other hand, traffic congestion has metastasized everywhere**. Study of 68 urban areas from Los Angeles to Corpus Christi to Cleveland to Providence: Annual congestion-related delay per driver rose steadily from 16 hours in 1982 → 45 hours per driver in 1997.

### The Car as Private Sanctuary

In short, we are spending more and more time alone in car. Many of us see this as time for quiet relaxation, especially those who came of age in midst of this driving boom.

**Survey in 1997**: 45% of all drivers — 61% of those aged 18-24, though only 36% of those aged 55+ — agreed that "driving is my time to think and enjoy being alone."

### Commuting Time's Impact on Civic Engagement

**The car and the commute are demonstrably bad for community life.**

> **Each additional ten minutes in daily commuting time cuts involvement in community affairs by 10 percent** — fewer public meetings attended, fewer committees chaired, fewer petitions signed, fewer church services attended, less volunteering, and so on.

In fact, although commuting time not quite as powerful an influence on civic involvement as education, it is more important than almost any other demographic factor. Time diary studies suggest similarly strong negative effect of commuting time on informal social interaction.

**Increased commuting time among residents of a community lowers average levels of civic involvement even among noncommuters.** In fact, the "civic penalty" associated with high-commute communities is almost as great for:
- Retired residents and others outside workforce as for full-time workers
- Weekend church attendance as for involvement in secular organizations

This appears to be classic "synergistic effect" — consequences of individual actions spill beyond individuals in question. **In language of economists, commuting has negative externalities.**

### Commuting's Effect Beyond Time Constraints

This otherwise puzzling fact is actually important clue that it is not simply time spent in car itself, but also **spatial fragmentation between home and workplace**, that is bad for community life.

**Example: Lexington, Massachusetts** — transformed over last 50 years from Middlesex country town to bedroom suburb for MIT, Harvard, and high-tech suburbs along route 128. Though still pleasant place to live, it is less self-sufficient civically than when most residents worked in town. Now that many residents commute out each day, many civic organizations have fallen on harder times — affects even residents who still work in town.

Moreover, **work-based ties now compete with place-based ties** rather than reinforcing them. If your co-workers come from all over metropolitan area, you must choose — spend evening with neighbors or with colleagues. (Of course, tired from harried commute, you may well decide to just stay at home by yourself.)

**In short, sprawl is a collective bad, both for commuters and for stay-at-homes.**

### Benefits of Suburban Living

Americans *chose* to move to suburbs and to spend more time driving, presumably because we found greater space, larger homes, lower-cost shopping and housing — and perhaps too, greater class and racial segregation — worth collective price we have paid in terms of community.

**DDB Needham Life Style survey** data on locational preferences suggest that during last quarter of twentieth century — years of rapid suburbanization — suburban living gradually became less attractive compared to residence in either central city or smaller towns. Whatever our private preferences, however, **metropolitan sprawl appears to have been a significant contributor to civic disengagement over last three or four decades for at least three distinct reasons.**

### Three Reasons Sprawl Hurts Civic Engagement

**First, sprawl takes time.** More time spent alone in car means less time for friends and neighbors, for meetings, for community projects, and so on. Though this is most obvious link between sprawl and disengagement, it is probably not the most important.

**Second, sprawl is associated with increasing social segregation**, and social homogeneity appears to reduce incentives for civic involvement, as well as opportunities for social networks that cut across class and racial lines. **Sprawl has been especially toxic for bridging social capital.**

**Third, most subtly but probably most powerfully, sprawl disrupts community "boundedness."** Commuting time is important in large part as proxy for growing separation between work and home and shops.

More than three decades ago, when (we now know in retrospect) civic engagement was at full flood, political scientists **Sidney Verba and Norman Nie** showed that residents of "well-defined and bounded" communities were much more likely to be involved in local affairs. In fact, Verba and Nie found commuting itself to be a powerful negative influence on participation.

Presciently, they wrote:

> "Communities that appear to foster participation—the small and relatively independent communities—are becoming rarer and rarer."

Three decades later this physical fragmentation of our daily lives has had a visible dampening effect on community involvement.

### The "Sprawl Civic Penalty"

Residents of large metropolitan areas incur a **"sprawl civic penalty"** of roughly 20% on most measures of community involvement.

More and more of us have come to incur this penalty over last thirty years. Coupled with suburbanization of American population represented in Figure 52, direct civic penalty associated with sprawl probably accounts for something less than one-tenth of total disengagement outlined in section II of this book.

It, like pressures of time and money, helps explain our national civic disengagement. Yet it cannot account for more than a small fraction of decline, for civic engagement is perfectly visible in smaller towns and rural areas as yet untouched by sprawl.

**Our roundup of suspects is not yet complete.**

---

## Chapter 13: Technology and Mass Media

### The Transformation of Communications and Leisure

When history of twentieth century is written with greater perspective, impact of technology on communications and leisure will almost surely be a major theme.

**Beginning of century**: Communications and entertainment industries hardly existed outside small publishing houses and music halls
**First quarter**: Passed before term *mass media* was invented
**End of century**: Gradual merger of massive telecommunications and entertainment industries had become very foundation for new economic era

### Two Especially Relevant Effects

**First: Individualization of news and entertainment**

No longer must we coordinate our tastes and timing with others to enjoy rarest culture or most esoteric information:
- **1900**: Music lovers needed to sit with scores of other people at fixed times listening to fixed programs; if in small towns (as most Americans), music likely supplied by enthusiastic local amateurs
- **2000**: With my hi-fi Walkman CD, wherever I live I can listen to precisely what I want when I want and where I want
- **As late as 1975**: Americans nationwide chose among handful of television programs
- **Barely quarter century later**: Cable, satellite, video, and Internet provide exploding array of individual choice

**Second: Private consumption of entertainment**

Electronic technology allows us to consume hand-tailored entertainment in private, even utterly alone:
- **Mid-twentieth century**: Low-cost entertainment available primarily in public settings — baseball park, dance hall, movie theater, amusement park
- **1930s**: Radio was rapidly becoming important alternative — first of series of electronic inventions that would transform American leisure
- **Last half of century**: Television and its offspring moved leisure into privacy of our homes

> **T. S. Eliot** observed early in television age: "It is a medium of entertainment which permits millions of people to listen to the same joke at the same time, and yet remain lonesome."

The artifice of canned laughter reflected both:
- Enduring fact that mirth is enhanced by companionship
- Novel fact that companionship could now be simulated electronically

At accelerating pace throughout century, electronic transmission of news and
<!-- pp. 221-240 -->

## The Technology of Mass Entertainment

### The Pace of Electronic Media Adoption

- Electronic entertainment transformed American life more rapidly than any previous technology
- **Table 2** shows technology adoption speeds: TV reached 75% household penetration in just **7 years** (1948 start), faster than telephone (67 years), automobile (52 years), or radio (14 years)
- Radio, VCR, and especially **television** spread 5-10x faster than other ubiquitous devices
- These innovations fundamentally changed how Americans spend time—and whether they're connected to social capital

### Newspapers and Civic Engagement

- **Alexis de Tocqueville** recognized newspapers as essential for democratic association coordination:

> "Only a newspaper can put the same thought at the same time before a thousand readers.... So hardly any democratic association can carry on without a newspaper."

- **Newspaper readers are machers and schmoozers**: controlling for age, education, and rootedness, readers join more organizations, attend more meetings, vote more, volunteer more, visit friends more, and trust neighbors more
- Causation unclear (selection vs. media effects), but **evidence strongly links newspaper reading and good citizenship**
- **Newspaper readership plunging**: 1948 circulation was 1.3 papers per household; by 1998, down **57%** despite education rising 50%
- Decline is **generational**, not individual—newspaper reading is a habit formed early in life

### Figure 53: Generational Succession Explains Newspaper Decline

- 3 in 4 Americans born before 1929 read daily newspapers
- Only half of boomers (1946-1960) continue the tradition
- Just **1 in 4 Gen X'ers** are readers
- Younger cohorts show no signs of becoming readers as they age—**each generation replaces readers with nonreaders**
- Reversing this trend difficult: "each year the ground is slipping away beneath our feet"

### TV and Newspapers: Complements, Not Substitutes

- Americans who watch TV news are **more** likely to read newspapers, not less
- TV news viewers are **more civic** than average Americans, though not as civic as newspaper readers
- Regular viewers of network news, NPR, and local TV news are more knowledgeable, vote more, attend more meetings—but still less distinctively civic than newspaper readers

### The Decline of News Interest Itself

- **Figure 54** shows generational drop in news interest: those born after 1960 have barely half the news interest of their parents/grandparents
- No evidence of life-cycle growth bringing younger generations to elder levels
- Network news audience plunged from **60% of adults (1993)** to **38% (1998)**
- Much of TV news decline is **generational**—audience aging rapidly (average age 57 for nightly news vs. 42 for prime-time)
- Half of Americans watch news with **remote in hand**, ready to switch

### Internet and Cable News: Not a Solution

- Early returns on Internet/cable news are **not encouraging**
- CNN viewers and Internet news followers are "generalists"—they also watch network news and read newspapers
- Internet emerged as **supplement, not substitute** for traditional news sources
- As Internet use expanded in late 1990s, using it for public affairs became relatively **less** important
- Americans relying **primarily** on Internet for news are actually **less civically involved** than those using traditional media

### Television Entertainment: The Real Story

- Most electronic media time/energy devoted to **entertainment**, not news
- 1950: barely 10% of homes had TV; 1959: **90%** had TV—**fastest technology diffusion ever recorded**
- Per capita viewing grew **17-20% during 1960s**, additional 7-8% in 1970s, another 7-8% from early 1980s to late 1990s

### Figure 55: TV Viewing Growth 1950-1998

- Average American now watches roughly **4 hours per day**—highest viewership in the world
- Time researchers **John Robinson** and **Geoffrey Godbey** estimate closer to 3 hours/day using time diaries
- TV absorbs almost **40% of average American's free time in 1995**—increase of roughly one-third since 1965
- Between 1965-1995: gained 6 hours/week leisure time, **spent almost all 6 hours watching TV**

> "Television is the 800-pound gorilla of leisure time." —Robinson and Godbey

### The Privatization of Leisure

- Multiple TV sets per household proliferated: by late 1990s **3/4 of U.S. homes** had more than one set
- **77% of sixth-graders** had TV in bedroom by 1999 (up from 6% in 1970)
- Two-thirds of kids aged 8-18 say TV usually on during meals
- 1980s added VCRs, video games; 1990s added PCs and Internet—more "screen time"
- **Single most important consequence**: TV brought us home
- 1982 Scripps-Howard survey: 8 in 10 popular leisure activities were **home-based**
- DDB Needham data 1975-1999: preference for "spending a quiet evening at home" rose steadily—those preferring this were **heavily dependent on televised entertainment**

### TV as "Electronic Hearth" or Social Isolator?

- Early enthusiasts called TV an "**electronic hearth**" fostering family togetherness
- **James Howard Kunstler's** polemic closer to truth:

> "The American house has been TV-centered for three generations. It is the focus of family life, and the life of the house correspondingly turns inward, away from its neighbors.... The outside world has become an abstraction filtered through television, just as the weather is an abstraction filtered through air conditioning."

### The Shift to Solitary and Habitual Viewing

- Time diaries: husbands and wives spend **3-4x as much time watching TV together** as talking to each other
- Married couples spend **6-7x as much time** watching TV as in community activities outside home
- As multiple sets proliferate, **viewing alone increases**: at least half watch by themselves
- Among children 8-18 watching alone: less than **5% watch with parents**, more than **1/3 entirely alone**

### From Selective to Habitual Viewing (Figure 57)

- **Roper polling 1979-1993** tracked shift: "Do you turn TV on first then look for something, or only if you know there's a program you want?"
- Late 1970s: **selective viewers** (turn on for specific program) outnumbered habitual viewers 3:2
- Mid-1990s: proportions **reversed**
- 1962 *The Manchurian Candidate* observation: "There are two kinds of people—those who walk into a room and turn the TV on, and those who walk into a room and turn the TV off"—**four decades later, first kind more common, second kind rarer**

### Generational Differences in Habitual Viewing

- **Habituation much more pervasive among younger generations** (including boomers vs. their elders)
- Americans born before 1933: **43% selective viewers** in 1993
- Americans born after 1963 (grew up with TV): **23% selective viewers** in 1993—**roughly half the rate**
- Habitual TV watching is **habit acquired in childhood**, unlikely to reverse due to generational succession

### Channel Surfing and Social Surfing

- **Figure 58**: Younger generations (including boomers) more likely to "surf" or "multitask" rather than follow single narrative
- Scholars found 1990s youth have **fewer, weaker, more fluid friendships** compared to 1950s teenagers
- Author suspects link between **channel surfing and social surfing** is more than metaphorical

### TV Throughout the Day (Figure 59)

- DDB Needham Life Style surveys 1993-1998: tracked TV viewing across 10 periods from waking to bedtime
- During **every** period, at least 1/4 of adults report some TV viewing
- After work, fraction rises to more than half, peaking at **86% during "prime time"**
- Roughly **half of all Americans** watch TV while eating dinner; nearly **1/3** during breakfast and lunch
- By century's end, **TV omnipresent in Americans' lives**

### Figure 60: Evening Activities—TV Dominates All

- **81% of Americans** report most evenings they watch TV
- Compare: 56% talk with family, 36% have snack, 27% do chores, 7% walk dog
- Watching TV at night has become **one of the few universals of contemporary American life**

### TV and Civic Disengagement: The Correlation

- **Each additional hour of TV per day** = roughly **10% reduction** in most forms of civic activism (controlling for poverty, age, education, etc.)
- If time diary estimates correct (Americans spent nearly 1 hour more per day on TV in 1995 vs. 1965), that factor alone might account for **perhaps 1/4 of entire drop in civic engagement** over the period

### Two Important Qualifications

1. **Causal direction unclear**: No evidence yet that arrow runs from TV to civic disengagement rather than reverse
2. **Effect comes from hours watched**, not necessarily character of watching/watcher/watched

### Figure 61: Heavy vs. Light TV Viewers (College-Educated, Working-Age)

- Study focuses on working-age, college-educated Americans to screen out lifecycle/education effects
- **Light viewers** (≤1 hour/day) vs. **heavy viewers** (≥3 hours/day):
  - 39% light viewers attended public meeting last year vs. 25% heavy viewers
  - 28% light viewers wrote Congress vs. 21% heavy viewers
  - 29% light viewers played leadership role in local organization vs. 18% heavy viewers
  - Light viewers nearly **3x more likely** to have made a speech (14% vs. 5%)

- Even among this select group, **heavy viewers outnumber light viewers 2:1**
- Major commitment to TV = incompatible with major commitment to community life

### Collective vs. Individual Civic Engagement

- TV particularly **toxic for collective activities** (meetings, committees, political party work)
- Watching lots of TV cuts collective activities like attending meetings or taking leadership roles by as much as **40%**
- Cuts individual activities (letter writing) by roughly **10-15%**
- **TV privatizes leisure time** and **privatizes civic activity**—dampening interactions with others even more than individual political activities

### TV Entertainment Dependence: The Single Most Consistent Predictor

- Half of Americans say "**television is my primary form of entertainment**"
- Asked whether they agree/disagree, this **simple question** is **the single most consistent predictor** of civic disengagement among all factors tested (including education, generation, gender, region, hometown size, work, marriage, children, income, financial worries, religiosity, race, mobility, commuting time, homeownership, etc.)

### What TV Maximalists Miss

- **TV minimalists** (definitely disagree "TV is my primary entertainment") volunteer **9x per year**
- **TV maximalists** (definitely agree) volunteer **4x per year**
- TV minimalists average **18 letters/year** to friends/relatives; TV maximalists **12**
- TV minimalists attend **9 club meetings** annually; TV maximalists **5**
- TV minimalists attend church **27x/year** on average; TV maximalists **19x**
- Reliance on televised entertainment is strong negative predictor of church attendance **even controlling for religiosity**

### Figures 62-66: TV Dependency and Social Disconnection

- **Figure 62**: Volunteering declines steadily from 9x (TV minimalists) to 5x (TV maximalists)
- **Figure 63**: Letter writing drops from 19 (minimalists) to 13 (maximalists)
- **Figure 64**: Club meetings drop from 9.5 (minimalists) to 5.5 (maximalists)
- **Figure 65**: Church attendance drops from 28 (minimalists) to 20 (maximalists)
- **Figure 66**: Community projects and road rage **inverse relationship**—TV minimalists report 3+ community projects and 1.5 finger incidents; TV maximalists report 1.5 projects and 3 finger incidents

- TV dependency associated with **less social communication in all forms**—written, oral, electronic
- Nothing—not low education, not full-time work, not long commutes, not poverty/financial distress—**more broadly associated with civic disengagement and social disconnection than TV entertainment dependency**

### International Evidence

- Negative correlation between TV and social involvement appears in time diaries and surveys from many countries
- Both in U.S. and abroad, heavy TV viewers (controlling for demographics) **significantly less likely to belong to voluntary associations and trust others**
- As TV ownership/usage spread across populations, it was linked to **reduced contacts with relatives, friends, neighbors**
- More TV meant more time at home but **indoors**, at expense of time in yard, street, visiting others' homes

### The Amish Verdict

- Dead-on summary from **Amish community member** in southeastern Pennsylvania responding to ethnographer's question about which technologies to admit/shun:

> "We can almost always tell if a change will bring good or bad tidings. Certain things we definitely do not want, like the television and the radio. They would destroy our visiting practices. We would stay at home with the television or radio rather than meet with other people. The visiting practices are important because of the closeness of the people. How can we care for the neighbor if we do not visit them or know what is going on in their lives?"

### Correlation Does Not Prove Causation

- People who are social isolates to begin with may gravitate toward TV as "line of leisurely least resistance"
- Without true experimental evidence (randomly exposing individuals to TV over long periods), cannot be certain TV itself is the **cause** of disengagement
- Putative effects of TV presumably build up over years—**a few minutes viewing in university lab unlikely to replicate deeper effects**

### Evidence Supporting TV as Cause

1. **Timing**: Epidemic of civic disengagement began little more than a decade after widespread TV availability
2. **Chapter 14 evidence**: Greater youthful exposure of any cohort to TV → greater degree of disengagement today
3. Younger generations exposed to TV throughout lives are **more habitual** in TV usage, and habitual usage associated with lesser civic engagement

### The Canadian "Natural Experiment"

- Strikingly direct evidence from studies of communities **just before and just after** TV introduction
- Most remarkable: three isolated northern Canada communities in 1970s studied by **Tannis MacBeth Williams** and colleagues
- **Notel** (pseudonym): without TV as study began due to poor reception
- **Unitel** and **Multitel**: had TV reception
- Treatment: introduction of single CBC channel to Notel
- During 2-year study: Unitel went from CBC only to CBC + 3 American networks; Multitel had all 4 channels throughout

### Why This Was a True Experiment

> "Except for anachronistically lacking television reception in 1973, [Notel] was typical. It was accessible by road, had daily bus service in two directions, and its ethnic mix was not unusual. The town just happened to be located in a valley in such a way that the transmitter meant to serve the area did not provide television reception for most residents." —Williams

- Study conducted **before widespread VCRs and satellite dishes**—will likely never be another example of essentially TV-free community in industrialized nation

### Results: TV Deflated Community Participation

> "Before Notel had television, residents in the longitudinal sample attended a greater variety of club and other meetings than did residents of both Unitel and Multitel, who did not differ. There was a significant decline in Notel following the introduction of television, but no change in either Unitel or Multitel."

- Clear evidence that **introduction of television deflated Notel residents' participation in community activities**
- No change in control towns (Unitel and Multitel)

<!-- pp. 241-260 -->

### Television's Impact on Community Participation

**Television affects active community members, not just passive ones**
- Research found television impacts participation of those central to community activities, not just peripheral members
- Residents more likely to be centrally involved in community activities absent television than with it present

**Television as cause, not just correlate**
- Major effect of television's arrival was reduction in participation across social, recreational, and community activities for all ages
- **Television privatizes leisure time**

### Three Mechanisms of Television's Civic Impact

**1. Time competition hypothesis**
- Social activities positively correlated: classical music listeners attend Cubs games, do-it-yourself projects correlate with volleyball and public speaking
- **Rolf Meyer-sohn's "the more, the more"** pattern—except for TV
- Television is the principal exception: only leisure activity that inhibits other leisure activities
- TV watching displaces religious participation, social visiting, shopping, parties, sports, and organizational participation
- **John Brehm and Wendy Rahn**: one hour less daily TV viewing equals civic-vitamin equivalent of five or six more years of education
- Displacement effects may be more significant for unstructured activities (hanging out with friends) than formal activities (organizational meetings)

**1970s Roper surveys: Americans "cocooning"**
- 47% reported watching more TV than in past (vs. 16% watching less)—net increase 31%
- 11% spending more time visiting friends/relatives (vs. 38% less)—net decrease 27%
- Shift toward home-based activities, especially TV watching, away from socializing outside the home

**Those watching more TV significantly less likely to:**
- Attend public meetings
- Serve in local organizations
- Sign petitions
- When demographically matched

**2. Psychological effects hypothesis**
- **Robert Kubey and Mihaly Csikszentmihalyi**: beeper study tracking time use and psychic well-being
- Television viewing is relaxing, low-concentration activity
- Viewers feel passive and less alert after watching
- Heavy-viewing evenings: people engage in other low-energy, slothful activities
- Light-viewing evenings: same people spend more time outside home in activities

**Figure 67**: Americans began cocooning in 1970s—massive shift toward home-based activities (especially TV) and away from socializing outside home

**Television as habit-forming and addictive**
- Heavy viewing associated with free time, loneliness, emotional difficulties
- TV attractive for unhappy people when nothing else to do
- Does not help much except as momentary escape
- **Kubey and Csikszentmihalyi**: "Heavy viewers spend more time with TV, but find it is less rewarding.... feeling badly in unstructured and solitary time leads to the use of television.... heavy viewing and the rapid montage of much contemporary television may also help reinforce an intolerance in the heavy viewer for daily moments that are not similarly chocked full of sight and sound"

**Psychological effects cross-culturally validated**
- **Michael Argyle** (British social psychologist): TV induces emotional state described as "relaxed, drowsy, and passive"
- **Sue Bowden and Avner Offer** (British researchers): "Television is the cheapest and least demanding way of averting boredom. Studies of television find that of all household activities, television requires the lowest level of concentration, alertness, challenge, and skill.... Activation rates while viewing are very low, and viewing is experienced as a relaxing release of tension. Metabolic rates appear to plunge while children are watching TV, helping them to gain weight"

**Experimental evidence: viewers demand bribes to give up TV**
- In experimental studies, viewers generally demand major bribe to give up TV
- Report TV less satisfying than other leisure activities and even work
- 1977 *Detroit Free Press*: only 5 of 120 families willing to give up TV for month for $500
- Those who gave up TV experienced boredom, anxiety, irritation, depression
- One woman: "It was terrible. We did nothing—my husband and I talked"

**Television dependence and physical malaise**
- **DDB Needham Life Style surveys**: self-reports on headaches, indigestion, sleeplessness
- Combined into single "malaise" index
- **Figure 68**: Malaise closely associated with dependence on televised entertainment
- Correlation persists after controlling for physical health, financial anxiety, exercise, cigarettes, religiosity, social connectedness, demographics
- Top predictors of malaise: physical health, financial insecurity, low education, TV dependence (all essentially equal)
- TV dependence as disruptive to constitution as financial anxiety and class deprivation
- By end of twentieth century, more than half of Americans said TV was primary form of entertainment

**Television as surprisingly unsatisfying experience**
- Time diaries and beeper studies: for average viewer, television about as enjoyable as housework and cooking
- Ranks well below all other leisure activities and below work itself
- **John Robinson and Geoffrey Godbey**: "Much of television's attraction is that it is ubiquitous and undemanding.... As an activity, television viewing requires no advance planning, costs next to nothing, requires no physical effort, seldom shocks or surprises, and can be done in the comfort of one's own home"

**Pseudopersonal connection hypothesis**
- Television provides kind of pseudopersonal connection to others
- Encountering TV personality face-to-face: powerful feeling you already know them
- Daily cheer of morning anchors or weekly drama reassures us we know these people, care about them, are involved in their lives
- **Joshua Meyrowitz**: "Electronic media create ties and associations that compete with those formed through live interaction in specific locations. Live encounters are certainly more 'special' and provide stronger and deeper relationships, but their relative number is decreasing"
- **Roderick Hart**: Television creates false sense of companionship, making people *feel* intimate, informed, clever, busy, and important—result is "remote-control politics" where we *feel* engaged without *being* engaged
- TV (especially entertainment) satisfies cravings without real nourishment

**Television induces passivity and shirks responsibility**
- Making us aware of every social and personal problem makes us less likely to do anything
- "When the problems of all others become relatively equal in their seeming urgency," many turn to "number one"
- **Shanto Iyengar**: prevailing TV coverage of problems like poverty leads viewers to attribute problems to individuals rather than societal failings, shrinking own responsibility
- **Allan McBride**: content analysis of most popular TV programs shows "television programs erode social and political capital by concentrating on characters and stories that portray a way of life that weakens group attachments and social/political commitment"
- Television surveys disarmingly direct and personal view of world events in setting dominated by entertainment values
- Television privileges personalities over issues, communities of interest over communities of place
- **Television viewing strongly linked to civic disengagement because of psychological impact of medium itself**

### 3. Programmatic Content Hypothesis

**Message matters: specific programming affects civic engagement**
- DDB Needham surveys ask which programs respondents "watch because you really like it"
- Can construct rough ranking of programs that attract most civic vs. least civic audiences

**Pro-civic hierarchy**
- Top: news programs and educational television
- Late 1990s: audiences for *NewsHour* and PBS shows generally more engaged in community life
- These audiences tended to avoid other TV fare

**Anti-civic hierarchy**
- Bottom: action dramas (*The Dukes of Hazzard*, *Miami Vice*), soap operas (*Dallas*, *Melrose Place*), reality TV (*America's Most Wanted*, *A Current Affair*)

**Figure 69: Types of Television Programs and Civic Engagement**
- More time watching news → more active in community
- More time watching soap operas, game shows, talk shows → less active in community
- Even among people spending same hours watching TV, what they watch closely correlated with civic activity
- *NewsHour* vs. *Jerry Springer Show* audiences underscore that not all television is antisocial

**Pro-social programming can have pro-social effects**
- Experimental research shows pro-social programming can encourage altruism
- Public affairs programming can reinforce wider sense of community by communicating common experience to entire nation
- Examples: Kennedy assassination, *Challenger* explosion, Oklahoma City bombing
- Television at civic best can be gathering place, powerful force for bridging social differences, nurturing solidarity, communicating essential civic information

**But must add deaths that purveyed melodrama, not civic enlightenment**
- Diana, JFK Jr., O.J. trial
- Bonds nurtured psychologically compelling but not sociologically compelling
- Each episode captivating but few lead to enduring changes in behavior or connection
- **"Parallel play"**: fairly primitive stage of social development—two kids in sandbox, each playing with toy but not really interacting
- Public spectacles of television leave us at arrested stage of development, rarely moving beyond parallel attentiveness to same external stimulus

### Television Fragmentation and Materialist Values

**"Television 'in the wild'" empirically linked to civic disengagement**
- Program types most closely associated with civic isolation constitute massive and growing share of TV programming
- "Target marketing" and advent of five-hundred-channel cable TV portend further fragmentation
- Number of channels received by average household: 19 (1985) → 49 (1997), continues to rise
- Television's ability to create single national "water-cooler" culture has shrunk
- Early 1950s: two-thirds of Americans watched top-rated program (*I Love Lucy*)
- Early 1970s: top-rated program (*All in the Family*) drew about half national TV audience
- Mid-1990s: audience share of *ER* and *Seinfeld* barely one-third
- Market segmentation provides choice and consumer satisfaction but undercuts TV's role in bringing us together

**Television encourages materialist values**
- According to **George Gerbner** and colleagues, heavy-viewing adolescents "were more likely to want high status jobs that would give them a chance to earn a lot of money but also wanted to have their jobs be relatively easy with long vacations and time to do other things"
- Materialism among college freshmen rose notably during era of maximum television exposure
- In college, students who watch more TV become even more materialistic compared with fellow students who watch less TV or none

### Summary: Electronic Communications Revolution

**Rise of electronic communications: one of most powerful social trends of twentieth century**
- Revolution has lightened souls and enlightened minds
- But also rendered leisure more private and passive
- More time and money spent on individually consumed goods and services
- Americans' leisure increasingly measured in "eyeballs"—watching things (especially electronic screens) occupies more time
- Doing things (especially with other people) occupies less time
- Visual entertainment emphasis especially common among generations reared in last several decades
- Watching TV, videos, computer windows onto cyberspace ever more common
- Sharing communal activities ever less so

**Holiday Bowling Lanes, New London, Connecticut: apotheosis of trend**
- Giant TV screen above each lane displaying evening's TV fare
- Even on full league play night, team members no longer in lively conversation
- Each stares silently at screen while awaiting turn
- Even while bowling together, watching alone

### Generational Impact

**Effects most marked among younger generations**
- **Sven Birkerts** emphasizes historical rupture television signaled
- "There is a ledge, a threshold, a point after which everything is different. I would draw the line, imprecisely, somewhere in the 1950s. That was when television worked its way into the fabric of American life, when we grew accustomed to the idea of parallel realities—the one that we lived in, the other that we stepped into whenever we wanted a break from our living"
- People born after mid-1950s are carriers of the new
- "The momentum of change has already made those designations all but meaningless"

**End of twentieth century TV viewing patterns**
- Watching more TV, more habitually, more pervasively, more often alone
- Watching more programs associated specifically with civic disengagement (entertainment as distinct from news)
- These trends coincided exactly with national decline in social connectedness
- Trends most marked among younger generations
- Americans most marked by TV dependence most likely to have dropped out of civic and social life
- Those who spent less time with friends, less involved in community organizations, less likely to participate in public affairs

**Evidence powerful and circumstantial**
- Cannot be fully conclusive about causal effects (not randomized experiments)
- Heavy users of electronic entertainment certainly isolated, passive, detached from communities
- Cannot be entirely certain they would be more sociable absent television
- **At minimum: television and electronic cousins are willing accomplices in civic mystery, and more likely than not, they are ringleaders**

## Chapter 14: From Generation to Generation

### Age as Key to Civic Decline Puzzle

**Previous findings: civic disengagement widespread but inconclusive**
- Television, sprawl, time and money pressures each contribute measurably
- Even small, shrinking minority insulated from such pressures—affluent single-wage-earner couples living outside major metros, seldom watching TV—have steadily disengaged over last two decades
- Seemingly living in "square" 1950s Pleas-antville, these folks went to half as many club meetings in 1990s as 1970s, five times more likely to be entirely disengaged from community life
- Even in tiny, civic-minded hamlets of pastoral Vermont, attendance at town meetings fell nearly half between early 1970s and late 1990s

**Age: striking exception to civic decline uniformity**
- Age second only to education as predictor of virtually all forms of civic engagement
- Trends in civic engagement *not* uniform across all age categories
- Middle-aged and older people more active in more organizations, attend church more often, vote more regularly, read and watch news more frequently, more philanthropic, more interested in politics, work on more community projects, volunteer more

**Two interpretations of age differences**
1. **Life cycle effects**: People at different ages behave differently because momentarily at different points in common life cycle
2. **Generational effects**: People enduringly belong to different generations

**Examples of each effect**
- **Eyesight**: life cycle effect—vision deteriorates with age for everyone
- **Military service**: generational effect—80% of men born in 1920s served in military vs. 10% born in 1960s, due to world affairs when each group reached eighteen

**Different social consequences**
- Life cycle effects: individuals change, but society as whole does not
- Generational effects: society changes, even though individuals do not
- Eyesight in America won't deteriorate in early decades of twenty-first century, but virtually certain veterans will become rarer

**Determining if age-related differences are generational**
- Need comparable evidence across several decades to follow each cohort through various life stages
- If successive cohorts retrace same ups and downs as they age: life cycle pattern
- If not: more likely age-related differences are generational

### Life Cycle Patterns in Civic Behavior

**Life cycle patterns typically caused by:**
1. Demands of family (marriage and parenting)
2. Slackening of energy (declining from adolescence to old age)
3. Shape of careers (entering and leaving labor force)

**Different forms of civic involvement peak at different life stages**
- Sports clubs attract energies of youth
- Time with friends peaks in early twenties, declines with marriage and kids, rebounds in sixties with retirement and widowhood
- Child-related activities (parent-teacher meetings, picnicking, athletic events) tied to prime parenting years (twenties and thirties)
- Membership in civic organizations and professional societies crests among men and women in forties and fifties
- Blood donation rises to peak in thirties, falls off sharply after fifty
- Money donation rises later in life
- Church involvement spurts during twenties (advent of marriage and children), plateaus, then resumes rising gently among seniors
- Volunteering used to have single peak in thirties (PTA bake sales, Little League coaching)
- Recent decades: second, postretirement spurt in volunteering has appeared

**Figure 70: Membership in Associations Rises and Falls with Age**
- Civic engagement typically traces pattern rising from early adulthood toward plateau in middle age, from which it gradually declines
- This humpback pattern represents natural arc of life's engagements

### Expected vs. Actual Generational Patterns

**If life cycle entirely explained age-related differences:**
- Older Americans should be much less involved civically than middle-aged people
- Classic sociological studies in 1950s and 1960s found exactly that
- By 1990s: middle-aged men and women unexpectedly not much more engaged than their elders

**Baby boomers passing through normal civic life cycle**
- Should have experienced waves of increasing civic involvement as boomers ascended normal life cycle of rising community involvement
- Should have seen boom in PTA membership in 1970s and 1980s
- Should have seen rapidly rising church membership
- Should have seen profusion of civic involvement in 1990s
- By same logic: should look forward to boom in volunteering and philanthropy as boomers retire in 2010s

**Reality: none of those past waves of civic engagement materialized**
- Quite the contrary
- Boomers and successors have not trod same ascending civic path traced by previous generations
- **This civic "dog that didn't bark" is important clue to America's civic decline**
- Expected life cycle upswings swamped by unexpected generational downswings
- Political interest and participation, church attendance, community projects, charitable giving, organizational involvement—all declined largely if not exclusively because of inexorable replacement of highly civic generation by others that are much less so

### Table 3: Generational Patterns of Civic Disengagement

**Examining civic engagement of successive generations at fixed life cycle milestones**
- Table holds life cycle differences constant to focus on generational differences
- Example: newspaper readership at beginning of 1970s
  - Young adults (18-29): 49% read newspaper daily
  - Other three age groups: roughly three-quarters read daily
  - Over sixty: 76% were newspaper readers
- Mid-1990s newspaper readership in same age groups:
  - Young adults: fallen to 21% (relative decline 57%)
  - Over sixty: also slipped but only by 10%
- Rate of decline much faster among younger cohorts than among older cohorts
- People over sixty in 1990s (born in 1930s or earlier) almost as likely to read newspapers as people that age in 1970s
- **Falloff in newspaper readership heavily concentrated in younger generations—younger the cohort, more rapid the decline**

**Pattern applies to virtually every form of civic engagement**
- Disengagement concentrated among younger cohorts, slightest among men and women born and raised before World War II
- Among over-sixty: reading newspapers, signing petitions, writing letters to editor, contacting Congress almost as common in 1990s as in 1970s
- Among youngest category: these activities half as common
- Oldest cohort church attendance essentially unchanged between 1973-74 and 1997-98
- Among under-thirty: fell by nearly one-third
- Even union membership and work for political party (every age group shows falloff): rate of decline significantly faster among younger cohorts

**Last three rows of table: participation in *any* of twelve civic activities**
- Fell by 11% among those over sixty
- Fell by 22% among aged 45-59
- Fell by 32% among aged 30-44
- Fell by 44% among under thirty
- Reading across row for 1970s: familiar life cycle humpback, with oldest cohort significantly less engaged than younger ones
- By 1990s: life cycle hump much flatter, as younger cohorts now only slightly more engaged than elders
- **More recent the cohort, more dramatic its disengagement from community life**
- This strong clue that overall decline in civic engagement had its roots in generational differences

### Figure 71: Generational Trends in Civic Engagement

**Key question: not *how old are people now*, but *when were they young***
- Figure 71 displays various measures of civic engagement according to respondents' year of birth
- Lines up Americans from left to right according to date of birth, beginning with those born in first third of twentieth century, continuing to generation of their grandchildren
- Each successive birth cohort posed series of tests of social capital and civic engagement

**Pattern observed**
- Moving from oldest generation toward younger generations (born around turn of last century to those born during Roaring Twenties): high and relatively stable levels of civic engagement and social capital
- Rather abruptly, starting with men and women born in 1930s: signs of reduced community involvement
- Preboomers still relatively civic in absolute terms but somewhat less so than older brothers and sisters
- Continuing to boomers then X'ers: downward trend in joining, trusting, voting, newspaper reading, church attending, volunteering, being interested in politics continues almost uninterruptedly for nearly forty years
- Attendance rates at churches and clubs decline across all cohorts rather than showing distinctive break in 1930s
- **Figure 71 shows each generation that has reached adulthood since 1950s has been less engaged in community affairs than its immediate predecessor**

**Intergenerational differences are extraordinary**
- Controlling for educational disparities
- Members of generation born in 1920s belong to almost twice as many civic associations as members of generation of their grandchildren born in late 1960s (roughly 1.9 vs. 1.1 memberships per capita)
- Grandparents more than twice as likely to trust other people as grandchildren (50% vs. 20%)
- Vote at nearly double rate of most recent cohorts (80-85% vs. 45-50%)
- Grandparents nearly twice as interested in politics (55% vs. 30-35%)
- Nearly twice as likely to attend church regularly (45% vs. 25%)
- Twice as likely to work on community project (35% vs. 15-20%)
- Almost three times as likely to read daily newspaper (75% vs. 25%)
- Provide lion's share of audience for television news

**Well-established life cycle patterns give little reason to expect youngest generation will ever match grandparents' levels**

### The Long Civic Generation (born 1910-1940)

**Deciphered with this key: Figure 71 depicts long civic generation**
- Born roughly between 1910 and 1940
- Broad group of people substantially more engaged in community affairs and more trusting than those younger than they
- **Core of civic generation: cohort born 1925-1930**
  - Attended grade school during Great Depression
  - Spent World War II in high school (or on battlefield)
  - First voted in 1948 or 1952
  - Set up housekeeping in 1950s
  - Saw their first television when in late twenties
- Since national polling began, this cohort has been exceptionally civic—voting more, joining more, reading more, trusting more, giving more

**Long civic generation played leading civic role despite less formal education**
- Only one-quarter of Americans born between 1900 and 1940 went beyond high school
- Compared with more than half of Americans born after that date
- As far as formal education concerned, members of long civic generation were "self-made" citizens
- **Charles Tilly** (born 1928): "We are the last suckers"

### Why Civic Disengagement Delayed Until 1960s-1980s

**Being raised after World War II was quite different experience**
- Post-war generations exposed to some anticivic X-ray that permanently and increasingly rendered them less likely to connect with community
- **Whatever that force might have been, it—rather than anything that happened during 1970s and 1980s—accounts for most of civic disengagement**
- But why did it take so long for effects to become manifest?
- If roots traced to 1940s and 1950s, why did effects not become conspicuous in PTA meetings, Masonic lodges, Red Cross, bar association, polling places, church pews, bowling alleys until 1960s, 1970s, 1980s?

**Visible effects delayed by two factors:**

**1. Postwar boom in college enrollments**
- Gave America timely civic booster shot
- Forestalled cataclysmic decline in political and social involvement that might otherwise have occurred sooner

**2. (Implied but not fully stated in this excerpt)**
<!-- pp. 261-280 -->

## Generational Succession and Civic Engagement

### The Long Civic Generation's Dominance

- **Long civic generation** (born 1910-1940) reached zenith in 1960, comprising two-thirds of electorate during Kennedy-Nixon election
- Many indices of social capital peaked at "high noon of the long civic generation's day in the sun"
- By 1992, this generation's share cut in half compared to 1960 as boomers and X'ers replaced them
- **Generational math**: Last quarter of 20th century saw boomers and X'ers triple from one out of four adults to three out of four
- This generational replacement is **"the single most important explanation for the collapse of civic engagement over the last several decades"**

> "Like Minerva's owl that flies at dusk, we come to appreciate how important the long civic generation has been to American community life just as its members are retiring."

- Political scientist **Ithiel de Sola Pool** observed in early 1960s: Was disengagement temporary weather or climatic shift? Now appears he spotted a genuine climate change
- Effects lag decades—erosion of social capital became visible only after the underlying process had begun

### The Graying of Civic America

- **Age gap in electoral turnout** widened significantly from 1960s to 1990s
- Early 1970s: People 60+ provided 12% of local organization officers/committee members, 20% of volunteers, 24% of club meeting attendance
- Mid-1990s: These figures rose to 20%, 35%, and 38% respectively, though seniors' population share barely budged
- Older generation's overrepresentation amplifies their voice on controversial issues (e.g., school taxes)
- Mid-1970s: People 45+ accounted for one-third of participants in town meetings and editorial letters
- Twenty years later: Their share in both rose to one-half
- This creates potential for **self-disenfranchisement of younger groups**

### The Baby Boom Generation (1946-1964)

- Oldest boomers in mid-fifties, youngest in mid-thirties as new century opens
- **Best-educated generation in American history**
- Experienced unprecedented affluence and community vitality in youth, but endured harder times as adults than parents did during Great Depression
- **First generation exposed to television throughout their lives**
- Political scientist **Paul Light**: By age 16, average boomer watched 12,000-15,000 hours of TV—"equivalent of 24 hours a day for 15 to 20 solid months"

> "There can be little doubt that television reduced the baby boom's contact with its peers and parents, and that the generation made its first contacts with the real world through the medium."

### Boomers' Political Alienation

- Indelibly marked by 1960s events: civil rights movement, Kennedy/King assassinations, Vietnam, Watergate
- **Distrusting of institutions**, alienated from politics despite campus activism in sixties/seventies
- Less knowledgeable about politics than parents were at comparable age (**Michael Delli Carpini**)
- **Less likely to**: follow politics regularly, express political opinions, have accurate political information, vote, campaign, attend meetings, contribute
- Biographer of sixties generation: Boomers distinguished by what they **reject** (mainstream politics, norms, institutions) not what they embrace

> "It is the rejection of mainstream politics rather than the development of an alternative political direction that most clearly distinguishes the sixties generation from preceding cohorts."

### Boomers' Social Characteristics

- **Slow to marry, quick to divorce**—marriage and parenthood became choices, not obligations
- 96% raised in religious tradition, but 58% abandoned it; only one-third of apostates returned
- **Less comfortable in bureaucracies**, less loyal to firms, more insistent on autonomy
- Grew up in uniformity (two-parent, two-child families, chrome cars, prefab homes, packed classrooms, *I Love Lucy*)
- Great emphasis on **individualism and tolerance for diversity**, rejected traditional social roles
- **Crowded schools** reduced opportunity for social learning and extracurricular participation
- Had to endure **diminished expectations and economic frustrations** due to competitive pressures within large cohort
- More **libertarian attitudes** than elders: less respect for authority, religion, patriotism
- High school classes of 1967 and 1973 were less trusting, less participatory, more cynical about authorities, more self-centered, more materialistic than early boomers
- **Highly individualistic**: more comfortable alone than on a team, with values than with rules
- Less moralistic about drug use—inclined to blame society rather than individuals
- **Tolerant generation**: more open-minded toward racial, sexual, political minorities
- Syndrome of tolerant, cynical, "laid-back" attitudes had **high social cost**—survey analyst **Cheryl Russell** characterizes boomers as **"free agents"**

### Generation X (1965-1980)

- X'ers often blamed by boomers for contemporary American society's troubles (materialism, individualism)
- **Evidence shows**: Erosion of social capital began **before any X'er was born**—X'ers cannot be blamed
- X Generation reflects **continuation of generational course begun after WWII**
- **Table 3 data**: Almost all forms of civic engagement continued to plummet among people in their twenties in the nineties (Gen X'ers)
- X'ers are **"second consecutive generation of free agents"**
- **Extremely personal and individualistic view of politics**
- Came of age celebrating personal goods and private initiative over shared public concerns
- Unlike boomers (once engaged), **X'ers have never made the connection to politics**—emphasize personal/private over public/collective
- **Visually oriented**, perpetual surfers, multitaskers, interactive media specialists
- Shaped by **uncertainty**: slow growth, inflation-prone 1970s-1980s, children of divorce explosion, insecurity
- No collective success stories—**no victorious D-Day, no liberating marches, no triumph over Hitler or racism/war**
- **Very inwardly focused** for understandable reasons

### Gen X Values and Behavior

- **UCLA survey of college freshmen** (Figure 72):
  - Late 1960s/early 1970s boomers: 45-50% rated politics/environment cleanup as very important vs. ~40% financial well-being
  - By 1998 (last X'ers entering college): Politics/environment dropped to 26%/19%, financial well-being shot up to 75%
- **University of Michigan high school seniors survey**: "Having lots of money" rated quite important rose from 46% (1976) to 70% (1990), drifted back to 60-65% (mid-1990s)
- **Political discussions** among high school students only half as common in late 1990s as late 1960s
- **Student election participation** plummeted faster than parents' national election participation: from ~75% (late 1960s) to 20% (mid-1990s)
- **Charitable donation intentions** fell by about a quarter between mid-1970s and mid-1990s
- **Trust collapsed**: High school seniors agreeing "most people can be trusted" sliced exactly in half—from boomers of 1976 (~61% trusting) to late X'ers of 1995 (23% trusting)

### X'ers in Adulthood

- Only 54% of X'er adults feel guilty when they don't vote (vs. 70%+ for older generations)
- **Much less likely to vote**, particularly in local elections
- Compared to older generations at same age: less interested in politics, less informed (except scandal/personality/sports), less likely to attend public meetings, contact officials, attend church, work on community projects, contribute financially
- X'ers **not** especially cynical about politics or political leaders—**those are traits they share with elders**
- But X'ers **are less inclined to get involved themselves**
- Collective action **even more foreign** to X'ers than to boomers

### Depression and Mental Health Trends

- **Public health epidemiologists**: Long-term trend toward increasing **depression and suicide** that is generationally based
- Depression struck **earlier and more pervasively** in each successive generation beginning with cohorts born after 1940
- Study: Of Americans born before 1955, only 1% had suffered major depression by age 75; of those born after 1955, 6% had become depressed by age 24
- Psychologist **Martin Seligman**: "The rate of depression over the last two generations has increased roughly tenfold"

### Youth Suicide Epidemic

- **1950-1995**: Suicide rate among adolescents aged 15-19 more than quadrupled
- Rate among young adults aged 20-24 nearly tripled (beginning at higher level)
- Most increase concentrated among young men; young women attempt suicide more frequently
- **Figure 73**: Pattern is *not* general rise in suicide—explosive growth in youthful suicide coincided with equally remarkable **decline in suicide among older groups**
- First half of 20th century: older people much more likely to commit suicide (accumulation of frustrations/frailties)
- Second half: suicide became less common among older people, more common among younger people
- **As long civic generation aged** (reducing traditionally high rates among old), less well-integrated boomers and X'ers entered population (raising traditionally low rates among young)
- Americans born/raised in 1920s-1930s about **half as likely** to commit suicide as people that age at midcentury
- Americans born/raised in 1970s-1980s **three or four times more likely** to commit suicide

> "The life experiences of people who came of age *after* 1950 were very different from those of people who came of age *before* 1950."

- Broadly similar trend found in many Western countries
- Researchers summarizing hundreds of studies:

> "It is striking that the rise in psychosocial disorders over the last 50 years is a phenomenon that applies to adolescents and young adults and not to older people. The explanation, therefore, has to lie in social, psychological or biological changes that impinge on younger age groups."

### Rising Malaise Among Youth

- **DDB Needham Life Style surveys**: Mid-1970s malaise symptoms (headaches, indigestion, sleeplessness) did not differ by age
- Next two decades: older people's symptoms tended to fade; middle-aged and younger people became more afflicted
- 1975-76 to 1998-99: Adults under thirty ranking high on malaise symptoms jumped from 31% to 45%
- Adults 60+ slipped from 33% to 30%
- Over half of growing gap attributable to added financial worries young people face, but substantial increase in youthful malaise remains unexplained even among financially comfortable
- **Life contentment** declined among people under fifty-five, increased modestly among people over that age
- 1940s-1950s: younger people were *happier* than older people
- By 1975: age and happiness essentially uncorrelated
- By 1999: younger people were *unhappier* than older people
- **Bottom line**: Widening generation gap in malaise and unhappiness—the younger you are, the worse things have gotten over last decades of 20th century in terms of headaches, indigestion, sleeplessness, general satisfaction with life, likelihood of taking your own life

### Social Isolation as Explanation

- Educational sociologists **Barbara Schneider and David Stevenson**: "Average American teenager typically spends approximately three and a half hours alone each day.... Adolescents spend more time alone than with family or friends"
- Compared with teenagers studied in 1950s, young people in 1990s reported fewer, weaker, more fluid friendships
- **Martin Seligman**: Depression epidemic spared close-knit old order Amish community, even though other mental diseases occur at same rate
- Traces growth of depression among younger Americans to **"rampant individualism"** coupled with **"events that have weakened our commitment to the larger, traditional institutions of our society"**

> "Individualism need not lead to depression as long as we can fall back on large institutions—religion, country, family. When you fail to reach some of your personal goals, as we all must, you can turn to these larger institutions for hope.... But in a self standing alone without the buffer of larger beliefs, helplessness and failure can all too easily become hopelessness and despair."

- Evidence shows trend encompasses not merely suicide but chronic symptoms of milder distress
- **Social isolation is well-established risk factor for serious depression** (partly because depressed people choose isolation, partly because isolation causes depression)
- Hard to believe generational decline in social connectedness and generational increase in suicide/depression/malaise are unrelated

### Countervailing Trend: Youth Volunteerism Upturn

- **Important countervailing fact**: Last ten years seen substantial **increase in volunteering and community service by young people**
- 1998 survey of entering college freshmen: record 74% volunteered during last year of high school (vs. low of 62% in 1989)
- Regular volunteerism (at least one hour a week) up: 42% vs. 27% in 1987
- Also confirmed in annual Michigan Monitoring the Future surveys and DDB Needham Life Style surveys
- **Not yet clear** if this reflects stronger public encouragement (including graduation requirements) or undergirding of broader civic infrastructure
- If driven only by official pressure without organizational infrastructure, increase may not prove durable
- More optimistic interpretation: forty-year trend toward generational disengagement is **at last bottoming out**

### Summary: Two Types of Forces

**Society-wide forces** (affected Americans of all ages):
- Especially detrimental to **private socializing** (card playing, entertaining at home)
- Declines moderately strong and visible in short run
- Behavior of individuals of virtually all generations affected
- **Allure of electronic entertainment** likely explanation—transformed how all spend time

**Generational forces** (produced substantial differences across generations):
- Especially affected **public engagement** (religious observance, trust, voting, following news, volunteering)
- Operated through generational succession—effects more gradual, less immediately visible
- Americans born first half of 20th century persistently more likely to vote, go to church, volunteer, keep up with public affairs, trust other people than Americans born second half

**Combined effects**:
- Some activities buffeted by **both** forces (club meetings, family dining, local organizational leadership)
- Because affected by both short-run and long-run changes, evidenced some of **most dramatic changes**:
  - 60% fall in club meetings
  - 53% fall in service as officer/committee member of local group
  - 60% increase in families dining apart

### Generational Change as Overall Explanation

- Link between generational change and declining civic engagement varies by domain
- **Rough summary**: About **half of overall decline in social capital and civic engagement can be traced to generational change**
- To say civic disengagement in contemporary America is largely generational **merely reformulates central puzzle**
- Roots of lonely bowling probably date to **1940s and 1950s**, rather than 1960s-1970s-1980s
- **Central question**: What force could have affected Americans who came of age after WWII so differently from their parents and even older brothers and sisters?

### Potential Explanations That Don't Fit

**Family instability** doesn't fit timing:
- Generational decline in civic engagement began with children of maritally stable 1940s-1950s
- Divorce rate actually fell after 1945
- Sharpest jump in divorce rate occurred in 1970s, long after cohorts showing sharpest declines in civic engagement had left home
- **Working mothers** also exonerated: plunge in civicness among children of 1940s-1950s-1960s happened while mom was still at home

**Economic adversity/affluence/government policies** don't fit:
- Slump affected equally those who came of age in placid fifties, booming sixties, busted seventies, go-go eighties

### War and National Unity

- **William Graham Sumner** (1906): "External conflict increases internal cohesion"

> "A differentiation arises between ourselves, the we-group, or in-group, and everybody else, or the others-groups, out-groups.... The relation of comradeship and peace in the we-group and that of hostility and war towards others-groups are correlative to each other. The exigencies of war with outsiders are what make peace inside.... Loyalty to the group, sacrifice for it, hatred and contempt for outsiders, brotherhood within, warlikeness without—all grow together, common products of the same situation."

- Membership in civic associations spurted after both major wars in 20th century
- Political scientist **Theda Skocpol** extended this to whole of American history
- Union membership historically grown rapidly during and immediately after major wars
- Historians **Susan Ellis and Katherine Noyes**: To understand origins of American volunteering, must consider history of American involvement in wars

> "Volunteers are frequently active in the movements that lead to war, in the support of efforts to win war, in the protest against war, and in rebuilding society after war."

### World War II's Civic Impact

**Civil War precedent**:
- Women in North formed Ladies' Aid Societies for bandages, clothing, tents
- Led to U.S. Sanitary Commission (largest relief organization during and after war)
- **Clara Barton** formed American Red Cross in 1881
- Gave powerful boost to fraternal associations (Knights of Pythias, Grange, Benevolent and Protective Order of Elks, Ancient Order of United Workmen, Grand Army of the Republic)—all founded 1864-1868
- Similar spurt in voluntary activity associated with WWI

**WWII's extraordinary civic burst**:
- Virtually every major association examined (PTA, League of Women Voters, ASME, Lions Club, American Dental Association, Boy Scouts) sharply expanded "market share" between mid-1940s and mid-1960s
- Similar postwar spurts in other community activities: league bowling, card playing, churchgoing, United Way giving
- Brought **shared adversity and shared enemy**
- Ushered in period of intense patriotism nationally and civic activism locally
- Directly touched nearly everyone
- **16 million men and women served** in armed forces (including 6 million volunteers)
- Of men born in 1920s (core of "long civic generation"), nearly **80% served in military**
- Millions of front windows displayed blue stars (emblem of son/husband in armed forces) and gold stars (lost loved one)
- Draft decisions lay in hands of thousands of lay draft boards across country

**Home front mobilization**:
- Patriotic themes pervaded popular culture (radio, newspapers, Hollywood, Broadway, Tin Pan Alley)
- Historian **Richard Lingeman**: "American flags were displayed everywhere—in front of homes, public buildings, fraternal lodges. Elks, Lions, Kiwanis, Rotary, even trailer camps, gas stations, and motor courts had them"
- War reinforced solidarity even among strangers:

> "You just felt that the stranger sitting next to you in a restaurant, or someplace, felt the same way you did about the basic issues."

**Voluntary cooperation emphasized**:
- Government sought voluntary cooperation, resorted to controls piecemeal—not least out of careful political calculation
- Democratic Party operative opposing gas rationing before 1942 elections: "An appeal by the President for voluntary cooperation will get patriotic support ... and will be politically safer"
- Treasury secretary **Henry Morgenthau** pressed for massive advertising campaign to sell War Bonds, hoping bond campaigns would "make the country war-minded"
- **Batman** flogged war bonds from comic book covers
- **Betty Grable** auctioned off nylons for $40,000
- **Marlene Dietrich** toured sixteen Ohio towns in a Jeep
- Worked: 25 million workers signed up for payroll savings plans; 1944 E-bond sales absorbed 7.1% of after-tax personal income

**Scrap drives** (superstar crooner **Bing Crosby**):

> Junk ain't junk no more, 'cause junk can win the war.
> What's junk to you has a job to do, 'cause junk ain't junk no more.
> Pots and pans, old garbage cans, the kettle that doesn't pour.
> Collect today for the USA, 'cause junk can win the war.

- June 1942: President asked public to turn in old tires, rubber raincoats, garden hose, rubber shoes, bathing caps, gloves—"whatever you have that is made of rubber"
- Boy Scouts posted at filling stations to remind drivers to donate car floor mats
- In less than four weeks roughly 400,000 tons of scrap rubber—six pounds for every man, woman, child in country (or at front)—collected

**Volunteer corps**:
- First six months of 1942: defense corps expanded from 1.2 million to 7 million
- By mid-1943: more than 12 million Americans registered
- With armbands, whistles, flashlights, volunteers supervised blackouts, planned gas decontamination, practiced first aid
- Chicago April 1942: 16,000 block captains took oath of allegiance in mass ceremony in Coliseum
- Local communities raised funds through "socials" to build observer posts for aircraft spotters
- Recruitment meeting in Hannibal, Missouri: parade followed by town meeting packed 4,000 people (another 15,000 outside because no room)
- **Red Cross volunteers** nationwide skyrocketed from 1.1 million (1940) to 7.5 million (1945)—rolling bandages, ferrying blood donors, training for emergency work

**Youth participation**:
- Junior Service Corps, High School Victory Corps, Scouts, Junior Red Cross, and 4-H (which took lead in Victory Garden program)
- At peak: nearly 20 million Victory Gardens in backyards and vacant lots, yielding 40% of all vegetables grown in country
- **Gary, Indiana eighth-graders** (two-year period) activities: taught infant care; collected phonograph records; distributed WAR WORKERS SLEEPING signs; sold war stamps at exhibition of captured Japanese submarine; discussed curfew law with City Council; distributed anti-black market pledge cards; took auxiliary fireman and police training; collected 500,000 pounds of wastepaper; sold average of $40,000 worth of war stamps a month; delivered Community Chest material to every home in city; sponsored Clean Plate campaign; participated in War Bond and tin can drives; collected library books for servicemen

**Junior Leagues and Civilian Defense Volunteer Offices (CDVOs)**:
- Social historian **Julie Siebel** recounted instructive example
- Prewar Junior Leagues brought together privileged young ladies to socialize and volunteer for local "good works"
- As early as 1929 introduced concept of "volunteer bureau" as clearinghouse for local volunteerism
- Before Pearl Harbor: AJLA working with **Eleanor Roosevelt** (former Junior Leaguer) to convert existing volunteer bureaus into official Civilian Defense Volunteer Offices
- With outbreak of war, AJLA became de facto government's Office of Civilian War Services
- By end of 1943: 4,300 CDVOs established nationwide
- Volunteers fixing school lunches, coordinating day care centers, running scrap drives, organizing social welfare activities
- After war many successfully transitioned to peacetime service
- 1947: 390 such bureaus still in operation (more than five times number existing before war)
- Multiply this example manifold to see organizational mechanisms undergirding massive postwar civic renaissance

**War's mobilizing power**:
- Not romanticizing ubiquity or effectiveness, or even esprit de corps generated
- As war progressed, gradually became clear energies (particularly of adult volunteers) could be better invested elsewhere
- Many programs sputtered to stop by 1944
- In meantime, demonstrated **mobilizing power of shared adversity**
- Sociologist **Lloyd Warner**: studying impact on one town, found sense of "unconscious well-being" because "everyone is doing something to help in the common desperate effort in a co-operative rather than a private spirit"
- Historian **Richard Polenberg**: "To a large extent, participation in a common cause tended to enhance feelings of comradeship and well-being"
- Almost surely no accident that those Indiana eighth-graders (and older brothers/sisters) became in later years dependable members of long civic generation

**Accentuating civic and economic equality**:
- War fostered social solidarity by accentuating equality
- Important that celebrities like **Joe DiMaggio, Clark Gable, William McChesney Martin** (head of NYSE), and all four sons of FDR entered armed services
- Relatively few celebrities saw combat, but instructive comparison with Vietnam War (notorious social inequality in military service contributed to widespread cynicism)
- Materially: combination of plentiful work in war industries, unionization, high taxes, rationing, perhaps other factors meant **WWII was probably most leveling event in American economic history**
- Fraction of all personal wealth held by top 1% fell from 31% (1939) to 23% (1945)
- Share of income received by top 5% fell from 28% to 19%

### War's Negative Effects

- Not all social changes fostered by WWII were good for American social capital
- Powerful explosion of solidarity and self-sacrifice triggered by Pearl Harbor did not continue throughout war
- Shortages and rationing led to hoarding and black marketeering
- Polenberg notes: "The longer the war lasted, the more the balance shifted from public and collective to private and personal concerns.... One in five Americans told interviewers that buying scarce goods at black market prices was sometimes justified"
- Vast population shifts disrupted families and communities, exacerbated regional, racial, and class tensions
- When massive new war plants sprouted in Ypsilanti (Michigan), Pascagoula (Mississippi), and Seneca (Illinois), conflict erupted between old-time residents and newcomers: "Folks in houses think trailer people are vermin"
- Racial tensions heightened by war—most obviously Japanese Americans interned in California, but also increased anti-Semitism and violent episodes like 1943 race riot in Detroit (twenty-five blacks and nine whites killed)
- In historical perspective: social changes spawned by war contributed directly to black civil rights advances of 1950s-1960s

**War's vindication and collective sacrifice**:
- As 20th century ends, Americans learned that no story is all heroes (we sometimes feel heroes don't really exist)
- But most Americans in 1945 felt war had been a just one and their terrible collective sacrifice—all those sons and daughters who would not come home—had been in some measure vindicated by victory
- This was not feeling repeated in 1950s in Korea or 1960s in Vietnam
- Long-term research on veterans: while Vietnam vets have been relatively isolated socially even decades after war, vets of WWII were more socially integrated

**Kennedy's call to unity** (1946):
- When 29-year-old **John F. Kennedy** running for Congress said:

> "Most of the courage shown in the war came from men's understanding of their interdependence on each other. Men were saving other men's lives at risk of their own simply because they realized that perhaps the next day their lives would be saved in turn. ...We must work together.... We must have the same unity that we had during the war."

- Most listeners must have nodded
- He and they had already formed the **long civic generation**
- Fifteen years later when he admonished nation, "Ask not what your country can do for you; ask what you can do for your country," to former Gary eighth-graders (now just turned thirty and settling down), it must have rung true in way that sadly it no longer does to most Americans

### War and Television as Twin Explanations

- One plausible explanation for strong generational effects: replacement of cohort whose values and civic habits were formed during period of heightened civic obligation with others whose formative years were different
- Generational patterns reinforce argument in previous chapter
- **Long civic generation was last cohort of Americans to grow up without television**
- More fully any given generation exposed to television in formative years, the lower its civic engagement during adulthood
- Chapter 13 showed: men and women raised in sixties, seventies, eighties not only watch television *more* than those born in thirties, forties, fifties—they also watch television *differently*—more habitually, even mindlessly
- Different ways television is used linked in turn to different degrees of civic engagement
- Although more research needed, seems likely effect of TV (chapter 13) and effect of generation (this chapter) are in some respects opposite sides of same coin

### Shift from Communal to Material Values

- Political scientist **Wendy Rahn**: generational differences continue to mark values expressed by successive cohorts more than half a century later (Figure 75)
- Changes probably part of larger societal shift toward individual and material values and away from communal values
- Figure 72 showed unmistakable evidence of transformation in values expressed by college freshmen over years
- Comparable evidence of similar shift across American society
- **Roper polls** (1975): To identify elements of "the good life," 38% of all adults chose "a lot of money," and identical 38% mentioned "a job that contributes to the welfare of society"
- Same question posed every three years; by 1996: those aspiring to contribute to society slipped to 32%, while those aspiring to lot of money leaped to 63%
- Other increasingly important elements: vacation home (rising from 19% in 1975 to 43% in 1996), second color TV (10% to 34%), swimming pool (14% to 36%), second car (30% to 45%), travel abroad (30% to 44%), job that pays more than average (45% to 63%), "really nice" clothes (36% to 48%)
- By contrast: happy marriage (84% to 80%), children (74% to 72%), "an interesting job" (69% to 61%) all declined
- **Figure 76**: Changes in American definition of "the good life" during last quarter of 20th century
- Much of growth in materialism attributable to generational replacement—cohort less concerned about material goods passes from scene, replaced by cohort who gives more priority to second color TV and really nice clothes

> "Community" means different things to different people: community of nations, Jamaica Plain, gay community, IBM community, Catholic community, Yale community
<!-- pp. 281-300 -->

## Chapter 14 Conclusion: Generational Change and Civic Engagement (continued)

### Generational Differences in Meaning of Community

- **Yankelovich Partners survey** (late 20th century) asked what "community" meant to Americans
- **Figure 77**: All generations cite family and friends most commonly as sources of belonging
- Coworkers equally important across generations (despite Chapter 5 findings)
- **Key finding**: Gen X'ers nearly half as likely as pre-1946 cohort to feel sense of belonging to:
  - Neighborhood
  - Church/synagogue
  - Local community
  - Various groups and organizations
- Baby boomers fall midway between older and younger generations
- **Electronic ties more important to Gen X** than older generations, but even for younger cohort, **kith and kin twenty times more important than cyber-friends**

### Loss of Wider Community Ties

- Younger generation returns to civic communities (residential, religious, organizational) without offsetting focus on belongingness beyond family, friends, coworkers
- Strong ties remain, but no longer complemented/reinforced by wider community ties
- Decline attributable to **replacement of unusually civic generation** by less embedded children and grandchildren

### The WWII Generation's Civic Legacy

- Decline shaped by **habits and values influenced by mid-century global cataclysm** (WWII)
- Not arguing war is necessary or praiseworthy for civic reengagement
- Must acknowledge enduring consequences—some powerfully positive—of "the war"
- Without glorifying martial virtues or moral sacrifice

> "When a generation of Americans early in the twentieth century reflected on both the horrors of war and the civic virtues that it inculcated, they framed their task as the search for 'the moral equivalent of war.'" (reference to early 20th century Americans)

- **Steven Spielberg's "Saving Private Ryan"** addresses this dilemma effectively
- Practical implication for civic renewal: finding moral equivalent of war

---

## Chapter 15: What Killed Civic Engagement? Summing Up

### Suspect #1: Family Structure Change

**Evidence of family breakdown:**
- Century-long divorce rate increase (accelerated mid-1960s to mid-1970s, then leveled)
- Rise in single-parent families
- One-person households more than doubled since 1950 (rising widows living alone)
- **General Social Survey**: Married adults fell from 74% (1974) to 56% (1998)
- Adults with children at home fell from 55% to 38%
- **Census Bureau**: Married-with-kids households (archetypal Ozzie and Harriet) dropped from 40% (1970) to 26% (1997)

**Impact on civic engagement: Minimal**
- Marriage and children do change social network types (more community organizations, less informal socializing)
- **Only two organizational affiliations strongly related to marital/parental status**:
  1. Church and youth-related activities
  2. School affairs (PTA, Scouts, public meetings on school matters)
- Parents more likely to volunteer than demographically matched singles/childless
- Church/youth activities are two most common volunteering sites in America

**Activities NOT boosted by marriage/parenthood:**
- Marriage and children **negatively correlated** with sports, political, cultural groups, business/professional groups, service clubs, ethnic organizations, neighborhood associations, hobby groups
- Married people attend **fewer** club meetings than singles
- Married people slightly more likely to give/attend dinner parties, entertain at home, take active role in local organizations
- Married people **less likely** to spend time informally with friends and neighbors
- Marriage rate decline should have moved social activities from home to public settings
- **No generic effects on civic engagement from marriage decline**
- Interest in politics slightly higher among single/childless adults than married people with parents
- **Having kids more important** than marriage per se for local involvement (leadership, meetings, volunteering)
- Effect doesn't extend beyond school/youth activities

**Divorce and civic engagement:**
- Divorce negatively related to religious organizations
- Unrelated (positively or negatively) to other civic involvement forms
- Divorced people (vs. never married) don't entertain friends less, volunteer less, attend club meetings less, work on fewer community projects
- Actually sign slightly more petitions, attend more public meetings, write Congress more
- **Divorce itself not seriously implicated in general civic disengagement trend**

### The Family-Religion Link

- Traditional family down, religious engagement down (a little)
- Probably some link, but nature unclear
- Could be: family dissolution → lower religious involvement
- Could be: lower religious involvement → greater acceptance of divorce/non-traditional family forms
- Decline of traditional family may have contributed to decline of traditional religion
- Reverse equally possible
- **Evidence NOT consistent** with thesis that overall decline in civic engagement and social connectedness attributable to traditional family decline
- Decline in family obligations should have freed up time for more social/community involvement

**Hypothetical scenario**: Holding traditional family structure constant and statistically giving extra weight to married people and parents:
- Might produce more religious participation
- Would produce more school and youth group involvement
- Volunteering would modestly increase
- **However**: No effect on secular organizations (Kiwanis to NAACP to AMA)
- No halt to decline in political activities (voting, party work)
- Would **decrease** time with friends and neighbors even more
- Apart from youth/church engagement, **none of major declines** in social capital and civic engagement can be accounted for by traditional family structure decline
- Important reasons for concern about erosion of traditional family values, but **civic disengagement is not among them**

### Suspect #2: Race and the Civil Rights Revolution

**Race fundamentally connected to American social history**
- Decline in social connectedness and social trust began after greatest successes of civil rights revolution (1960s)
- Timing suggests possibility of **civic "white flight"** — legal desegregation led whites to withdraw from community associations
- Controversial and cannot be settled definitively here

**Three key facts:**

1. **Racial differences in associational membership not large** until 1980s
   - Controlling for education and income, blacks belonged to more associations than whites (more likely to belong to religious and ethnic organizations, no less likely for any other type)
   - Chapter 8 showed racial differences in social trust very large even controlling for education, income, etc.
   - Reflect real experiences over many generations, not collective paranoia

2. **Erosion of social capital affected all races**
   - Inconsistent with "white flight" thesis
   - African Americans dropping out of religious/civic organizations at least as rapidly as white Americans
   - Sharpest drop in civic activity between 1970s and 1990s was among college-educated African Americans
   - Among whites, pace of civic disengagement **uncorrelated with racial intolerance or support for segregation**
   - Avowedly racist/segregationist whites no quicker to drop out than tolerant whites
   - Decline in group membership essentially identical among whites who favor segregation, oppose it, and blacks

3. **Generational differences (Chapter 14) hard to reconcile with white flight theory**
   - Why should disengagement be hardly visible among Americans who came of age in first half of century (when society objectively more segregated and subjectively more racist) than 1960s-1970s?
   - If racial prejudice responsible, disengagement should be especially pronounced among most bigoted individuals and generations
   - But it's not

**Conclusion:**
- Evidence not conclusive but shifts burden of proof
- Racism a primary explanation for growing civic disengagement? Virulent racism continues in American society
- Evidence suggests **reversing civil rights gains would do nothing to reverse social capital losses**

### Suspect #3: Big Government and the Welfare State

**Timing of downturn in social connectedness** suggests to some observers: important cause is big government and welfare state growth
- By "crowding out" private initiative, state intervention has stunted civil society

**Some government policies destroyed social capital:**
- **Slum clearance policies** (1950s-1960s) replaced physical capital but destroyed social capital by disrupting existing community ties
- Certain social expenditures and tax policies may have created disincentives for civic-minded philanthropy

**However, harder to see which government policies responsible for decline in:**
- Bowling leagues
- Family dinners
- Literary clubs

**Empirical approach**: Examine civic engagement and public policy differences across political jurisdictions
- Among U.S. states: differences in social capital appear **essentially uncorrelated** with various welfare spending or government size measures
- Citizens in free-spending states no more engaged than citizens in frugal ones
- Cross-national comparison sheds light: Among advanced Western democracies, social trust and group membership **positively correlated** with government size (if anything)
- Social capital highest in **big-spending welfare states of Scandinavia**

**This simple analysis cannot tell us:**
- Whether social connectedness encourages welfare spending
- Whether welfare state fosters civic engagement
- Whether both result of some other unmeasured factor(s)
- Sorting out underlying causal connections would require much more thorough analysis
- Even this simple finding not easily reconciled with notion that government undermines social capital

**Trends in American government size over last half century (Figure 78):**
- Only two things really changed regarding government size relative to U.S. economy (last half century):
  1. Defense spending generally declined steadily (1951-1998)
  2. State and local spending rose steadily (1947-1975)
- Two things have **NOT really changed**:
  1. Size of federal domestic spending (averaged 2.2% of GNP late 1940s and late 1990s; 2.7% at peak mid-1960s)
  2. Relative size of federal vs. state and local spending (last 25 years)

**Social capital trends:**
- Increased a lot 1947-1965
- Decreased a lot 1965-1998
- **Figure 78 seems inconsistent** with any theory blaming decline of social capital or civic engagement on either big government or relative size of federal government vs. state/local government

### Suspect #4: Capitalism and the Market

**If big government not primary cause**, how about big business, capitalism, and the market?
- Social critics long feared capitalism would undermine preconditions for social ties and trust
- Grand masters of 19th-century social theory (**Georg Simmel, Karl Marx**) argued market capitalism created "cold society" lacking interpersonal warmth necessary for friendship, devaluing human ties to mere commodities

**Problem with this generic theory:**
- Explains too much
- America epitomized market capitalism for several centuries during which stocks of social capital and civic engagement went through great swings
- **A constant can't explain a variable**

**One version of economic determinism may have more validity:**
- **Gradual but accelerating nationalization and globalization of economic structures**
- Replacement of local banks, shops, other locally based firms by far-flung multinational empires often means decline in civic commitment by business leaders
- As Wal-Mart replaces corner hardware store, Bank of America takes over First National Bank, local owners succeeded by impersonal markets
- Incentives for business elites to contribute to community life atrophy

**Urbanist Charles Heying** showed how **"corporate delocalization"** in last third of 20th century tended to strip Atlanta of civic leadership
- Social cohesion and civic commitment of Atlanta's elite rose from 1930s to peak in 1960s, then declined to 1990s
- Very much same trajectory as other measures of social capital
- Heying offers suggestive evidence of similar trends in places as diverse as Chicago, Philadelphia, Dayton, Shreveport
- One of Boston's top developers complained privately about demise of "the Vault" (celebrated cabal of local business leaders)

> "Where are the power elite when you need them? They're all off at corporate headquarters in some other state."

**Global economic transformations having important impact on community life across America**
- Link most direct regarding larger philanthropic and civic activities
- Less clear why corporate delocalization should affect readiness to attend church social, have friends over for poker, or even vote for president
- Nevertheless, **connection between civic disengagement and corporate disengagement worth exploring**

---

## SECTION FOUR: So What?

## Chapter 16: Introduction

### The Civic Nostalgia Market

**By virtually every conceivable measure**, social capital eroded steadily and sometimes dramatically over past two generations
- Quantitative evidence overwhelming
- Most Americans didn't need charts/graphs to know something bad happening in communities and country
- Americans have growing sense at some visceral level of disintegrating social bonds
- No coincidence that on eve of millennium, **market for civic nostalgia hotter than market for blue-chip stocks**

**Examples:**
- **Tom Brokaw's book** profiling heroic WWII generation got mixed reviews from critics but was runaway best-seller
- In Los Angeles: on-again, off-again movement to rename LAX airport after actor **Jimmy Stewart** (military hero in real life who brought civic heroes **Jefferson Smith** and **George Bailey** to silver screen)
- **American nostalgia in late 20th century**: no run-of-the-mill, rosy-eyed remembrance of things past
- Attempt to recapture a time when public-spiritedness really did carry more value and when communities really did "work"

**As we buy books and rename airports:**
- Seem to be saying that at profound level **civic virtue and social capital do matter**

### Does Social Capital Matter?

**Yes** — impressive and growing body of research suggests civic connections help make us **healthy, wealthy, and wise**
- Living without social capital not easy
- Whether one is villager in southern Italy, poor person in American inner city, or well-heeled entrepreneur in high-tech industrial district

**To believe social capital benefits individuals and communities:**
- Must first understand how social capital works its magic
- High levels of trust and citizen participation operate through variety of mechanisms to produce socially desirable outcomes
- Mechanism(s) at work vary by circumstance and outcome

### How Social Capital Works

**1. Resolving Collective Action Problems**

**Social scientists concerned about "dilemmas" of collective action:**
- Such dilemmas ubiquitous, dynamics straightforward
- People often might all be better off if they cooperate, with each doing her share
- But each individual benefits more by shirking her responsibility, hoping others will do work for her
- Moreover, even if she is wrong and others shirk too, she still better off than if she had been only sucker
- If every individual thinks others will do work, nobody will end up taking part, all worse off than if all had contributed

**Examples:**
- Supporting government through tax system
- Limiting lawn sprinklers and long showers during arid summers
- These and other coordination challenges go by various names: "collective-action problems," "the prisoner's dilemma," "the free-rider problem," "the tragedy of the commons"
- All share one feature: Best solved by institutional mechanism with power to ensure compliance with collectively desirable behavior
- **Social norms and networks that enforce them provide such mechanism**

**2. Greasing the Wheels of Community Advancement**

**Where people are trusting and trustworthy:**
- Subject to repeated interactions with fellow citizens
- Everyday business and social transactions less costly
- No need to spend time and money making sure others will uphold their end of arrangement or penalizing them if they don't

**Economists and political scientists demonstrated how social capital translates into:**
- Financial capital and resource wealth for businesses and self-governing units
- **Nobel Prize-winning economist Kenneth Arrow** concluded:

> "Virtually every commercial transaction has within itself an element of trust, certainly any transaction conducted over a period of time. It can be plausibly argued that much of the economic backwardness in the world can be explained by a lack of mutual confidence."

**3. Widening Awareness of Interconnected Fates**

**People with active and trusting connections to others:**
- Whether family members, friends, or fellow bowlers
- Develop or maintain character traits good for rest of society
- **Joiners become more tolerant, less cynical, and more empathetic** to misfortunes of others
- When people lack connections to others: unable to test veracity of their own views, whether in give-and-take of casual conversation or in more formal deliberation
- Without such opportunity: more likely to be swayed by worst impulses
- No coincidence that random acts of violence (such as 1999 spate of schoolyard shootings) tend to be committed by people identified as **"loners"**

**4. Information Conduits**

**Networks that constitute social capital serve as conduits for flow of helpful information** that facilitates achieving our goals

**Example: Job searches through personal connections (Chapter 19):**
- Many Americans—perhaps even most—get jobs through personal connections
- If we lack that social capital, economic prospects seriously reduced
- Even if we have lots of talent and training ("human capital")
- Similarly, communities that lack civic interconnections find it harder to share information and thus mobilize to achieve opportunities or resist threats

**5. Psychological and Biological Processes**

**Social capital operates through psychological and biological processes to improve individuals' lives:**
- Mounting evidence suggests people whose lives are rich in social capital cope better with traumas and fight illness more effectively
- **Social capital appears to be complement, if not substitute, for:**
  - Prozac
  - Sleeping pills
  - Antacids
  - Vitamin C
  - Other drugs we buy at corner pharmacy

> "Call me [or indeed almost anyone] in the morning" might actually be better medical advice than "Take two aspirin" as cure for what ails us

### Illustrative Example: The Smiths and the PTA

**Consider stylized example (technically fabricated, depicts reality for many parents):**
- **Bob and Rosemary Smith**, parents of six-year-old Jonathan
- Live in urban community full of both delights and troubles
- Support public education in principle
- Would like first-grader exposed to children from diverse backgrounds (opportunity public schools provide)
- But Smiths' local elementary school is shambles: teachers demoralized, paint chipping off walls, no money for extracurricular activities or computer equipment
- Worried about Jonathan's ability to learn and thrive in this environment
- **Choice**: Pull child out of public schools and pay dearly to put him in private school, OR stick around and try to improve public school

**If Smiths want to stick around and start PTA:**
- Chances they will be able to do so depend upon two things:
  1. Existence of other concerned parents also likely to join
  2. Likelihood such association will be effective in improving school conditions
- **Here social capital comes in**:
  - More Smiths know and trust their neighbors
  - Greater their ability to recruit and retain reliable members of new PTA
  - In cohesive neighborhoods filled with lots of overlapping connections
  - Individuals more easily learn who can be counted on
  - Can make better use of moral suasion to ensure continued attention to problems at hand

**Assume Smiths succeed in starting PTA:**
- Several months later: active membership of seventeen parents
- What does this new institution, this addition to stock of social capital, do for individuals involved and community at large?

**Benefits:**
- Belonging to PTA almost certainly inculcates civic skills in parents
- People who might never have designed project, given presentation, lobbied public official, or spoken up at meeting are pressed to do so
- PTA serves to establish and enforce norms of commitment and performance on part of school officials, teachers, perhaps even students
- Allows for deepening of interpersonal bonds and "we-ness" between families and educators
- On more personal note: PTA meetings bound to establish or strengthen norms of reciprocity and mutual concern among parents
- These connections will almost certainly pay off in myriad unexpected ways in future:
  - If Bob loses his job: will now have fifteen other adults upon whom he can call for employment leads or even simple moral support
  - If Rosemary decides to start lobbying group to press for better child health facilities in city: will have fifteen other potential lobbyists to aid in her cause
  - At very least: Bob and Rosemary will have another couple or two with whom they can catch movie on Friday nights
- All these gains—civic skills, social support, professional contacts, volunteer labor, moviegoing partners—arose because Smiths wanted to put computers in their kid's school

**Community connectedness not just about warm fuzzy tales of civic triumph:**
- In measurable and well-documented ways, **social capital makes enormous difference in our lives**

### Five Illustrative Fields

**This section considers five illustrative fields:**
1. Child welfare and education
2. Healthy and productive neighborhoods
3. Economic prosperity
4. Health and happiness
5. Democratic citizenship and government performance

**Evidence that social capital makes us smarter, healthier, safer, richer, and better able to govern a just and stable democracy**

---

### Geographic Pattern of Social Capital in America

**Comparing differences in social capital and civic engagement across fifty states:**
- Most evidence drawn from work of other scholars in many disciplines
- Seek analytic leverage by comparing differences across states
- Since comparisons will appear in several different guises, useful to describe geographic pattern of social capital in contemporary America

**To rate average social capital of various states:**
- Combined number of independent measures summarized in **Table 4**
- From variety of sources compiled state-level measures of:
  - Participation in range of civic and political activities during preceding year
  - Group membership
  - Attendance at public meetings on town or school affairs
  - Service as officer or committee member for some local organization
  - Attendance at club meetings
  - Volunteer work and community projects
  - Home entertaining

**Table 4: Measuring Social Capital in the American States**

*Components of Comprehensive Social Capital Index | Correlation with Index*

**Measures of community organizational life:**
- Served on committee of local organization in last year (percent): 0.88
- Served as officer of some club or organization in last year (percent): 0.83
- Civic and social organizations per 1,000 population: 0.78
- Mean number of club meetings attended in last year: 0.78
- Mean number of group memberships: 0.74

**Measures of engagement in public affairs:**
- Turnout in presidential elections, 1988 and 1992: 0.84
- Attended public meeting on town or school affairs in last year (percent): 0.77

**Measures of community volunteerism:**
- Number of nonprofit (501[c]3) organizations per 1,000 population: 0.82
- Mean number of times worked on community project in last year: 0.65
- Mean number of times did volunteer work in last year: 0.66

**Measures of informal sociability:**
- Agree that "I spend a lot of time visiting friends": 0.73
- Mean number of times entertained at home in last year: 0.67

**Measures of social trust:**
- Agree that "Most people can be trusted": 0.92
- Agree that "Most people are honest": 0.84

**These fourteen indicators:**
- Of formal and informal community networks and social trust
- Turn out sufficiently intercorrelated that they appear to tap single underlying dimension
- In other words: fourteen indicators measure related but distinct facets of community-based social capital
- Combined into single **Social Capital Index**
- Table 4 summarizes these fourteen indicators and their correlation with summary index

**Differences among states on underlying measures substantial:**
- Ratios of roughly 3:1 between high- and low-ranking states
- Social trust ranges from 17% in Mississippi to 67% in North Dakota
- Average number of associational memberships per capita varies from 1.3 (Louisiana, North Carolina) to 3.3 (North Dakota)
- Turnout in recent presidential elections varied 42% (South Carolina) to 69% (Minnesota)
- Number of nonprofit organizations per 1,000 inhabitants ranges from 1.2 (Mississippi) to 3.6 (Vermont)
- Average number of club meetings attended per year varies from 4 (Nevada) to 11 (North and South Dakota)
- Volunteering rate varies from 5 times per year (Nevada, Mississippi, Louisiana) to twice that (Utah)
- Fraction of population reporting attending public meeting on town or school affairs in previous year ranges from 10% (Georgia, New York) to 32% (New Hampshire), 29% (Utah), 26% (Wisconsin)

**Correlations in Table 4 imply:**
- Interstate differences go together
- Places with dense associational networks tend to have frequent public meetings on local issues
- Places with high electoral turnout tend to have high social trust
- Places with lots of local clubs tend to support many nonprofit organizations
- **Figure 80**: Maps differences in social capital and civic engagement across American states, much like weather map

**Geographically speaking:**
- National social-capital "barometric map" fairly straightforward
- Primary "high-pressure" zone centered over headwaters of Mississippi and Missouri Rivers, extends east and west along Canadian border
- Primary "low-pressure" area centered over Mississippi Delta and extends outward in rising concentric circles through former Confederacy
- California and mid-Atlantic states lie near national average
- **Can explore effects of different levels of social capital** by comparing quality of life in these different states
- Minnesota and Mississippi differ from one another in many ways, not merely in their level of social capital
- Must be cautious about inferring causation from mere correlation
- Contrasts summarized in Figure 80 provide useful initial test bed for exploring what difference social capital might make

### Historical Roots: Tocqueville's Observation

**Cursory glance at map of America's social-capital resources leads to question:**
- "Where in the world did these differences come from?"
- Answering in detail is task for another day
- But this pattern has deep historical roots

**Alexis de Tocqueville** (patron saint of contemporary social capitalists) observed precisely same pattern in travels in America of 1830s:
- Attributing it, at least in part, to patterns of settlement:

> "As one goes farther south [from New England], one finds a less active municipal life; the township has fewer officials, rights, and duties; the population does not exercise such a direct influence on affairs; the town meetings are less frequent and deal with fewer matters. For this reason the power of the elected official is comparatively greater and that of the voter less; municipal spirit is less wide awake and less strong.... Most of the immigrants who founded the northwestern states came from New England, and they brought the administrative habits of their old home to the new."

**Well-trod paths of migration helped establish regional and local patterns of social capital in contemporary America:**
- Interstate differences astonishingly similar to differences in "state political culture" as drawn from 1950s by political historian **Daniel Elazar**
- Who traced them in turn to patterns of 19th-century immigration

**One surprisingly strong predictor of degree of social capital in any state in 1990s:**
- Fraction of its population that is of **Scandinavian stock**

**Still more striking:**
- Spatial correlation between low social capital at end of 20th century and slavery in first half of 19th century
- **More virulent system of slavery then, less civic state today**
- **Slavery was social system *designed* to destroy social capital** among slaves and between slaves and freemen
- Well-established networks of reciprocity among oppressed would have raised risk of rebellion
- Egalitarian bonds of sympathy between slave and free would have undermined very legitimacy of system
- After emancipation: dominant classes in South continued to have strong interest in inhibiting horizontal social networks
- Not happenstance that **lowest levels of community-based social capital found where century of plantation slavery followed by century of Jim Crow politics**
- **Inequality and social solidarity are deeply incompatible**

**Whether patterns of immigration and slavery provide sole explanation:**
- For contemporary differences in levels of social capital
- Issue deserves more concerted attention than can be devoted here
- However: clear historical continuities relevant to one aspect of current inquiry
- Whether social capital is cause or merely effect of contemporary social circumstance
- If regional and local patterns of civic engagement and social connectedness were evanescent and mutable, then correlations between social capital and other social facts (like educational performance or public health or crime) might well reflect *effect* of those factors *on* social capital
- If, on other hand, regional and local profiles of social capital represent long-standing traditions, then **more plausible that social capital is *cause*, not merely *effect*, of contemporary social circumstance**

### Evidence Scope and Limitations

**Evidence presented in this section on wide range of individual and collective benefits from social capital:**
- While impressive in scope, neither exhaustive nor conclusive
- Scholars in fields as far-flung as medicine, criminology, economics, urban sociology, and state politics actively exploring correlates and consequences of social capital
- Much more work needed to prove power of social capital
- In particular: show in detail how and when its effects are clearest and most beneficial
- **Do not offer generalizations in this section as final word**
- But evidence reviewed shows that in measurable ways **it matters** that social capital and civic engagement have declined in America over last several decades
- Same evidence strongly suggests that in many disparate domains important to Americans today **more social capital and civic engagement would improve things**
<!-- pp. 301-320 -->

## Chapter 18: Safe and Productive Neighborhoods

### Criminology and "Social Disorganization" Theory

- Scholars, especially criminologists, have long puzzled over why some neighborhoods have more vandalism, graffiti, street crime, gang scuffles
- Neighborhood characteristics persisted over decades despite population turnover
- Beginning 1920s, criminologists developed "ecological" theories of crime and juvenile delinquency
- Theories focused on **"social disorganization"** as engine of bad behavior
- Disorganization marks urban communities with: high population turnover, anonymous neighbors, ethnically mixed groups, rare local organizations, disadvantaged youths trapped in "subcultures" cut off from adult world

### Robert J. Sampson on Crime and Social Capital

- **Criminologist Robert J. Sampson** summarizing empirical studies: Even controlling for poverty and other factors, communities characterized by:
  - (a) Anonymity and sparse acquaintanceship networks
  - (b) Unsupervised teenage peer groups and attenuated control of public space
  - (c) Weak organizational base and low social participation in local activities
  - Face increased risk of crime and violence
- Example: Living in high-mobility neighborhood doubles risk of becoming crime victim vs. stable neighborhood
- "Social disorganization" school didn't adequately explain *how and why* these characteristics produced increased crime

### Jane Jacobs and *The Death and Life of Great American Cities*

- **Jane Jacobs** (1961 classic): **"Social capital"** (term she helped invent) differentiates safe/organized cities from unsafe/disorganized ones
- Scathing indictment of twentieth-century urban planning and renewal efforts
- Argued: Cities configured to maximize informal contact among neighbors = safer streets, better child care, happier residents
- Regular contact with local grocer, families on front stoop, priest walking blocks, street fairs, conveniently traversed parks → sense of continuity and responsibility in local affairs
- > "The sum of such casual, public contact at a local level—most of it fortuitous, most of it associated with errands, all of it metered by the person concerned and not thrust upon him by anyone—is a feeling for the public identity of people, a web of public respect and trust, and a resource in time of personal and neighborhood need."
- Decades since, many scholars across disciplines elaborated these insights
- Conclusion: Higher levels of social capital, all else equal, translate into lower levels of crime

### State-Level Analysis: Homicide and Social Capital

- Figure 84 shows states with more social capital have dramatically fewer murders
- Inverse relationship "astonishingly strong—as close to perfect as one might find between any two social phenomena"
- Many reasons why high-social-capital states might have low homicide rates (wealthier, better educated, less urban, more egalitarian income distribution)
- Further analysis controlling for these factors: relationship between social capital and safe streets is real
- Social capital about as important as poverty, urbanism, racial composition as determinant of homicide prevalence
- **Social capital is *more important* than a state's education level, rate of single-parent households, and income inequality** in predicting murders (1980-95 period)
- Correlation remains strong when controlling for statewide levels of fear about crime—implies causal arrow runs, at least in part, from social capital to crime

### The Southern Violence Puzzle

- Why is the South different? Murder rates much higher in former Confederacy since before Civil War
- This difference continued undiluted throughout twentieth century
- During 1980s and 1990s, murder rate in South roughly 2x that in North
- Regional distinction found among both whites and blacks
- Many interpretations offered: psychological, cultural, societal, economic, even racial
- Regional difference persists even controlling for race, age, economic inequality, urbanization, education, poverty, and other established predictors of murder rates
- Something about "southernness" associated with high potential for lethal violence

**Competing explanations for Southern violence:**
- "Southern world view that defines the social, political, and physical environment as hostile … the symbiosis of profuse hospitality and intense hostility toward strangers"
- "Culture of honor" manifest in nineteenth-century dueling and traceable to eighteenth-century immigration patterns

- Figure 84 suggests social capital (or its absence) may be the missing link
- Once differences in social capital taken into account, hoary regional difference vanishes
- South is no more violent than expected given its well-established social-capital deficit
- Explanation accounts not only for gross difference between North and South, but also for differences *within* North and South
- **Lethal violence is endemic wherever social capital is deficient**

### Pugnacity and Social Capital

- DDB Needham Life Style surveys question: "I'd do better than average in a fist fight"
- On average, 38% of Americans pick the pugnacious alternative
- Men 2x as likely to agree as women (53% to 26%), but women slowly narrowed truculence gap (20-25% late 1970s → 30% late 1990s)
- Significant state-to-state differences
- Nearly half of Louisiana, West Virginia, New Mexico residents agree vs. less than third in South Dakota, Maine, Iowa, Minnesota, New Hampshire, Nebraska
- Figure 85 shows pugnacity strongly correlated with low social capital
- Perhaps in absence of emollient effects of community connectedness and social trust, self-help system of enforcing social order has emerged
- Citizens in low-social-capital states readier for a fight (perhaps because they need to be) and predisposed to mayhem

### Neighborhood Effects on Crime and Delinquency

- State differences dovetail with research examining crime/delinquency rates at local or census-tract level
- Studies use sophisticated statistical techniques to explore "neighborhood effects" on problems from child abuse to dropout rates to teen pregnancy to drug use
- Unifying premise: A person's behavior depends not only on own characteristics, but also on characteristics of neighbors, school peers, etc.
- Rigorous debate over whether studies actually proven anything besides tendency of likeminded people to congregate in same places
- Critics note: Clustering appears because families with similar values or parenting practices feel more comfortable living near one another
- Even if neighborhood effects exist, might be trivial compared to "family effects" like parental nurturing and guidance

**Despite criticisms:**
- Sheer number and diversity of studies finding neighborhood effects on crime have persuaded author effects are real
- Although magnitude varies, scholars demonstrate that over and above individual predisposition, kids who live amid other risk-taking kids are more likely to fall into bad patterns
- Boston example: Kids whose neighborhood peers use drugs, commit crimes, befriend gang members are themselves substantially more likely to do so, regardless of initial proclivities
- Chicago: Young black men in neighborhoods with white-collar professionals 3x more likely to graduate high school than comparable young men in neighborhoods with less educated residents
- Dozens more studies suggest people profoundly motivated not merely by their own choices/circumstances, but also by choices/circumstances of neighbors
- My fate depends on not only whether *I* study, stay off drugs, go to church, but also on whether *my neighbors* do these things

### How Neighborhood Effects Work

- Recent scholarly efforts to understand processes better
- Researchers believe social capital—or lack of it—is big piece of puzzle
- On one hand, presence of social capital (individuals connected through trusting networks and common values) allows enforcement of positive standards for youths, offers access to mentors, role models, educational sponsors, job contacts outside neighborhood
- Social networks provide emotional and financial support for individuals and supply political leverage and volunteers for community institutions
- By contrast, absence of positive norms, community associations, informal adult friendship and kin networks leaves kids to own devices
- Such settings: youths most likely to act on shortsighted or self-destructive impulses

### Gangs as Misguided Social Capital

- In such settings, youths most prone to create own social capital in form of gangs or neighborhood "crews"
- **Sociologist Robert Sampson:** Low social capital is one of primary features of socially disorganized communities
- Best evidence on changing levels of neighborhood connectedness: Most Americans less embedded in neighborhood than a generation ago
- Due in part to:
  - Women (long stalwart neighborhood builders) now much more likely away at work during day than their mothers
  - Professional men spending longer hours on job than their fathers
- As noted in Section II, people less likely today to socialize with neighbors and work on community projects

### The Inner-City Crisis and Urban Flight

- Decline in neighborhood social capital (community monitoring, socializing, mentoring, organizing) is one important feature of inner-city crisis, in addition to purely economic factors
- Many students of urban life have commented on flight of jobs and middle-class families from American cities
- Their departure represents drain of both human and financial capital and, by extension, social capital

### William Julius Wilson: *The Truly Disadvantaged*

- **William Julius Wilson** (nation's leading urban sociologist), 1987 classic
- > "The basic thesis is not that ghetto culture went unchecked following the removal of higher-income families in the inner city, but that the removal of these families made it more difficult to sustain the basic institutions in the inner city (including churches, stores, schools, recreational facilities, etc.) in the face of prolonged joblessness. And as the basic institutions declined, the social organization of inner-city neighborhoods (defined here to include a sense of community, positive neighborhood identification, and explicit norms and sanctions against aberrant behavior) likewise declined."

### Elijah Anderson: Philadelphia's Moral Cohesion Erosion

- **Urban ethnographer Elijah Anderson:** Based on years studying inner-city Philadelphia, documented steady erosion in "moral cohesion" of low-income neighborhoods
- Links decline of social capital to exodus of financial and human capital
- Departure of middle-class blacks "has diminished an extremely important source of moral and social leadership within the black community"
- Senior statesmen and stateswomen of neighborhood (the "old heads") have stuck around, but numbers dwindling, lost moral authority
- Male "old head" was "a man of stable means who was strongly committed to family life, to church, and, most important, to passing on his philosophy, developed through his own rewarding experience with work, to young boys he found worthy"
- "Been losing prestige and credibility as a role model" as legitimate jobs have disappeared and illicit economic activity proved highly lucrative
- Community "mothers" (once occupied porch stoops, served as neighborhood's eyes and ears) now "overwhelmed by a virtual proliferation of 'street kids'—children almost totally without parental supervision, left to their own devices"
- These women no longer enjoy informal permission they once had to intervene on behalf of neighbors
- > "As family caretakers and role models disappear or decline in influence, and as unemployment and poverty become more persistent," Anderson concludes, "the community, particularly its children, becomes vulnerable to a variety of social ills, including crime, drugs, family disorganization, generalized demoralization, and unemployment."

### Chicago Neighborhoods Study: Sampson, Raudenbush, and Earls

- People who live and work in inner cities recognize people and processes Anderson describes
- Not only in minority and impoverished neighborhoods that social-capital deficits lead to crime and social pathologies
- Anderson's ground-level insights about how social capital underpins healthy neighborhoods quantified in sophisticated analyses of neighborhood and individual data
- One of best: widely noted study of Chicago neighborhoods by **Robert J. Sampson**, **Stephen Raudenbush**, and **Felton Earls**
- Based on extensive survey and crime data
- Study found two characteristics—**mutual trust and altruism among neighbors, and their willingness to intervene when they see children misbehaving**—went a long way to explain why some neighborhoods less crime prone than others
- A neighborhood's **"collective efficacy"** was better predictor than poverty or residential instability of whether person likely to be victimized
- Other measures of social capital (individual participation in local organizations, number of neighborhood-based programs, extent of kin and friendship ties in neighborhood) didn't seem to make much difference
- Authors conclude: > "Reductions in violence appear to be more directly attributable to informal social control and cohesion among residents."

### British Crime Data: Sampson and W. Byron Groves

- Earlier study by Sampson and **W. Byron Groves** analyzed British crime data
- Found in areas where people connected through tight bonds of friendship and looser yet more diverse acquaintanceship ties, and where people active in local committees and clubs, there are fewer muggings, assaults, burglaries, auto thefts, etc.
- **Most interesting finding:** Traditional neighborhood "risk factors" (high poverty and residential mobility) may not be as big a part of crime problem as most people assume
- Sampson and Groves's analysis: While poorer, less stable areas do have substantially higher rates of street robbery, this is not simply because of poverty and instability per se
- Rather, these places have higher crime rates in large part because adults don't participate in community organizations, don't supervise teenagers, and aren't linked through networks of friends
- Similarly, study of dozen New York neighborhoods found participation in community organizations helped lessen effects of socioeconomic disadvantage on juvenile delinquency
- **Put another way:** Young people rob and steal not only because they are poor, but also because adult networks and institutions have broken down

### Family Social Capital and Neighborhood Effects

- Just as neighborhoods can affect families, families can affect neighborhoods
- In economists' terms, family social capital has "positive externalities," spilling out of home and into streets
- Northern California scholars found: Presence of lots of stable families in neighborhood associated with lower levels of youthful lawbreaking, not because adults serve as role models or supervisors, but because adults rear well-adjusted and well-behaved kids
- Thus "good families" have ripple effect by increasing pool of "good peers" that other families' kids can befriend
- If we think of youthful troublemaking as communicable disease (sort of behavioral chicken pox spreading through high schools and friendship groups), then stable families provide vaccines that reduce number of contagious kids capable of infecting others

### Integration Paradox and "Decent" Values

- Yet integration of families into neighborhoods may not always be beneficial
- If neighborhood norms and networks at odds with what ethnographer Anderson calls "decent" values, then families who become enmeshed in community may run afoul of own better natures
- Northern California high school students study: Extent to which parents knew child's friends, and knew parents of those friends, was strong indicator of child's classroom engagement and refusal to use alcohol and drugs
- But such positive effects of "parents knowing parents" found only in areas where school engagement and substance abuse were not a problem
- In areas where students more troubled, social integration of parents actually exacerbated problems of living in community with poorly adjusted peers
- **In other words, social integration into a community of bad actors may not produce good results**

### Gangs as Social Capital

- Inner-city gangs might also be seen as misguided attempt at neighborhood-based social capital building in areas where constructive institutions sadly lacking
- Although experts agree gangs hard to identify and count, most evidence suggests numbers growing
- Some gangs are hierarchical enterprises whose sole business is business, especially marketing drugs and guns
- Other gangs closer to mutual aid societies based on horizontal bonds of interpersonal trust, reciprocity, and friendship defended to the death
- In many cases gang members tolerated and well integrated into mainstream community

### Ruth Horowitz on Latino Gangs in Chicago

- **Ruth Horowitz:** Excellent study of Latino gangs in Chicago
- Describes extensive social capital that existed within them:

> The Lions have been together as a group for almost ten years and during that time there has been a continual exchange, both individual and collective, of goods, services, and personal information. Small exchanges have occurred continuously but the larger obligations often take years to fulfill. The constant lending of money or buying of rounds of beer provides a daily continuity of social relationships and the flow of exchanges. Whoever has cash pays for the beer; no questions are asked, no accounts are recorded. The same is true of small loans and meals. The more serious mutual obligations, such as owing someone for help in an ongoing struggle for precedence or for going to jail without revealing the names of the other participants, are often continued over an extended period.

- Former Los Angeles gang member **Sanyika Shakur** explained such long-term obligations in language of streets: > "If you are in this 'hood,
<!-- pp. 321-340 -->

## Chapter 18 (continued): Social Capital in Poor Communities

### Gangs as Social Capital

- Gang life involves **reciprocal obligations** and **norms** that serve members' interests—similar to bowling teams
- Gang member quote: "If you leave and are successful, you're obligated. You have double indemnity: you have the cultural obligation, and you have the 'hood obligation... the cultural obligation: If you don't come back and contribute, you'll get your 'guild pass' revoked. Then you have the responsibility for the 'hood thing, which can get you murdered if you don't come back."
- External effects typically harmful to bystanders—not all social capital is beneficial
- Gangs serve as social institutions where mainstream organizations are absent or debilitated
- Used by ward politicians for organizing, crime syndicates for entry-level employees, community groups for volunteer labor/money/protection
- **Washington, D.C. case:** Women activists in public housing used drug gangs as benefactors—gang provided money for children's programs, activists reciprocated by ensuring organizing proceeded without street interference
- Where constructive social capital and institutions wither, gangs emerge to fill the void

### Carol Stack's *All Our Kin* (1960s)

- Classic study of black families in "the Flats," an inner-city neighborhood in the Midwest
- Residents: mostly second-generation northerners, single women raising children, on public assistance
- **Dense exchange networks:** "alliances of individuals trading and exchanging goods, resources, and the care of children"
- Stack impressed by "intensity of their acts of domestic cooperation, and the exchange of goods and services among these persons, both kin and non-kin"
- **High trust requirement:** Gift rarely repaid immediately—networks require high trust to function
- Inner cities were marked by **well-organized, invisible networks of altruism and obligation**
- Networks = extended, socially constructed, well-recognized "kin groups" (relatives, romantic partners' family, friends, friends of friends)
- Urban poor constantly seek to expand networks for child care, cash assistance, temporary shelter, other assistance
- **Network monitoring:** Members monitored each other for shirking, imposed strong sanctions against those who take more than they give
- Stack's Flats: "richly textured depiction of a wealth of social capital among the struggling poor"

### Decline of Inner-City Social Networks

- **Recent studies:** Inner-city social networks not as dense or effective as Stack found in late 1960s
- Like sprawling suburbs and small villages, inner cities have less social capital than they once did
- Reciprocity systems persist but remain an important, often overlooked asset for poor people

### Social Capital and Disadvantaged Areas

- Social capital is "far more often than not" a good thing for disadvantaged neighbors
- Where lacking, effects of poverty, unemployment, and family breakdown are magnified
- Preliminary evidence: social trust, organizational participation, and neighborhood cohesion help break link between economic disadvantage and teenage troublemaking
- **Problem:** Social capital often lacking in disadvantaged areas, difficult to build
- **"Neighborhood crime watch" programs:** Most likely to succeed in middle-class, stable neighborhoods that already benefit from social trust and networks
- Creates a **vicious circle:** low trust/cohesion → higher crime → even lower trust/cohesion
- Inner cities need virtuous circle (existing social capital facilitates more), but face vicious circle instead
- Social-capital-intensive strategies may help "unwind" negative spiral but are challenging

### Community Policing in the 1980s-90s

- Police departments implemented "applied social capitalism," fighting crime by building partnerships between law enforcement and community residents
- Evidence suggests community policing reduces social disorder and crime through creation/activation of local social capital
- **Chicago Alternative Policing Strategy (CAPS):** Created uniform opportunities for participation, mobilized wider participation across community segments (**Wesley Skogan** and **Susan Harnett**)
- **Boston's 10-Point Coalition:** Working partnership between police and public, brokered by local ministers—only local ministers had the connections and trust (social capital) to make it work
- Crime drop in 1990s big cities may be partly due to residents/leaders learning to capitalize more effectively on local social capital stocks

### Chapter Summary

- **Chapter reviewed:** Salient evidence that social capital contributes to safe and productive neighborhoods; its absence hampers improvement
- Most evidence drawn from inner cities, where scholarly energies have been invested
- Had "culture of suburbia" and middle-class white communities attracted equal attention, could draw more balanced assessment of social-capital impact in Grosse Point and central Detroit
- Effects of social capital on neighborhood life are not limited to poor or minority communities

### Why Social Capital Matters More for the Poor

- **Poor people lack economic and human capital**, making social capital disproportionately important to their welfare
- Erosion of social capital and community engagement affected Grosse Point and inner-city Detroit equally in degree
- But **impact** greater in inner city, which lacks cushioning of other capital forms
- School shootings in suburban/rural communities at end of 20th century: reminder that breakdown of community in privileged settings means affluence and education are insufficient to prevent collective tragedy

---

## Chapter 19: Economic Prosperity

### Social Capital and Economic Success: Individual Level

- Areas high in social capital maintain livable spaces AND get ahead
- Growing research: where trust and social networks flourish, individuals, firms, neighborhoods, nations prosper
- Social capital helps mitigate socioeconomic disadvantage

### Social Connections and Employment

- People from well-to-do families with valuable social ties more likely to succeed economically—not just because richer/better educated, but because they can and will ply their connections
- Conversely, individuals from socially isolated areas held back by lack of financial/educational resources AND lack of social ties for a "hand up"
- **Social networks influence employment:** job leads, advice, strategic information, letters of recommendation

### Mark Granovetter's "Strength of Weak Ties" (1970s)

- Counterintuitive fact: **casual acquaintances more important assets than close friends/family** for job searches
- Close friends/kin ("strong ties") likely know same people and opportunities
- Distant acquaintances ("weakties") link to unexpected opportunities, thus more valuable
- Finding replicated and expanded by researchers interested in social mobility
- "Weak ties" have especially strong impact on fortunes of people at margins of mainstream economic/social institutions
- Debate exists over precise influence—skeptics argue employer racism, educational requirements, city dwellers' lack of access to suburban growth centers are equally/more important obstacles
- Mounting evidence suggests social capital does matter and helps surmount employment barriers

### Ethnic Immigrant Communities

- When social networks and institutions present, unemployed people take advantage to good ends
- **Ethnic immigrant communities:** Employers rely on employees to recruit/train new workers
- Social-capital approach speeds training, improves employee morale, enhances loyalty
- **Ethnic networks as employment networks:** Chinese "rag trade" in New York
- Study of niche economies: solidaristic hiring practices boosted immigrants' wages to level of similarly skilled whites
- Immigrant networks provide financing to entrepreneurs—gifts from family, loans from **rotating credit associations**
- **Rotating credit association:** Group periodically based, members make regular contributions to common fund, made available in whole or part to each contributor in rotation—widespread where formal credit institutions unwilling/unable to provide credit to small borrowers
- **Korean business owners study:** ~70% used debt financing to start enterprises; 41% got money from family, 24% from friends (vs. 37% from financial institution)

### Beyond Ethnic Enclaves

- Economic advantages extend beyond ethnic enclaves
- Surveys: unemployed people look first to friends/relatives for job leads
- 85% of young men in one survey used personal networks to find employment (vs. 54-58% using state agencies/newspapers)
- Los Angeles: two-thirds of white and black women who looked for job in past five years landed latest/current position with help of someone in firm—interestingly, most help came from people outside their own neighborhoods
- Diverse surveys suggest roughly one-half of people get jobs through friend or relative
- Other studies: institutionalized social-capital networks matter for job attainment
- **Church attendance:** One of strongest predictors of whether inner-city black youths will become gainfully employed—religious beliefs have almost no impact, suggesting it's the **social networking aspect of churchgoing**, not religious aspect, behind economic success

### Social Capital Beyond Employment

- **Sociologist Ronald Burt:** Social and organizational ties embodied in business executive's Rolodex at least as important as educational qualifications and experience
- Studies from Albany to Singapore, Dresden to Detroit: at all levels of social hierarchy and all parts of economy, social capital is powerful resource for achieving occupational advancement, social status, economic rewards—**perhaps even more important than human capital** (education and experience)
- **Banking in Chicago (Brian Uzzi):** Firms that embed commercial transactions with lender in social attachments receive lower interest rates on loans
- **Buying and selling:** Prefer to deal with people we know—**sociologists Paul Dimaggio and Hugh Louch** found "people who transact with friends and relatives report greater satisfaction with results than people who transact with strangers"

### Why Social Capital Matters

- Social capital matters because our networks connect us to potential economic partners, provide high-quality information, vouch for us
- For many white-collar jobs, **connections = access** to other people and institutions—what is actually hiring us
- Social networks have undeniable monetary value

### The Problem: Social Capital Absent Where Needed Most

- Leading scholars of urban life note: social networks absent in precisely the places where needed most
- **Chicago example (Wilson's "truly disadvantaged"):** Blacks in extreme poverty substantially less likely than blacks in low-poverty areas to have current partner or best friend
- Extreme poverty resident less likely to have partner/friend who completed high school or had steady work
- Partners/friends of blacks in less destitute neighborhoods more likely to have completed high school or steady work
- Data suggest: residents of extreme-poverty areas have fewer social ties AND ties of less social worth (measured by social position of relatives, parents, siblings, best friends)—**lower volumes of social capital**
- Similar conclusions in other cities
- **Red Hook, Brooklyn:** Deterioration of neighborhood associations and church activities inhibited growth of social networks just as employers making most hires through "word of mouth"
- **Los Angeles County:** Neighborhood poverty kept workers' wages down not because lacked transportation to well-paying jobs, but because lacked access to networks of people who could tell them about good job opportunities—**social contacts extremely lucrative in poverty**
- **Atlanta study:** Each employed person in one's social network increases annual income by $1,400
- Networks more lucrative for whites than minority groups—blacks who gain job information from neighbors earn less than blacks who obtain jobs through contacts outside neighborhood
- Suggests among disadvantaged, **"bridging" social capital may be most lucrative form**
- People in economically disadvantaged areas suffer doubly: lack material resources to get ahead AND lack social resources that might enable them to amass material resources

### Potential Downsides of Social Capital

- Some ways social capital may be economically counterproductive
- Scholars studying ethnic "niche" economies (retail, manufacturing, service sectors dominated by one immigrant group) questioned whether tight bonds of trust and solidarity might restrict growth and mobility
- Ethnic enclaves provide start-up capital and customers, but pressures of solidarity can drag down individuals and businesses that succeed "too much" or try to expand beyond ethnically based market
- Some sociologists noted: less successful community members sometimes take advantage of bonds of obligation and responsibility felt by more successful members—fast-rising entrepreneurs face excessive demands for jobs, money, favors from struggling family/neighbors
- To realize full potential, entrepreneurs may need to reach beyond own ethnic groups/neighborhoods and forge ties to broader world—customers, financial institutions, civic associations
- Where social capital not productive, must be sought elsewhere

### Exploitative Networks

- Tight networks also may be exploited by commercial concerns seeking easy profits
- **Amway and other businesses:** Rely on quasi-independent agents to recruit others into merchandising—agents call upon friends/neighbors to buy and sell products
- Some view as anathema to tacit norms of reciprocity and altruism governing good social relations
- These exceptions aside, most researchers agree social capital does help individuals prosper
- Only real debate: how big a role social capital plays relative to human or financial capital

### Social Capital and Neighborhood Economic Health

- Social capital can help neighborhoods (and even entire nations) create wealth
- Happens in many different ways

### Housing Values and Neighborhood Stability

- **Pittsburgh study:** Other things equal, neighborhoods with high social capital far less likely to decline than low-social-capital areas
- Areas where residents vote, sustain vibrant neighborhood associations, feel attached to neighborhood, see it as good place to live → other people want to move in, housing values remain comparatively high
- Positive impact held even after accounting for proximity to downtown, racial composition, residents' socioeconomic status
- **Lesson:** Homeowners who are also good neighbors take their social capital to the bank

### Regional Economic Growth

- At local/regional level, mounting evidence social capital among economic actors can produce aggregate economic growth
- Not saying more bowling leagues and PTAs will necessarily cause town economy to prosper
- Saying: under certain conditions, cooperation among economic actors might be better engine of growth than free-market competition

### Case Study 1: Tupelo, Mississippi

- In 1940, one of poorest counties in poorest state—no exceptional natural resources, university, industrial concern, major highways, or population centers nearby
- 1936: ravaged by fourth deadliest tornado in U.S. history
- 1937: only significant factory closed after deeply divisive strike
- **George McLean:** University-trained sociologist and native son, returned to run local newspaper
- Through exceptional leadership, united Tupelo's business and civic leaders around idea: town and Lee County would never develop economically until they had developed as a community
- McLean persuaded local business leaders and farmers to pool money to buy siring bull—start of lucrative dairy industry
- To create less hierarchical social order: town's elite Chamber of Commerce disbanded, **Community Development Foundation** opened to everyone, set to work improving local schools, starting community organizations, building medical center, establishing vocational education center
- Businesses welcomed only if paid high wages to all employees and shared this as a goal
- Rural Development Councils set up in outlying areas to encourage self-help collective action
- Technical training to local cleanup campaigns—cooperative action for shared goals had been countercultural

### Tupelo's Success

- Over next fifty years under McLean's and successors' leadership, Tupelo became national model of community and economic development
- Garnered numerous awards, attracted constant stream of visitors eager to copy success
- Since 1983: Lee County added 1,000 industrial jobs a year, garnered hundreds of millions in new investment, produced arguably best school system in Mississippi, constructed world-class hospital, kept unemployment and poverty rates well below state (sometimes national) average
- Community's success based on unwavering commitment: citizens would not benefit individually unless pursued goals collectively
- Unthinkable today to enjoy social prominence in Tupelo without also getting involved in community leadership
- **Tupelo residents invested in social capital—networks of cooperation and mutual trust—and reaped tangible economic returns**

### Case Study 2: Silicon Valley vs. Route 128

- **Silicon Valley:** "social-capital approach" at root of economic miracle
- Led by small group of computer entrepreneurs, aided by resource-rich university community
- Emerged as world capital of high-tech development and manufacturing
- Success due largely to **horizontal networks of informal and formal cooperation** among fledgling companies
- Nominally competitors, companies' leaders shared information, problem-solving techniques, and beers after work
- Developed trade associations, industry conferences, and **"Homebrew Computer Club"** (hobbyists' group whose ranks produced leaders of 20+ computer companies)
- In industry where job turnover is high, key players had repeated interactions with one another in variety of settings: "a colleague might become a customer or a competitor; today's boss could be tomorrow's subordinate"
- Far from producing anxiety and distrust, "continual shuffling and reshuffling tended to reinforce the value of personal relationships and networks"
- Informal networks expanded to include firms on periphery of high-tech nexus: lawyers specializing in intellectual property, business incorporation, venture capitalists, suppliers, etc.
- Early 1990s when Silicon Valley's economic condition began to slip: local businesses under aegis of **San Jose Chamber of Commerce** traded on existing stock of social capital and created **Joint Venture: Silicon Valley**—nonprofit networking organization that helped enhance public-private cooperation on everything from taxes to building permits to literacy

### Route 128 Corridor (Boston)

- Silicon Valley's major U.S. competitor
- Did NOT develop such interfirm social capital
- Maintained traditional norms of corporate hierarchy, secrecy, self-sufficiency, territoriality
- Employees rarely went out after work with one another or with people from other firms
- Route 128's "I'll succeed on my own" philosophy is largely responsible for its poor economic performance relative to Silicon Valley's
- According to leading study of two high-tech centers: **"The contrasting experience of Silicon Valley and Route 128 suggests that industrial systems built on regional networks are more flexible and technologically dynamic than those in which experimentation and learning are confined to individual firms"**
- **Alfred Marshall:** British economist long ago recognized advantages of such "industrial districts," which allow for information flows, mutual learning, and economies of scale
- Even before Silicon Valley, model had succeeded in north-central Italy (crafts and consumer goods), western Michigan (furniture), and Rochester, New York (optics)

### Social Capital and Global Competitiveness

- Cooperative models for increasingly competitive global economy
- **Francis Fukuyama:** Social commentator argued economies whose citizens have high levels of social trust—high social capital—will dominate the twenty-first century
- When can't trust employees or other market players, we end up squandering wealth on surveillance equipment, compliance structures, insurance, legal services, enforcement of government regulations
- Conversely, studies of biotech industry by organization theorists like **Walter Powell** and **Jane Fountain:** social networks that embody norm of reciprocity—social capital—are "key enablers" of innovation, mutual learning, and productivity growth, as important as physical and human capital, particularly in rapidly evolving fields

### Research Caveats

- Understanding detailed linkages between social capital and economic performance is lively field of inquiry
- Would be premature to claim too much for efficacy of social capital or describe exactly when and how networks of social connectedness boost aggregate productivity of economy
- Research on social capital and economic development in "Third World" appearing at rapid rate (South Africa, Indonesia, Russia, India, Burkina Faso)
- Rich work under way on how Americans might improve plight of poorest communities by enabling them to invest in social capital and empowering them to capitalize on social assets they already have
- Links between social networks and economic success at individual level are understood
- Can be reasonably confident: you will benefit if you acquire richer social network
- Not yet entirely clear whether this reflects merely ability to grab larger share of fixed pie, or whether if we all have richer social networks, we all gain
- Early returns encourage view that social capital of right sort boosts economic efficiency, so that if our networks of reciprocity deepen, we all benefit, and if they atrophy, we all pay dearly

---

## Chapter 20: Health and Happiness

### Social Capital and Health: Overview

- Of all domains, importance of social connectedness best established in case of health and well-being
- Scientific studies of effects of social cohesion on physical and mental health can be traced to **Emile Durkheim**, *Suicide* (19th century)
- Self-destruction not merely personal tragedy but sociologically predictable consequence of degree of integration into society—rarer among married people, rarer in tightly knit religious communities, rarer in times of national unity, more frequent when rapid social change disrupts social fabric
- Social connectedness matters to our lives in the most profound way

### Modern Public Health Research

- Recent decades: public health researchers extended insight to virtually all aspects of health, physical and psychological
- Dozens of painstaking studies from Alameda (California) to Tecumseh (Michigan): established beyond reasonable doubt that **social connectedness is one of most powerful determinants of our well-being**
- More integrated we are with community, less likely we experience colds, heart attacks, strokes, cancer, depression, and premature death of all sorts
- Protective effects confirmed for close family ties, friendship networks, participation in social events, and simple affiliation with religious and other civic associations
- Both "machers" and "schmoozers" enjoy remarkable health benefits

### James House Study

- After reviewing dozens of scientific studies, sociologist **James House** and colleagues concluded: **positive contributions to health made by social integration and social support rival in strength the detrimental contributions of well-established biomedical risk factors** like cigarette smoking, obesity, elevated blood pressure, and physical inactivity
- Statistically speaking, evidence for health consequences of social connectedness as strong today as was evidence for health consequences of smoking at time of first surgeon general's report on smoking
- If trends in social disconnection as pervasive as argued in section II, then "bowling alone" represents one of nation's most serious public health challenges

### Mechanisms: Why Social Cohesion Matters for Health

1. **Tangible assistance:** Social networks furnish money, convalescent care, transportation—reduces psychic and physical stress
2. **Safety net function:** If you go to church regularly and slip in bathtub and miss a Sunday, someone more likely to notice
3. **Reinforcing healthy norms:** Social networks may reinforce healthy norms—socially isolated people more likely to smoke, drink, overeat, engage in other health-damaging behaviors
4. **Political organization:** Socially cohesive communities best able to organize politically to ensure first-rate medical services
5. **Physiological triggering mechanism:** Social capital might actually serve as physiological triggering mechanism, stimulating people's immune systems to fight disease and buffer stress

### Biochemical Effects of Social Isolation

- Research suggests social isolation has measurable biochemical effects on body
- Animals who have been isolated develop more extensive atherosclerosis (hardening of arteries) than less isolated animals
- Among both animals and humans, loneliness appears to decrease immune response and increase blood pressure
- **Lisa Berkman:** Leading researcher, speculated that social isolation is "a chronically stressful condition to which the organism respond[s] by aging faster"

### Evidence: Individual and Community Level

- Studies documented strong correlation between connectedness and health at community level
- Others zeroed in on individuals, both in natural settings and experimental conditions
- Studies careful to account for confounding factors—panoply of other physiological, economic, institutional, behavioral, and demographic forces that might also affect individual's health
- Many cases studies are **longitudinal:** check on people over many years to get better understanding of what lifestyle changes might have caused people's health to improve or decline
- Researchers able to show social isolation *precedes* illness to rule out possibility that isolation was caused by illness
- Over last twenty years, more than a dozen large studies in United States, Scandinavia, and Japan have shown: **people who are socially disconnected are between two and five times more likely to die from all causes, compared with matched individuals who have close ties with family, friends, and the community**

### Harvard School of Public Health Study

- Excellent overview of link between social capital and physical health across United States
- Using survey data from nearly 170,000 individuals in all fifty states
- Found (as expected): people who are African American, lack health insurance, are overweight, smoke, have low income, or lack college education are at greater risk for illness than more socioeconomically advantaged individuals
- Also found **astonishingly strong relationship between poor health and low social capital**
- States whose residents most likely to report fair or poor health were same states in which residents most likely to distrust others
- **Moving from state with wealth of social capital to state with very little social capital** (low trust, low voluntary group membership) **increased one's chances of poor to middling health by roughly 40-70 percent**
- When researchers accounted for individual residents' risk factors, relationship between social capital and individual health remained
- Indeed, researchers concluded: if one wanted to improve one's health, **moving to high-social-capital state would do almost as much good as quitting smoking**
- Authors' conclusion complemented by our own analysis: found strong positive relationship between comprehensive index of public health and Social Capital Index, along with strong negative correlation between Social Capital Index and all-cause mortality rates

### Case Study: Roseto, Pennsylvania

- Small Italian American community, subject of nearly forty years of in-depth study, beginning in 1950s
- Medical researchers noticed happy but puzzling phenomenon: Compared with residents of neighboring towns, Rosetans just didn't die of heart attacks
- Age-adjusted heart attack rate less than half that of neighbors; over seven-year period not a single Roseto resident under forty-seven had died of heart attack
- Researchers looked for usual explanations: diet, exercise, weight, smoking, genetic predisposition, etc.—but none held answer
- Indeed, Rosetans actually more likely to have some risk factors than people in neighboring towns
- Researchers began to explore Roseto's social dynamics
- Town founded in 19th century by people from same southern Italian village
- Through local leadership, immigrants created mutual aid society, churches, sports clubs, labor union, newspaper, Scout troops, park and athletic field
- Residents developed tight-knit community where conspicuous displays of wealth were scorned and family values and good behaviors reinforced
- Rosetans learned to draw on one another for financial, emotional, and other forms of support
- By day congregated on front porches to watch comings and goings, and by night gravitated to local social clubs
- In 1960s researchers began to suspect **social capital (though they didn't use the term) was key to Rosetans' healthy hearts**
- Researchers worried that as socially mobile young people began to reject tight-knit Italian folkways, heart attack rate would begin to rise
- Sure enough, by 1980s Roseto's new generation of adults had heart attack rate above that of neighbors in nearby and demographically similar town

### Other Supporting Studies

- Roseto story particularly vivid and compelling, but numerous other studies supported medical researchers' intuition that social cohesion matters
- Not just in preventing premature death, but also in preventing disease and speeding recovery
- **Long-term study in California:** People with fewest social ties have highest risk of dying from heart disease, circulatory problems, and cancer (in women), even after accounting for individual health status, socioeconomic factors, and use of preventive health care
- Other studies linked lower death rates with membership in voluntary groups and engagement in cultural activities; church attendance; phone calls and visits with friends and relatives; and general sociability such as holding parties at home, attending union meetings, visiting friends, participating in organized sports, or being members of highly cohesive military units
- Connection with social capital persisted even when studies examined other factors that might influence mortality (social class, race, gender, smoking and drinking, obesity, lack of exercise, and health problems)
- Not simply that healthy, health-conscious, privileged people (who might happen also to be more socially engaged) tend to live longer
- **Broad range of illnesses shown to be affected by social support** and fact that link is even tighter with death than with sickness tend to suggest that effect operates at quite fundamental level of general bodily resistance
- What these studies tell us: **social engagement actually has an independent influence on how long we live**

### Health at the State Level

- State-level findings suggestive, but far more definitive evidence provided by wealth of studies examining individual health as function of individual social-capital resources
- Found strong positive relationship between comprehensive index of public health and Social Capital Index
- Strong negative correlation between Social Capital Index and all-cause mortality rates
- (See Table 6 for measure of public health and health care; Figure 86 for correlations)

### Individual Health and Social Networks

- Social networks help you stay healthy
- Finding by team of researchers at Carnegie Mellon University: people with more diverse social ties get fewer colds is by no means unique
- Stroke victims who had strong support networks functioned better after stroke and recovered more physical capacities than stroke victims with thin social networks
- Older people involved with clubs, volunteer work, and local politics consider themselves to be in better general health than uninvolved people, even after accounting for socioeconomic status, demographics, level of medical care use, and years of retirement

### The Bottom Line on Health

- **As rough rule of thumb:** if you belong to no groups but decide to join one, you cut your risk of dying over next year in half
- If you smoke and belong to no groups, it's toss-up statistically whether you should stop smoking or start joining
- These findings in some ways heartening: it's easier to join a group than to lose weight, exercise regularly, or quit smoking

### Declining Self-Reported Health

- But findings sobering too
- As saw in section II, there has been general decline in social participation over past twenty-five years
- Figure 87 shows same period witnessed significant decline in self-reported health, despite tremendous gains in medical diagnosis and treatment
- Of course, by many objective measures (including life expectancy), Americans are healthier than ever before
- But these self-reports indicate we are feeling worse
- Self-reports in turn closely linked to social connectedness—precisely less connected Americans who are feeling worse
- Facts alone do not *prove* we are suffering physically from our growing disconnectedness
- But taken in conjunction with more systematic evidence of health effects of social capital, this evidence is another link in argument that erosion of social capital has measurable ill effects

### Depression and Social Connectedness

- Observed in chapter 14: remarkable coincidence that during same years social connectedness declining, depression and even suicide have been increasing
- Also noted: coincidence has deep generational roots—generations most disconnected socially also suffer most from what some public health experts call "Agent Blue"
- In any given year 10% of Americans now suffer from major depression
- Depression imposes fourth largest total burden of any disease on Americans overall
- Much research shown: social connections inhibit depression
- Low levels of social support directly predict depression, even controlling for other risk factors
- High levels of social support lessen severity of symptoms and speed recovery
- Social support buffers us from stresses of daily life
- Face-to-face ties seem to be more therapeutic than ties that are geographically distant
- In short, even within single domain of depression, **we pay very high price for our slackening social connectedness**

### Life Satisfaction and Happiness

- Countless studies document link between society and psyche
- People who have close friends and confidants, friendly neighbors, and supportive coworkers less likely to experience sadness, loneliness, low self-esteem, and problems with eating and sleeping
- Married people consistently happier than people who are unattached, all else being equal
- These findings will hardly surprise most Americans
- In study after study, people themselves report that good relationships with family members, friends, or romantic partners—far more than money or fame—are prerequisites for their happiness
- **Single most common finding from half century's research on correlates of life satisfaction** not only in United States but around the world: **happiness is best predicted by breadth and depth of one's social connections**

### Social Capital and Subjective Well-Being

- Can see how social capital ranks as producer of warm, fuzzy feelings by examining questions from DDB Needham Life Style survey archives:
  - "I wish I could leave my present life and do something entirely different."
  - "I am very satisfied with the way things are going in my life these days."
  - "If I had my life to live over, I would sure do things differently."
  - "I am much happier now than I ever was before."

<!-- pp. 341-360 -->

### Marriage, Education, and Social Capital's Impact on Happiness

**Marriage as happiness driver**: Controlling for education, age, gender, marital status, income, and civic engagement, marriage's effect on life contentment equals moving ~70 percentiles up the income hierarchy (15th to 85th percentile).

> "Getting married is the 'happiness equivalent' of quadrupling your annual income."

**Education's marginal impact**: Four additional years of education (e.g., attending college) = happiness equivalent of roughly doubling annual income, when controlling for income itself.

**Civic connections rival marriage and affluence**: Regular club attendance, volunteering, entertaining at home, or church attendance = happiness equivalent of getting a college degree or more than doubling income.

> "Civic connections rival marriage and affluence as predictors of life happiness."

### Diminishing Marginal Returns of Social Interaction

**Figure 88**: Shows declining marginal productivity of social interaction for happiness. Biggest returns between "never" and "once a month" for volunteering, clubs, entertaining. Little gain after ~one meeting per 3 weeks; after fortnightly encounters, additional interaction shows **negative** correlation with happiness.

**Church attendance exception**: More frequent attendance correlates with higher happiness, at least through weekly attendance.

### Direction of Causation

**Bidirectional relationship**: Happy people may be more likely to marry, get raises, continue school, join clubs, host parties. Putnam's purpose: illustrate that social connections have profound links with psychological well-being.

> "The Beatles got it right: we all 'get by with a little help from our friends.'"

### Life Satisfaction Decline Since the 1960s

**Generational happiness gap**: Since the Fab Four era, life satisfaction among adult Americans has declined steadily. Half the decline = financial worries; half = declines in social capital (lower marriage rates, decreasing connectedness).

**Age distribution**: Slump greatest among young and middle-aged adults (20-55). People over 55 are actually **happier** than their age cohort a generation ago.

**Causes of younger generations' unhappiness**:
- Financial insecurity despite rising prosperity
- Less social connectedness—fewer friends, less church attendance, fewer club meetings than earlier generations

**Martin Seligman's diagnosis**: Modern society encourages belief in personal control and autonomy over commitment to duty and communal enterprise. This heightens expectations about achievement through choice and grit, leaving people unprepared for life's inevitable failures. Social capital safety nets (families, churches, friends) no longer strong enough to cushion the fall.

> "In our personal lives as well as in our collective life, the evidence of this chapter suggests, we are paying a significant price for a quarter century's disengagement from one another."

---

## Chapter 21: Democracy

### Historical Foundations of Participatory Democracy

**Oscar Wilde's quip**: "The trouble with socialism is that it would take too many evenings."

**Central question**: How many evenings does liberal democracy take?

**Two views of democratic citizenship**:
1. Conventional: Health requires citizens to perform **ourpublic** duties (voting, etc.)
2. Expansive/controversial: Health depends on widespread participation in **inprivate** voluntary groups—networks of civic engagement embodying social capital

### Jefferson's Ward Republics

**Thomas Jefferson (1816 letter)**: Proposed dividing counties into wards small enough that every citizen could attend meetings in person. Ward governments would handle schools, poor relief, police, military forces, public roads.

> "Making every citizen an acting member of the government, and in the offices nearest and most interesting to him, will attach him by his strongest feelings to the independence of his country, and its republican constitution."

### Tocqueville on Local Civic Activity

**Alexis de Tocqueville**: Local civic activity served as handmaiden of national democratic community.

> "It is difficult to draw a man out of his own circle to interest him in the destiny of the state... because he does not understand what influence the destiny of the state can have upon his own lot. But if it is proposed to make a road cross the end of his estate, he will see at a glance that there is a connection between the small public affair and his greatest private affairs; and he will discover, without its being shown to him, the close tie that unites private to general interest."

### John Stuart Mill on Participatory Democracy

**Character-building effects**: Without shared participation in public life, citizens think of collective interests only in competition with others, not jointly. A neighbor becomes "only a rival."

**The engaged citizen**:
> "Is called upon...to weigh interests not his own; to be guided, in case of conflicting claims, by another rule than his private partialities.... He is made to feel himself one of the public, and whatever is for their benefit to be for his benefit."

### John Dewey on Face-to-Face Democracy

**Conundrum**: How to reconcile modern, large-scale, technologically advanced society with democracy's exigencies?

> "Fraternity, liberty and equality isolated from communal life are hopeless abstractions.... Democracy must begin at home, and its home is the neighborly community."

**Robert Westbrook**: "Only in local, face-to-face associations could members of a public participate in dialogues with their fellows, and such dialogues were crucial to the formation and organization of the public."

### The Founders' Skepticism About Voluntary Associations

**James Madison**: Called groups organized around particular interests "mischiefs of faction." Fear: elected representatives would sacrifice the common good for pet projects of the few. Must be tolerated for liberty but controlled.

**Michael Schudson**: Founders "were far from sharing a pluralist vision, still attached as they were to the notions of consensus, property, virtue, and deference that came naturally to them."

### Contemporary Democracy Theory: Mediating Associations

**External effects** on government:
- Express interests and demands
- Protect from abuses of power
- Political information flows through social networks
- Association membership clarifies views, increases zeal, unites energies toward clearly indicated goals

**Tocqueville**:
> "When some view is represented by an association, it must take clearer and more precise shape. It counts its supporters and involves them in its cause; these supporters get to know one another, and numbers increase zeal. An association unites the energies of divergent minds and vigorously directs them toward a clearly indicated goal."

**Voice amplification**: Without associations willing to speak up, individuals have limited ability to be heard unless rich or famous. (**Amy Gutmann**)

**East Germany democracy movement example**: Recruitment through friendship networks; informal bonds more important than ideology, fear of repression, or formal organizing.

### Internal Effects: Schools for Democracy

**Civic skills training**: Associations are "schools for democracy" where members learn to run meetings, speak in public, write letters, organize projects, debate issues.

**William Muraskin on Prince Hall Masonry**: Training membership in leadership roles; teaching bourgeois social roles; bringing leadership potential to practical fruition.

**Best civic skill-building institutions**: For working-class Americans, voluntary associations and churches offer best opportunities—even better than workplace. Two-thirds+ of members in religious, literary, youth, fraternal/service organizations exercise civic skills like giving presentations or running meetings.

**Churches' egalitarian role**: One of few vital institutions where low-income, minority, disadvantaged citizens can learn politically relevant skills and be recruited into political action. Without them, class bias in politics would be much greater.

### Deliberative Democracy and Public Deliberation

**Recent theoretical attention**: Promise and pitfalls of "deliberative democracy."

**Homogeneous associations**: Some argue voluntary associations best enhance deliberation when microcosms of nation (economically, ethnically, religiously). Others argue even homogeneous organizations enhance deliberative democracy by making public interactions more inclusive (e.g., minority groups pushing for nondiscrimination regulations, ethnic curricula, government board representation).

### Civic Virtues Learned Through Association

**Follow-up study of high school seniors**: Regardless of social class, academic background, self-esteem, those in voluntary associations far more likely to vote, participate in campaigns, discuss public issues two years post-graduation.

**Trustworthiness**: Repeated interactions reduce likelihood of shirking or cheating.

**Reciprocity**: As shown in Chapter 7, more civic engagement → more concern for generalized other (volunteering, blood donation, charity).

**Democratic deliberation**: Reciprocity = willingness of opposing sides to agree on ground rules for mutual accommodation after sufficient discussion, even when they don't agree on outcomes. Regular connections don't **ensure** empathy, but social isolation virtually guarantees its absence.

### Critics of Pluralism

**Three major concerns**:

1. **Interest groups distort decision-making**: From Theodore Lowe's *End of Liberalism* (1960s) to Jonathan Rauch's *Demosclerosis* (1990s), critics argue specialized lobbies paralyze well-intentioned officials and stifle reforms. Reminiscent of Madison's "mischiefs of faction" worry. Bargaining among diverse groups leads to greatest good for greatest number → greatest goodies for best-organized few.

2. **Associational bias favors the privileged**: People with education, money, status, close ties with fellow community members far more likely to benefit politically under pluralism than the uneducated, poor, unconnected. Social capital benefits those who already have stock to trade. Associationalism is class-biased (virtually every study confirms).

> "The flaw in the pluralist heaven is that the heavenly chorus sings with a strong upper-class accent." — **E.E. Schattschneider**

3. **Political polarization and cynicism**: Citizen group politics almost by nature extremist—people with strongly held views tend to be leaders and activists. Roper Social and Political Trends archives show ideological extremism and civic participation are correlated, though with unexpected implications.

### Participation and Extremism

**Data on ideological self-identification**: Americans at political poles more engaged in civic life; moderates have dropped out.

**Controlling for demographics**: Americans who describe themselves as "very" liberal or "very" conservative more likely to attend public meetings, write Congress, be active in local civic organizations, attend church than moderates.

**Strengthened correlation over 20th century**: People characterizing themselves as "middle of the road" ideologically have disproportionately disappeared from public meetings, local organizations, political parties, rallies.

**1990s data**: Self-described middle-of-the-roaders ~**one-half** as likely to participate in public meetings, local civic organizations, political parties as mid-1970s. "Moderate" liberals/conservatives declined by **one-third**. Declines smallest among "very" liberal or conservative.

**Civic disengagement exacerbates "faction" problem**: More moderate voices have fallen silent. Extreme views have become more dominant in grassroots civic life as moderates dropped out.

### Psychic Engagement and Political Discussion

**Social capital's role**: Most political discussions happen informally—dinner table, office water cooler. We form views through interchange with friends and neighbors in civic networks.

**Cathy J. Cohen and Michael C. Dawson**: Informal networks not available to everyone. African Americans in poverty clusters suffer from dearth of political information and opportunity. Detroit study: Even non-destitute residents in high-poverty neighborhoods far less likely to attend church, belong to voluntary organizations, attend public meetings, talk politics than similar people in advantaged neighborhoods. Inner-city neighborhoods often lack institutions to mobilize citizens.

**Vicious cycle**: People don't participate because they're not mobilized; not mobilized, they can never savor fruits of participation.

### Citizenship by Proxy?

**Argument**: Large national membership groups (AARP, Audubon Society, NAACP) can represent interests efficiently—citizens hire them as they hire mechanics or money managers.

**Michael Schudson**: "This is not Tocquevillian democracy," but these organizations may be highly efficient uses of civic energy. Citizens may get same civic payoff for less personal hassle—especially if politics conceived as public policies.

**Theda Skocpol's counterargument**: In classic civic America, millions of ordinary men and women could interact with one another, participate in groups side by side with the privileged, exercise influence in both community and national affairs. Recent times: old civic America bypassed, shoved aside by professionally dominated advocacy groups and nonprofit institutions rarely attached to memberships worthy of the name.

> "Ideas of shared citizenship and possibilities for democratic leverage have been compromised in the process."

**Peter Skerry**: Broad national membership organizations dominated not by local input but by headquarters staff. These people pulled toward wishes of major patrons: wealthy individuals, foundations, government agencies that fund them. Organizations rely on media strategies emphasizing threats from "enemies," giving us politics fraught with posturing and confrontation rather than reasoned debate.

### Local Engagement and Government Responsiveness

**James T. Hamilton study**: Neighborhoods where people owned homes and voted were (holding other factors constant) less likely to get hazardous waste plants than neighborhoods where people rented and rarely voted. Hazardous waste companies locate where they expect least locally organized opposition.

**Civic disengagement undermines neighborhood empowerment**—and vice versa (two sides of same coin).

---

## Chapter 21 (continued): Social Capital and Government Performance

### Italian Regional Government Study

**Beginning 1970**: Italians established nationwide set of powerful regional governments. Twenty new institutions virtually identical in form, but social, economic, political, cultural contexts differed dramatically (preindustrial to postindustrial, Catholic to Communist, feudal to modern).

**Research approach**: Like botanist studying genetically identical seeds in different plots—sought to understand government performance by studying how institutions evolved in diverse settings.

**Outcomes**: Some governments dismal failures (inefficient, lethargic, corrupt). Others remarkably successful (innovative day care programs, job training centers, investment promotion, environmental standards, family clinics, managing public business efficiently, satisfying constituents).

### What Explained Performance Differences?

**Seemingly obvious factors proved irrelevant**:
- Government organization too similar
- Party politics/ideology made little difference
- Affluence and prosperity had no direct effect
- Social stability or political harmony not correlated with good government

**Best predictor**: Strong traditions of civic engagement—voter turnout, newspaper readership, membership in choral societies and literary circles, Lions Clubs, soccer clubs.

### Civic vs. Uncivic Regions

**Civic communities** (e.g., Emilia-Romagna, Tuscany):
- Many active community organizations
- Citizens engaged by public issues, not by patronage
- Trust one another to act fairly and obey law
- Leaders relatively honest, committed to equality
- Social and political networks organized horizontally, not hierarchically
- Value solidarity, civic participation, integrity
- **Democracy works**

**Uncivic regions** (e.g., Calabria, Sicily):
- Characterized by **incivisme** (French term)
- Very concept of citizenship is stunted
- Meager engagement in social and cultural associations
- Public affairs = somebody else's business (*i notabili*—the bosses, the politicians)
- Laws made to be broken (fearing others' lawlessness, everyone demands sterner discipline)
- Trapped in interlocking vicious circles; nearly everyone feels powerless, exploited, unhappy
- Representative government less effective than in more civic communities

### Historical Depth of Civic Traditions

**Astonishingly deep roots**: Enduring traditions of civic involvement and social solidarity traced back nearly a millennium to 11th century when communal republics were established in Florence, Bologna, Genoa—exactly the communities that today enjoy civic engagement and successful government.

**Core of civic heritage**: Rich networks of organized reciprocity and civic solidarity:
- Guilds, religious fraternities, tower societies for self-defense in medieval communes
- Cooperatives, mutual aid societies, neighborhood associations, choral societies in 20th century

### How Civic Engagement Affects Government: Demand and Supply Sides

**Demand side**: Citizens in civic communities expect better government, and (through their own efforts) they get it. As shown in hazardous waste study, decision makers expect citizens to hold them politically accountable; more inclined to temper worst impulses rather than face public protests.

**Supply side**: Representative government performance facilitated by social infrastructure of civic communities and democratic values of officials and citizens. Social capital lowers transaction costs and eases dilemmas of collection action. Where people know one another, interact weekly at choir practice or sports matches, and trust one another to behave honorably, they have model and moral foundation for further cooperative enterprises.

**Light-touch government**: Works more efficiently with social capital. Police close more cases when citizens monitor neighborhood comings/goings. Child welfare departments do better "family preservation" when neighbors and relatives provide social support. Public schools teach better when parents volunteer in classrooms and ensure kids do homework. When community involvement lacking, burdens on government employees (bureaucrats, social workers, teachers) much greater and success more elusive.

### US State-Level Evidence

**Daniel Elazar's political cultures (1950s)**:
- **Traditionalistic** (South): Elites resistant to innovation
- **Individualistic** (Mid-Atlantic, western states): Strong parties, professional politicians, economic growth focus
- **Moralistic** (Northeast, upper Midwest, Pacific Northwest): "Good government," issue-based campaigning, social innovation prized

**Correlation with social capital**: Elazar's political-culture map looks much like distribution of social capital (figure 80). Traditionalistic states (lowest social capital) also lowest in Elazar's index. Individualistic states (moderate social capital). Moralistic states (highest social capital). Correlation between political-culture index and Social Capital Index strikingly large.

### US State Government Performance

**Social capital–rich "moralistic" states**:
- Unusually innovative in public policy
- Merit systems governing hiring of government employees
- More issue-oriented politics, focused on social and educational services
- Apparently less corrupt

**Preliminary studies**: States high in social capital sustain government that is more effective and innovative.

### Municipal-Level Evidence

**High grassroots involvement**:
- Blunts patronage politics
- Secures fairer distribution of federal community development grants

**Cities with institutionalized neighborhood organizations** (Portland OR, St. Paul MN): More effective at passing proposals local people want. Higher levels of support for and trust in municipal government.

### Social Capital and Tax Compliance

**Tax system legitimacy**: Turns on belief that we all do our share. Yet IRS cannot audit everyone—rational citizens have every reason to believe that if they pay their share, they subsidize cheaters. Recipe for disillusionment.

**State-level analysis**: Where citizens view others as basically honest, tax compliance higher than in low-social-capital states. Controlling for per capita income, income inequality, racial composition, urbanism, education levels, **social capital is the only factor that successfully predicts tax compliance**.

**Individual taxpayers**: Those who believe others are dishonest or distrustful of government more likely to cheat. Willingness to pay my share depends crucially on perception that others are doing the same.

> In community rich in social capital, government is "we," not "they." In this way social capital reinforces government legitimacy: I pay my taxes because I believe that most other people do, and I see the tax system as basically working as it should.

**Figure 89**: Tax Evasion Is Low Where Social Capital Is High—shows strong correlation between Social Capital Index and low IRS criminal referrals/convictions (1982-97).

### Social Capital and Public Broadcasting

**Public goods problem**: Public broadcasting = classic example. I obtain benefit whether or not I pay; my contribution unlikely to keep station on air. Why should any rational, self-interested listener send a check to local station?

**Answer in social capital–rich communities**: Civic norms sustain expanded sense of "self-interest" and firmer confidence in reciprocity. Communities ranking high on turnout and social trust provide significantly higher contributions to public broadcasting (controlling for education, affluence, race, tax deductibility, public spending). If social capital stocks diminish, more of us tempted to "free-ride"—not merely by ignoring appeals to "viewers like you," but by neglecting myriad civic duties that allow democracy to work.

### Military Effectiveness and Crisis Response

**Military units**: More effective when bonds of solidarity and trust are high.

**Communities with strong social networks and grassroots associations**: Better at confronting unexpected crises than communities lacking such civic resources.

**Collective action requires**: Actions that violate immediate self-interest and assume neighbors will act collectively too. Modern society replete with opportunities for free-riding and opportunism. Democracy doesn't require that citizens be selfless saints, but in many modest ways it assumes most of us much of the time will resist temptation to cheat.

> Social capital, the evidence increasingly suggests, strengthens our better, more expansive selves. The performance of our democratic institutions depends in measurable ways upon social capital.

<!-- pp. 361-380 -->

## The Paradox of Social Capital and Tolerance

### America's Growing Tolerance (1950s-1990s)

- **Michael Schudson** and **Alan Wolfe**: Americans became more tolerant while less connected—"Might not the gain in liberty be worth the cost in community?"
- America in 1990s far more tolerant than 1950s-1970s across all measures (racial integration, gender equality, civil liberties)
- **Table 7** and **Figure 90**: All 21 tolerance questions moved in more tolerant direction over last quarter of 20th century

### Dramatic Shifts in Racial Attitudes

- 1956: 50% of white Americans favored separate schools; 1995: only 4%
- 1963: 45% would move if blacks moved next door; 1997: 1%
- 1973: 20% had someone of another race to dinner; 1996: 42%
- 1987: 46% opposed interracial dating; 1999: 23%
- 1963: 61% supported laws banning interracial marriage; 1998: 11%
- Interracial social bridges strengthening even as most social capital declined

### Gender Equality and Civil Liberties Progress

- 1973: 45% favored banning homosexuality books from libraries; 1998: 26%
- 1987-1999: Support for firing homosexual teachers fell from >50% to <33%
- 1975: 50% agreed "most men better suited emotionally for politics than women"; 1999: <25%
- Behind each statistical trend: Americans increasingly liberated from stigma and oppression

### The Core Paradox: Does Tolerance Require Disengagement?

**Question**: Did decline of old-fashioned clubs reflect people dropping out because clubs weren't tolerant? Did we become tolerant *because* we freed ourselves from parochial social influences?

**Table 8: Social Capital and Tolerance: Four Types of Society**

|  | Low Social Capital | High Social Capital |
|---|---|---|
| **High tolerance** | (1) *Individualistic*: You do your thing, I'll do mine | (3) *Civic community* (Salem without "witches") |
| **Low tolerance** | (2) *Anarchic*: War of all against all | (4) *Sectarian community* (in-group vs. out-group; Salem with "witches") |

**Key insight**: Tolerance and social capital are NOT opposite ends of single continuum—four logically possible types exist. Cell (3) combines high social capital and high tolerance. Is this achievable?

### Evidence: Social Capital Actually Increases Tolerance

- Individuals more engaged with communities are *more* tolerant than stay-at-home neighbors, not less
- Correlation between social participation and tolerance is *positive* even controlling for education
- Especially strong link for gender and race: more community organization involvement → more open to gender equality and racial integration
- Social joiners and civic activists *more* tolerant of dissent and unconventional behavior
- Pattern discovered by social scientists during repressive McCarthy period of 1950s, confirmed repeatedly since
- Comprehensive study of citizen-participation initiatives in five American cities: very active participants considerably more tolerant toward unpopular speakers (controlling for socioeconomic status)
- Exception: religious involvement in fundamentalist churches linked to intolerance
- **No empirical study confirms supposed link between community involvement and intolerance**
- **George Babbitt** may have been arrogant and opinionated, but empirical evidence suggests his bigotry would have been worse if *not* exposed to Zenith's community life

### State-Level Analysis: Social Capital and Tolerance Go Together

**Figure 91**: Citizens of high-social-capital states far more tolerant of civil liberties and committed to racial/gender equality than low-social-capital citizens

- Relationship holds controlling for education, income, urbanism
- Most tolerant communities in America = places with greatest civic involvement
- Conversely, communities where residents bowl alone = least tolerant places in America

### Generational Dynamics: Tolerance vs. Engagement

- Most changes in tolerance and civic engagement over last 30 years traceable to generational succession
- Newer, more tolerant, less engaged generations gradually replaced older, less tolerant, more engaged cohorts
- **Critical distinction**: Generational dividing line for tolerance ≠ generational dividing line for engagement

**Tolerance trends**:
- Almost entirely due to replacement of less tolerant people born in first half of 20th century by more tolerant boomers and Gen X
- People born after ~1945 more tolerant than those born before
- **Sociologist James C. Davis**: *People born in 1970s or 1980s are no more tolerant than parents born in 1940s and 1950s*
- Generational engine producing greater tolerance halted with advent of boomers
- Late X'ers no more tolerant than early boomers

**Engagement trends**:
- Something in *second* half of 20th century made people less civically engaged
- Late X'ers much less engaged than early boomers
- Biggest generational losses in engagement still lie ahead

**The 1940-45 cohort**: Liberal communitarians par excellence
- Most engaged, but less tolerant (parents' generation)
- Children as tolerant but less engaged
- Inherited parents' sense of community but discarded intolerance
- Successfully passed tolerance to children but failed to transmit communitarian habits
- Liberal communitarian cultural matrix that civil rights movement emerged from already fading by entering 21st century

### Key Conclusion: Social Capital and Tolerance Have Symbiotic Relationship

Looking across varied states and communities: social capital and tolerance have symbiotic relationship, NOT inverse relationship. Generational roots of growing tolerance and declining civic engagement are quite distinct. No reason to assume community engagement must have illiberal consequences.

## Social Capital and Equality

### Is Social Capital at War with Equality?

**Concern**: Social capital, especially bonding social capital that bonds us with others like us, often reinforces social stratification
- Abundant social capital of 1950s often exclusionary along racial, gender, and class lines
- Generally, haves engage in more civic activity than have-nots
- Strengthening voluntary associations may widen class differences

### The Historical Evidence: Complementary, Not Warring

**Empirical reality**: Community and equality are *mutually reinforcing, not mutually incompatible*

**Historical correlation**:
- Social capital and economic equality moved in tandem through most of 20th century
- 1950s-1960s: America more egalitarian in wealth/income distribution than in more than a century
- Same decades = high point of social connectedness and civic engagement
- Record highs in equality and social capital coincided
- Circumstantial evidence points to WWII epoch as key

**Reversal around 1965-70**:
- Last third of 20th century: growing inequality *and* eroding social capital
- End of 20th century: gap between rich and poor increasing for nearly 3 decades (longest sustained increase in inequality in at least a century)
- First sustained decline in social capital in at least that long
- Timing striking: around 1965-70 America reversed course, becoming both less economically just and less well connected socially and politically

**Conclusion**: Fraternity and equality are complementary, not warring values

### State-Level Analysis: Equality and Social Capital Go Together

**Figure 92**: American states with highest social capital = states most characterized by economic equality
- Income distributed more equally in high-social-capital states
- Gap between rich and poor especially large in low-social-capital states

**Figure 93**: High-social-capital states show civic equality
- People from different social classes equally likely to attend public meetings, lead local organizations
- In low-social-capital states, civic life monopolized by haves, leaving have-nots out
- Both across space and across time, equality and fraternity strongly *positively* correlated

### Causal Interpretations

Three plausible alternatives (cannot fully adjudicate):

1. **Social capital helps produce equality**: Historically main weapon of have-nots who lacked other forms of capital. "Solidarity forever" = strategically sensible rallying cry for ethnic minorities or working class. Well-knit communities can sustain more egalitarian social and political arrangements.

2. **Equality fosters social capital**: Great disparities of wealth and power inimical to widespread participation and broadly shared community integration. Causal arrow points from equality toward civic engagement and social capital.

3. **External forces cause both**: Social connectedness and equality fostered by same forces, such as leveling and annealing effects of massive (and victorious) war.

**Verdict**: Evidence powerfully contradicts view that community engagement must necessarily amplify inequality. Every reason to think twin master trends of our time—less equality, less engagement—reinforce one another.

### Practical Implications

Many practical tensions may arise between fraternity vs. liberty and equality. Could easily conceive initiatives fostering one value at expense of others.

**However**: Empirical evidence clearly contradicts simple view that *only* way to have more fraternity is to sacrifice liberty and equality.

**False optimism**: To console ourselves that collapse of American community has at least brought us more liberal, egalitarian America

**False pessimism**: To refrain from efforts to rebuild community for fear such efforts will lead inevitably to intolerance and injustice

## The Deepest Paradox: Is Fraternity at War with Itself?

### Social Divisiveness as Central Normative Issue

**The challenge**: Fraternity most easily created *in opposition to* something or someone else. Fraternity most natural within socially homogeneous groups.

**Historical examples**:
- Southern white identity forged in part in resistance to racial integration
- Jews unified by anti-Semitism
- Some African Americans fear integration might undermine racial solidarity
- **Gunnar Myrdal**: "An American dilemma"—race = most important embodiment of ethical crosscurrents around social capital in contemporary America

### Race and Social Capital in America

**Legacy of slavery and Jim Crow**:
- Thwarted connections that might otherwise have been made among dispossessed of both races
- Parts of US where social trust and social capital lowest today = places where slavery and racialist policy most entrenched historically
- Civil rights movement aimed at destroying certain exclusive, nonbridging forms of social capital—racially homogeneous schools, neighborhoods

**The deeper question**: What was to follow? Remains high on national agenda at beginning of 21st century as at beginning of 20th.

**The easy answer**: "More bridging social capital"—bonds of connection crossing racial lines
- Workplace integration = by far greatest success for this approach (see chapter 5)

### The Busing Controversy: The Dilemma Illustrated

School integration posed more sharply the trade-offs between bridging and bonding social capital. Both sides fundamentally concerned about social capital (though no one used that language):

**Proponents**: Only through racially integrated schools could America generate sufficient social capital—familiarity, tolerance, solidarity, trust, habits of cooperation, mutual respect—across racial divide

**Opponents**: In most parts of America, neighborhood schools provided unique site for building social capital—friendship, habits of cooperation, solidarity

**Tragic conclusion**: Both sides probably right

### The "Aluminum Magic Wand" Dilemma

**Political scientist Eileen McDonagh's formulation**: "Is it better to have neighborhoods legally restricted on basis of race, but with everyone having everyone else over for dinner, or is it better to have neighborhoods unrestricted on basis of race, but with very little social interaction going on between neighbors?"

**This was the dilemma** embodied in busing controversy. If we ignore it, efforts to reinvigorate community in America may simply lead to more divided society.

### Fraternity vs. Fraternity: The Scope Problem

Earlier observation: Bridging and bonding social capital good for different things
- Strong ties with intimate friends → chicken soup when you're sick
- Weak ties with distant acquaintances → more likely to produce job leads

**From collective point of view**: Scope of social capital we need depends on scale of problems we face

**The aluminum magic wand vs. second-best wand**:
- Golden magic wand: Would miraculously create more bridging social capital
- Aluminum magic wand: Could only create more bonding social capital (more blacks and whites to church, but not same church; more Hispanics and Anglos to soccer field, but not same field)
- Should we use the aluminum wand?

### What Kind of Social Capital Do We Need?

**For different problems, different scopes**:

- Small children getting stimulation and structure: A little "familism" (bonding) goes long way
- Improving public schools: Need social capital at community level—residential communities (neighborhood school model) or communities of like-minded families (charter school model)
- Other issues (deciding welfare system replacement, quality of public debate): Need social capital of most broad and bridging kind that will most improve quality of public debate

**Critical insight**: For our biggest collective problems we need precisely the sort of bridging social capital that is toughest to create

**Challenge**: This will be central as we turn to most important question of this book: So what do we do now?

---

## SECTION FIVE: What Is to Be Done?

---

## Chapter 23: Lessons of History: The Gilded Age and the Progressive Era

### Introduction: Historical Parallels

Over last 3 decades, social, economic, and technological changes rendered obsolete significant stock of America's social capital. Growing social-capital deficit threatens educational performance, safe neighborhoods, equitable tax collection, democratic responsiveness, everyday honesty, even health and happiness.

**Key question**: Is erosion of social capital ineluctable consequence of modernity, or can we do something about it?

History instructs. Unexpectedly relevant and optimistic lessons found in period uncannily like our own: **Gilded Age and Progressive Era** (decades at end of 19th/beginning of 20th century)

**Deep parallels**: Challenges facing American society at end of 19th century foreshadowed those we face in our own time

### The Gilded Age Transformation (1870-1900)

**Century ago**: America also just experienced period of dramatic technological, economic, and social change rendering obsolete significant stock of social capital

**In 3-4 decades after Civil War**:
- Industrial Revolution
- Urbanization
- Massive waves of immigration transformed American communities
- Millions left family and friends on farm for Chicago, Milwaukee, Pittsburgh
- Millions more left community institutions in Polish shtetl or Italian village for Lower East Side or North End

**Classic symptoms of social-capital deficit**:
- Crime waves
- Degradation in cities
- Inadequate education
- Widening gap between rich and poor
- "Saturnalia" of political corruption

### The Progressive Response (1890s-1910s)

**But even as problems erupting**: Americans beginning to fix them

Within few decades around turn of century:
- Quickening sense of crisis
- Coupled with inspired grassroots and national leadership
- Produced extraordinary burst of social inventiveness and political reform

**Most major community institutions in American life today** were invented or refurbished in that most fecund period of civic innovation in American history

**Note**: Progressive Era not only example of practical civic enthusiasm in American history, and surely not flawless, but contains many instructive parallels to our own era

**This chapter**: Tells story of that exceptional epoch, offering inspiration, enlightenment, and a few cautionary tales

### Technological and Economic Change (1870-1900)

Between roughly 1870 and 1900, America evolved rapidly from rural, localized, traditional society to modern, industrialized, urban nation.

**At end of Civil War**: America remained predominantly land of small farms, small towns, small businesses (as at time of Tocqueville's visit in 1830s)

**By turn of century**: Rapidly becoming nation of cities, teeming with immigrants from European/American villages, toiling in factories operated by massive industrial combines

### Technological Revolution

**In 8 decades up to 1870**: US Patent Office recognized 118,000 inventions
**Next 4 decades**: Patents generated at nearly 20x this rate

**New inventions** revolutionized agricultural productivity (reaper), transformed home (sewing machine, canned food), but most momentous: Inventions underlying American industrial, transportation, urban revolutions—steam boiler, steel, electricity, telegraph, telephone, elevator, air brake, many more

**Steel production**: Mushroomed from 77,000 tons (1870) to 11.2 million tons (1900)
**Factories**: Nearly quadrupled from 140,000 (1865) to 512,000 (1900), and grew even faster
- 1865: Typical New England mill employed only 200-300 people
- 1915: First Ford Motor plant employed no fewer than 15,000

### The Electrical Revolution

**Journalist Mark Sullivan** on electricity at turn of century:

> "electricity was streaking up and down the country, literally like lightning—wires to provide it with a pathway were everywhere being extended, like long nerves of new growth, from central power houses, from the city to the suburb, and longer capacity for transmission carrying it to distant villages, from the villages to the farm—everywhere ending in a switch, by the turning of which man could tap for himself a practically limitless reservoir of physical power."

### Transportation and Communication Revolution

Railroad and telegraph transformed America from small, isolated "island communities" to integrated national economic unit

**1870-1900**: Nationwide rail network grew from 53,000 to 193,000 miles

**Historian Sean Dennis Cashman**: "A transcontinental railroad network brought farm and factory, country and town, closer together. Telegraph and telephone, electricity and press increased public knowledge, business efficiency, and political debate."

### Corporate Revolution

Along with technological revolutions came revolution in scale of enterprise—seed time of modern corporation

**Corporate organization** decimated many occupations (small merchant, independent artisan) while creating new ones (company administrator, unskilled industrial worker)

**1897-1904**: First great merger wave swept Wall Street, leaving massive new corporations—Standard Oil, General Electric, Du Pont, U.S. Steel, American Tobacco, Nabisco, many others

**In fact**: In relationship to size of total economy, merger wave at end of 19th century not rivaled until megamergers of 1990s

### Economic Growth and Inequality

**Economic historian Glenn Porter** on dramatic changes in structure and scale:

> "For the first time, whole industries came to be identified with names of powerful individuals who dominated them—Cornelius Vanderbilt, E. H. Harriman, James J. Hill in railroads, Cyrus McCormick in reapers, John D. Rockefeller in oil, J. P. Morgan in finance, James B. Duke in tobacco, Gustavus Swift and Philip Armour in meatpacking, Andrew Carnegie in steel.... Similarly, improvements in transportation and communications and growth of cities opened opportunities for mass merchandising in new fields of department stores, mail-order houses, chain stores. Montgomery Ward and Sears, Roe-buck & Company led way among mail-order firms, while distributors such as A&P and Woolworth's set new patterns in chain store retailing."

**Material standard of living**: Improved substantially during half century after close of Civil War
- Per capita wealth increased ~60%
- Real per capita GNP rose 133%
- 1871-1913: Expansion of American economy averaged 4.3% annually

**However, gains not spread evenly** across social classes or time:
- Gap between rich and poor, and gap between skilled and unskilled laborers, widened
- **Historian Mark Wahlgren Summers**: "in work experience, in satisfaction with American society, in pay scales and control over own lives"
- 1896 **Charles B. Spaur** estimated: 1% of population owned >50% of all national wealth, while 44% of families at bottom owned only 1.2%
- **Jeffrey Williamson and Peter Lindert**: Economic inequality increased rapidly during years of early industrialization prior to Civil War and continued to rise irregularly to very high levels, probably peaking just before WWI
- Not until final decades of 20th century would economic inequality widen as it did during 19th century
- Despite growing maldistribution, real income and standard of living of American workers did rise significantly in late 19th/early 20th centuries

### Economic Instability

Several severe recessions ("panics") interrupted economic progression
- Unemployment surpassed 16% in depressions of 1873-77 and 1893-97
- No period of economic distress in American history as deep and traumatic as years from 1893 to 1897
- That depression followed by almost 2 decades of nearly uninterrupted growth
- Prosperity of these 2 decades produced society confident and efficient enough to contemplate large-scale innovation to address problems—crime, violence, disease, urban squalor, political corruption, even growing inequalities of wealth and power
- Also gave birth to broad and internally diverse Progressive coalition united in optimistic assumption that society capable of improvement via intentional reform

### Population Growth and Urbanization (1870-1900)

**1870-1900**: National population nearly doubled from 40 million to 76 million
**Cities**: Population tripled from 10 million to 30 million

Large cities grew faster still, and new ones added to roles almost yearly. Number of cities with >50,000 population tripled from 25 to 78 in this period.

**Examples of explosive urban growth (1870-1890)**:
- Boston: Rose by 79% to nearly 450,000
- San Francisco: Doubled to nearly 300,000
- Milwaukee: Tripled to >200,000
- Denver: Multiplied twentyfold to 107,000
- Chicago: Barely a village in 1860, had population of 2.2 million by 1910

Year after year endless stream of hopeful emigrants from American farms and European villages poured into anonymous teeming cities of tenements and skyscrapers. These migrants living not merely in new community, but in setting so unfamiliar and disjointed that many doubted it deserved term *community* at all.

### Immigration Wave (1870-1900)

Most new urban dwellers also living in new country

**30 years between 1870 and 1900**: Nearly 12 million persons immigrated to US
- More than had come in previous 2.5 centuries
- In following 14 years: Nearly another 13 million would arrive

**1870**: 1/3 of all industrial workers in America foreign born
**1900**: More than half were

**1890**: Immigrant adults actually outnumbered native adults in 18 of 20 cities with population >100,000

### Changing Immigrant Demographics

Immigrants came from wide variety of European countries plus Canada and East Asia. Germans, Irish, French Canadians, British, and Scandinavians most numerous up to 1890, but during following 2 decades (**historian Steven Diner**):

> "immigrants, mostly Catholics and Jews from unfamiliar countries of Southern and Eastern Europe, poured into America in record numbers to work in its expanding industrial economy. Often living in dense urban neighborhoods where foreign tongues predominated, they created their own churches, synagogues, and communal institutions."

### Cultural Tensions

**By 1890**: Cacophony of strange tongues and strange customs triggered national debate about "Americanization" and ethnic identity—similar in many respects to debate about "multiculturalism" and "English only" today

**Historian Sean Dennis Cashman**: "When in 1889 and 1890 states of Illinois and Wisconsin decided that English was to be medium of instruction in schools, there was great outcry from Germans and Scandinavians."

### Urban Life: Opportunity and Insecurity

New Chicagoan living life and facing risks quite different from rural Iowa or rural Slovakia
- Had come in search of economic opportunity, often found it
- But also encountered profound insecurity
- Urban workers frequently unemployed
- Older systems of "outdoor relief" (local, temporary public assistance) swamped by new demands
- Newer system of "indoor relief" (poorhouse) replaced traditional social safety nets
- Traditional nets of family, friends, community institutions no longer fit way new urban workers had come to live

### New Consumer Culture

New affluence + ingenuity gradually combined to produce new culture of leisure and materialism

**Invention of phonograph and movies** (1896-1902): Portended radical transformation in nature of mass leisure in new century

**Examples**:
- 1908: NYC alone had >600 five-cent storefront movie theaters ("nick-elodeons")
- 1914: 0.5 million records produced annually
- 1921: Figure would balloon to >100 million
- 1897: **Mr. Dooley** (Finley Peter Dunne's fictional Irish American barman) derided new emphasis on material consumption:

> "I have seen America spread out fr'm th' Atlantic to th' Pacific with a branch office iv th' Standard Ile Comp'ny in ivry hamlet. I've seen th' shackles dropped fr'm th' slave, so's he cud by lynched in Ohio. ...An' th' invintions ... th' cottongin an' th' gin sour an' th' bicycle an' th' flyin'-machine an' th' nickel-in-th'-slot machine an' th' Croker machine an' th' sody fountain an'—crownin' wurruk iv our civilization—th' cash raygister."

**Decade later**: Harvard philosopher **William James** expressed same disdain in elevated language, bemoaning "moral flabbiness born of exclusive worship of bitch-goddess SUCCESS. That—with squalid cash interpretation put on word 'success'—is our national disease."

### Progressive Cultural Changes

Other cultural changes during Gilded Age more progressive:
- As Industrial Revolution advanced, middle-class male and female spheres became less rigidly delimited
- Women assumed new public roles, demanded vote, got advanced education, increasingly worked and played alongside men
- Critical ingredients: Advances in education of women and (for middle-class women, able to enjoy fruits of new timesaving domestic appliances) new leisure
- During Gilded Age women began to break out of traditional "proper sphere," many joining local reform efforts under banner of "municipal housekeeping" and few entering professions, including law and medicine
- Laid groundwork for "new woman" of Progressive Era

### The Overwhelming Pace of Change

To those who lived through this epoch, what was most striking was simply the overwhelmingly accelerated pace of change itself

Nothing in experience of average American at end of 20th century matches wrenching transformation experienced at beginning of century by immigrant raised as peasant in Polish village who within few years was helping construct avant-garde skyscrapers of Louis Sullivan in city of "big shoulders" beside Lake Michigan

Even for native-born Americans, pace of change in last decades of 19th century extraordinary

**Bostonian Henry Adams** later wrote of his own boyhood: "The American boy of 1854 stood nearer the year 1 than to the year 1900."
<!-- pp. 381-400 -->

## Chapter 17: The Gilded Age and Progressive Era Context

### Urban Crisis and Middle-Class Reaction

- Late 19th century cities seen as deeply dysfunctional: dirty streets, inadequate schools, poor sanitation, foul stables, unconnected sewers
- Evangelist **Josiah Strong** called cities the locus of murder, crime, and vice
- Historian **Don Kirschner**: cities were "esthetically repulsive, commercially spastic, culturally balkanized, morally depraved, medically lethal, socially oppressive, and politically explosive"
- Revisionist historians (e.g., **Jon Tieford**) note practical achievements: clean water, efficient transportation, extensive libraries
- **Machine politics** had beneficial effects for urban immigrants, providing political access
- **Lincoln Steffens**: "The misgovernment of the American people is misgovernment *by* the American people"
- City machines offered patronage, contracts, protection to illegitimate business; corruption was rampant (Boss Tweed paid $179,729.60 for three tables and forty chairs)

### Economic Inequality and Political Alienation

- **Robber barons** (Rockefeller, Morgan, Carnegie) accumulated unprecedented wealth while most Americans lacked protections against railroad exploitation, expensive credit, price deflation
- Industrial trusts transformed economic power into political power
- Workers attempted unionization but faced violence and recurrent depressions
- Historian **Steven Diner**: Middle-class Americans watched trusts manipulate Congress, suppress dissent; government appeared captive of special interests

### Race and Immigration

- Ethnic cleavages reinforced class lines
- **Nell Irvin Painter**: middle/upper classes were largely Protestant, native-born, British descent; working classes were foreign, Catholic, or (in South) black
- **Defensive nativism** emerged: unions feared wage competition, Protestant conservatives opposed Jews and "Papists," social reformers worried immigration exacerbated urban problems
- **American Protective Association** (founded 1887) claimed 2.5 million members (7% of adults) by 1894
- **"Just say no" temperance movement** appealed to native-born Protestants fighting immigrant cultural traditions

### Racial Segregation and Disenfranchisement

- After Reconstruction (1877), southern whites violently excluded blacks from politics
- **1896: *Plessy v. Ferguson*** endorsed "separate but equal" Jim Crow laws
- Segregation spread from railcars to streetcars, hospitals, jails, theaters
- **1880s lynchings**: averaged one every other day somewhere in America
- **1890-1908**: virtually all southern states disenfranchised African Americans using poll tax, literacy test, grandfather clause
  - Electoral participation fell 62% average (100% in North Carolina, 99% Louisiana, 98% Alabama, 83% Florida)
- Northern civic institutions also excluded working-class people, African Americans, Jews, Catholics
- Racist doctrines gained intellectual credibility
- **Nathaniel Shaler** (Harvard): argued blacks reverting to savagery
- **Teddy Roosevelt** and **Woodrow Wilson** coincided with "the nadir of race relations in America" (**Wilson Carey McWilliams**)

### Technology and Community Debate

- Railroad, rural free delivery, mail-order firms (Sears, Roebuck, Montgomery Ward, A&P, Woolworth's) disrupted local commerce—precursors to Wal-Mart and Amazon
- **William Allen White** (Progressive journalist): "Mail order house unrestricted will kill our smaller towns, creating great cities with their inevitable caste feeling"
- Iowa newspaper: contrasted impersonal Marshall Field vs. hometown merchant who "dropped a tear of sympathy"

#### Optimistic View: Technology Enables Connection

- **Optimists**: new communications (rail, telegraph, telephone) would expand altruism and unify society
- **William Allen White**: electric wire, iron pipe, street railroad, newspaper, telephone "have made us all one body.... There are no outlanders. It is possible for all men to understand one another.... Indeed it is but the dawn of a spiritual awakening"
- **Herbert Croly**: new media would allow active citizenry to "meet" despite distance, reducing need for representation—sounds timely for Internet era

#### Cautious View: Technology Threatens Face-to-Face Ties

- **John Dewey** and **Mary Parker Follett**: concerned about intertwining new technology with face-to-face ties
- **Dewey**: "The Great Society created by steam and electricity may be a society [but] it is no community. The invasion of the community by the new and relatively impersonal and mechanical modes of combined human behavior is the outstanding fact of modern life"
- **Follett**: "Real solidarity will never be accomplished except by beginning somewhere the joining of one small group with another.... Only by actual union, not by appeals to the imagination, can the varied neighborhood groups be made the constituents of a sound, normal, unpartisan city life"
- **Jean Quandt**: Working in Roxbury suburb, Follett observed "a free, full community life lived within the sustaining and nourishing power of the community bond ... is almost unknown now"
- Follett sought to create community centers as institutions for civic engagement, integrating churches, trade associations, lodges, youth groups

### Professionalization vs. Grassroots Democracy

- Progressives worried about professionalization replacing participation with spectatorship
- **Robert Park**: "In politics, religion, art and sport we are represented now by proxies where formerly we participated in person"
- **John Dewey**: cheap amusement diverts from political concern and organization into "an effective public"
- **Dilemma**: professionals could do more effective job than volunteers, but disempowering ordinary members diminished grassroots civic engagement and fostered oligarchy
- In the end, professionalism would win out

### Social Darwinism to Social Reform

- **Gilded Age ideology**: social Darwinism—survival of fittest with minimal government interference
- Critics gradually gained upper hand intellectually and politically
- **Historian Painter**: "Americans came increasingly to feel that society needed to be democratized to ensure everyone a decent chance for life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness"
- **Muckraking journalism** triggered philosophical shift:
  - **Jacob Riis**: *How the Other Half Lives* (1890)—slum tenements
  - **Lincoln Steffens**: *Shame of the Cities* (1904)—urban corruption
  - **Ida Tarbell**: *McClure's* (1904)—Standard Oil depredations
  - **Upton Sinclair**: *The Jungle* (1905)—immigrant laborer abuses
- Progressive intellectuals articulated yearning for community values of small-town life, nostalgia for materialism, individualism, and "bigness" of new America

### Historical Parallels: Then and Now

- **Walter Lippmann** (1914): "We are unsettled to the very roots of our being.... We are not used to a complicated civilization, we don't know how to behave when personal contact and authority have disappeared. There are no precedents to guide us, no wisdom that wasn't made for a simpler age. *We have changed our environment more quickly than we know how to change ourselves*"
- **Booth Tarkington** (Pulitzer Prize novelist): reflected on late-19th-century Indianapolis nostalgia—"homelike" pleasant town with neighborly understanding, clean air, time to live

> Not quite so long ago as a generation, there was no panting giant here, no heaving, grimy city; there was but a pleasant big town of neighborly people who had understanding of one another, being on the whole, much of the same type.... The good burghers were given to jogging comfortably about in phaetons or in surreys for a family drive on Sunday. No one was very rich; few were very poor; the air was clean, and there was time to live. —**Booth Tarkington**

- **Robert Barrows**: Tarkington's lament oversimplifies but reflects a reality readers of his generation accepted
- **Charles Horton Cooley** (1912): "in our own life the intimacy of the neighborhood has been broken up by the growth of an intricate mesh of wider contacts which leaves us strangers to people who live in the same house ... diminishing our economic and spiritual community with our neighbors"

### Progressive Vision: Small-Town Values in Industrial Society

- Progressive thinkers came from small towns, recognized both oppressive features ("small-town herd") and virtues (community rooted in interpersonal ties)
- **William Allen White**: "Reading of a wedding or the birth of a child, we have that neighborly feeling that breeds the real democracy"
- Small-town neighborliness = informal network of mutual aid, **social capital** in pure form
- **Jane Addams**: village gossip kept men informed about who needed help, enabled "the good lying next at hand"
- Small-town ethos emphasized widespread participation, egalitarian rather than paternalistic community
- Progressives decried erosion of close-knit ties in urbanizing, industrializing America
- Impersonal market ties replaced sturdier bonds of family, friendship, small-town solidarity
- Echoed European theorists: **Sir Henry Maine** (status vs. contract), **Ferdinand Tönnies** (Gemeinschaft vs. Gesellschaft), **Emile Durkheim** (mechanical vs. organic solidarity), **Georg Simmel** (town vs. metropolis)
- **Benjamin Disraeli** (1845): "In great cities men are brought together by the desire of gain. They are not in a state of co-operation, but of isolation, as to the making of fortunes; and for all the rest they are careless of neighbours. Christianity teaches us to love our neighbour as ourself; modern society acknowledges no neighbour"
- Yet these thinkers remained hopeful that social bonds could be reconstructed in arm's-length society
- **Historian Quandt**: "The easy sense of belonging, the similarity of experience, and the ethic of participation might be more easily maintained in the small locality than anywhere else, but this did not preclude their cultivation in different soil"

### Middle-Class Flight and Sociability Deficit

- **Gilded Age**: middle class fled immigrant cities to suburbs, retreated into tight neighborhood enclaves, dismissed municipal politics, allowed industrial capitalism to proceed unchecked
- **Paul Boyer**: "the middle class was in fact abandoning the immigrant cities and their complex problems—fleeing to the suburbs, retreating into tight neighborhood enclaves, dismissing municipal politics with ridicule"
- **Jeffrey A. Charles**: "by the turn of the century ... sociability alone appeared to be an inadequate response to the feeling of crisis that gripped the middle class.... [S]ocial redemption required a new type of cooperative activism ... serving the community"

### Woodrow Wilson and the New Age

- **Woodrow Wilson** (1912 presidential campaign): spoke of transformation America had undergone in preceding four decades

> We have come upon a very different age from any that preceded us.... Yesterday, and ever since history began, men were related to one another as individuals.... All over the Union, people are coming to feel they have no control over the course of their affairs. To-day, the everyday relationships of men are largely with great impersonal concerns, with organizations, not with other individual men. Now this is nothing short of a new social age, a new era of human relationships, a new stage-setting for the drama of life. —**Woodrow Wilson**

### Summary: Era Like Our Own

**IT WAS, IN SHORT, A TIME VERY LIKE OUR OWN:**
- Technological advance and unparalleled prosperity, but nostalgic for integrated connectedness
- New communications modes promised new community, but thoughtful observers worried those forms would be fool's gold
- Optimism from economic advances battled pessimism from intractable social ills
- New concentrations of wealth and corporate power raised questions about democracy's meaning
- Massive urban concentrations of impoverished ethnic minorities posed questions of social justice and stability
- Comfortable middle class torn between seductive escape and deeper demands of redemptive solidarity
- New commerce, restructured workplace, spatial organization threatened older solidarity forms
- Immigration changed America's complexion, seemed to imperil *unum* in *pluribus*
- Materialism, political cynicism, spectatorship over action seemed to thwart idealistic reformism
- Older social connections abraded—even destroyed—by technological, economic, social change
- Path from past could not be retraced; few saw path to better future clearly
- Complacency bred of technological prowess succeeded by dissatisfaction, civic inventiveness, organized reform efforts fueled by discontent and hopefulness

### Progressive Outlook: Activist, Not Fatalist

- Progressives too practical to seek return to smaller, simpler, pastoral age
- Admired past virtues but understood we could not go back
- Industrial Age made possible material prosperity essential for civic progress
- Issue: not "modernity, yes or no?" but how to reform institutions and adapt habits to secure enduring values
- Outlook was **activist and optimistic, not fatalist and despondent**
- **Distinctive characteristic**: conviction that social evils would not remedy themselves; foolhardy to wait passively for time's cure
- **Herbert Croly**: did not believe the future would take care of itself—**Neither should we**

### The Progressive Response

- **Richard McCormick**: final years of 19th century might chart course for Americans entering 21st century
- Amid hard times, Americans questioned adequacy of institutions and whether democracy and economic equality were possible in industrial society
- Hundreds poured energies into settlement houses where they lived and worked among urban poor
- New generation of ministers sought to make Christianity relevant by aligning churches with the disadvantaged
- Municipal reform entered new phase as businessmen and professionals enlisted broad support for urban improvement programs
- Women's clubs turned from discussing literature to addressing social problems
- **Seeds of Progressivism planted during depression of 1890s**

### The Associational Boom (1870-1920)

- Late 19th century: veritable **"boom" in association building**
- American penchant for clubs dated to earliest Republic years
- Some Progressive Era associations dated from first third of 19th century; many from Civil War and aftermath
- Earlier foundations supported massive new civic structure in late 19th/early 20th centuries
- **Social club movement** swept land in late 19th century, emphasizing self-help and amateurism
- **1876**: Henry Martyn Robert published *Robert's Rules of Order* to bring order to mushrooming anarchy of meetings
- Handbooks on establishing boys' clubs and women's clubs appeared
- College fraternities and sororities expanded rapidly in 1880s-1890s

### Growth in Voluntary Associations

- **1870s-1910s**: Americans created/joined unprecedented number of voluntary associations
- New association types multiplied; chapters of preexisting associations proliferated; associations federated into state and national organizations
- Everywhere—great cities to small heartland towns—voluntary associations grew faster than population
- **Per capita density of associations** (fraternal, religious, ethnic, labor, professional, civic) rose sharply through second half of 19th century
- Then, shortly after turn of century, density began to stagnate
- **Figure 94**: shows growth in local organizations per capita in 26 diverse communities (1840-1940)—mirrors explosive growth in U.S. newspapers 1880-1910, stagnation 1920-1940

### Foundation of 20th-Century Civil Society

- Standing at verge of another century, foundation stone of 20th-century civil society set by generation of 1870-1900
- Institutional ferment ended early 20th century; long period of infilling followed as organizations founded in Gilded Age/Progressive Era added membership ranks
- **Figure 94** traces not merely associational building but an arc of civic creativity and entrepreneurship
- **1870-1920**: civic inventiveness reached crescendo unmatched in American history (not just numbers but range and durability)
- **Theda Skocpol** and colleagues: **half of *all* the largest mass membership organizations in two centuries of American history**—associations that *ever* enrolled at least 1% of adult male or female population—were founded 1870-1920
- **Figure 95**: number of such large membership associations grew dramatically in late 19th century, reaching plateau in 1920s, hardly budging during rest of 20th century

### Major Civic Institutions Founded 1870-1920

- **Table 9**: displays evidence of social-capital innovations around turn of 20th century
- Red Cross, NAACP, Knights of Columbus, Hadassah, Boy Scouts, Rotary, PTA, Sierra Club, Gideon Society, Audubon Society, American Bar Association, Farm Bureau Federation, Big Brothers, League of Women Voters, Teamsters Union, Campfire Girls—**hard to name a major mainline civic institution in American life today that was *not* invented in these few decades**
- Organizations founded in that fecund period have been unusually long-lived
- Of all 506 contemporary "societies and associations" listed in *Encarta 2000 World Almanac*, almost twice as many were founded 1890-1920 as 1960-1990
- **Figure 96**: distribution of founding dates reveals remarkable extent American civil society at close of 20th century still rested on organizational foundations laid at beginning of century
- Age distribution (elderly outnumber youthful) implies birth rate declined or infant mortality rate risen—organizational entrepreneurs at turn of century were more prolific or successful than in our own time

### Gender Segregation in Association Building

- America a century ago was more gendered place than our own; most organizations founded in that period segregated by sex
- Not surprising that most prominent example of organizational proliferation: **fraternal groups**
- Freemasonry had earlier origins, but Gilded Age ushered in massive expansion of fraternal groups
- **W. S. Harwood** (1897): "Every fifth, or possibly every eighth, man you meet is identified with some fraternal organization"
- **1910**: historian **David Beito** estimates conservatively one-third of all adult males over 19 were members

### Fraternalism: Benefits and Values

- Fraternalism represented reaction against individualism and anomie of rapid social change; asylum from disordered, uncertain world
- Fraternal groups provided material benefits (life/health insurance) and social solidarity and ritual
- **Mutual aid** based on reciprocity (today's recipient, tomorrow's donor) was core feature
- **Beito**: "They successfully created vast social and mutual aid networks among the poor"
- Nation's largest fraternal organizations (Masons, Odd Fellows, Knights of Pythias, Ancient Order of United Workmen, Modern Woodmen) reported hundreds of thousands of members in local chapters
- Geographically extended structure facilitated coinsurance to mitigate local crises (natural disasters, epidemics)
- By joining lodge, initiate adopted set of values: mutualism, self-reliance, business training, thrift, leadership skills, self-government, self-control, good moral character
- Values reflected fraternal consensus cutting across intractable divisions (race, gender, income)

### Diversity Within Fraternalism

- Men of all social ranks joined fraternal societies; encompassed middle-class and working-class members; typically segregated by race and gender
- Comparable organizations for African Americans and women served same functions (mutual aid, moral uplift)
- Segregation repugnant to our values, but as ascendant form of social capital, fraternal organization definitely not limited to middle-class white males
- **Knights of Columbus, B'nai B'rith, Prince Hall Freemasonry** (black Masons)—various ethnic groups spawned own fraternal organizations
- Early 20th century: fraternal organizations challenged by new service clubs (Rotary, Kiwanis, Lions, Jaycees) and professional associations offering business contacts, modern face, outward civic zeal—at expense of "brotherhood" of fraternalism

### Women's Associations

- Spontaneous grassroots crusade of 1873-74 across Midwest reinvigorated temperance movement, resulted in formation of **Woman's Christian Temperance Union (WCTU)**
- **Frances Willard**: adopted national policy of "Do Everything"—WCTU advocated prison reform, formed youth groups, established kindergartens, even endorsed labor reform
- 1890s WCTU began to decline; after Willard's death (1898), narrowed focus to temperance and prohibition
- New women's groups emerged from independent reading/study groups
- **1890**: translocal network linked together to form **General Federation of Women's Clubs**
- Women's associations turned toward explicit involvement in public affairs: child labor, women's employment, kindergartens, myriad social reforms including women's suffrage

### Immigrant and Ethnic Associations

- Emigration devalues social capital; most social connections left behind
- Immigrants rationally strive to conserve social capital via **chain migration** (immigrants from given locale settle near one another in new homeland)
- **Benevolent society for mutual aid** was bedrock: financial security, camaraderie, political representation
- Chinese tong member: "We are strangers in a strange country. We must have an organization (tong) to control our country fellows and develop our friendship"
- **Rowland Berthoff**: immigrants accustomed to tightly knit communal life quickly adopted fraternal form to bind together local ethnic communities against unpredictable American life
- **Germans** especially associational
- Italians, Jews, Poles, others from southern/Eastern Europe quickly organized mutual aid societies, free loan societies, burial societies, social/sports/recreational clubs, foreign-language newspapers, churches, synagogues
- **1910**: two-thirds of all Poles in America belonged to at least one of ~7,000 Polish associations
- Similar figures for Jews, Slovaks, Croats, etc.
- National fraternal organizations (B'nai B'rith, Hadassah, Knights of Columbus) attracted large numbers after turn of century

### African American Associations

- Building of associations among freed blacks followed similar pattern: mutual aid, burial, social associations, black fraternal and women's groups
- Released from bondage, exercising civic freedoms, facing profound social dislocation, blacks founded/joined associations in great numbers (1870-1900)
- **W. E. B. Du Bois**: *The Philadelphia Negro*—emphasized importance of black secret societies (Odd Fellows, Freemasons) providing "pastime from monotony of work, field for ambition and intrigue, chance for parade, insurance against misfortune"
- Church played unique role in social-capital formation within African American community
- Associations arose linking blacks and whites in support of social reform—**NAACP** and **Urban League**

### Religious Revival and Social Gospel

- Religion played substantial role in civic revitalization despite increasingly secular industrial culture
- **Salvation Army** (evangelical Protestant movement) spread from Britain to America (1880), ministering to unchurched urban poor with missionary zeal and mass marketing (marches, brass bands, "Hallelujah lassies")
- Era of **"Social Gospel"** and **"muscular Christianity"**
- Social Gospel: turn-of-the-century effort by liberal Protestant theologians and ministers to bring pressing social problems (urban poverty) to attention of middle-class parishioners
- Reaction against individualism, laissez-faire, inequality; attempt to make religion relevant to new social/intellectual circumstances

### The Social Congregation

- **E. Brooks Holifield**: "the social congregation"—late 19th century, thousands of congregations transformed into centers for worship *and* activities (Sunday school, concerts, church socials, women's meetings, youth groups, girls' guilds, boys' brigades, sewing circles, benevolent societies, day schools, temperance societies, athletic clubs, scout troops)
- **Henry Ward Beecher** advised Yale seminarians to "multiply picnics," and congregations proceeded beyond picnics to gymnasiums, parish houses, camps, baseball teams, military drill groups
- Protestant congregations by 1923 gave 25-35% of offerings to missions and benevolent causes (up from 14-18% at turn of century)

### Chautauqua Movement

- **Chautauqua movement** (founded 1874, upstate New York): summer institute for Methodist Sunday school teachers
- Spawned nationwide series of extension schools, study groups, tent lecture circuits (speakers: Eugene Debs to Warren Harding)
- **1919**: one commentator estimated "one out of every eleven persons in the country, man, woman, or child, attended a lyceum or Chautauqua program every year"
- Radio (later TV) would provide more alluring entertainment, though less opportunity for grassroots, cross-class civic deliberation

### Catholic and Black Church Engagement

- Catholics more sympathetic to plight of poor (more Catholics belonged to laboring classes)
- Church played special role in black community
- **Evelyn Higginbotham**: black church "housed a diversity of programs including schools, circulating libraries, concerts, restaurants, insurance companies, vocational training, athletic clubs—all catering to a mass population much broader than the membership of individual churches.... held political rallies, clubwomen's conferences, and school graduations"
- Socially reformist Christianity was central inspiration for much social activism
- **1912 Progressive convention**: delegates broke into emotional chorus of "Onward, Christian Soldiers!"

### Organized Labor Movement

- Era in which organized labor movement became serious force
- **Knights of Labor**: premise that workers of all types should be enrolled in "one big union"—boomed from 28,100 members (1880) to 729,000 (six years later), then fell to 100,000 (1890), collapsed (1894) due to internal conflicts (skilled vs. unskilled, blacks vs. whites)
- Leading role taken by **American Federation of Labor**, along with series of unions organized along craft and industrial lines (mine workers, machinists, longshoremen, electrical workers, garment workers, teamsters, etc.)

<!-- pp. 401-420 -->

## Chapter 23 (continued): Lessons of History: The Gilded Age and the Progressive Era

### Labor Unions as Social Capital

- **Union growth 1897-1904**: Union membership nearly quadrupled from 3.5% to 12.3% of nonagricultural workforce—a more durable expansion than previous waves
- **Historians Thomas Cochran and William Miller**: Unions were part of members' social lives, not merely economic tools
  - Labor unions embedded in clubs, lodges, fraternal orders
  - Mutual benefit policies provided security against accidents and unemployment
  - Union socials, dances, picnics, lectures offered "stimulating leisure-time activity"

### Youth Organizations (1901-1910)

- **Extraordinary burst of creativity**: Most nationwide youth organizations founded in single decade
  - Boy Scouts, Girl Scouts, Campfire Girls, 4-H, Boys Clubs, Girls Clubs, Big Brothers, Big Sisters, American Camping Association
- **Progressive focus on youth development**: Reformers devoted energies to creating constructive paths for young people
- **Marketing genius**: Combined enduring social values (trustworthy, loyal, helpful) with pure fun of camping, sports, play
- Kindergartens and high schools became recognizable elements of public schooling
- Playgrounds spread rapidly; **Playground Association of America** founded 1906
- Public recreation centers aimed to involve entire families in wholesome leisure

### Child Protection Movement

- **New York Society for Prevention of Cruelty to Children** (1874) spawned similar organizations
- By 1908: fifty-five local societies for prevention of cruelty to children
- Progressives didn't long nostalgically for "lost social control"—they blazed constructive new paths

### Settlement Houses

- **Settlement house movement**: Imported from mid-Victorian England
- **Hull House** (founded by **Jane Addams**, Chicago, 1889): Six by 1891, seventy-four by 1897, ~400 by 1910
- Idealistic young middle-class men and women lived in urban slums for years
- Activities: education, "moral uplift," debate societies, lecture series, bathing/sanitation training, manual skills, kindergartens, daycare, art galleries, coffeehouses, gymnasiums, nurseries
- **Mark Wahlgren Summers**: Settlement houses offered comprehensive community services

### Settlement House Impact

- **Ironically, greatest long-term effect on service givers, not recipients**
- **Jane Addams** hoped firsthand contact would give meaning to young college graduates
- Leaders produced: **Florence Kelley**, **Eleanor Roosevelt**, **Gerard Swope** (GE president), **Walter Sherman Gifford** (AT&T president)
- **Richard McCormick**: Settlements served as training grounds for Progressive social reform across all domains—tenement houses, public playgrounds, child labor abolition, better hours/wages for working women

### Progressivism as Civic Communitarian Reaction

- **Peter Levine**: Movement so broad (Upton Sinclair and J. Edgar Hoover, W.E.B. Du Bois and Robert Taft) it "can hardly be called a movement at all"
- **Core interpretation**: Progressive Era represented civic communitarian reaction to ideological individualism of Gilded Age
- Began with social goals broader and more immediate than political goals
- **Frederick Law Olmsted** (Central Park designer, Yosemite commissioner): Parks and recreation overcome isolation and suspicion

> "Playgrounds are actually coming in considerable numbers and in all parts of the country, and everywhere they produce the same social results. That is, they bring about fine community spirit, awaken civic consciousness and co-operation, and make for a whole-souled companionship instead of individualism and isolation."

- **Important goal: strengthen social capital** (though they didn't use this terminology)
- **Social capital** term itself invented by Progressive Era educator **L. J. Hanifan** re: community centers

### Kindergarten Movement

- Borrowed from institution invented by German progressive educators
- First American kindergarten launched by **Elizabeth Palmer Peabody** (Boston, "lady bountiful")
- By late 1870s: spreading rapidly; by 1908: 400+ kindergartens run by women's clubs, temperance groups, churches
- Inspired by innovative educational philosophy encouraging childhood creativity
- Volunteer organizers sought to provide wholesome education for immigrant children and influence child-rearing techniques
- Grew adult connectedness: mothers' clubs, sewing clubs
- Eventually incorporated into public school system, but important residue remained
- **National Congress of Mothers** (1897) → **Congress of Mothers and Teachers** (1924) → **PTA**

### Progressive Method

- **Civic engagement at the heart**: **Richard McCormick** describes their distinctive reform method
- Typically began by organizing voluntary association, investigating problem, gathering facts, analyzing via social sciences
- Proposed solution popularized through education and moral suasion campaigns
- If it seemed to work, taken over by government as public function

### Social Entrepreneurs and New Organizations

- Temperance movement aimed to create "cohesive structure of reciprocal responsibility" facing industrialization/urbanization
- Often built on preexisting social networks, especially religious ones
- Local and national reform movements built on foundations of informal/nonpolitical groups

### Women's Reading Groups Transform into Political Force

- 1890s depression: women's reading groups expanded agenda to social service and advocacy
- **General Federation of Women's Clubs (GFWC)** (1890): Campaigned for food inspection, housing codes, safer drinking water, workplace protection for women, services for poor/sick/disabled/children
- **National Congress of Mothers**: Sought public support for infant health clinics, juvenile courts, probation homes, kindergartens, playgrounds
- **National Association of Colored Women's Clubs of America** (1896): Barred by segregation from GFWC; campaigned against alcoholic consumption, supported nurseries, kindergartens, homes for unwed mothers
- **Rheta Childe Dorr** on suffrage: "Home is not contained within the four walls of an individual home. Home is the community."
- Suffrage movement was merely most visible culmination of feminist organizing at turn of century

### Labor Mobilization Waves

- Closing decades of nineteenth century: most vivid period of class conflict in American history
- **Ida Tarbell**: "The eighties dripped with blood"
- Despite efforts to broaden labor's agenda, most durable nineteenth-century unions focused on employment conditions
- Turn-of-century unionization burst: fifteen unionists elected to Congress (1910); threat of "socialism" prompted political establishment to encompass labor reform
- **National Consumers League** (1899, founded by **Florence Kelley**): Enabled middle-class women shoppers to boycott firms failing to provide decent working conditions for women employees

### Progressivism as Multi-Class Movement

- Evades simple "top down" or "bottom up" classification
- Some organizations (4-H, Grange) were federal government creations
- Others sprang up in response to local initiatives
- **Lateral diffusion of initiatives** from one community to another
- **Theda Skocpol**: Organizational expansion technique reminiscent of Methodist/circuit-riding clergy disseminating congregations pre–Civil War

### Lateral Learning: Social Centers/Community Centers

- 1890s: **John Dewey** at Hull House, Universities of Wisconsin and Chicago developed university extension schools
- **Tom Johnson** (Progressive mayor of Cleveland): Conceived periodic tent meetings for civic give-and-take
- 1907: Civic organizations in Rochester, NY established "social centers" in public schools for publicly funded popular debate
- Within three years: hundreds of such meetings held annually in Rochester
- **Democrat and Chronicle** (March 20, 1910): "evenings devoted to discussions of business conditions, health, art, social organization, high prices of liquor question and neighborhood problems"
- 1911 observer: "the topic being the commission form of government, a Polish washwoman and the president of the WCTU were opposed by a day cleaner and a college professor"
- By 1916: "social center" or "community center" movement spread across country
- Evoked L. J. Hanifan's first recorded reference to "social capital"

### Geographic Distribution

- Major metropolitan/intellectual centers (NY, Boston) part of process, but much creative action in heartland communities
- Association building wave of late nineteenth century actually began in small heartland towns, not cosmopolitan metropolises
- High school movement spread most rapidly in small Midwest/West towns
- **Historians Arthur Link and Richard McCormick**: "Progressivism was the only reform movement ever experienced by the whole American nation"

### Political Achievements

- Most thoroughgoing renovation of public policies and institutions in American history
- Secret ballot (1888, Kentucky); popular initiative and referendum (1898, South Dakota); presidential primary elections (1900, Minnesota); city manager system (1903, Galveston); direct election of senators (1913); women's suffrage (1893 Colorado; 1920 U.S. Constitution)
- All introduced and diffused nationwide in few short decades
- Most intense period of local administrative reform in U.S. history

### National-Level Reforms

- **Federal Reserve** (1913), income tax (1913), **Bureau of the Budget** (1921)
- First consumer protection legislation: **Food and Drug Administration**, federal meat inspection (1906), **Federal Trade Commission** (1914)
- First environmental legislation: national forest system (1905), national park system (1913)
- **Departments of Commerce and Labor** (1913), **General Accounting Office** (1921)
- Strengthened antitrust regulations (1903); child labor laws (1916); eight-hour day (railways, 1916); workmen's compensation (1916)
- First federal regulation of telecommunications industry (1910); **U.S. Bureau of Investigation** (1908; renamed FBI 1935)
- Federal campaign finance regulation (1907); biggest trade liberalization in half century (1913)
- Foundations for federal water policy (1902); **Mother's Day** (1914)
- Hardly any area of public policy left untouched

### Political Reform Assessment

- Not all reforms proved as successful as advocates expected
- Few in retrospect look positively pernicious
- Taken as whole: impressive achievement within constitutional system built to thwart radical change
- Rested on broad-based, grassroots, nationwide political movement sweeping both major parties in first decade of century
- Political mobilization drew on energies and organizations created during social capital building of previous decades

### From Social Networks to Political Action

- Wave began last third of nineteenth century with organizations (fraternal/cultural groups) focused on members' private concerns (leisure, self-help)
- Late nineteenth/early twentieth century: associations gradually turned attention to community issues, eventually political reform
- **Earlier inward-oriented phase of social networks paved way for later outward-oriented phase of political action**
- Central fact: **Investment in social capital was not an alternative to, but a prerequisite for, political mobilization and reform**

### Critiques of Progressive Era

#### Technocratic Elitism

- Professional historians note Progressives' propensity to favor technocratic elitism
- Proposing "professional," "expert" solutions adopted antipolitical stance demobilizing public participation
- Electoral turnout began descent from 1896 (hasn't yet recovered)
- Partisan politics was great enemy; Progressives preferred "boards" and "commissions" dominated by middle-class professionals
- Conscious of corruption/dependency in machine, blind to machine's role allowing access to public sphere for otherwise powerless (immigrants)
- **Philip Ethington**: "saddest perhaps is the deep and enduring damage done to democracy by her closest friends"—instead of deliberative democracy, we got direct, plebiscitary democracy

#### Social Control vs. Social Revolution Debate

- Did middle-class reformers organize voluntary associations to exert social control over rambunctious, uncouth working-class immigrants?
- Or did benevolent institutions strengthen immigrant/working-class communities and reduce social inequality?
- Or were middle-class reformers prodded to action by working-class "clients"?
- **Historian Painter**: To reduce this to top-down social control ignores intentions and agency of those whose lives were changed; fear of working-class violence explains much progressive reform

### Risks of Excessive Communitarianism

- Even celebrants recognized potential for excessive social control and subordination of individual
- Communitarian impulses could easily go too far
- WWI example: **William Dudley Foulke** (president, National Municipal League) suggested draft be used for public service after war

> "The public welfare may require of some that they shall marry and rear children for the sake of the community. They must be ready to do it whether they so desire or not. It may require of some, that they shall give up the use of intoxicating liquor or discontinue some other habit that involves extravagance or demoralization … whether there is a prohibitory law or not."

- Illustrates risk of overdone communitarianism ("big brother-ism, American style")

### Racial Segregation and Exclusion

- **Most troubling**: Racial segregation and social exclusion central to Progressive Era public agenda
- **Jim Crow** legalized (1896), **NAACP** founded (1909) to attack legal race discrimination
- 1915: second **Ku Klux Klan** founded (in part) to enforce segregation by illegal means
- Not all "civic innovations" were beneficent and progressive
- Risk: emphasizing community exacerbates division and exclusion
- Social capital inevitably easier to foster within homogeneous communities; emphasis on creation may inadvertently shift balance away from bridging toward bonding social capital
- **One of most instructive lessons from that earlier era**

### Positive Lessons: Institutional Durability

- Institutions of civil society formed 1880-1910 lasted nearly a century
- In those few decades, voluntary structures of American society assumed modern form
- Trends toward civic disengagement reviewed in Section II register decay of that very structure over last third of twentieth century

### Positive Lessons: Diagnosing the Problem

- Progressive Era leaders and forebears correctly diagnosed problem of social-capital/civic engagement deficit
- Tempting in 1890 to say "Life was much nicer back in the village. Everybody back to the farm"—they resisted that
- Similarly, among those concerned about social-capital deficit today, tempting to say "Life was much nicer back in the fifties. Would all women please report to the kitchen, and turn off the TV?"
- Social dislocation can easily breed reactionary nostalgia

### Call for Contemporary Civic Inventiveness

- **Message**: We desperately need era of civic inventiveness to create renewed institutions/channels for reinvigo-rated civic life
- Challenge: reinvent twenty-first-century equivalent of Boy Scouts, settlement house, playground, Hadassah, United Mine Workers, NAACP
- What we create may look nothing like Progressive institutions (just as theirs weren't carbon copies of earlier small-town folkways)
- Need to be ready to experiment as Progressives were
- **Willingness to err—and then correct our aim—is the price of success in social reform**

### Looking Forward from Twenty-First Century

- Hard to imagine time without Boy Scouts, but century ago twentieth-century equivalent of Tom Sawyer's gang on Mississippi would involve beanies, merit badges, Scout's oath must have seemed fanciful
- Boy Scouts provided new and successful forum for youthful community building
- Some solutions to today's civic deficit may seem initially preposterous
- Should be wary of straining civic inventiveness through conventional filters
- Specific reforms no longer appropriate, **but practical, enthusiastic idealism of that era—and its achievements—should inspire us**

---

## Arts and Social Capital (Conclusion)

### Arts as Bridge-Building

- Goal: ensure by 2010 Americans participate in (not merely consume) cultural activities from group dancing to songfests to community theater to rap festivals
- **Let us discover new ways to use the arts as a vehicle for convening diverse groups of fellow citizens**
- Art matters for its own sake beyond social effects—aesthetic objectives remain important
- Art especially useful in transcending conventional social barriers
- Social capital often a valuable by-product of cultural activities whose main purpose is purely artistic

### Examples of Arts-Based Community Building

- **Liz Lerman's Dance Exchange**: built community togetherness using modern dance, bringing together unemployed shipyard workers and white-collar professionals in Portsmouth (N.H.)
- **Roadside Theater Company**: mustered diverse local folks in declining Appalachian towns to celebrate traditions and restore community confidence through dramatization of local stories and music
- **Museum of the National Center for African American Artists** (Boston): convened diverse groups of black Americans (Haitians, Jamaicans, Afro-Brazilians, native African Americans) to build and parade twenty-foot fish sculptures to New England Aquarium
- **Toni Blackman's Freestyle Union** (Washington, D.C.): uses **ciphering** (novel combination of hip-hop, rap poetry, improvisational poetry slams) to attract people from all walks of life—from Filipino break-dancer to right-to-life Christian
- **Baltimore Museum of Art**: urges local residents to exploit public spaces on "Freestyle Thursdays" by inviting local choral groups and others to perform
- **Chicago's Gallery 37**: provides apprenticeships for diverse young budding artists—rich and poor, suburban and inner city, black, white, Latino—to follow their own muses, building social connections among artist-mentors, artist-apprentices, and observers
- **David Simpson** (Mattole Valley, northern California): used community theater to build bridges between loggers and environmentalists
- Many of these activities produce great art, but all produce great bridging social capital—**in some respects an even more impressive achievement**

## Politics and Government

### The Central Challenge for Democracy

- Politics and government is where inquiry about social capital began, and where Putnam concludes challenges to readers concerned about restoring community bonds
- **Nowhere is the need to restore connectedness, trust, and civic engagement clearer than in the now often empty public forums of our democracy**
- Challenge to government officials, political consultants, politicians, and citizens
- Goal: **Let us find ways to ensure that by 2010 many more Americans will participate in the public life of our communities—running for office, attending public meetings, serving on committees, campaigning in elections, and even voting**
- Perhaps foolhardy to hope to reverse entire decline of last three to four decades in ten years, but American democracy would surely feel beneficent effects of even partial reversal

### Campaign Reform

- **Campaign reform (above all, campaign finance reform)** should aim at increasing importance of social capital—and decreasing importance of financial capital—in elections (federal, state, local)
- Since time distributed more equally across population than money, privileging time-based participation over check-based participation would begin to reverse growing inequality in American politics
- Government authority should be **decentralized as far as possible** to bring decisions to smaller, local jurisdictions, while recognizing and offsetting potential negative effect of decentralization on equality and redistribution
- Liberals alert to benefits of social capital should be readier to transfer governmental authority downward in exactly the same measure that compassionate conservatives should be readier to transfer resources from have to have-not communities
- **Decentralization of government resources and authority to neighborhood councils** has worked in cities like Minneapolis, Portland, and Seattle, creating new social capital in form of potluck dinners, community gardens, and flea markets
- Deft design needed to ensure balance between bridging and bonding does not tip too far toward urban fragmentation

### Policy Design and Social Capital

- Policy designers of whatever partisan persuasion should become more **social capital–savvy**, seeking to do minimum damage to existing stocks of social capital even as they look for opportunities to add new stocks
- Idea: **"social-capital impact statement"** for new programs—less bureaucratic and legalistic than environmental impact statements, but equally effective at calling attention to unanticipated consequences
- Example: greatest damage to social capital in inner city of Indianapolis, Indiana, in last half century was unintended disruption of neighborhood networks when neighborhoods were pierced by **Interstate 65** in early 1960s
- **Front-Porch Alliance** created by former mayor **Stephen Goldsmith** more than a quarter century later was worthy effort to help restore some Indianapolis neighborhood institutions, but Goldsmith himself would say it would have been better to avoid the damage in the first place

### Avoiding False Debates

- All domains of social-capital creation need to avoid false debates
- One false debate: **"top-down versus bottom-up"**—roles of national and local institutions in restoring American community need to be complementary; neither alone can solve the problem
- Another false debate: whether government is the problem or the solution
- Accurate answer (from historical record as argued in chapter 15): **it can be both**
- Many of most creative investments in social capital in American history—from county agents and 4-H to community colleges and March of Dimes—were direct result of government policy
- Government may be responsible for some small portion of declines in social capital traced in this volume, and it cannot be sole solution
- **Hard to imagine meeting challenges set for America in 2010 without using government**

### Individual vs. Institutional Change

- Final false debate: whether what is needed to restore trust and community bonds in America is individual change or institutional change
- Honest answer: **"Both"**
- America's major civic institutions, both public and private, are somewhat antiquated a century after most were created
- They need to be reformed in ways that invite more active participation
- Whether specific suggestions made for institutional reform are persuasive or not is less important than possibility that we may have **a national debate about how to make our institutions more social capital–friendly**
- In the end, institutional reform will not work—indeed, will not happen—unless you and I, along with fellow citizens, resolve to become reconnected with our friends and neighbors
- **Henry Ward Beecher's advice** a century ago to **"multiply picnics"** is not entirely ridiculous today
- We should do this, ironically, not because it will be good for America—though it will be—**but because it will be good for us**

## APPENDIX 1: Measuring Social Change

### Primary Strategy: Triangulation

- Primary strategy: **triangulate among as many independent sources of evidence as possible**, following model of global warming researchers
- Exploration of social change inevitably constrained by fact that no one thought ahead to collect really perfect evidence half a century ago (reliability of friends, helpfulness of strangers, honesty of shopkeepers, frequency of block parties)
- Need to look for convincing proof not in single pair of polls or even single series of surveys, but instead for **convergence across a number of different series**, each carried out by different researchers
- Where possible, should look for change not merely in poll data, but also in institutions and behavior
- Core principle: **No single source of data is flawless, but the more numerous and diverse the sources, the less likely that they could all be influenced by the same flaw**
- Two independent (though necessarily imperfect) strands of evidence are better than one, and more than two are better still, especially if they have **different imperfections**

### Organizational Records

- **Organizational records** are firmest indicators in some respects
- Through them can directly compare civic involvement of Americans in 1950s, 1970s, and 1990s
- Assiduous record keeping of thousands of club secretaries and county clerks and church treasurers across decades much more reliable than frail recollections of "how things used to be"
- Constituency of group, meaning of "membership," assiduousness of information gathering can change over time
- **"Membership"** in union may not mean same thing in 1998 as in 1938; occupation of "teamsters" has surely changed
- Problems of comparability less severe for organizational records than for most other sorts of data
- Because organizations keep records over long periods, comparisons can extend back decades or even centuries, giving longer perspective on recent events
- Is 10 percent slump in membership or contributions from one year to next truly significant, or merely a commonplace down-tick? **Only long-term records can really tell**

### Limitations of Organizational Records

**Life cycles**: Organizations themselves have life cycles that may be independent of vitality of communities in which they exist. If Elks club is fading, perhaps its place is being taken by myriad other organizations, all of them still too young and small and effervescent to worry about keeping careful membership records. If we confine ourselves to examining membership records of long-standing organizations, we will miss new and rapidly growing groups.

**Birth and death rates**: Nothing whatever can be inferred about civic vitality of a community from **birth** of new organizations, unless at same time we also examine **death** rate of older ones. Discovery that, say, half of all environmental organizations now in existence were founded in last decade proves absolutely nothing about organizational trends, unless we also know how many similar groups have disappeared over same period. This issue especially problematic if (as is true, for example, of Internal Revenue Service records of nonprofit organizations) a list of organizations is not pruned regularly to eliminate defunct organizations.

**Dark matter**: Not all community activity is embodied in record-keeping organizations—indeed, probably most is not. One scholar estimates that **80 percent** of all community groups represent social **"dark matter"**—that is, without formal structure, without an address, without archives, without notice in newspapers, and thus invisible to conventional chroniclers. If we confine our attention to membership rosters, we may miss massive change or massive stability. Worse yet, if community life is, for whatever reason, becoming richer, but less formally organized, tracking membership figures alone would lead us to precisely the wrong conclusion.

### Social Surveys

- Deficiencies in organizational records can to some extent be offset by one of most useful inventions of twentieth century—**the systematic social survey**
- Well-designed poll can provide useful snapshot of opinions and behavior
- Even better, series of comparable surveys can yield kind of **social time-lapse photography**
- Just as one snapshot a day from single camera pointed unvaryingly at same garden patch can yield marvelous movie of botanical birth and growth, so single survey question, if repeated regularly, can produce striking image of social change
- Moreover, if question has been formulated deftly enough, it can encompass more diverse and changing social landscape than study of any single organization
- Through surveys can examine involvement not merely in League of Women Voters, but in any club that respondent thinks worth mentioning
- Can assess attendance not merely at official "town meeting," but at any local meeting
- Best of all, surveys can capture informal activities—not merely voting, but chatting with your neighbor; not merely organizational membership, but poker games
- **Surveys, in short, can illuminate the "dark matter" of community life**

### Limitations of Surveys

**Comparability**: Just as camera in time-lapse photography must be motionless to capture motion, so survey questions must be (more or less) unchanging to capture change. Example: experienced pollsters know that harder you probe, more responses you get. Thus number of organizational memberships that poll uncovers is heavily dependent on number of probes. To question "How many groups do you find the average American belongs to?" it is only slight exaggeration to respond "As many as you'd like, if I ask hard enough." Moreover, as survey researchers have become more sophisticated, they have discovered many other pitfalls for unwary student of change: **"order effects"** (answers depend in part on order in which questions are posed), **"house effects"** (different survey organizations obtain consistently different results to same question), and so on. Our social camera can be jiggled easily. Especially risky to compare results from questions posed at different times by different survey organizations. Only few survey archives contain data carefully enough controlled to ensure our social time-lapse photograph is reliable.

**Continuity**: Reliability of our time-lapse sequence is also very dependent on number of snapshots at our disposal. **In assessing social change, two observations are better than one, but many is much better than two**. Literally nothing at all can be sensibly said about change from single photo or single survey. Though this point seems obvious, otherwise intelligent folks sometimes claim to detect directions of social change from single observation, which is **just as silly as to make a claim about global warming from a single glance at the thermometer**. Data from two points in time offer some leverage for testing claims about change but are vulnerable to measurement inconsistency at either end. Single measurement error—subtle change in question order, for example—might lead to mistaken judgment about overall trend. Or suppose survey of church attendance in 1964 was taken in middle of August vacations and same question in 1994 happened to be posed during Easter week. With only two points in time, might well be misled into thinking that religious observance was booming in 1990s. Random fluctuations can invalidate judgments based on only few data points.

**Multiple measurements**: Change measured at multiple points in time becomes exponentially more reliable; if given variable increases steadily from time 1 to time 2, from time 2 to time 3, and so on to time 4, it becomes virtually impossible to conceive of series of measurement slipups that might have produced the trend. In short, for reliable assessment of social change, **we need not merely comparable measurements, but comparable measurements repeated as many times as possible**. For that reason, in this book Putnam has relied most heavily on surveys that posed same question dozens—even hundreds—of times over last quarter of twentieth century.

**Comprehensiveness**: Just as in case of membership rosters, surveys must cover wide range of activities. Even if question is literally invariant, its accuracy as measure may change over time. Might consider question about frequency of bowling as indicator of informal social togetherness. However, if bowling were gradually replaced by softball or soccer as leisure sport of choice among Americans, then accurately reported decline in team bowling might simply have been offset by rise in softball or soccer, both team sports. **So we must cast our net as widely as possible**.

**Timeliness**: Since social change proceeds unevenly, **measurement periods must be matched to hypotheses about the scale and timing of change**. Interest is not "social change" in abstract. Want to know what, if anything, has happened to our communities over last half century or so. Just as we could infer little about global warming by comparing yesterday to today, so too we can infer little about social change over past several decades by examining evidence over last few years—or over last few centuries, for that matter. So must always ask about any trend not just "What's changing?" but **"What's changing over what period?"** Fair test of thesis requires comparable data over as much of last three to five decades as possible.

### Survey Archives Used

**Good news**: Several national survey archives provide comparable, continuous, and comprehensive evidence on contours of social change

**Bad news**: With rare exceptions, these collections did not begin before mid-1970s. There is reason to suspect some important shifts in American community life began in mid-1960s, but few cameras began operating until about a decade later. Cannot be sure what was happening before shutter on social time-lapse camera was first triggered, but survey archives probably missed some of most interesting action. This deficiency is one important reason for taking advantage of organizational records. Also reason for paying special attention to those few surveys that span earlier period, such as **University of Michigan–NORC** study cited in chapters 3, 4, and 6.

### Absolute vs. Relative Measurement

- One last issue of methodology: Should we measure absolute or relative change, and if relative, relative to what?
- Should we consider absolute number of participants or contributions to some community purpose, or should we instead use some relative standard of comparison?
- Organizations and headline writers often boast of growing participation in absolute terms—"the XYZ Club has a record number of members this year!" "Record number of Angeleños go to the polls!" "Local church giving hits all-time high!"
- **But absolute numbers can be badly misleading**
- If total vote rises by 5 percent, while voting-age population is rising by 10 percent, participation has actually fallen
- Conversely, if membership in Grange falls by 5 percent, while number of farmers is falling by 50 percent, involvement of average farmer has actually risen
- If membership in local Parent-Teacher Association has fallen merely because there are fewer parents nowadays, we would not want to count that as evidence of civic decline
- Conversely, if number of lawyers in town doubled, while membership in bar association grew by only 5 percent, it would be misleading to conclude that lawyers were becoming more active in professional affairs
- In short, we generally should consider what economists call **"market share"**: What proportion of **the eligible population** takes part in any given activity?

### Controversial Case: Controlling for Education

- One important (and highly controversial) instance of relative vs. absolute change: When examining changes in civic involvement, should we control for educational levels?
- Argument for doing so is simple and powerful: **Education is one of the most important predictors—usually, in fact, the most important predictor—of many forms of social participation**—from voting to chairing local committee to hosting dinner party
- Moreover, educational levels of American public rose very sharply during precisely the period of interest to us
- So it seems logical to "control for" education, by asking, for example, about civic involvement of average college graduate
- In effect, to control for education in this way is to assume that given growth in educational levels, we should expect growth in civic involvement, and if we find declines **relative to educational levels**, that implies that some other factor must be depressing involvement
- By analogy, if we found that vocabulary skills in America were steady or falling despite rising levels of education, we surely would look for some other factor (like TV, for example) that might have been simultaneously tending to depress literacy
- At least until recently, to control for educational levels has been conventional approach of social scientists in estimating changes in social and political participation

**Counterargument**: Recently, some scholars have pointed out that many of sociological effects of education may themselves be relative, not absolute. If more people now have college degrees, perhaps sociological significance of credential has been devalued. Social status is, for example, associated with education, but we would not necessarily assume that just because more Americans are educated than ever before, America has a greater volume of social status than ever before. To extent that education is merely about sorting people, not about adding to their skills and knowledge and civic values and social connections, it is misleading to "control for" educational change.

**Core issue**: Whether (holding constant my own education) I am less likely or more likely to participate civically if those around me become more educated. In some cases effect of education may be relative, so that (intimidated by eggheads around me) I may be less likely to speak up at public meeting in college town than I would in more normal community. In these cases effect of education is mainly **relative**, and we should not expect that rising educational levels would push up participation. In other cases it seems likely that my propensity to participate will actually rise with level of education of my neighbors. I am more likely to join reading group, for example, if I live in community with lots of other educated readers. In these cases we should expect that rising levels of education should push up participation rates even faster.

**Evidence from this research**: Evidence uncovered in course of this research strongly suggests that effects of education on social participation are typically **absolute, not relative**. My education increases my social participation, and generally speaking, your education does **not** lower my participation. So if we both graduate from college, we should both tend to become more civically engaged. Under these circumstances it would be appropriate to control for rising educational levels. However, doing so has effect of amplifying declines in participation and minimizing increases, so given nature of argument, **the more conservative course is not to control for education**.

**Putnam's approach**: In analyses reported in this book Putnam generally **do** control for changes in population, but **do not** usually control for changes in educational composition of population. This rule of thumb stacks cards against hypothesis. Upshot is that **evidence presented in this book may well understate the gross decline in civic engagement in America over the last half century**.

### Statistical Controls for Cause and Effect

- Statistical controls also relevant to another recurrent issue in this book: assessing causes and effects
- Suppose interested in connection between TV watching and civic engagement, and suppose find that heavy TV watchers are rarely active in organizations
- Before concluding that TV inhibits civic participation, however, must consider other factors that might make this correlation spurious: perhaps working-class people watch more TV, whereas organizational leadership is monopolized by middle class
- One way to check this possibility is to **control statistically for social class**, in effect comparing participation rates of people of same class whose viewing habits differ
- Statistical techniques such as **multiple regression** allow us to control simultaneously for many possible confounding variables, particularly when (as, fortunately, in our case) very large survey archives are available
- **Virtually every generalization in this book has been subjected to detailed statistical analysis of this sort**, controlling simultaneously for age (or year of birth), gender, education, income, race, marital status, parental status, job status (working full-time, part-time, or not at all), and size of community of residence
- In addition, where relevant, Putnam controlled for other background factors, including year of survey, region, financial worries, homeownership, residential mobility (both past and anticipated), commuting time, general leisure activity, self-reported time pressure, self-reported health, and other factors
- To be sure, controls of this sort, though necessary, are not always sufficient to rule out spuriousness
- For this reason Putnam has ensured that data that underlie conclusions will be readily available to other researchers, so that they can explore alternative interpretations
- However, Putnam has also undertaken due diligence in analyses for this book to rule out obvious spuriousness
- To keep complicated statistical apparatus from interfering with presentation of main conclusions, graphs and charts here typically present data without multivariate controls, but in each case Putnam has also conducted extensive tests to be sure that underlying relationship was not spurious

### Presentation of Data

- One final cosmetic issue about figures in this book: In every case Putnam presents every available data point
- Often, however, short-term fluctuations obscure longer-term trends
- Example: figure 2 presents annual data from Department of Commerce on number of political organizations. Even cursory examination reveals clear biennial rhythm (more organizations in election years), along with few other deviations from longer trend (such as modest dip in 1995)
- In this, as in all other graphs, Putnam shows both dotted line linking actual data points and darker, smoother curve that conveys longer-term trend
- Darker lines (calculated simply as best-fitting polynomial curves) are intended to ease reading of figures, but purists who prefer unvarnished data may simply ignore darker lines

### Primary Survey Sources

**National Election Studies (NES)** and **General Social Survey (GSS)**:
- Two most widely used academic survey research archives for American social and political behavior
- Virtually every two years since 1952, coinciding with national elections, Survey Research Center of University of Michigan has surveyed sample of Americans about their political behavior (NES)
- Roughly every other year since 1974 National Opinion Research Corporation at University of Chicago has conducted broadly similar set of surveys on social behavior (GSS)
- Both archives provide high-quality scientific evidence about changes in Americans' attitudes and behavior
- For purposes of this book, utility of NES is limited—it focuses on elections and gives little attention to everyday civic participation
- GSS covers wider range of activities, although in domains most central to our interests its continuous coverage is largely confined to formal group membership, church attendance, and social trust
- Fortunately, in course of this research Putnam's colleagues discovered several other important survey archives to supplement GSS and NES

**Roper Social and Political Trends archive**:
- Roughly ten times per year between September 1973 and October 1994 the Roper survey organization interviewed in person national cross section of approximately 2,000 persons of voting age
- Yielding survey archive of more than 410,000 respondents over more than two decades
- Sampling method (multistage, stratified probability sample with quotas for sex, age, and employed women) remained essentially constant over entire period
- Many questions of social and political significance were asked repeatedly over this period
- Not all questions were asked in all surveys
- **One crucially important set of questions** relevant to civic engagement (summarized in table 1) appeared on every single survey along with standard demographic information
- This massive sample enables us to examine even forms of participation, like running for public office, that are quite rare

**DDB Needham Life Style surveys (DDB)**:
- Begun in 1975 and still continuing
- Provide regular barometric readings on scores of social, economic, political, and personal themes, from international affairs and religious beliefs to financial worries and condom usage
- Annual sample of 3,500–4,000; through 1999 contained more than 87,000 respondents over last quarter of twentieth century
- **To extent that it can be shown to be methodologically reliable, the DDB Needham Life Style archive constitutes one of the richest known sources of data on social change in America in last quarter of twentieth century**
- Because of its novelty and importance, Putnam presents additional information about this archive

**DDB Needham process**: Each year since 1975 the DDB Needham advertising agency has commissioned Market Facts, a commercial polling firm, to question national panel of American households about their consumer preferences and behavior. Most of roughly twenty-page written questionnaire is taken up with inquiries about detergents, mutual funds, automobiles, and so on. However, every year core set of questions has been posed about "life style" issues, including media usage, financial worries, social and political attitudes, self-esteem, and wide range of social behavior, such as reading, travel, sports and other leisure activities, family life, and community involvement.

**Important limitation**: Until 1985 only married households were included in sample. However, Putnam found few cases in which observed **trends** between 1985 and 1999 differ significantly between married and single respondents, although in number of cases there are modest differences in **levels**. Example: married people attend church more often than single people do, while singles attend club meetings more often than married people, but trends in both church- and clubgoing are essentially identical for two groups. In all cases where this sampling peculiarity poses potential problems of analysis, Putnam analyzed data separately by marital status to confirm that "missing 1975–84 singles" did not vitiate substantive conclusions. Where levels and/or trends in traits of interest vary by marital status, Putnam made appropriate adjustment to track changes over entire 1975–98 period.

**Second limitation**: DDB Needham Life Style data come not from random samples of population, but from form of **quota sampling called "mail panels"**. Participants in such surveys—which are frequently used by commercial polling firms—are initially self-selected. Given that few people who choose to participate might differ significantly from many who do not, this sampling procedure requires that we consider seriously possibility of response bias in these data.

**Mail panel methodology**: Sampling begins when Market Facts acquires from commercial list brokers names, addresses, and sometimes demographic characteristics of very large numbers of Americans—from driver's license bureaus, telephone directories, and many other sources. Large samples from these lists are then invited by mail to express willingness in advance to respond periodically to mail and phone inquiries about commercial products and services, as well as other current issues. According to Market Facts officials, rate of favorable response to such invitations varies across different sectors of population—from perhaps less than 1 percent among racial minorities and inner-city residents to perhaps 5–6 percent among middle-aged, middle-class "middle Americans." From this prerecruited "mail panel" (numbering perhaps five hundred thousand at any one time) are then drawn random, demographically balanced samples for annual DDB Needham Life Style surveys (as well as hundreds of other commercial and other surveys throughout year). Each Life Style respondent is mailed long written questionnaire that he or she is asked to complete and return within several weeks. At this stage response rate (roughly 70–80 percent) is typically higher than for conventional random samples.

**Potential drawbacks of mail panel approach**:

1. Because initial recruitment is by mail, literacy in English is essential requirement, and thus bottom of educational ladder is underrepresented, as are non–English speakers
2. Effective response rates are much lower among racial minorities
3. Adults under twenty-five are slightly underrepresented, probably because their mobility makes them harder to track

**Sample characteristics**: In round numbers, sample contains 5 percent too few high school dropouts, 10 percent too few single respondents, 10 percent too many parents, and half as many racial minorities. Moreover, sample may also underrepresent highest and lowest categories of family income. These data reasonably represent middle 80–90 percent of American society, but they do not well represent ethnic minorities, very poor, very rich, and very transient. They may also slightly overrepresent portion of public that is most engaged with mass media. **Thus a crucial question about the DDB Needham Life Style survey archive is the degree to which these known sample biases inhibit our ability to estimate social trends from these data**.

**Validation questions**:
1. Do people who join mail panel differ in substantively relevant ways from people who are willing to respond to conventional surveys?
2. Has **degree** of difference between Life Style panel and conventional surveys changed over time, thus rendering judgments about trends suspect?

**Validation results**: If answer to question 1 is "Yes," then in some respects DDB Needham Life Style might be inaccurate descriptively. Only if answer to question 2 is also "Yes," however, will **trends** in Life Style data misrepresent trends as they would appear in conventional random survey. Constant bias would be disconcerting, but only **changing** bias would affect judgments about trends.

**Comparison with conventional surveys**: Reassuring information available from several studies that have directly compared results from mail panels and conventional samples. First, apart from demographic disparity just described (fewer young, poor, and racial minorities in mail panel), there are surprisingly few differences between two approaches, even on variables that might be thought to be especially sensitive to difference in techniques. Two different samples do not differ in religious affiliation and religiosity; in public policy views (on tax policy, abortion, gun control); in their views about their own and nation's economic circumstances; in their altruism (volunteering, philanthropy) or general "positivity"; in their basic consumer orientations, purchasing habits, ownership or use of common products; in their health or fitness; or in their leisure time. Only significant differences are 1) partisanship (mail panels are slightly less Democratic, probably because of underrepresentation of racial minorities); and 2) media usage (mail panelists watch slightly more television and read slightly more newspapers). That low response rates may not bias substantive results can also be inferred from recent study that compared results from "easy to reach" and "hard to reach" samples. Aside from clear differences on racial issues, upshot is that there are no significant differences on other issue stances, on media use, on engagement in daily activities, and on feelings about other people.

**Additional validation**: Additional reassurance comes from comparison between two most widely reported national surveys of consumer confidence in United States—one (from University of Michigan) that relies on conventional random sampling and another (from Conference Board) that relies on mail panel. Long-run changes charted by two methods have been very similar. (Semiannual correlation between two indexes over more than three decades is R² = .55.) For fine-grained, month-to-month changes, one or other of these two surveys might be preferred, but broad-gauge impressions of annual trends that one would glean from two are quite similar.

**Cross-validation with GSS**: To explore more fully reliability of DDB Needham Life Style data, Putnam took advantage of fact that data set includes more than dozen diverse questions that are comparable to questions posed on regular basis over roughly same time span in General Social Survey. These measures include attitudes toward feminism, legalization of marijuana and abortion, views of Soviet Union, financial worries, military service, basic social values, smoking, video usage, hunting and gun ownership, and (especially relevant to our interests) social trust, church attendance, and leisure activities. For each of these items, Putnam posed three tests:

1. Do **levels** of response on these variables differ between two samples, taking into account obvious differences in question wording?
2. Do **trends** that one would infer about underlying trait differ between two samples?
3. Do underlying patterns of **demographic correlates** of these variables differ between two samples?

**Yonish and Putnam finding**: As **Steven Yonish** and Putnam report in detail elsewhere, in every case answer is **"No"**. For purposes of describing and explaining this wide range of attitudes and behavior, two surveys are virtually indistinguishable, despite marked differences in sampling (random vs. quota), questioning procedure (personal interviews vs. mail questionnaires), and in some cases question wording. Not only are trends on all comparable items virtually identical in two archives, but deeper structure of relations between these items and demographic categories is also very similar.

**Specific example**: According to General Social Survey, for example, probability that in 1990 a thirty-five-year-old single white mother with two years of college education and part-time job who rented apartment in middle-size New England city favored marijuana legalization is 35 percent, whereas comparable probability according to DDB Needham Life Style data was 38 percent, a difference well within sampling error. Similarly, controlling simultaneously for year of survey, year of birth, marital status, employment status, parental status, education, income, race, region of country, and type of residence, GSS data suggest that women attend church exactly 5.3 more times per year than men, whereas DDB Needham Life Style data imply that difference between sexes in churchgoing is 4.8 times per year—once again a difference well within sampling error. **That the DDB Needham Life Style data pass this very stringent test of comparability with the GSS data—the most scientifically reputable data available on these topics—increases our confidence in the DDB Needham Life Style archive**.

**Leisure activities comparison**: Finally, two archives contain directly comparable questions about range of leisure activities. Appendix table 1 shows responses to series of questions regarding "leisure or recreational activities… done in the past twelve months." Incidence of these activities in two surveys was astonishingly similar, well within limits of sampling error.

**Conclusion on DDB Needham reliability**: In short, just as ice cores, though not infallible, are invaluable source of information about climatic change, particularly when cross-checked against other measures, **for purposes of estimating basic trends in social participation over last quarter of twentieth century the DDB Needham Life Style archive is a valuable source of information**, particularly if (as throughout analyses in this book) results from this archive are consistent with results from other modes of measurement.

### Frequency Conversion Algorithm

- Both General Social Survey and DDB Needham Life Style surveys typically ask respondents to estimate frequency of various activities, such as church attendance, but two surveys use slightly different categories for this purpose
- In order to facilitate comparison between these two archives—and, more generally, to simplify presentation of estimated frequencies for various activities—Putnam converted raw data in each case into estimated annual frequencies, using algorithm in appendix table 2
- Reasonable observers might differ over exactly what "several times a year," for example, means in quantitative terms, but basic results are not sensitive to exactly what integers are assigned to various ranks

### Americans' Use of Time Archive

- Another valuable data archive used frequently in this book derives from **Americans' Use of Time** project, managed in recent decades by Professor **John Robinson** of University of Maryland
- Based on careful time diaries kept by national samples of Americans in 1965, 1975, 1985, and 1995
- Abundant details about these data available in Robinson's book with **Geoffrey Godbey**, *Time for Life: The Surprising Ways Americans Use Their Time*
- One special feature of these data deserves brief mention: One major advantage of this data archive is that it begins in 1965, just about same time that (other data suggest) various forms of social capital began to decline
- However, 1965 data differed somewhat from subsequent years, in that 1965 sample excluded respondents who lived in areas with no city greater than fifty thousand in population, as well as households in which no member aged eighteen to sixty-five was part of nonagricultural labor force
- Since 1965 sample excluded rural and retired families, raw figures for that year slightly misrepresent what would have been found in national sample that year
- To estimate 1965 figures that are more nearly comparable to later, nationwide data, Putnam adjusted raw data for 1965, using observed differences in 1975 and 1985 surveys between full national sample and subset of respondents who would have been included within 1965 sampling frame
- In addition, weighted raw data to ensure that each day of week was equally represented in final sample
- These adjustments account for minor discrepancies between results presented by Robinson and Godbey and results reported here
