### Terminological Note

- **"Church"** used inclusively throughout the text to refer to **all religious institutions** regardless of faith tradition
- Includes **mosques, temples, and synagogues**
- Simplification for ease of reference rather than theological preference

<!-- p. 696 -->

- **Experimental social psychologists** have found that even casual social interaction can have powerful effects on **reciprocity**
- When a casual **"stranger"** speaks briefly in a hallway to an unwitting subject, the subject is quicker to provide help when subsequently "overhearing" the confederate having an apparent seizure—compared to no previous contact
  - Reference: **Bibb Latané and John M. Darley**, *The Unresponsive Bystander: Why Doesn't He Help?* (Englewood Cliffs, N.J.: Prentice-Hall, 1970), 107–109

- **Marriage and greeting cards**: While marriage increases the frequency with which women send greeting cards, it cuts in half the frequency with which men do so, regardless of whether their wives work or not
  - This sociological "finding" will hardly be news to most couples

<!-- p. 697 -->

- Virtually all small towns in **New Hampshire** (where the author is writing the book) supported **town bands** in that era; few do now

<!-- p. 698 -->

### Historical Period Definitions

- **"Gilded Age"** refers roughly to period **1870–1900**
- **"Progressive Era"** refers roughly to period **1900–1915**
- Neither term is used with great precision
- Division between periods is not strict—developments associated with Progressive movement had antecedents during earlier Gilded Age period, and Gilded Age developments persisted into later Progressive period

